<MILESTONE N="3b" UNIT="fol."><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">LIBER PRIMUS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="l">INCIPIT LIBER BOICII DE CONSOLACIONE PHILOSOPHIE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><DIV2 N="1" TYPE="metre">

<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">Carmina qui quondam studio florente peregi.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Allas I wepyng am constreined to bygynne vers of sorouful matere.  &para; &THORN;at whilom in florysching studie made delitable ditees.  For loo rendyng muses of poetes enditen to me &thorn;inges to be writen.  and drery vers of wrecchednes weten my face wi&thorn; verray teers. &para; At &thorn;e leest no drede ne my&yogh;t[e] ouer-come &thorn;o muses. &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne weren felawes and folweden my wey.  &thorn;at is to seyne when I was exiled.  &thorn;ei &thorn;at weren glorie of my you&yogh;th whilom weleful and grene conforten now &thorn;e sorouful werdes of me olde man. for elde is comen vnwarly vpon me hasted by &thorn;e harmes &thorn;at I haue.  and sorou ha&thorn; comaunded his age to be in me.  &para; Heeres hore ben schad ouertymelyche vpon myne heued. and &thorn;e slak[e] skyn tremble&thorn; vpon myn emty body.  &thorn;ilk[e] dee&thorn; of men is welful &thorn;at ne come&thorn; not in &yogh;eres &thorn;at ben swete (.i. mirie.) but come&thorn; to wrecches often yclepid.</P><P>&para; Allas allas wi&thorn; how deef an eere dee&thorn; cruel tourne&thorn; awey fro wrecches and naie&thorn; to closen wepyng eyen.  &para; While fortune vnfei&thorn;ful fauored[e] me wi&thorn; ly&yogh;te goodes (.s. temporels.) &thorn;e sorouful houre &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;e dee&thorn; had[de] almost dreynt myne heued. &para; But now for fortune clowdy ha&thorn; chaunged hir disceyuable chere to me warde. myn vnpitouse lijf drawe&thorn; a long vnagreable dwellynges in me.  &para; O &yogh;e my <PB N="5">frendes what or wherto auaunted[e] &yogh;e me to be weleful: for he &thorn;at ha&thorn; fallen stood not in stedfast degree.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="1" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">HIC DUM MECUM TACITUS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>In &thorn;e mene while &thorn;at I stille recorded[e] &thorn;ise &thorn;inges wi&thorn; my self. and markede my wepli compleynte wi&thorn; office of poyntel. I saw stondyng aboue &thorn;e hey&yogh;t of my heued a woman of ful greet reuerence by semblaunt hir eyen brennyng and clere seing ouer &thorn;e comune my&yogh;t of men. wi&thorn; a lijfly colour and wi&thorn; swiche vigoure and strenke&thorn; &thorn;at it ne my&yogh;t[e] not be emptid.  &para; Al were it so &thorn;at sche was ful of so greet age.  &thorn;at men ne wolde not trowe in no manere &thorn;at sche were of oure elde. &thorn;e stature of hir was of a doutous iugement. for sumtyme sche constreyned[e] and schronk hir seluen lyche to &thorn;e comune mesure of men. and sumtyme it semed[e] &thorn;at sche touched[e] &thorn;e heuene wi&thorn; &thorn;e hey&yogh;te of hir heued. and when sche hef hir heued heyer sche perced[e] &thorn;e selue heuene. so &thorn;at &thorn;e sy&yogh;t of men lokyng was in ydel.  &para; Hir clo&thorn;es weren maked of ry&yogh;t delye &thorn;redes and subtil crafte of perdurable matere. &thorn;e wyche clo&thorn;es sche hadde wouen wi&thorn; hir owen hondes: as I knew wel aftir by hir selfe. declaryng and schewyng to me &thorn;e beaute.  &thorn;e wiche clo&thorn;es a derkenes of a forleten and dispised elde had[de] duskid and dirkid as it is wont to dirken by-smoked ymages.  &para; In &thorn;e ne&thorn;erest[e] <PB N="6">hem or bordure of &thorn;ese clo&thorn;es men redden ywouen in swiche a gregkysche .P. &thorn;at signifie&thorn; &thorn;e lijf actif.  And abouen &thorn;at lettre in &thorn;e hey&yogh;est[e] bordure a grekysche T. &thorn;at signifie&thorn; &thorn;e lijf contemplatif. &para; And by-twene &thorn;ese two lettres &thorn;ere weren seien degrees nobly wrou&yogh;t in manere of laddres.  By wyche degrees men my&yogh;t[en] clymbe fro &thorn;e ne&thorn;emast[e] lettre to &thorn;e ouermast[e].  &para; Na&thorn;eles hondes of sum men hadde korue &thorn;at clo&thorn;e by vyolence and by strenke&thorn;. &para; And eueryche man of hem hadde born away syche peces as he my&yogh;te geet[e].  &para; And forso&thorn;e &thorn;is forsaide woman ber bookes in hir ry&yogh;t honde. and in hir lefte honde sche ber a ceptre.  &para; And when sche sau&yogh; &thorn;ese poetical muses aprochen aboute my bedde. and endytyng wordes to my wepynges. sche was a lytel ameued and glowed[e] wi&thorn; cruel eyen.  &para; Who quod sche ha&thorn; suffred aprochen to &thorn;is seek[e] man &thorn;ise comune strumpetis 
 of siche a place &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="4" UNIT="fol.">men clepen &thorn;e theatre. &para; &THORN;e wyche only ne asswagen not his sorowes. wi&thorn; no remedies. but &thorn;ei wolde fede and norysche hem wi&thorn; swete venym.  &para; Forso&thorn;e &thorn;ise ben &thorn;o &thorn;at wi&thorn; &thorn;ornes and prykkynges of talent&yogh; or affecciouns wiche &thorn;at ben no &thorn;ing fruteliyng nor profitable destroyen &thorn;e cornes plenteuouse of frutes of reson.  &para; For &thorn;ei holden &thorn;e hertes of men in usage. but &thorn;ei ne delyuere not folk fro maladye. but if &yogh;e muses hadde wi&thorn;drawen <PB N="7">fro me wi&thorn; &yogh;oure flateries. any vnkonnyng and vnprofitable man as men ben wont to fynde comunely amonges &thorn;e peple.  I wolde wene suffre &thorn;e lasse greuously. &para; For-why in syche an vnprofitable man myne ententes weren no &thorn;ing endamaged.  &para; But &yogh;e wi&thorn;drawen me &thorn;is man &thorn;at ha&thorn; ben norysched in studies or scoles of Eleaticis and of achademicis in grece.  &para; But go&thorn; now ra&thorn;er awey &yogh;e meremaydenes wyche ben swete til it be at &thorn;e laste. and suffre&thorn; &thorn;is man to be cured and heled by myne muses. &thorn;at is to say by notful sciences. &para; And &thorn;us &thorn;is compaygnie of muses I-blamed casten wro&thorn;ely &thorn;e chere adounward to &thorn;e er&thorn;e and schewyng by redenesse hir schame &thorn;ei passeden sorowfuly &thorn;e &thorn;reschefolde.  &para; And I of whom &thorn;e sy&yogh;t plonged in teres was derked so &thorn;at I ne my&yogh;t[e] not knowe what &thorn;at woman was of so imperial auctorite.  &para; I wex al a-besid and astoned. and caste my sy&yogh;t adoune in to &thorn;e er&thorn;e. and bygan stille forto abide what sche wolde don afterwarde.  &para; &THORN;o come sche nere and sette hir doun vpon &thorn;e vterrest[e] corner of my bedde. and sche by-holdyng my chere &thorn;at was cast to &thorn;e er&thorn;e heuy and greuous of wepyng. compleinede wi&thorn; &thorn;ise wordes &thorn;at I schal sey &thorn;e perturbacioun of my &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="2" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">HEU QUAM PRECIPITI MERSA PROFUNDO.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Allas how &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t of man dreint in ouer &thorn;rowyng depnesse dulle&thorn; and forleti&thorn; hys propre clerenesse. myntynge to gone in to foreyne derknesses as ofte as hys anoious bisines wexi&thorn; wi&thorn;-outen mesure. <PB N="8">&thorn;at is dryuen to and fro wi&thorn; worldly wyndes.  &para; &THORN;is man &thorn;at sumtyme was fre to whom &thorn;e heuene was open and knowen and was wont to gone in heuenelyche pa&thorn;es. and sau&yogh; &thorn;e ly&yogh;tnesse of &thorn;e rede sunne. and sau&yogh; &thorn;e sterres of &thorn;e colde moone. and wyche sterre in heuene vse&thorn; wandryng risorses yflit by dyuerse speres. &para; &THORN;is man ouer comere hadde comprehendid al &thorn;is by noumbre. of accountyng in astronomye.  &para; And ouer &thorn;is he was wont to seche &thorn;e causes whennes &thorn;e sounyng wyndes moeuen and bisien &thorn;e smo&thorn;e water of &thorn;e see. and what spirit turne&thorn; &thorn;e stable heuene. and whi &thorn;e sterre ryse&thorn; oute of &thorn;e reede eest. to falle in &thorn;e westren wawes. and what attempri&thorn; &thorn;e lusty houres of &thorn;e fyrste somer sesoun &thorn;at hi&yogh;te&thorn; and apparaile&thorn; &thorn;e er&thorn;e wi&thorn; rosene floures.  &para; And who make&thorn; &thorn;at plenteuouse autumpne in fulle &yogh;eres fleti&thorn; wi&thorn; heuy grapes.  &para; And eke &thorn;is man was wont to telle &thorn;e dyuerses causes of nature &thorn;at weren yhid. &para; Allas now lie&thorn; he emptid of ly&yogh;t of hys &thorn;ou&yogh;t. and hys nekke is pressid wi&thorn; heuy cheynes and bere&thorn; his chere enclined adoune for &thorn;e greet[e] wey&yogh;t. and is constreyned to loke on foule er&thorn;e.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="2" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">SET MEDICINE INQUIT TEMPUS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Bvt tyme is now quod sche of medicine more &thorn;en of compleynte.  &para; Forso&thorn;e &thorn;en sche entendyng to me warde wi&thorn; al &thorn;e lokyng of hir eyen saide.  &para; Art not &thorn;ou he quod sche &thorn;at sumtyme I-norschid wi&thorn; my mylke and fostre[d] wi&thorn; my meetes were ascaped and comen to corage of a perfit man.  &para; Certys I &yogh;af &thorn;e <PB N="9">syche armures &thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;ou &thorn;i self ne haddest first caste hem away. &thorn;ei schulden haue defendid &thorn;e in sykernesse &thorn;at may not be ouer-comen.  &para; Knowest &thorn;ou me not. <MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="fol.">Why art &thorn;ou stille. is it for schame or for astonynge.  
It were me leuer &thorn;at it were for schame. but it seme&thorn; me &thorn;at astonynge ha&thorn; oppressed &thorn;e.  &para; And whan sche say me not oonly stille. but wi&thorn;-outen office of tonge and al doumbe. sche leide hir honde softely vpon my brest and seide.  &para; Here nis no peril quod sche. &para; He is fallen in to a litargie. whiche &thorn;at is a comune sekenes to hertes &thorn;at ben desceiued.  &para; He ha&thorn; a litel for&yogh;eten hym self. but certis he schal ly&yogh;tly remembren hym self.  &para; &YOGH;if so be &thorn;at he ha&thorn; knowen me or now. and &thorn;at he may so done I wil wipe a litel hys eyen. &thorn;at ben derked by &thorn;e cloude of mortel &thorn;inges &para; &THORN;ise wordes seide sche. and wi&thorn; &thorn;e lappe of hir garment yplitid in a frounce sche dried[e] myn eyen &thorn;at were ful of &thorn;e wawes of my wepynges.</P></DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">TUNC ME DISCUSSA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;us when &thorn;at ny&yogh;t was discussed and chased awey. derknesses forleften me. and to myn eyen repeyre a&yogh;eyne her firste strenke&thorn;. and ry&yogh;t by ensample as &thorn;e sonne is hid when &thorn;e sterres ben clustred. &thorn;at is to sey when sterres ben couered wi&thorn; cloudes by a swifte wynde &thorn;at hy&yogh;t chorus. and &thorn;at &thorn;e firmament stont derked by wete ploungy cloudes. and &thorn;at &thorn;e sterres not apperen vpon heuene.  &para; So &thorn;at &thorn;e ny&yogh;t seme&thorn; sprad vpon er&thorn;e.  &para;  Yif &thorn;an &thorn;e wynde &thorn;at hy&yogh;t borias <PB N="10">sent out of &thorn;e kaues of &thorn;e contre of Trace beti&thorn; &thorn;is ny&yogh;t. &thorn;at is to seyn chasi&thorn; it away and descouere&thorn; &thorn;e closed day.  &para; &THORN;an schine&thorn; phebus yshaken wi&thorn; sodeyne ly&yogh;t and smyte&thorn; wi&thorn; hys bemes in meruelyng eyen.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="3" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">HAUT</FOREIGN><NOTE>MS. <FOREIGN LANG="l">hanc.</FOREIGN></NOTE><FOREIGN LANG="l"> ALITER TRISTICIE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Ry&yogh;t so and none o&thorn;er wyse &thorn;e cloudes of sorowe dissolued and don awey.  &para; I took heuene. and receyuede mynde to knowe &thorn;e face of my fyciscien. &para; So &thorn;at I sette myne eyen on hir and festned[e] my lokyng.  I byholde my norice philosophie. in whos houses I hadde conuersed and haunted fro my &yogh;ou&thorn;e. and I seide &thorn;us.  &para; O &thorn;ou maistresse of alle uertues descendid fro &thorn;e souereyne sete.  Whi art &thorn;ou comen in to &thorn;is solitarie place of myn exil.  &para; Art &thorn;ou comen for &thorn;ou art mad coupable wi&thorn; me of fals[e] blames. &para; O quod sche my norry scholde I forsake &thorn;e now. and scholde I not parte wi&thorn; &thorn;e by comune trauaille &thorn;e charge &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast suffred for envie of my name.  &para; Certis it nar[e] not leueful ne sittyng to philosophie to leten wi&thorn;-outen compaignie &thorn;e wey of hym &thorn;at is innocent. &para; Scholde I &thorn;an redoute my blame and agrisen as &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;er were byfallen a newe &thorn;ing. q. d. non.  &para; For trowest &thorn;ou &thorn;at philosophi be now al&thorn;erfirst assailed in perils by folk of wicked[e] maneres.  &para; Haue I not stryuen wi&thorn; ful greet strife in olde tyme byfore &thorn;e age of my plato a&yogh;eins &thorn;e foolhardines of foly and eke &thorn;e same plato lyuyng. hys maistre socrates deserued[e] victorie of vnry&yogh;tful dee&thorn; in my presence. &para; &THORN;e heritage of wyche socrates. &thorn;e heritage is to seyne 
<PB N="11">&thorn;e doctrine of &thorn;e whiche socrates in hys oppinioun of felicite &thorn;at I clepe welfulnesse &para; Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e people of epicuriens and stoyciens and many o&thorn;er enforceden hem to go rauische eueryche man for his part &thorn;at is to seyne. &thorn;at to eueryche of hem wolde drawen to &thorn;e defence of his oppinioun &thorn;e wordes of socrates.  &para; &THORN;ei as in partie of hir preye todrowen me criynge and debatyng &thorn;er a&yogh;eins. and tornen and torenten my clo&thorn;es &thorn;at I hadde wouen wi&thorn; myn handes. and wi&thorn; &thorn;e cloutes &thorn;at &thorn;ei hadden arased oute of my clo&thorn;es. &thorn;ei wenten awey wenyng &thorn;at I hadde gon wi&thorn; hem euery dele.  In whiche epicuryens and stoyciens.  for as myche as &thorn;er semed[e] somme traces and steppes of myne habit. &thorn;e folye of men wenyng &thorn;o epicuryens and stoyciens my <MILESTONE N="5" UNIT="fol.">familers peruertede (.s. persequendo)  
somme &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e errour of &thorn;e wikked[e] or vnkunnyng[e] multitude of hem.  &para; &THORN;is is to seyne for &thorn;ei semeden philosophres: &thorn;ei weren pursued to &thorn;e dee&thorn; and slayn.  &para; So yif &thorn;ou hast not knowen &thorn;e exilynge of anaxogore. ne &thorn;e empoysenyng of socrates. ne &thorn;e tourment&yogh; of &yogh;eno for &thorn;ei [weren] straungers.  &para; &YOGH;it my&yogh;test &thorn;ou haue knowen &thorn;e senectiens and &thorn;e Canyos and &thorn;e sorancis of wyche folk &thorn;e renoun is ney&thorn;er ouer oolde ne vnsolempne.  &para; &THORN;e whiche men no &thorn;ing ellys ne brou&yogh;t[e] hem to &thorn;e dee&thorn; but oonly for &thorn;ei weren enfourmed of my maneres. and semeden moste vnlyke to &thorn;e studies of wicked folk.  &para; And for&thorn;i &thorn;ou au&yogh;test not to wondre &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at I in &thorn;e bitter see of &thorn;is lijf be <PB N="12">fordryuen wi&thorn; tempestes blowyng aboute. in &thorn;e whiche tempeste &thorn;is is my most purpos &thorn;at is to seyn to displese to wikked[e] men.  &para; Of whiche schrews al be &thorn;e oost neuer so grete it is to dispyse. for it nis gouerned wi&thorn; no leder of resoune. but it is rauysched only by flityng errour folyly and ly&yogh;tly.  &para; And if &thorn;ei somtyme makyng an ost a&yogh;eynest vs assaile vs as strengere. oure leder drawe&thorn; to gedir hys rycchesse in to hys toure. and &thorn;ei ben ententif aboute sarpulers or sachels vnprofitable forto taken. but we &thorn;at ben hey&yogh; abouen syker fro al tumulte and wode noise. ben stored and enclosed in syche a palays. whider as &thorn;at chateryng or anoying folye ne may not attayne.  &para; We scorne swiche rauiners and honters of foulest[e] &thorn;inges.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="4" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUISQUIS COMPOSITO.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Who so it be &thorn;at is clere of vertue sad and wel ordinat of lyuyng. &thorn;at ha&thorn; put vnderfote &thorn;e prowed[e] wierdes and loki&thorn; vpry&yogh;t vpon ey&thorn;er fortune. he may holde hys chiere vndiscomfited.  &para; &THORN;e rage ne &thorn;e manace of &thorn;e commoeuyng or chasyng vpwarde hete fro &thorn;e botme. ne schal not moeue &thorn;at man. ne &thorn;e vnstable mountaigne &thorn;at hy&yogh;t veseuus. &thorn;at wirche&thorn; oute &thorn;oru&yogh; hys broken[e] chemineys smokyng fires.  &para; Ne &thorn;e wey of &thorn;onder ly&yogh;t &thorn;at is wont to smyte hey&yogh;e toures ne schal not mouene &thorn;at man.  &para; Wherto &thorn;en wrecches drede &yogh;e tyrauntes &thorn;at ben wode and felownes wi&thorn;-outen ony strenke&thorn;.  &para; Hope after no &thorn;ing ne drede nat. and <PB N="13">so schalt &thorn;ou desarmen &thorn;e ire of &thorn;ilke vnmy&yogh;ty tyraunt. &para; But who so &thorn;at quakyng drede&thorn; or desire&thorn; &thorn;ing &thorn;at nis not stable of his ry&yogh;t. &thorn;at man &thorn;at so do&thorn; ha&thorn; cast awey hys schelde and is remoeued fro hys place. and enlace&thorn; hym in &thorn;e cheyne wi&thorn; whiche he may be drawen.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="4" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">SENTIS NE INQUIT.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>FElest &thorn;ou quod sche &thorn;ise &thorn;inges and entren &thorn;ei ou&yogh;t in &thorn;i corage.  &para; Art &thorn;ou like an asse to &thorn;e harpe. Whi wepest &thorn;ou whi spillest &thorn;ou teres.  &para; Yif &thorn;ou abidest after helpe of &thorn;i leche. &thorn;e byhoue&thorn; discouere &thorn;i wounde.  &para; &THORN;o .I. &thorn;at hadde gadered strenke&thorn; in my corage answered[e] and seide. and nede&thorn; it &yogh;itte quod .I. of rehersyng or of amonicioun. and schewe&thorn; it not ynou&yogh; by hym self &thorn;e scharpnes of fortune &thorn;at wexe&thorn; woode a&yogh;eynes me.  &para; Ne moeue&thorn; it nat &thorn;e to seen &thorn;e face or &thorn;e manere of &thorn;is place (.i. prisoun.).  &para; Is &thorn;is &thorn;e librarie wyche &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddest chosen for a ry&yogh;t certeyne sege to &thorn;e in myne house.  &para; &THORN;ere as &thorn;ou desputest of[te] wi&thorn; me of &thorn;e sciences of &thorn;inges touching diuinitee and touchyng mankynde.  &para; Was &thorn;an myn habit swiche as it is now. was &thorn;an my face or my chere swiche as now<NOTE PLACE="superlinear"><FOREIGN LANG="l">quasi diceret non.</FOREIGN></NOTE>. &para; Whan I sou&yogh;t[e] wi&thorn; &thorn;e secretys of nature. whan &thorn;ou enfourmedest my maners and &thorn;e resoun of al my lijf. to &thorn;e ensaumple of &thorn;e ordre of heuene.  &para; Is nat &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="superlinear"><FOREIGN LANG="l">ironice</FOREIGN>.</NOTE> &thorn;e gerdoun &thorn;at I refere to &thorn;e to whom I haue be obeisaunt.  &para; Certis &thorn;ou enfourmedist by &thorn;e mou&thorn;e of plato &thorn;is sentence.  &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;at commune &thorn;inges or comunabletes weren <PB N="14">blysful yif &thorn;ei &thorn;at haden studied al fully to wisdom gouerneden &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges. or ellys yif it so by-felle &thorn;at 
 &thorn;e gouernours <MILESTONE N="5b" UNIT="fol.">of communalites studieden in grete wisdomes. &para; &THORN;ou saidest eke by &thorn;e mou&thorn;e of &thorn;e same plato &thorn;at it was a necessarie cause wyse men to taken and desire &thorn;e gouernaunce of comune &thorn;inges. for &thorn;at &thorn;e gouernementes of comune citees y-left in &thorn;e hondes of felonous tourmentours Citi&yogh;enis ne scholde not brynge inne pestilence and destruccioun to goode folk.  &para; And &thorn;erfore I folowynge &thorn;ilk auctoritee (.s. platonis). desiryng to put[te] fur&thorn;e in execusioun and in acte of comune administracioun &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at .I. hadde lerned of &thorn;e among my secre restyng whiles.  &para; &THORN;ou and god &thorn;at put[te] &thorn;ee in &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;tis of wise folk ben knowen wi&thorn; me &thorn;at no &thorn;ing brou&yogh;t[e] me to maistrie or dignite: but &thorn;e comune studie of al goodenes.  &para; And &thorn;er-of come&thorn; it &thorn;at by-twixen wikked folk and me han ben greuouse discordes. &thorn;at ne my&yogh;ten not be relesed by prayeres. &para; For &thorn;is libertee ha&thorn; fredom of conscience &thorn;at &thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;e of more my&yogh;ty folk ha&thorn; alwey ben despised of me for saluacioun of ry&yogh;t.  &para; How ofte haue .I. resisted and wi&thorn;stonde &thorn;ilk man &thorn;at hy&yogh;t[e] conigaste &thorn;at made alwey assautes a&yogh;eins &thorn;e propre fortunes of poure feble folke.  &para; How ofte haue .I. &yogh;itte put of. or cast out hym trigwille prouost of &thorn;e kynges hous bo&thorn;e of &thorn;e wronges &thorn;at he hadde bygon[ne] to done and eke fully performed.  &para; How ofte haue I couered and defended by &thorn;e auctorite of me put a&yogh;eins perils. &thorn;at is to seine put myne auctorite in peril for &thorn;e wreched pore folke. &thorn;at <PB N="15">&thorn;e couetise of straungeres vnpunysched tourmentid alwey wi&thorn; myseses and greuaunces oute of noumbre.  &para; Neuer man drow me &yogh;itte fro ry&yogh;t to wrong.  When I say &thorn;e fortunes and &thorn;e rychesse of &thorn;e people of &thorn;e prouinces ben harmed ey&thorn;er by priue rauynes or by comune tributis or cariages. as sory was I as &thorn;ei &thorn;at suffred[e] &thorn;e harme.  <FOREIGN LANG="l">Glosa.</FOREIGN>  &para; Whan &thorn;at theodoric &thorn;e kyng of gothes in a dere &yogh;ere hadde hys gerners ful of corne and comaundede &thorn;at no man ne schold[e] bie no corne til his corne were solde and &thorn;at at a dere greuous pris. &para; But I withstod &thorn;at ordinaunce and ouer-com it knowyng al &thorn;is &thorn;e kyng hym self.  &para; Coempcioun &thorn;at is to seyn comune achat or bying to-gidere &thorn;at were establissed vpon poeple by swiche a manere imposicioun as who so bou&yogh;t[e] a busshel corn he most[e] &yogh;eue &thorn;e kyng &thorn;e fifte part.  <FOREIGN LANG="l">Textus.</FOREIGN>  &para; Whan it was in &thorn;e soure hungry tyme &thorn;ere was establissed or cried greuous and inplitable coempcioun &thorn;at men seyn wel it schulde greetly tourmentyn and endamagen al &thorn;e prouince of compaigne I took strif a&yogh;eins &thorn;e prouost of &thorn;e pretorie for comune profit.  &para; And &thorn;e kyng knowyng of it I ouercom it so &thorn;at &thorn;e coempcioun ne was not axed ne took effect.  &para; Paulyn a counseiller of Rome &thorn;e rychesse of &thorn;e whyche paulyn &thorn;e houndys of &thorn;e palays. &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;e officeres wolde han deuoured by hope and couetise  &para; &YOGH;it drow I hym out of &thorn;e Iowes .s. faucibus of hem &thorn;at gapeden.  &para; And for as myche as &thorn;e peyne of &thorn;e accusacioun aiuged byforn ne scholde not sodeynly henten ne punischen wrongfuly Albyn a counseiller of <PB N="16">Rome. I put[te] me a&yogh;enis &thorn;e hates and indignaciouns of &thorn;e accusour Ciprian.  &para; Is it not &thorn;an ynought yseyn &thorn;at I haue purchased greet[e] discordes a&yogh;eins my self. but I aughte be more asseured a&yogh;enis alle o&thorn;er folk &thorn;at for &thorn;e loue of ry&yogh;twisnesse .I. ne reserued[e] neuer no &thorn;ing to my self to hem ward of &thorn;e kynges halle .s. officers. by &thorn;e whiche I were &thorn;e more syker.  &para; But &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e same accusours accusyng I am condempned.  &para; Of &thorn;e noumbre of whiche accusours one basilius &thorn;at somtyme was chased out of &thorn;e kynges seruice. is now compelled in accusyng of my name for nede of foreine moneye.  &para; Also opilion and Gaudencius han accused me. al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;e Iustice regal hadde sumtyme demed hem bo&thorn;e to go in to exil. for her treccheries and fraudes wi&thorn;-outen noumbre.  &para; To whiche iugement &thorn;ei wolde not obeye.  but defended[e] hem by sykernesse of holy 
 houses.                    <MILESTONE N="6" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;at is to seyne fledden in to seyntuaries. and whan &thorn;is was aperceiued to &thorn;e kyng. he comaunded[e] but &thorn;at &thorn;ei voided[e] &thorn;e citee of Rauenne by certeyne day assigned &thorn;at men scholde merken hem on &thorn;e forheued wi&thorn; an hoke of iren and chasen hem out of toune. &para; Now what &thorn;ing seme&thorn; &thorn;e my&yogh;t[e] be lykned to &thorn;is cruelte.  For certys &thorn;ilk same day was receyued &thorn;e accusyng of my name by &thorn;ilk[e] same accusours.  &para; What may be seid herto.  ha&thorn; my studie and my konnyng deserued &thorn;us. or ellys &thorn;e forseide dampnacioun of me. made &thorn;at hem ry&yogh;tful accusours or no (q.d. non). &para; Was not fortune asshamed of &thorn;is. [Certes alle hadde nat fortune ben asshamyd] &thorn;at innocence was accused. &yogh;it au&yogh;t[e] sche haue had schame of &thorn;e fil&thorn;e of myn accusours. <PB N="17">&para; But axest &thorn;ou in somme of what gilt .I. am accused. men seyne &thorn;at I wolde sauen &thorn;e compaignie of &thorn;e senatours.  &para; And desirest &thorn;ou to here in what manere .I. am accused &thorn;at I scholde han distourbed &thorn;e accusour to beren lettres. by whiche he scholde han maked &thorn;e senatours gilty a&yogh;eins &thorn;e kynges Real maieste.  &para; O meistresse what demest &thorn;ou of &thorn;is. schal .I. forsake &thorn;is blame &thorn;at I ne be no schame to &thorn;e (q. d. non).  &para; Certis .I. haue wold it. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;e sauuacioun of &thorn;e senat. ne I schal neuer leten to wilne it. and &thorn;at I confesse and am a-knowe. but &thorn;e entent of &thorn;e accusour to be destourbed schal cese. &para; For schal I clepe it a felonie &thorn;an or a synne &thorn;at I haue desired &thorn;e sauuacioun of &thorn;e ordre of &thorn;e senat. and certys &yogh;it hadde &thorn;ilk same senat don by me &thorn;oru&yogh; her decret&yogh; and hire iugementys as &thorn;ou&yogh; it were a synne or a felonie &thorn;at is to seyne to wilne &thorn;e sauuacioun of hem (.s senatus).  &para; But folye &thorn;at lieth alwey to hym self may not chaunge &thorn;e merit of &thorn;inges.  &para; Ne .I. trowe not by &thorn;e iugement of socrates &thorn;at it were leueful to me to hide &thorn;e so&thorn;e. ne assent[e] to lesynges. &para; But certys how so euer it be of &thorn;is I put[te] it to gessen or preisen to &thorn;e iugement of &thorn;e and of wise folk.  &para; Of whiche &thorn;ing al &thorn;e ordinaunce and &thorn;e so&thorn;e for as moche as folk &thorn;at ben to comen aftir oure dayes schollen knowen it.  &para; I haue put it in scripture and remembraunce. for touching &thorn;e lettres falsly maked.  by whiche lettres I am accused to han hooped &thorn;e fredom of Rome.  What appertene&thorn; me to speken &thorn;er-of.  Of whiche lettres &thorn;e fraude hadde ben schewed apertly if <PB N="18">I hadde had libertee forto han vsed and ben at &thorn;e confessioun of myn accusours.  &para; &THORN;e whiche &thorn;ing in alle nedys ha&thorn; grete strenke&thorn;.  &para; For what o&thorn;er fredom may men hopen.  Certys I wolde &thorn;at some o&thorn;er fredom my&yogh;t[e] be hoped.  &para; I wolde &thorn;an haue answered by &thorn;e wordes of a man &thorn;at hy&yogh;t[e] Canius. for whan he was accused by Gayus Cesar Germeins son &thorn;at he (canius) was knowyng and consentyng of a coniuracioun maked a&yogh;eins hym (.s. Gaius).  &para; &THORN;is Canius answered[e] &thorn;us.  &para; Yif I had[de] wist it &thorn;ou haddest not wist it.  In whiche &thorn;ing sorwe ha&thorn; not so dulled my witte &thorn;at I pleyne oonly &thorn;at schrewed[e] folk apparailen folies a&yogh;eins vertues.  &para; But I wondre gretly how &thorn;at &thorn;ei may performe &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ei had[de] hoped forto done.  For why. to wylne schrewednesse &thorn;at come&thorn; parauenture of oure defaute.  &para; But it is lyke to a monstre and a meruaille.  &para; How &thorn;at in &thorn;e present sy&yogh;t of god may ben acheued and performed swiche &thorn;inges. as euery felonous man ha&thorn; conceyued in hys &thorn;ou&yogh;t a&yogh;eins innocent.  &para; For whiche &thorn;ing oon of &thorn;i familers not vnskilfully axed &thorn;us.  &para; &YOGH;if god is. whennes comen wikked[e] &thorn;inges. and yif god ne is whennes comen goode &thorn;inges. but al hadde it ben leueful &thorn;at felonous folk &thorn;at now desiren &thorn;e bloode and &thorn;e dee&thorn; of alle goode men. and eke of al &thorn;e senat han wilned to gone destroien me. whom &thorn;ei han seyn alwey batailen and defenden goode men and eke al &thorn;e senat.  &YOGH;it hadde I not desserued of &thorn;e fadres.  &thorn;at is to seyne of &thorn;e senatours &thorn;at &thorn;ei scholde wilne my destruccioun. <PB N="19">&para; &THORN;ou remembrest wele as I gesse &thorn;at whan I wolde don or <MILESTONE N="6b" UNIT="fol.">seyn any &thorn;ing. &thorn;ou &thorn;i self alwey present reweledest  
me.  &para; At &thorn;e citee of verone whan &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng gredy of comune slau&yogh;ter. caste hym to transporten vpon al &thorn;e ordre of &thorn;e senat. &thorn;e gilt of his real maieste of &thorn;e whiche gilt &thorn;at albyn was accused. wi&thorn; how grete sykernesse of peril to me defended[e] I al &thorn;e senat.  &para; &THORN;ou wost wel &thorn;at I seide so&thorn;e. ne I auaunted[e] me neuer in preysyng of my self.  &para; For alwey when any wy&yogh;t resceiue&thorn; preciouse renoun in auauntyng hym self of hys werkes: he amenusi&thorn; &thorn;e secre of hys conscience.  &para; But now &thorn;ou mayst wel seen to what ende I am comen for myne innocence. I receiue peyne of fals felonie in gerdoun of verray vertue.  &para; And what open confessioun of felonie had[de] euer iugis so accordaunt in cruelte. &thorn;at is to seyne as myne accusyng ha&thorn;.  &para; &THORN;at o&thorn;er errour of manswitte or ellyscondicioun of fortune &thorn;at is vncerteyne to al mortal folk ne submytted[e] summe of hem. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;at it ne cheyned[e] summe iuge to han pitee or compassioun.  &para; For al &thorn;ou&yogh; I had[de] ben accused &thorn;at I wolde brenne holy houses. and strangle prestys wi&thorn; wicked swerde.  &para; or &thorn;at .I. had[de] gray&thorn;ed dee&thorn; to alle goode men algatis &thorn;e sentence scholde han punysched me present confessed or conuict.  &para; But now I am remewed fro &thorn;e Citee of rome almost fyuehundre&thorn; &thorn;ousand pas. I am wi&thorn; outen defence dampned to proscripcioun and to &thorn;e dee&thorn;. for &thorn;e studie and bountees &thorn;at I haue done to &thorn;e senat.  &para; But o wel ben &thorn;ei wor&thorn;i of mercye (as who sei&thorn; nay.) &thorn;er my&yogh;t[e] neuer <PB N="20">&yogh;it non of hem ben conuicte.  Of swiche a blame as myn is of swiche trespas myn accusours seyen ful wel &thorn;e dignitee. &thorn;e wiche dignite for &thorn;ei wolde derken it wi&thorn; medelyng of some felonye. &thorn;ei beren me on honde and lieden. &thorn;at I hadde polute and defouled my conscience wi&thorn; sacrelege. for couetise of dignite.  &para; And certys &thorn;ou &thorn;i self &thorn;at art plaunted in me chacedest oute &thorn;e sege of my corage al couetise of mortal &thorn;inges. ne sacrilege ne had[de] no leue to han a place in me byforne &thorn;ine eyen.  &para; For &thorn;ou drouppedest euery day in myn eeres and in my &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;ilk comaundement of pictogoras. &thorn;at is to seyne men schal seruen to god. and not to goddes.  &para; Ne it was no couenaunt ne no nede to taken helpe of &thorn;e foulest spirites.  &para; I &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast ordeyned or set in syche excellence &thorn;at [&thorn;ou] makedest me lyke to god. and ouer &thorn;is &thorn;e ry&yogh;t clene secre chaumbre of myn house. &thorn;at is to seye my wijf and &thorn;e compaignie of myn honeste frendis. and my wyues fadir as wel holy as wor&thorn;i to ben reuerenced &thorn;oru&yogh; hys owen dedis. defenden me of al suspeccioun of syche blame.  &para; But o malice.  &para; For &thorn;ei &thorn;at accusen me taken of &thorn;e philosophie fei&thorn;e of so grete blame.  &para; For &thorn;ei trowen &thorn;at .I. haue had affinite to malyfice or enchauntement&yogh; by cause &thorn;at I am replenissed and fulfilled wi&thorn; &thorn;i techynges. and enformed of &thorn;i maners. &para; And &thorn;us it suffice&thorn; not only &thorn;at &thorn;i reuerence ne auayle me not. but &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou of &thorn;i fre wille ra&thorn;er be blemissed wi&thorn; myne offensioun.  &para; But certys to &thorn;e harmes &thorn;at I haue &thorn;ere bytyde&thorn; &yogh;it &thorn;is encrece of harme. &thorn;at &thorn;e <PB N="21">gessinge and &thorn;e iugement of myche folk ne loken no &thorn;ing to &thorn;e[de]sertys of &thorn;inges but only to &thorn;e auenture of fortune.  &para; And iugen &thorn;at only swiche &thorn;inges ben purueied of god.  whiche &thorn;at temporel welefulnesse commendi&thorn;.  <FOREIGN LANG="l">Glosa.</FOREIGN>  &para; As &thorn;us &thorn;at yif a wy&yogh;t haue prosperite. he is a good man and wor&thorn;i to haue &thorn;at prosperite. and who so ha&thorn; aduersite he is a wikked man. and god ha&thorn; forsake hym. and he is wor&thorn;i to haue &thorn;at aduersite.  &para; &THORN;is is &thorn;e opinioun of somme folke. <NOTE PLACE="margin">Text begins again</NOTE>and &thorn;er of come&thorn; &thorn;at good gessyng.  &para; Fyrste of al &thorn;ing forsake&thorn; wrecches certys it greue&thorn; me to &thorn;ink[e] ry&yogh;t now &thorn;e dyuerse sentences &thorn;at &thorn;e poeple sei&thorn; of me.  &para; And &thorn;us moche I seye &thorn;at &thorn;e laste charge of contrarious fortune is &thorn;is.  <MILESTONE N="7" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;at whan &thorn;at ony blame is laid vpon a caytif. men wenen &thorn;at he ha&thorn; deserued &thorn;at he suffre&thorn;.  &para; And I &thorn;at am put awey from goode men and despoiled from dignitees and defoulid of my name by gessyng haue suffred torment for my goode dedis. &para; Certys me seme&thorn; &thorn;at I se &thorn;e felonus couines of wikked men abounden in ioie and in gladnes.  &para; And I se &thorn;at euery lorel shapi&thorn; hym to fynde oute newe fraudes forto accusen goode folke. and I se &thorn;at goode men ben ouer&thorn;rowen for drede of my peril.  &para; and euery luxurious tourmentour dar don alle felonie vnpunissed and ben excited &thorn;erto by &yogh;iftes. and innocent&yogh; ne ben not oonly despoiled of sykernesse but of defence and &thorn;erfore me list to crien to god in &thorn;is manere.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="5" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">O STELLIFERI CONDITOR ORBIS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>O&thorn;ou maker of &thorn;e whele &thorn;at bere&thorn; &thorn;e sterres. whiche &thorn;at art fastned to &thorn;i perdurable chayere.  and 

<PB N="22">turnest &thorn;e heuene wi&thorn; a rauyssyng sweighe and constreinest &thorn;e sterres to suffren &thorn;i lawe.  &para; So &thorn;at &thorn;e mone somtyme schynyng wi&thorn; hir ful hornes metyng wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e bemes of &thorn;e sonne.  &para; Hir bro&thorn;er hide&thorn; &thorn;e sterres &thorn;at ben lasse. and somtyme whan &thorn;e mone pale wi&thorn; hir derke hornes approche&thorn; &thorn;e sonne. leesith hir ly&yogh;tes.  &para; And &thorn;at &thorn;e euesterre esperus whiche &thorn;at in &thorn;e first[e] tyme of &thorn;e ny&yogh;t brynge&thorn; fur&thorn;e hir colde arysynges come&thorn; eft a&yogh;eynes hir vsed cours. and is pale by &thorn;e morwe at &thorn;e rysynge of &thorn;e sonne. and is &thorn;an cleped lucifer.  &para; &THORN;ou restreinest &thorn;e day by schorter dwellyng in &thorn;e tyme of colde wynter &thorn;at make&thorn; &thorn;e leues to falle.  &para; &THORN;ou diuidest &thorn;e swifte tides of &thorn;e ny&yogh;t when &thorn;e hote somer is comen.  &para; &THORN;i my&yogh;t attempre[&thorn;] &thorn;o variaunt&yogh; sesons of &thorn;e &yogh;ere. so &thorn;at &yogh;epherus &thorn;e deboneire wynde bringe&thorn; a&yogh;ein in &thorn;e first[e] somer sesoun &thorn;e leues &thorn;at &thorn;e wynde &thorn;at hy&yogh;t[e] boreas ha&thorn; reft awey in autumpne. &thorn;at is to seyne in &thorn;e laste eende of somer. and &thorn;e sedes &thorn;at &thorn;e sterre &thorn;at hy&yogh;t arcturus saw ben waxen hey[e] cornes whan &thorn;e sterre sirius eschaufe&thorn; hym.  &para; &THORN;ere nis no &thorn;ing vnbounde from hys olde lawe ne forlete&thorn; hym of hys propre estat. &para; O &thorn;ou gouernour gouernyng alle &thorn;inges by certeyne ende. why refusest &thorn;ou oonly to gouerne &thorn;e werkes of men by dewe manere.  &para; Whi suffrest &thorn;ou &thorn;at slidyng fortune turne&thorn; to grete vtter chaungynges of &thorn;inges. so &thorn;at anoious peyne &thorn;at scholde duelly punisshe felouns punissit&yogh; innocent&yogh;.  &para; And folk of wikked[e] maneres sitten in hei&yogh;e chaiers. and anoienge folk <PB N="23">treden and &thorn;at vnry&yogh;tfully in &thorn;e nekkes of holy men. &para; And vertue clere and schynyng naturely is hid in dirke dirkenesses. and &thorn;e ry&yogh;tful man beri&thorn; &thorn;e blame and &thorn;e peyne of &thorn;e felowne.  &para; Ne &thorn;e forsweryng ne &thorn;e fraude couered and kembd wi&thorn; a fals colour ne a-noye&thorn; not to schrewes.  &para; &THORN;e whiche schrewes whan hem lyst to vsen her streng&thorn;e &thorn;ei reioisen hem to putten vndir hem &thorn;e souerayne kynges.  whiche &thorn;at poeple wi&thorn;[outen] noumbre dreden.  &para; O &thorn;ou what so euer &thorn;ou be &thorn;at knyttes[t] alle bondes of &thorn;inges loke on &thorn;ise wrecched[e] er&thorn;es.  we men &thorn;at ben nat a foule party but a faire party of so grete a werke we ben turmentid in &thorn;e see of fortune.  &para; &THORN;ou gouernour wi&thorn;draw and restreyne &thorn;e rauyssinge flodes and fastne and forme &thorn;ise er&thorn;es stable wi&thorn; &thorn;ilke [bonde] wi&thorn; whiche &thorn;ou gouernest &thorn;e heuene &thorn;at is so large.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="5" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">HIC UBI CONTINUATO DOLORE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Whan I hadde wi&thorn; a continuel sorwe sobbed or broken out &thorn;ise &thorn;inges sche wi&thorn; hir chere peisible and no &thorn;ing amoeued. wi&thorn; my compleyntes seide &thorn;us. whan I say &thorn;e quod sche sorweful and wepyng I wist[e] on-one &thorn;at &thorn;ou were a wrecche and exiled.  but I wist[e] neuer how fer &thorn;ine exile was: &yogh;if &thorn;i tale ne hadde schewed it to me. but certys al be &thorn;ou fer fro &thorn;i contre.  &thorn;ou nart <MILESTONE N="7b" UNIT="fol.">nat put out of it.  but &thorn;ou hast fayled of &thorn;i weye and gon amys.  &para; and yif &thorn;ou hast leuer forto wene &thorn;an &thorn;ou be put out of &thorn;i contre. &thorn;an hast &thorn;ou put oute &thorn;i self ra&thorn;er &thorn;en ony o&thorn;er wy&yogh;t ha&thorn;. &para; For no wy&yogh;t but &thorn;i self ne my&yogh;t[e] neuer haue don <PB N="24">&thorn;at to &thorn;e.  &para; For &yogh;if &thorn;ou remembre of what contre &thorn;ou art born. it nis not gouerned by emperoures. ne by gouernement of multitude. as weren &thorn;e contres of hem of athenes.  &para; But o lorde and o kyng and &thorn;at is god &thorn;at is lorde of &thorn;i contree. whiche &thorn;at reioise&thorn; hym of &thorn;e dwellyng of hys Cite&yogh;enis. and not forto putte hem in exile.  Of &thorn;e whiche lorde it is a souerayne fredom to be gouerned by &thorn;e bridel of hym and obeie to his iustice.  &para; Hast &thorn;ou for&yogh;eten &thorn;ilke ry&yogh;t olde lawe of &thorn;i Citee. in &thorn;e whiche Citee it is ordeyned and establissed &thorn;at what wy&yogh;t &thorn;at ha&thorn; leuer founden &thorn;er inne hys sete or hys house. &thorn;en ellys where: he may not be exiled by no ry&yogh;t fro &thorn;at place.  &para; For who so &thorn;at is contened in-wi&thorn; &thorn;e paleis [and the clos] of &thorn;ilke Citee. &thorn;er nis no drede &thorn;at he may deserue to ben exiled.  &para; But who &thorn;at lette&thorn; &thorn;e wille forto enhabit[e] &thorn;ere. he forlete&thorn; also to deserue to ben Cite&yogh;ein of &thorn;ilke Citee. &para; So &thorn;at I seye &thorn;at &thorn;e face of &thorn;is place ne amoeue&thorn; me nat so myche as &thorn;ine owen face.  Ne .I. ne axe not ra&thorn;er &thorn;e walles of &thorn;i librarie apparailled and wrou&yogh;t wi&thorn; yvory and wi&thorn; glas &thorn;an after &thorn;e sete of &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t. In whiche I putte nat somtyme bookes. but .I. putte &thorn;at &thorn;at make&thorn; bookes wor&thorn;i of pris or precious &thorn;at is to sein &thorn;e sentence of my books.  &para; And certeinly of &thorn;i decertes by-stowed in commune good. &thorn;ou hast seid so&thorn;e but after &thorn;e multitude of &thorn;i goode dedys. &thorn;ou hast seid fewe. and of &thorn;e vnhonestee or falsnesse of &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben opposed a&yogh;eins &thorn;e. &thorn;ou hast remembred &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben knowe to alle folk. and of &thorn;e felonies and fraudes of &thorn;ine accusours. it seme&thorn; &thorn;e haue I-touched it forso&thorn;e ry&yogh;tfully and schortly.  &para; Al my&yogh;ten &thorn;o <PB N="25">same &thorn;inges bettere and more plentiuousely be couth in &thorn;e mou&thorn;e of &thorn;e poeple &thorn;at knowe&thorn; al &thorn;is.  &para; &THORN;ou hast eke blamed gretly and compleyned of &thorn;e wrongful dede of &thorn;e senat.  &para; And &thorn;ou hast sorwed for my blame. and &thorn;ou hast wepen for &thorn;e damage of &thorn;i renoune &thorn;at is appaired. and &thorn;i laste sorwe eschaufed a&yogh;eins fortune and compleinest &thorn;at gerdouns ne ben not euenliche &yogh;olde to &thorn;e desertes of folk. and in &thorn;e lattre ende of &thorn;i woode muse &thorn;ou priedest &thorn;at &thorn;ilke pees &thorn;at gouerne&thorn; &thorn;e heuene scholde gouerne &thorn;e er&thorn;e &para; But for &thorn;at many tribulaciouns of affecciouns han assailed &thorn;e. and sorwe and Ire and wepyng todrawen &thorn;ee dyuersely  &para; As &thorn;ou art now feble of &thorn;ou&yogh;t. my&yogh;tyer remedies ne schullen not &yogh;it touchen &thorn;e for whiche we wil[e] vsen somedel ly&yogh;ter medicines. So &thorn;at &thorn;ilk[e] passiouns &thorn;at ben woxen harde in swellyng by perturbacioun folowyng in to &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t mowen woxe esy and softe to receyuen &thorn;e strenke&thorn; of a more my&yogh;ty and more egre medicine by an esier touchyng.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="6" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">CUM PHEBI RADIIS GRAUE CANCRI SIDUS ENESTUAT.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e heuy sterre of &thorn;e cancre eschaufe&thorn; by &thorn;e beme of phebus. &thorn;at is to seyne whan &thorn;at phebus &thorn;e sonne is in &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e Cancre.  Who so &yogh;eue&thorn; &thorn;an largely hys sedes to &thorn;e feldes &thorn;at refuse to receiuen hem. lete hym gon bygyled of trust &thorn;at he hadde to hys corn. to acorns or okes. yif &thorn;ou wilt gadre violett&yogh;. ne go &thorn;ou not to &thorn;e purper wode whan &thorn;e felde chirkynge agrise&thorn; of colde by &thorn;e felnesse of &thorn;e wynde &thorn;at hy&yogh;t aquilon  &para;  Yif &thorn;ou desirest or <PB N="26">wolt vsen grapes ne seke &thorn;ou nat wi&thorn; a glotonus hande to streine and presse &thorn;e stalkes of &thorn;e vine in &thorn;e first somer sesoun.  for bachus &thorn;e god of wyne ha&thorn; ra&thorn;er &yogh;euen his &yogh;iftes to autumpne &thorn;e latter ende of somer. 
 &para;  God tokeni&thorn; and assigne&thorn; <MILESTONE N="8" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;e tymes. ablyng hem to her propre offices.  &para; Ne he ne suffre&thorn; not stoundes whiche &thorn;at hym self ha&thorn; deuided and constreined to be medeled to gidre  &para;  And for&thorn;i he &thorn;at forlete&thorn; certeyne ordinaunce of doynge by ouer&thorn;rowyng wey. he ne ha&thorn; no glade issue or ende of hys werkes.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="6" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">PRIMUM IGITUR PATERIS ROGACIONIBUS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>FIrst wolt &thorn;ou suffre me to touche and assaie &thorn;e stat of &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t by a fewe demaundes.  so &thorn;at I may vnderstonde what be &thorn;e manere of &thorn;i curacioun.  &para; Axe me quod .I. atte &thorn;i wille what &thorn;ou wilt.  and I schal answere.  &para; &THORN;o saide sche &thorn;us. whe&thorn;er wenest &thorn;ou quod sche &thorn;at &thorn;is worlde be gouerned by foolisshe happes and fortunes. or elles wenest &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;er be in it any gouernement of resoun.  Certes quod .I. ne trowe not in no manere &thorn;at so certeyne &thorn;inges scholde be moeued by fortunouse fortune. but I wot wel &thorn;at god maker and mayster is gouernour of &thorn;is werk.  Ne neuer nas &yogh;it day &thorn;at my&yogh;t[e] putte me oute of &thorn;e so&thorn;enesse of &thorn;at sentence.  &para; So is it quod sche. for &thorn;e same &thorn;ing songe &thorn;ou a lytel here byforne and byweyledest and byweptest. &thorn;at only men weren put oute of &thorn;e cure of god.  &para; For of alle o&thorn;er &thorn;inges &thorn;ou ne doutest nat &thorn;at &thorn;ei nere gouerned by reson. but how (.i. pape.). I wondre gretly certes whi &thorn;at &thorn;ou art seek. si&thorn;en &thorn;ou art put in to so holesom a sentence. but lat vs seken <PB N="27">depper.  I coniecte &thorn;at &thorn;ere lakke&thorn; I not what.  but sey me &thorn;is. si&thorn;en &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne doutest nat &thorn;at &thorn;is worlde be gouerned by god  &para; wi&thorn; swycche gouernailes takest &thorn;ou hede &thorn;at it is gouerned.  &para; vnne&thorn; quod .I. knowe .I. &thorn;e sentence of &thorn;i questioun. so &thorn;at I ne may nat &yogh;it answeren to &thorn;i demaundes.  &para; I nas nat deceiued quod sche &thorn;at &thorn;ere ne faile&thorn; sumwhat. by whiche &thorn;e maladie of perturbacioun is crept in to &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t. so as &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of &thorn;e paleys schynyng is open.  &para; But seye me &thorn;is remembrest &thorn;ou ou&yogh;t what is &thorn;e ende of &thorn;i &thorn;inges. whider &thorn;at &thorn;e entencioun of al kynde tende&thorn;. &para; I haue herd told it somtyme quod .I. but drerynesse ha&thorn; dulled my memorie.  &para; Certys quod sche &thorn;ou wost wel whennes &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges ben comen and proceded.  I wot wel quod .I. and ansewered[e] &thorn;at god is &thorn;e bygynnyng of al.  &para; And how may &thorn;is be quod sche &thorn;at si&thorn;en &thorn;ou knowest &thorn;e bygynnyng of &thorn;inges. &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne knowest not what is &thorn;e endyng of &thorn;inges. but swiche ben &thorn;e customes of perturbaciouns. and &thorn;is power &thorn;ei han. &thorn;at &thorn;ei may moeue a man fro hys place. &thorn;at is to seyne from &thorn;e stablenes and perfeccioun of hys knowyng. but certys &thorn;ei may not al arace hym ne alyene hym in al.  &para; But I wolde &thorn;at &thorn;ou woldest answere to &thorn;is.  &para;  Remembrest &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;ou art a man  &para; <HI REND="i">Boice.</HI>  &para; Whi scholde I nat remembre &thorn;at quod .I. <HI REND="i">Philosophie.</HI>  &para; Maiste &thorn;ou not telle me &thorn;an quod sche what &thorn;ing is a man.  &para; Axest not me quod I. whe&thorn;ir &thorn;at be a resonable best mortel.  I wot wel and I confesse wel &thorn;at I am it.  &para; Wistest &thorn;ou neuer &yogh;it &thorn;at &thorn;ou were ony o&thorn;er &thorn;ing quod she. <PB N="28">No quod .I. now wot I quod she o&thorn;er cause of &thorn;i maladie and &thorn;at ry&yogh;t grete  &para; &THORN;ou hast left forto knowe &thorn;i self what &thorn;ou art. &thorn;oru&yogh; whiche I haue pleynelyche knowen &thorn;e cause of &thorn;i maladie.  or ellis &thorn;e entre of recoueryng of &thorn;in hele.  &para; Forwhy for &thorn;ou art confounded wi&thorn; for&yogh;etyng of &thorn;i self. for&thorn;i sorwest &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;ou art exiled of &thorn;i propre goodes.  &para; And for &thorn;ou ne wost what is &thorn;e ende of &thorn;inges. for[&thorn;i] demest [&thorn;ou] &thorn;at felonous and wikked men ben my&yogh;ty and weleful for &thorn;ou hast for&yogh;eten by whiche gouernement&yogh; &thorn;e worlde is gouerned.  &para; For&thorn;i wenest &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;ise mutaciouns of fortune fleten wi&thorn; outen gouernour. &thorn;ise ben grete causes not oonly to maladie. but certes grete causes to dee&thorn;  &para; But I &thorn;anke &thorn;e auctour and &thorn;e makere of heele &thorn;at nature ha&thorn; not al forleten &thorn;e. and I haue g[r]ete norissinges of &thorn;i hele. and &thorn;at is &thorn;e so&thorn;e sentence of gouernaunce of &thorn;e worlde. &thorn;at &thorn;ou byleuest &thorn;at &thorn;e gouernynge of it nis nat subgit ne vnderput 
 to &thorn;e folie <MILESTONE N="8b" UNIT="fol.">of &thorn;ise happes auenterouses.  but to &thorn;e resoun of god  &para; And &thorn;er fore doute &thorn;e no&thorn;ing.  For of &thorn;is litel spark &thorn;ine heet of lijf schal shine.  &para; But for as muche as it is not tyme &yogh;itte of fastere remedies &para; And &thorn;e nature of &thorn;ou&yogh;tes disseiued is &thorn;is &thorn;at as ofte as &thorn;ei casten aweye so&thorn;e opyniouns: &thorn;ei clo&thorn;en hem in fals[e] opiniouns. [of whichefalseopyniouns] &thorn;ederknesse of perturbacioun wexe&thorn; vp. &thorn;at comfounde&thorn; &thorn;e verray insy&yogh;t.  and &thorn;at derkenes schal .I. say somwhat to maken &thorn;inne and wayk by ly&yogh;t and meenelyche remedies. so &thorn;at after &thorn;at &thorn;e derknes of desseyuynge desyrynges is don awey.  &thorn;ou mow[e] knowe &thorn;e schynyng of verray ly&yogh;t. </P></DIV2><PB N="29"><DIV2 N="7" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">NUBIBUS ATRIS CONDITA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;E sterres couered wi&thorn; blak[e] cloudes ne mowen geten a doun no ly&yogh;t.  &YOGH;if &thorn;e trouble wynde &thorn;at hy&yogh;t auster stormynge and walwyng &thorn;e see medle&thorn; &thorn;e heete &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;e boylyng vp from &thorn;e botme &para; &THORN;e wawes &thorn;at somtyme weren clere as glas and lyke to &thorn;e fair[e] bry&yogh;t[e] dayes wi&thorn;stant anon &thorn;e sy&yogh;tes of men. by &thorn;e fil&thorn;e and ordure &thorn;at is resolued. and &thorn;e fletyng streme &thorn;at royle&thorn; doun dyuersely fro hey&yogh;e mountaignes is arestid and resisted ofte tyme by &thorn;e encountrynge of a stoon &thorn;at is departid and fallen from some roche.  &para; And for&thorn;i yif &thorn;ou wilt loken and demen so&thorn;e wi&thorn; clere ly&yogh;t. and holde &thorn;e weye wi&thorn; a ry&yogh;t pa&thorn;e.  &para; Weyue &thorn;ou ioie. drif fro &thorn;e drede. fleme &thorn;ou hope. ne lat no sorwe aproche. &thorn;at is to sein lat noon of &thorn;ise four passiouns ouer come &thorn;e. or blynde &thorn;e. for cloudy and dirke is &thorn;ilk &thorn;ou&yogh;t and bounde with bridles. where as &thorn;ise &thorn;inges regnen.</P></DIV2>


<TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="l">EXPLICIT LIBER PRIMUS.</FOREIGN></TRAILER></DIV1><DIV1 N="2" TYPE="book"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">INCIPIT LIBER SECUNDUS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><DIV2 N="1" TYPE="prose">

<HEAD N="1" TYPE="prose"><FOREIGN LANG="l">POSTEA [PAU]LISPER CONTICUIT.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>After &thorn;is she stynte a litel. and after &thorn;at she hadde gadred by atempre stillenesse myn attencioun she seide &thorn;us.  &para; As who so my&yogh;t[e] seye &thorn;us.  After &thorn;ise &thorn;inges she stynt[e] a lytel.  and whanne she aperceiued[e] by atempre stillenesse &thorn;at I was ententif to herkene hire. she bygan to speke in &thorn;is wyse.  &para; Yif <PB N="30">I quod she haue vnderstonden and knowe vtterly &thorn;e causes and &thorn;e habit of &thorn;i maladie. &thorn;ou languissed and art deffeted for talent and desijr of &thorn;i ra&thorn;er fortune. &para;  She &thorn;at ilke fortune only &thorn;at is chaunged as &thorn;ou feinest to &thorn;e ward. ha&thorn; peruerted &thorn;e clerenesse and &thorn;e astat of &thorn;i corage.  &para; I vnderstonde &thorn;e felefolde colour and deceites of &thorn;ilke merueillous monstre fortune. and how she vse&thorn; ful flatryng familarite wi&thorn; hem &thorn;at she enforce&thorn; to bygyle. so longe til &thorn;at she confounde wi&thorn; vnsuffreable sorwe hem &thorn;at she ha&thorn; left in despeir vnpurueyed.  &para; and if &thorn;ou remembrest wel &thorn;e kynde &thorn;e maners and &thorn;e desert of &thorn;ilke fortune. &thorn;ow shalt wel knowe as in hir &thorn;ou neuer ne haddest ne hast ylost any fair &thorn;ing.  But as I trowe I shal not gretly trauaile to don &thorn;e remembren of &thorn;ise &thorn;inges. &para;  For &thorn;ou were wont to hurtlen [and despysen] hir wi&thorn; manly wordes whan she was blaundissinge and presente and pursewedest hir wi&thorn; sentences &thorn;at were drawen oute of myne entre.  &thorn;at is to seyne out of myn informacioun  &para; But no sudeyne mutacioun ne bytide&thorn; nat wi&thorn; outen a maner chaungyng of curages. and so is it byfallen &thorn;at &thorn;ou art departed a litel fro &thorn;e pees of &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t. but now is tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou drynke and atast[e] some softe and delitable &thorn;inges. so &thorn;at whan &thorn;ei ben entred wi&thorn; inne &thorn;e. it mow make weye to strenger drynkes of medycynes.  &para; Com nowe fur&thorn;e &thorn;erfore &thorn;e suasioun of swetnesse Rethoryen. whiche &thorn;at go&thorn; oonly &thorn;e ry&yogh;t wey whil she forsake&thorn; not myne estatut&yogh;.  &para; And wi&thorn; Rethorice com for&thorn;e musice a damoisel of oure house &thorn;at synge&thorn; now ly&yogh;ter moedes <PB N="31">or prolaciouns now heuyer<MILESTONE N="9" UNIT="fol.">what ayle&thorn; &thorn;e man. what  
is it &thorn;at ha&thorn; cast &thorn;e in to murnyng and in to wepyng. I trow[e] &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast sen some newe &thorn;ing and uncou&thorn;e. &para; &THORN;ou wenest &thorn;at fortune be chaunged a&yogh;eins &thorn;e &para;  But &thorn;ou wenest wrong. yif &thorn;ou [&thorn;at] wene. Alwey &thorn;o ben hire maners. she ha&thorn; ra&thorn;er [kept] as to &thorn;e ward hire propre stablenes in &thorn;e chaungyng of hyre self.  &para;  Ry&yogh;t swyche was she whan she flatered[e] &thorn;e. and desseiued[e] &thorn;e wi&thorn; vnleueful lykynges of false welefulnesse. &thorn;ou hast now knowen and ataynt &thorn;e doutous or double visage of &thorn;ilke blynde goddesse fortune.  &para; She &thorn;at &yogh;it couere&thorn; hir and wymple&thorn; hir to o&thorn;er folk. ha&thorn; shewed hir euerydel to &thorn;e.  &para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou approuest hir and &thorn;enkest &thorn;at she is good.  vse hir maners and pleyne &thorn;e nat.  &para; And if &thorn;ou agrisest hir fals[e] trecherie. dispise and cast aweye hir &thorn;at pleye&thorn; so harmefully. for she &thorn;at is now cause of so myche sorwe to &thorn;e. sholde be to &thorn;e cause of pees and [of] ioie.  &para; she ha&thorn; forsaken &thorn;e forso&thorn;e. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at neuer man may be syker &thorn;at she ne shal forsake hym.  <HI REND="i">Glose</HI>. &para;  But na&thorn;eles some bookes han &thorn;e text &thorn;us.  For so&thorn;e she ha&thorn; forsaken &thorn;e ne &thorn;er nis no man syker &thorn;at she ne ha&thorn; not forsaken.  &para;  Holdest &thorn;ou &thorn;an &thorn;ilke welefulnesse preciouse to &thorn;e &thorn;at shal passen. and is present fortune derwor&thorn;i to &thorn;e. whiche &thorn;at nis not fei&thorn;ful forto dwelle. and whan she go&thorn; aweye &thorn;at she brynge&thorn; a wy&yogh;t in sorwe  &para;  For syn she may nat be wi&thorn;holden at a mans wille. she make&thorn; hym a wrecche when she departe&thorn; fro hym.  &para;  What o&thorn;er &thorn;ing is <PB N="32">flitting fortune but a manere shewyng of wrycchednesse &thorn;at is to comen. ne it ne suffri&thorn; nat oo[n]ly to loken of &thorn;ing &thorn;at is present byforne &thorn;e eyen of man. but wisdom loke&thorn; and mesure&thorn; &thorn;e ende of &thorn;inges. and &thorn;e same chaungyng from one to an o&thorn;er. &thorn;at is to seyne fro aduersite to prosperite make&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e manaces of fortune ne ben not forto dreden. ne &thorn;e flatrynges of hir to ben desired.  &para;  &THORN;us atte &thorn;e last it byhoue&thorn; &thorn;e to suffren wi&thorn; euene wille in pacience al &thorn;at is don inwi&thorn; &thorn;e floor of fortune. &thorn;at is to seyne in &thorn;is worlde. &para;  Sy&thorn;en &thorn;ou hast oones put &thorn;i nekke vnder &thorn;e &yogh;okke of hir. for if &thorn;ou wilt write a lawe of wendyng and of dwellyng to fortune whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast chosen frely to be &thorn;i lady  &para;  Art &thorn;ou nat wrongful in &thorn;at and makest fortune wro&thorn;e and aspere by &thorn;in inpacience. and &yogh;it &thorn;ou mayst not chaungen hir.  &para; Yif &thorn;ou committest [and] bitakest &thorn;i sayles to &thorn;e wynde. &thorn;ou shalt be shouen not &thorn;ider &thorn;at &thorn;ou woldest(:) but whider &thorn;at &thorn;e wynde shoue&thorn; &thorn;e  &para;  Yif &thorn;ou castest &thorn;i seedes in &thorn;e feldes &thorn;ou sholdest haue in mynde &thorn;at &thorn;e &yogh;eres ben o&thorn;er while plenteuous and o&thorn;er while bareyne.  &para; &THORN;ou hast bytaken &thorn;iself to &thorn;e gouernaunce of fortune. and for&thorn;i it byhoue&thorn; &thorn;e to ben obeisaunt to &thorn;e manere of &thorn;i lady. and enforcest &thorn;ou &thorn;e to aresten or wi&thorn;stonden &thorn;e swyftnesse and &thorn;e sweyes of hir tournyng whele.  &para;  O &thorn;ou fool of alle mortel fooles if fortune bygan to dwelle stable. she cesed[e] &thorn;an to ben fortune. 
</P></DIV2><PB N="33"><DIV2 N="1" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">HEC CUM SUPERBA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Whan fortune wi&thorn; a proude ry&yogh;t hande ha&thorn; turnid hir chaungyng stoundes she fare&thorn; lyke &thorn;e maners of &thorn;e boillyng eurippe. <HI REND="i">Glose</HI> .  Eurippe is an arme of &thorn;e see &thorn;at ebbith and flowi&thorn;. and somtyme &thorn;e streme is on one syde and somtyme on &thorn;at o&thorn;er.<HI REND="i">Texte</HI>&para; She cruel fortune kaste&thorn; adoune kynges &thorn;at somtyme weren ydred.  and she deceiuable enhaunseth vp &thorn;e humble chere of hym &thorn;at is discomfited. and she ney&thorn;er here&thorn; ne recche&thorn; of wrecched[e] wepynges. and she is so harde &thorn;at she lau&yogh;e&thorn; and scorne&thorn; &thorn;e wepyng of hem &thorn;e whiche she ha&thorn; maked wepe wi&thorn; hir free wille.  &para;  &THORN;us she pleye&thorn; and &thorn;us she preue&thorn; hir streng&thorn;e and shewe&thorn; a grete wondre to alle hir seruaunt&yogh;.  &para;  Yif &thorn;at a wy&yogh;t is seyn weleful and ouer&thorn;rowe in an houre.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="2" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">VELLEM AUTEM PAUCA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>CErtis I wolde plete wi&thorn; &thorn;ee a fewe &thorn;inges vsynge &thorn;e wordes of fortune tak heede now &thorn;i self. yif &thorn;at she axe&thorn; ry&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="fol.">&para;  O &thorn;ou man wher fore makest &thorn;ou  
me gilty by &thorn;ine euerydayes pleynynges. what wronges haue I don &thorn;e. what goodes haue I byreft &thorn;e &thorn;at weren &thorn;ine. stryf or plete wi&thorn; me by fore what iuge &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt of &thorn;e possessioun of rycchesse or of dignites &para; And yif &thorn;ou maist shewe me &thorn;at euer any mortal man ha&thorn; receyued any of &thorn;ese &thorn;inges to ben his in propre. &thorn;an wol I graunt[e] frely &thorn;at [alle] &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges weren &thorn;ine whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ou axest.  &para; Whan &thorn;at nature brou&yogh;t[e] &thorn;e for&thorn;e out of &thorn;i moder wombe.  I receyued[e] &thorn;e naked <PB N="34">and nedy of al &thorn;ing. and I norysshed[e] &thorn;e wi&thorn; my rychesse. and was redy and ententif &thorn;oru&yogh; my fauour to sustene &thorn;e.  &para; And &thorn;at make&thorn; &thorn;e now inpacient a&yogh;eins me. and I envirounde &thorn;e wi&thorn; al &thorn;e habundaunce and shinyng of al goodes &thorn;at ben in my ry&yogh;t.  &para; Now it lyke&thorn; me to wi&thorn; drawe myne hande. &thorn;ou hast had grace as he &thorn;at ha&thorn; vsed of foreyne goodes. &thorn;ou hast no ry&yogh;t to pleyne &thorn;e. as &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou haddest vtterly lorn alle &thorn;i &thorn;inges. whi pleynest &thorn;ou &thorn;an. I haue don &thorn;e no wrong. Ricches honoures and swyche o&thorn;er &thorn;inges ben of my ry&yogh;t.  &para; My seruauntes knowen me for hir lady. &thorn;ei comen wi&thorn; me and departen whan I wende.  I dar wel affermen hardyly. &thorn;at yif &thorn;o &thorn;inges of whiche &thorn;ou pleynest &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast forlorn hadde ben &thorn;ine. &thorn;ou ne haddest not lorn hem.  &para; shal I &thorn;an only be defended to vse my ry&yogh;t.  &para; Certis it is leueful to &thorn;e heuene to make clere dayes. and after &thorn;at to keuere &thorn;e same dayes wi&thorn; derke ny&yogh;tes.  &para; &THORN;e er&thorn;e ha&thorn; eke leue to apparaile &thorn;e visage of &thorn;e er&thorn;e now with floures and now wi&thorn; fruyt. and to confounde hem somtyme wi&thorn; raynes and wi&thorn; coldes.  &para; &THORN;e see ha&thorn; eke hys ry&yogh;t to be somtyme calme and blaundyshing wi&thorn; smo&thorn;e water. and somtyme to be horrible wi&thorn; wawes and wi&thorn; tempestes. &para; But &thorn;e couetyse of men &thorn;at may not be staunched shal it bynde me to be stedfast. syn &thorn;at stedfastnesse is vnkou&thorn; to my maneres.  &para; Swyche is my streng&thorn;e. and &thorn;is pley. I pley[e] continuely. I tourne &thorn;e whirlyng whele wi&thorn; &thorn;e tournyng cercle &para; I am glade to chaunge &thorn;e lowest to &thorn;e heyeste. and &thorn;e heyest to &thorn;e loweste. <PB N="35">wor&thorn;e vp yif &thorn;ou wilt. so it be by &thorn;is lawe. &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne holde not &thorn;at I do &thorn;e wronge &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou descende doun whanne resoun of my pleye axe&thorn; it.  Wost &thorn;ou not how Cresus kyng of lyndens of whiche kyng Cirus was ful sore agast a litel byforne &thorn;at &thorn;is rewlyche Cresus was cau&yogh;t of Cirus and lad to &thorn;e fijr to be brent. but &thorn;at a reyne descended[e] doun from heuene &thorn;at rescowed[e] hym &para; And is it out of &thorn;i mynde how &thorn;at Paulus consul of Rome whan he hadde take &thorn;e kyng of perciens weep pitou[s]ly for &thorn;e captiuitee of &thorn;e self[e] kyng.  What o&thorn;er &thorn;inges bywaylen &thorn;e criinges of Tragedies. but only &thorn;e dedes of fortune. &thorn;at wi&thorn; an vnwar stroke ouerturne&thorn; &thorn;e realmes of grete nobley &para; <HI REND="i">Glose</HI>. Tragedie is to seyne a dite of a prosperite for a tyme &thorn;at endi&thorn; in wrechednesse.  Lernedest nat &thorn;ou in grek whan &thorn;ou were &yogh;onge &thorn;at in &thorn;e entre or in &thorn;e seler of Iuppiter &thorn;er ben couched two tunnes. &thorn;at on is ful of good &thorn;at o&thorn;er is ful of harme.  &para; What ry&yogh;t hast &thorn;ou to pleyne. yif &thorn;ou hast taken more plenteuously of &thorn;e goode syde &thorn;at is to seyne of my rycchesse and prosperites. and what eke. yif I be nat departed fro &thorn;e. What eke. yif my mutabilitee &yogh;iue&thorn; &thorn;e ry&yogh;tful cause of hope to han &yogh;it better &thorn;inges.  &para; Na&thorn;eles desmaie &thorn;e nat in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t. and &thorn;ou &thorn;at art put in comune realme of alle: ne desijr[e] nat to lyue by &thorn;ine oonly propre ry&yogh;t.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="2" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">SI QUANTAS RAPIDIS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;ou&yogh; plentee &thorn;at is goddesse of rycches hielde adoun wi&thorn; ful horn. and wi&thorn;drawe&thorn; nat hir hand.  &para; As many recches as &thorn;e see turne&thorn; vpwardes sandes whan it <PB N="36">is moeued wi&thorn; rauysshing blastes. or ellys as many rycches as &thorn;er shynen bry&yogh;t[e] sterres on heuene on &thorn;e sterry ny&yogh;t. &yogh;it for al &thorn;at mankynde nolde not cesce to wope wrecched[e]  pleyntes.  &para; And al be it so <MILESTONE N="10" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;at god receyue&thorn; gladly her prayers and &yogh;eue&thorn; hem as ful large muche golde and apparaile&thorn; coueytous folk wi&thorn; noble or clere honours. &yogh;it seme&thorn; hem haue I-gete no&thorn;ing but alwey her cruel ravyne deuourynge al &thorn;at &thorn;ei han geten shewi&thorn; o&thorn;er gapinges. &thorn;at is to seye gapen and desiren &yogh;it after moo rycchesse.  &para; What brideles my&yogh;ten wi&thorn;holde to any certeyne ende &thorn;e desordene coueitise of men &para; Whan euere &thorn;e ra&thorn;er &thorn;at it fleti&thorn; in large &yogh;iftis: &thorn;e more ay brenne&thorn; in hem &thorn;e &thorn;rest of hauyng.  &para; Certis he &thorn;at quakyng and dredeful wene&thorn; hym seluen nedy. he ne lyue&thorn; neuere mo ryche.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="3" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">HIIS IGITUR SI PRO SE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;erfore yif &thorn;at fortune spake wi&thorn; &thorn;e for hir self in &thorn;is manere.  For so&thorn;e &thorn;ou ne haddest [nat] what &thorn;ou my&yogh;test answere. and if &thorn;ou hast any &thorn;ing wherwi&thorn;. &thorn;ou mayist ry&yogh;tfully tellen &thorn;i compleynt.  &para; It byhoue&thorn; &thorn;e to shewen it. and .I. wol &yogh;eue &thorn;e space to tellen it.  &para; Certeynely quod I &thorn;an &thorn;ise ben faire &thorn;inges and enoyntid wi&thorn; hony swetnesse of rethorike and musike. and only while &thorn;ei ben herd &thorn;ei ben deliciouse. &para; But to wrecches is a deppere felyng of harme. &thorn;is is to seyn &thorn;at wrecches felen &thorn;e harmes &thorn;at &thorn;ei suffren more greuously &thorn;an &thorn;e remedies or &thorn;e delites of &thorn;ise wordes mowe gladen or comforten hem. so &thorn;at <PB N="37">whan &thorn;ise &thorn;inges stynten forto soun[e] in eres. &thorn;e sorwe &thorn;at is inset greue&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t.  Ry&yogh;t so is it quod she. &para; For &thorn;ise ne ben &yogh;it none remedies of &thorn;i maladie. but &thorn;ei ben a manere norissinges of &thorn;i sorwe &yogh;it rebel a&yogh;eyne &thorn;i curacioun.  &para; For whan &thorn;at tyme is. I shal moue swiche &thorn;inges &thorn;at percen hem self depe.  &para; But na&thorn;eles &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt not wilne to leten &thorn;i self a wrecche.  &para; Hast &thorn;ou for&yogh;eten &thorn;e noumbre and &thorn;e manere of &thorn;i welefulnesse.  I holde me stille how &thorn;at &thorn;e souerayn men of &thorn;e Citee token &thorn;e in cure and kepynge whan &thorn;ou were orphelyn of fadir and modir. and were chosen in affinite of princes of &thorn;e Citee. &para; And &thorn;ou bygunne ra&thorn;er to ben leef and deere &thorn;an forto ben a ney&yogh;bour. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ing is &thorn;e most preciouse kynde of any propinquitee or aliaunce &thorn;at may ben.  &para; Who is it &thorn;at ne seide &thorn;ou nere ry&yogh;t weleful wi&thorn; so grete a nobley of &thorn;i fadres in lawe.  &para; And wi&thorn; &thorn;e chastite of &thorn;i wijf. and wi&thorn; &thorn;e oportunite and noblesse of &thorn;i masculyn children. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;i sones and ouer al &thorn;is me lyst to passe of comune &thorn;inges. &para; How &thorn;ou haddest in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t dignitees &thorn;at weren warned to olde men. but it delite&thorn; me to comen now to &thorn;e singuler vphepyng of &thorn;i welefulnesse.  &para; Yif any fruyt of mortal &thorn;inges may han any wey&yogh;te or price of welefulnesse.  &para; My&yogh;test &thorn;ou euere for&yogh;eten for any charge of harme &thorn;at my&yogh;t[e] byfallen. &thorn;e remembraunce of &thorn;ilke day &thorn;at &thorn;ou sey[e] &thorn;i two sones maked conseillers. and ylad to gidre from &thorn;in house vndir so gret assemble of senatours. and vndir &thorn;e bly&thorn;enesse of poeple. and whan &thorn;ou say[e] hem sette in &thorn;e court in her <PB N="38">chaieres of dignites.  &para; &THORN;ou rethorien or pronouncere of kynges preysinges. deseruedest glorie of wit and of eloquence. whan &thorn;ou sittyng bytwix &thorn;i two sones conseillers in &thorn;e place &thorn;at hy&yogh;t Circo. and fulfildest &thorn;e abydyng of multitude of poeple &thorn;at was sprad about &thorn;e wi&thorn; large praysynge and laude as men syngen in victories. &thorn;o &yogh;aue &thorn;ou wordes of fortune as I trowe. &thorn;at is to seyne. &thorn;o feffedest &thorn;ou fortune wi&thorn; glosynge wordes and desseiuedest hir. whan she accoied[e] &thorn;e and norsshed[e] &thorn;e as hir owen delices.  &para; &THORN;ou hast had of fortune a &yogh;ifte &thorn;at is to seyn swiche gerdoun &thorn;at she neu[er]e &yogh;af to preue man  &para; Wilt &thorn;ou &thorn;erfore leye a rekenyng wi&thorn; fortune. she ha&thorn; now twynkeled first vpon &thorn;e wi&thorn; a wykked eye.  &para; Yif &thorn;ou considere &thorn;e noumbre and &thorn;e manere of &thorn;i blysses. and of &thorn;i 
 sorwes. <MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;ou maist nat forsake &thorn;at &thorn;ou nart &yogh;it blysful. For if &thorn;ou &thorn;erfore wenest &thorn;i self nat weleful for &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;o semeden ioyful ben passed.  &para; &THORN;er nis nat whi &thorn;ou sholdest wene &thorn;i self a wrecche. for &thorn;inges &thorn;at now semen soory passen also.  &para; Art &thorn;ou now comen firste a sodeyne gest in to &thorn;e shadowe or tabernacle of &thorn;is lijf. or trowest &thorn;ou &thorn;at any stedfastnesse be in mannis &thorn;inges.  &para; Whan ofte a swifte houre dissolue&thorn; &thorn;e same man. &thorn;at is to seyne whan &thorn;e soule departi&thorn; fro &thorn;e body.  For al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at yelde is &thorn;er any fei&thorn; &thorn;at fortunous &thorn;inges willen dwelle. &yogh;it na&thorn;eles &thorn;e last[e] day of a mannis lijf is a manere dee&thorn; to fortune. and also to &thorn;ilke &thorn;at ha&thorn; dwelt. and &thorn;erfore what wenist &thorn;ou &thorn;ar recche yif &thorn;ou forlete hir in deynge or ellys &thorn;at she fortune forlete &thorn;e in fleenge awey. <PB N="39"></P></DIV2><DIV2 N="3" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">CUM PRIMO POLO.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Whan phebus &thorn;e sonne bygynne&thorn; to spreden his clerenesse with rosene chariettes. &thorn;an &thorn;e sterre ydimmyd pale&thorn; hir white cheres. by &thorn;e flamus of &thorn;e sonne &thorn;at ouer come&thorn; &thorn;e sterre ly&yogh;t.  &para; &THORN;is is to seyn whan &thorn;e sonne is risen &thorn;e day sterre wexi&thorn; pale and lesi&thorn; hir ly&yogh;t for &thorn;e grete bry&yogh;tnesse of &thorn;e sonne.  &para; Whan &thorn;e wode wexe&thorn; redy of rosene floures in &thorn;e first somer sesoun &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e bre&thorn;e of &thorn;e wynde Zephirus &thorn;at wexe&thorn; warme.  &para; Yif &thorn;e cloudy wynde auster blowe felliche. &thorn;an go&thorn; awey &thorn;e fayrnesse of &thorn;ornes.  Ofte &thorn;e see is clere and calme wi&thorn;oute moeuyng floodes.  And ofte &thorn;e horrible wynde aquilon moeue&thorn; boylyng tempestes and ouer whelwe&thorn; &thorn;e see.  &para; Yif &thorn;e forme of &thorn;is worlde is so [&yogh;eelde] stable. and yif it tourni&thorn; by so many entrechaungynges. wilt &thorn;ou &thorn;an trusten in &thorn;e trublynge fortunes of men. wilt &thorn;ou trowen in flittyng goodes. It is certeyne and establissed by lawe perdurable &thorn;at no &thorn;ing &thorn;at is engendred nys stedfast no stable.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="4" TYPE="prose">  <HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">TUNC EGO UERA INQUAM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;anne seide I &thorn;us.  O norice of alle uertues &thorn;ou seist ful so&thorn;e.  &para; Ne I may nat forsake &thorn;e ry&yogh;t[e] swifte cours of my prosperitee. &thorn;at is to seine. &thorn;at prosperitee ne be comen to me wondir swiftly and soone. but &thorn;is is a &thorn;ing &thorn;at gretly smerti&thorn; me whan it remembre&thorn; me.  &para; For in alle aduersitees of fortune &thorn;e most vnsely kynde of contrariouse fortune is to han ben weleful.  &para; But &thorn;at &thorn;ou quod she abaist &thorn;us &thorn;e tourment of &thorn;i fals[e] opinioun &thorn;at maist &thorn;ou not ry&yogh;tfully <PB N="40">blamen ne aretten to &thorn;inges. as who sei&thorn; for &thorn;ou hast &yogh;itte many habundaunces of &thorn;inges.  &para; <FOREIGN LANG="l">Textus</FOREIGN>. For al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;e ydel name of auenterouse welefulnesse moeue&thorn; &thorn;e now. it is leueful &thorn;at &thorn;ou rekene with me of how many[e] &thorn;inges &thorn;ou hast &yogh;it plentee. &para; And &thorn;erfore yif &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddest for most precious in alle &thorn;i rycchesse of fortune be kept to &thorn;e by &thorn;e grace of god vnwemmed and vndefouled. Mayst &thorn;ou &thorn;an pleyne ry&yogh;tfully vpon &thorn;e myschief of fortune. syn &thorn;ou hast &yogh;it &thorn;i best[e] &thorn;inges.  &para; Certys &yogh;it lyue&thorn; in goode poynt &thorn;ilke precious honour of mankynde. &para; Symacus &thorn;i wyues fadir whiche &thorn;at is a man maked al of sapience and of vertue. &thorn;e whiche man &thorn;ou woldest b[i]en redely wi&thorn; &thorn;e pris of &thorn;in owen lijf. he byweyle&thorn; &thorn;e wronges &thorn;at men don to &thorn;ee. and not for hym self. for he liue&thorn; in sykernesse of any sentence put a&yogh;eins hym.  &para; And &yogh;it lyue&thorn; &thorn;i wif &thorn;at is attempre of witte and passyng o&thorn;er women in clennes of chastitee. and for I wol closen shortly her bountes she is lyke to hir fadir.  I telle &thorn;e welle &thorn;at she lyue&thorn; loo&thorn; of hir life. and kepi&thorn; to &thorn;ee oonly hir goost. and is al maat and ouer-comen by wepyng and sorwe for desire of &thorn;e  &para; In &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ing only I mot graunten &thorn;at &thorn;i welefulnesse is amenused.  &para; What shal I seyn eke of &thorn;i two sones conseillours of whiche as of children 
 of hir age &thorn;er shine&thorn;<MILESTONE N="11" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;e lyknesse of &thorn;e witte of hir fadir and of hir eldefadir. and si&thorn;en &thorn;e souereyn cure of alle mortel folke is to sauen hir owen lyues. &para; O how weleful art &thorn;ou &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou knowe &thorn;i goodes. <PB N="41">&para; But &yogh;itte ben &thorn;er &thorn;inges dwellyng to &thorn;e wardes &thorn;at no man doute&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne ben more derwor&thorn;e to &thorn;e &thorn;en &thorn;ine owen lijf.  &para; And for&thorn;i drie &thorn;i teres for &yogh;itte nys nat eueriche fortune al hateful to &thorn;e warde. ne ouer greet tempest ha&thorn; nat &yogh;it fallen vpon &thorn;e. whan &thorn;at &thorn;in ancres cliue fast[e] &thorn;at nei&thorn;er wole suffre &thorn;e comfort of &thorn;is tyme present. ne &thorn;e hope of tyme comynge to passen ne to fallen.  &para; And I preie quod I &thorn;at fast[e] mot[en] &thorn;ei holden.  &para; For whiles &thorn;at &thorn;ei halden. how so euere &thorn;at &thorn;inges ben. I shal wel fleten fur&thorn;e and eschapen. &para; But &thorn;ou mayst wel seen how greet[e] apparailes and aray &thorn;at me lakke&thorn; &thorn;at ben passed awey fro me.  &para; I haue sumwhat auauneed and for&thorn;ered &thorn;e quod she. if &thorn;at &thorn;ou anoie nat or for&thorn;enke nat of al &thorn;i fortune.  As who sei&thorn;.  &para; I haue somwhat comforted &thorn;e so &thorn;at &thorn;ou tempest nat &thorn;e &thorn;us wi&thorn; al &thorn;i fortune. syn &thorn;ou hast &yogh;it &thorn;i best[e] &thorn;inges.  &para; But I may nat suffre &thorn;in delices. &thorn;at pleinst so wepyng. and anguissous for &thorn;at o&thorn;er lakke&thorn; somwhat to &thorn;i welefulnesse.  &para; For what man is so sad or of so perfit welefulnesse. &thorn;at he ne stryue&thorn; or pleyne&thorn; on some half a&yogh;eine &thorn;e qualitee of his estat.  &para; For whi ful anguissous &thorn;ing is &thorn;e condicioun of mans goodes.  &para; For ey&thorn;er it come&thorn; al to gidre to a wy&yogh;t. or ellys it laste&thorn; not perpetuely. &para; For som man ha&thorn; grete rycchesse. but he is asshamed of hys vngentil lynage. and som man is renomed of noblesse of kynrede. but he is enclosed in so grete angre for nede of &thorn;inges. &thorn;at hym were leuer &thorn;at he were vnknowe. and som man habunde&thorn; bo&thorn;e in rychesse and noblesse. but &yogh;it he bywaile&thorn; hys chast[e] <PB N="42">lijf. for he ha&thorn; no wijf.  &para; and som man is wel and selily maried but he ha&thorn; no children. and norisshe&thorn; his ricchesse to &thorn;e heires of straunge folk.  &para; And som man is gladded wi&thorn; children. but he wepi&thorn; ful sory for &thorn;e trespas of his son or of his dou&yogh;tir.  &para; and for &thorn;is &thorn;er accorde&thorn; no wy&yogh;t ly&yogh;tly to &thorn;e condicioun of his fortune. for alwey to euery man &thorn;ere is in mest somwhat &thorn;at vnassaie&thorn; he ne wot not or ellys he dredi&thorn; &thorn;at he ha&thorn; assaied.  &para; And adde &thorn;is also &thorn;at euery weleful man ha&thorn; a wel delicat felyng.  &para; So &thorn;at but yif alle &thorn;inges fallen at hys owen wille for he inpacient or is nat vsed to han none aduersitee. an-oone he is &thorn;rowe ado&umacr;ne for euery lytel &thorn;ing.  &para; And ful lytel &thorn;inges ben &thorn;o &thorn;at wi&thorn;drawen &thorn;e somme or &thorn;e perfeccioun of blisfulnesse fro hem &thorn;at ben most fortunat.  &para; How many men trowest &thorn;ou wolde demen hem self to ben almost in heuene yif &thorn;ei my&yogh;ten atteyne to &thorn;e leest[e] partie of &thorn;e remenaunt of &thorn;i fortune.  &para; &THORN;is same place &thorn;at &thorn;ou clepist exil is contre to hem &thorn;at enhabiten here. and for&thorn;i.  No&thorn;ing wrecched. but whan &thorn;ou wenest it  &para; As who sei&thorn;. &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;i self ne no wy&yogh;t ellys nys no wrecche but whan he wene&thorn; hym self a wrecche by reputacioun of his corage.</P></DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">CONTRAQUE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>And a&yogh;einewarde al fortune is blisful to a man by &thorn;e agreablete or by &thorn;e egalite of hym &thorn;at suffre&thorn; it. &para; What man is &thorn;at. &thorn;at is so weleful &thorn;at nolde chaungen his estat whan he ha&thorn; lorn pacience. &thorn;e swetnesse of mannes welefulnesse is yspranid wi&thorn; many[e] bitternesses. <PB N="43">&thorn;e whiche welefulnesse al &thorn;ou&yogh; it seme swete and ioyeful to hym &thorn;at vse&thorn; it. &yogh;it may it not be wi&thorn;-holden &thorn;at it ne go&thorn; away whan it wol.  &para; &THORN;an is it wel sen how wrecched is &thorn;e blisfulnesse of mortel &thorn;inges. &thorn;at nei&thorn;er it dwelli&thorn; perpetuel wi&thorn; hem &thorn;at euery fortune receyuen agreablely or egaly.  &para; Ne it ne delite&thorn; not in al. to hem &thorn;at ben anguissous.  &para; O ye mortel folkes what seke<MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="fol.">&yogh;e &thorn;an blisfulnesse oute of &yogh;oure self. whiche  
&thorn;at is put in &yogh;oure self.  Errour and folie confounde&thorn; &yogh;ow  &para; I shal shewe &thorn;e shortly. &thorn;e poynt of souereyne blisfulnesse.  Is &thorn;er any &thorn;ing to &thorn;e more preciouse &thorn;an &thorn;i self  &para; &THORN;ou wilt answere nay.  &para; &THORN;an if it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou art my&yogh;ty ouer &thorn;i self &thorn;at is to seyn by tranquillitee of &thorn;i soule. &thorn;an hast &thorn;ou &thorn;ing in &thorn;i power &thorn;at &thorn;ou noldest neuer lesen. ne fortune may nat by-nyme it &thorn;e. and &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst knowe &thorn;at blisfulnesse [ne] may nat standen in &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben fortunous and temperel. &para; Now vndirstonde and gadir it to gidir &thorn;us yif blisfulnesse be &thorn;e souereyne goode of nature &thorn;at liue&thorn; by resoun  &para; Ne &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing nis nat souereyne goode &thorn;at may be taken awey in any wyse. for more wor&thorn;i &thorn;ing and more digne is &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at may nat be taken awey.  &para; &THORN;an shewi&thorn; it wele &thorn;at &thorn;e vnstablenesse of fortune may nat attayne to receyue verray blisfulnes.  &para; And &yogh;it more ouer.  &para; What man &thorn;at &thorn;is toumblyng welefulnesse leedi&thorn;. ei&thorn;er he woot &thorn;at [it] is chaungeable. or ellis he woot it nat.  &para; And yif he woot it not. what blisful fortune may &thorn;er be in &thorn;e blyndenesse of ignoraunce. and yif he woot &thorn;at it is chaungeable. he mot alwey ben adrad &thorn;at he ne lese &thorn;at &thorn;ing. &thorn;at he ne doute&thorn; nat but &thorn;at he may leesen <PB N="44">it.  &para; As whoo sei&thorn; he mot ben alwey agast lest he leese &thorn;at he wot wel he may leese.  &para; For whiche &thorn;e continuel drede &thorn;at he ha&thorn; ne suffri&thorn; hym nat to ben weleful.  &para; Or ellys yif he leese it he wene to be dispised and forleten hit.  &para; Certis eke &thorn;at is a ful lytel goode &thorn;at is born wi&thorn; euene hert[e] whan it is loost.  &para; &THORN;at is to seyne &thorn;at men don no more force. of &thorn;e lost &thorn;an of &thorn;e hauynge.  &para; And for as myche as &thorn;ou &thorn;i self art he to whom it ha&thorn; ben shewid and proued by ful many[e] demonstraciouns. as I woot wel &thorn;at &thorn;e soules of men ne mowen nat dien in no wise. and eke syn it is clere. and certeyne &thorn;at fortunous welefulnesse endi&thorn; by &thorn;e dee&thorn; of &thorn;e body.  &para; It may nat ben douted &thorn;at yif &thorn;at dee&thorn; may take awey blysfulnesse &thorn;at al &thorn;e kynde of mortal &thorn;ingus ne descendi&thorn; in to wrecchednesse by &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e dee&thorn;.  &para; And syn we knowen wel &thorn;at many a man ha&thorn; sou&yogh;t &thorn;e fruit of blisfulnesse nat only wi&thorn; suffryng of dee&thorn;. but eke wi&thorn; suffryng of peynes and tourmentes. how my&yogh;t[e] &thorn;an &thorn;is present lijf make men blisful. syn &thorn;at whanne &thorn;ilke self[e] lijf is endid. it ne make&thorn; folk no wrecches.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="4" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUISQUIS UOLET</FOREIGN><NOTE>MS. <FOREIGN LANG="l">ualet.</FOREIGN></NOTE><FOREIGN LANG="l"> PERHENNEM CAUTUS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>What maner man stable and war &thorn;at wil founden hym a perdurable sete and ne wil not be cast doune wi&thorn; &thorn;e loude blastes of &thorn;e wynde Eurus. and wil dispise &thorn;e see manassynge wi&thorn; floodes  &para; Lat hym eschewe to bilde on &thorn;e cop of &thorn;e mountayngne. or in &thorn;e moyste sandes.  &para; For &thorn;e fel[le] wynde auster tourmente&thorn; &thorn;e cop of &thorn;e mountayngne wi&thorn; alle his streng&thorn;es.  &para; and &thorn;e <PB N="45">lowe see sandes refuse to beren &thorn;e heuy wey&yogh;te. and for&thorn;i yif &thorn;ou wolt flee &thorn;e perilous auenture &thorn;at is to seine of &thorn;e worlde  &para; Haue mynde certeynly to ficchyn &thorn;i house of a myrie site in a lowe stoone.  &para; For al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e wynde troublyng &thorn;e see &thorn;ondre wi&thorn; ouere&thorn;rowynges &para; &THORN;ou &thorn;at art put in quiete and welful by streng&thorn;e of &thorn;i palys shalt leden a cleer age. scornyng &thorn;e wodenesses and &thorn;e Ires of &thorn;e eir.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="5" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">SET CUM RACIONUM IAM IN TE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>But for as moche as &thorn;e noryssinges of my resouns descenden now in to &thorn;e. I trowe it were tyme to vsen a litel strenger medicynes.  &para; Now vndirstonde here al were it so &thorn;at &thorn;e &yogh;iftis of fortune nar[e] nat brutel ne transitorie. what is &thorn;er in hem &thorn;at may be &thorn;ine<MILESTONE N="12" UNIT="fol.">in any tyme. or ellis &thorn;at it nys foule if &thorn;at it be  
considered and lokid perfitely.  &para; Richesse ben &thorn;ei preciouse by &thorn;e nature of hem self. or ellys by &thorn;e nature of &thorn;e.  What is most wor&thorn;i of rycchesse. is it nat golde or my&yogh;t of moneye assembled.  &para; Certis &thorn;ilke golde and &thorn;ilke moneye shine&thorn; and &yogh;eue&thorn; better renoun to hem &thorn;at dispenden it. &thorn;en to &thorn;ilke folke &thorn;at mokeren it.  For auarice make&thorn; alwey mokeres to be hated. and largesse make&thorn; folke clere of renoun &para; For syn &thorn;at swiche &thorn;ing as is transfered from o man to an o&thorn;er ne may nat dwellen wi&thorn; no man. Certis &thorn;an is &thorn;ilke moneye precious. whan it is translated in to o&thorn;er folk. and stynte&thorn; to ben had by vsage of large &yogh;euyng of hym &thorn;at ha&thorn; &yogh;euen it. and also yif al &thorn;e moneye &thorn;at is ouer-al in &thorn;e world were <PB N="46">gadered towar[d] o man. it sholde maken al o&thorn;er men to ben nedy as of &thorn;at.  &para; And certys a voys al hool &thorn;at is to seyn wi&thorn;-oute amenusynge fulfille&thorn; to gyder &thorn;e heryng of myche folke. but Certys &yogh;oure rycchesse ne mowen nat passen vnto myche folk wi&thorn;-oute amenussyng &para; And whan &thorn;ei ben apassed. nedys &thorn;ei maken hem pore &thorn;at forgon &thorn;e rycchesses.  &para; O streite and nedy clepe I &thorn;ise rycchesses. syn &thorn;at many folke [ne] may nat han it al. ne al may it nat comen to on man wi&thorn;-oute pouerte of al o&thorn;er folke.  &para; And &thorn;e shynynge of gemmes &thorn;at I clepe preciouse stones. drawe&thorn; it nat &thorn;e eyen of folk in to hem warde. &thorn;at is to seyne for &thorn;e beaute.  &para; For certys yif &thorn;er were beaute or bounte in shynyng of stones. &thorn;ilke clerenesse is of &thorn;e stones hem self. and nat of men.  &para; For whiche I wondre gretly &thorn;at men merueilen on swiche &thorn;inges.  &para; For whi what &thorn;ing is it &thorn;at yif it wante&thorn; moeuyng and ioynture of soule and body &thorn;at by ry&yogh;t my&yogh;t[e] semen a faire creature to hym &thorn;at ha&thorn; a soule of resoun. &para; For al be it so &thorn;at gemmes drawen to hem self a litel of &thorn;e laste beaute of &thorn;e worlde. &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e entent of hir creatour and &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e distinccioun of hem self. &yogh;it for as myche as &thorn;ei ben put vndir &yogh;oure excellence. &thorn;ei han not desserued by no weye &thorn;at &yogh;e shullen merueylen on hem.  &para; And &thorn;e beaute of feeldes delite&thorn; it nat mychel vnto &yogh;ow. <HI REND="i">Boyce</HI> . &para; Whi sholde it nat deliten vs. syn &thorn;at it is a ry&yogh;t fayr porcioun of &thorn;e ry&yogh;t fair werk. &thorn;at is to seyn of &thorn;is worlde.  &para; And ry&yogh;t so ben we gladed somtyme of &thorn;e face of &thorn;e see whan it is clere.  And also merueylen we on &thorn;e heuene and <PB N="47">on &thorn;e sterres. and on &thorn;e sonne. and on &thorn;e mone. <HI REND="i">Philosophie.</HI>  &para; Apperteine&thorn; quod she any of &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges to &thorn;e. whi darst &thorn;ou glorifie &thorn;e in &thorn;e shynynge of any swiche &thorn;inges.  Art &thorn;ou distingwed and embelised by &thorn;e spryngyng floures of &thorn;e first somer sesoun. or swelli&thorn; &thorn;i plente in fruytes of somer. whi art &thorn;ou rauyshed wi&thorn; ydel ioies. why enbracest &thorn;ou straunge goodes as &thorn;ei weren &thorn;ine.  Fortune shal neuer maken &thorn;at swiche &thorn;inges ben &thorn;ine &thorn;at nature of &thorn;inges maked foreyne fro &thorn;e.  &para; Syche is &thorn;at wi&thorn;-outen doute &thorn;e fruytes of &thorn;e er&thorn;e owen to ben on &thorn;e norssinge of bestes.  &para; And if &thorn;ou wilt fulfille &thorn;i nede after &thorn;at it suffise&thorn; to nature &thorn;an is it no nede &thorn;at &thorn;ou seke after &thorn;e superfluite of fortune.  &para; For wi&thorn; ful fewe &thorn;inges and with ful lytel &thorn;ing nature halt hire appaied. and yif &thorn;ou wilt achoken &thorn;e fulfillyng of nature wi&thorn; superfluites  &para; Certys &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt &thorn;resten or pouren in to nature shullen ben vnicyeful to &thorn;e or ellis anoies.  &para; Wenest &thorn;ou eke &thorn;at it be a fair &thorn;inge to shine wi&thorn; dyuerse clo&thorn;ing. of whiche clo&thorn;ing yif &thorn;e beaute be agreable to loken vpon. I wol merueylen on &thorn;e nature of &thorn;e matere of &thorn;ilke clo&thorn;es. or ellys on &thorn;e werkeman &thorn;at wrou&yogh;t[e] hem. but al so a longe route of meyne. maki&thorn; &thorn;at a blisful <MILESTONE N="12" UNIT="fol.">man. &thorn;e whiche seruauntes yif &thorn;ei ben  
vicio&umacr;s of condiciouns it is a greet charge and a destruccioun to &thorn;e house. and a greet enmye to &thorn;e lorde hym self  &para; And yif &thorn;ei ben goode men how shal straung[e] or foreyne goodenes ben put in &thorn;e noumbre of &thorn;i rycchesse. so &thorn;at by alle &thorn;ise forseide &thorn;inges. it is clerly shewed &thorn;at neuer none of &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ou accoumptedest for &thorn;in goodes nas nat &thorn;i goode.  &para; In &thorn;e whiche &thorn;inges yif &thorn;er be no beaute to ben desired. <PB N="48">whi sholdest &thorn;ou be sory yif &thorn;ou leese hem. or whi sholdest &thorn;ou reioysen &thorn;e to holden hem.  &para; For if &thorn;ei ben fair of hire owen kynde. what appertene&thorn; &thorn;at to &thorn;e. for as wel sholde &thorn;ei han ben faire by hem self. &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei weren departid from alle &thorn;in rycchesse. &para; For-why faire ne precio&umacr;s ne weren &thorn;ei nat. for &thorn;at &thorn;ei comen amonges &thorn;i rycchesse. but for &thorn;ei semeden fair and precious. &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou haddest leuer rekene hem amonges &thorn;i rycchesse. but what desirest &thorn;ou of fortune wi&thorn; so greet a noyse and wi&thorn; so greet a fare  &para; I trowe &thorn;ou seke to dryue awey nede wi&thorn; habundaunce of &thorn;inges.  &para; But certys it turne&thorn; to &yogh;ow al in &thorn;e contrarie. for whi certys it nedi&thorn; of ful many[e] helpynges to kepen &thorn;e dyuersite of preciouse ostelment&yogh;. and so&thorn;e it is &thorn;at of many[e] &thorn;inges han &thorn;ei nede &thorn;at many[e] &thorn;inges han. and a&yogh;eyneward of litel nedi&thorn; hem &thorn;at mesuren hir fille after &thorn;e nede of kynde and nat after &thorn;e outrage of couetyse  &para; Is it &thorn;an so &thorn;at ye men ne han no propre goode. I-set in &yogh;ow.  For whiche &yogh;e moten seken outwardes &yogh;oure goodes in foreine and subgit &thorn;inges.  &para; So is &thorn;an &thorn;e condicioun of &thorn;inges turned vpso doun. &thorn;at a man &thorn;at is a devyne beest by merit of hys resoun. &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;at hym self nys ney&thorn;er fair ne noble. but if it be &thorn;oru&yogh; possessioun of ostelmentes. &thorn;at ne han no soules. &para; And certys al o&thorn;er &thorn;inges ben appaied of hire owen beautes. but &yogh;e men &thorn;at ben semblable to god by &yogh;oure resonable &thorn;ou&yogh;t desiren to apparaille &yogh;oure excellent kynde of &thorn;e lowest[e] &thorn;inges. ne &yogh;e ne vndirstonde nat how gret a wrong &yogh;e don to &yogh;oure creatour. for he wolde &thorn;at man kynde were moost wor&thorn;i and noble of <PB N="49">any o&thorn;er er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges. and &yogh;e &thorn;resten adoun &yogh;oure dignitees by-ne&thorn;en &thorn;e lowest[e] &thorn;inges.  &para; For if &thorn;at al &thorn;e good of euery &thorn;ing be more preciouse &thorn;an is &thorn;ilk &thorn;ing whos &thorn;at &thorn;e good is. syn &yogh;e demen &thorn;at &thorn;e foulest[e] &thorn;inges ben &yogh;oure goodes. &thorn;anne summytten &yogh;e and putten &yogh;oure self vndir &thorn;o foulest[e] &thorn;inges by &yogh;oure estimacioun.  &para; And certis &thorn;is bitidi&thorn; nat wi&thorn; out &yogh;oure desert.  For certys swiche is &thorn;e condicioun of al man kynde &thorn;at oonly whan it ha&thorn; knowyng of it self. &thorn;an passe&thorn; it in noblesse alle o&thorn;er &thorn;inges. and whan it forleti&thorn; &thorn;e knowyng of it self. &thorn;an it is brou&yogh;t byne&thorn;en alle beestes.  &para; For-why alle o&thorn;er [leuynge] beestes han of kynde to knowe not hem self. but whan &thorn;at men leten &thorn;e knowyng of hem self. it come&thorn; hem of vice. but how brode shewe&thorn; &thorn;e errour and &thorn;e folie of &yogh;ow men &thorn;at wenen &thorn;at ony &thorn;ing may ben apparailled wi&thorn; straunge apparaillement&yogh;  &para; but for-so&thorn;e &thorn;at may nat be don. for yif a wy&yogh;t shyne&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben put to hym. as &thorn;us. yif &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges shynen wi&thorn; whiche a man is apparailled.  &para; Certis &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges ben commendid and preised wi&thorn; whiche he is apparailled.  &para; But na&thorn;eles &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at is couered and wrapped vndir &thorn;at dwelle&thorn; in his fil&thorn;e. and I denye &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing be good &thorn;at anoye&thorn; hym &thorn;at ha&thorn; it.  &para; Gabbe I of &thorn;is. &thorn;ou wolt seye nay. &para; Certys rycchesse han anoyed ful ofte hem &thorn;at han &thorn;e rycchesse.  &para; Syn &thorn;at euery wicked shrew and for hys wickednesse &thorn;e more gredy aftir o&thorn;er folkes rycchesse wher so euer it be in any place. be it golde or <PB N="50">
 precious stones. and weni&thorn; hym <MILESTONE N="13" UNIT="fol.">only most wor&thorn;i &thorn;at ha&thorn; hem  &para; &thorn;ou &thorn;an &thorn;at so besy dredest now &thorn;e swerde and &thorn;e spere. yif &thorn;ou haddest entred in &thorn;e pa&thorn;e of &thorn;is lijf a voide wayfaryng man. &thorn;an woldest &thorn;ou syng[e] by-fore &thorn;e &thorn;eef.  &para; As who sei&thorn; a poure man &thorn;at bere&thorn; no rycchesse on hym by &thorn;e weye. may boldly syng[e] byforne &thorn;eues. for he ha&thorn; nat wher-of to ben robbed. &para; O preciouse and ry&yogh;t clere is &thorn;e blysfulnesse of mortal rycchesse. &thorn;at whan &thorn;ou hast geten it. &thorn;an hast &thorn;ou lorn &thorn;i syke[r]nesse.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="5" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">FELIX IN MIRUM PRIOR ETAS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Blysful was &thorn;e first age of men. &thorn;ei helden hem apaied wi&thorn; &thorn;e metes &thorn;at &thorn;e trewe er&thorn;es brou&yogh;ten fur&thorn;e.  &para; &thorn;ei ne destroyed[e] ne desceyued[e] not hem self wi&thorn; outerage.  &para; &thorn;ei weren wont ly&yogh;tly to slaken her hunger at euene wi&thorn; acornes of okes  &para; &thorn;ei ne cou&thorn;e nat medle &thorn;e &yogh;ift of bacus to &thorn;e clere hony. &thorn;at is to seyn. &thorn;ei cou&thorn;e make no piment of clarre. ne &thorn;ei cou&thorn;e nat medle &thorn;e bri&yogh;t[e] flies of &thorn;e contre of siriens wi&thorn; &thorn;e venym of tirie. &thorn;is is to seyne. &thorn;ei cou&thorn;e nat dien white flies of sirien contre wi&thorn; &thorn;e blode of a manar shelfysshe. &thorn;at men fynden in tyrie. wi&thorn; whiche blode men deien purper.  &para; &thorn;ei slepen holesom slepes vpon &thorn;e gras. and dronken of &thorn;e rynnyng watres. and laien vndir &thorn;e shadowe of &thorn;e hey&yogh;e pyne trees.  &para; Ne no gest ne no straunger [ne] karf &yogh;it &thorn;e heye see wi&thorn; oores or wi&thorn; shippes. ne &thorn;ei ne <PB N="51">hadden seyne &yogh;itte none newe strondes to leden merchaundyse in to dyuerse contres.  &para; &thorn;o weren &thorn;e cruel clariouns ful whist and ful stille. ne blode yshed by egre hate ne hadde nat deied &yogh;it armurers. for wherto or whiche woodenesse of enmys wolde first moeuen armes. whan &thorn;ei seien cruel woundes ne none medes ben of blood yshad  &para; I wolde &thorn;at oure tymes sholde turne a&yogh;eyne to &thorn;e oolde maneres.  &para; But &thorn;e anguissous loue of hauyng brenne&thorn; in folke moore cruely &thorn;an &thorn;e fijr of &thorn;e Mountaigne of Ethna &thorn;at euer brenne&thorn;. &para; Allas what was he &thorn;at first dalf vp &thorn;e gobets or &thorn;e wey&yogh;tys of gold couered vndir er&thorn;e. and &thorn;e precious stones &thorn;at wolden han ben hid. he dalf vp precious perils. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;at he &thorn;at hem first vp dalf. he dalf vp a precious peril. for-whi. for &thorn;e preciousnesse of swyche ha&thorn; many man ben in peril.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="6" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUID AUTEM DE DIGNITATIBUS ET CETERA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>But what shal I seyne of dignitees and of powers. &thorn;e whiche [ye] men &thorn;at nei&thorn;er knowen verray dignitee ne verray power areysen hem as heye as &thorn;e heuene. &thorn;e whiche dignitees and powers yif &thorn;ei come to any wicked man &thorn;ei don [as] greet[e] damages and distruccioun as do&thorn; &thorn;e flamme of &thorn;e Mountaigne Ethna whan &thorn;e flamme wit walwi&thorn; vp ne no deluge ne do&thorn; so cruel harmes.  &para; Certys ye remembri&thorn; wel as I trowe &thorn;at &thorn;ilke dignitee &thorn;at men clepi&thorn; &thorn;e emperie of consulers &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at somtyme was bygynnyng of fredom.  &para; &YOGH;oure eldres coueiteden to han don a-wey &thorn;at dignitee for &thorn;e pride of &thorn;e conseilers. <PB N="52">&para; And ry&yogh;t for &thorn;e same pride &yogh;oure eldres byforne &thorn;at tyme hadden don awey out of &thorn;e Citee of rome &thorn;e kynges name. &thorn;at is to seien. &thorn;ei nolden haue no lenger no kyng  &para; But now yif so be &thorn;at dignitees and powers ben &yogh;euen to goode men. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ing is ful &yogh;elde. what agreable &thorn;inges is &thorn;er in &thorn;o dignitees. or powers. but only &thorn;e goodenes of folk &thorn;at vsen hem. &para; And &thorn;erfore it is &thorn;us &thorn;at honour ne come&thorn; nat to vertue for cause of dignite. but a&yogh;einward. honour come&thorn; to dignite by cause of vertue. but whiche is &yogh;oure derwor&thorn;e power &thorn;at is so clere and so requerable &para; O &yogh;e er&thorn;elyche bestes considere &yogh;e nat ouer whiche &thorn;ing &thorn;at it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;e han power.  &para; Now yif &thorn;ou say[e] a mouse amongus<MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="fol.">o&thorn;er myse &thorn;at chalenged[e]  to hymself ward ry&yogh;t and power ouer alle o&thorn;er myse. how gret scorne woldest &thorn;ou han of hit.  &para; <FOREIGN LANG="l">Glosa.</FOREIGN>  &para; So fare&thorn; it by men. &thorn;e body ha&thorn; power ouer &thorn;e body. For yif &thorn;ow loke wel vpon &thorn;e body of a wy&yogh;t what &thorn;ing shalt &thorn;ou fynde moore frele &thorn;an is mannes kynde. &thorn;e whiche ben ful ofte slayn wi&thorn; bytynge of smale flies. or ellys wi&thorn; &thorn;e entryng of crepyng wormes in to &thorn;e priuetees of mennes bodyes.  &para; But wher shal men fynden any man &thorn;at may exercen or haunten any ry&yogh;t vpon an o&thorn;er man but oonly vpon hys body. or ellys vpon &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben lower &thorn;en &thorn;e body. whiche I clepe fortunous possessiouns  &para; Mayst &thorn;ou euer haue any comaundement ouer a fre corage  &para; Mayst &thorn;ou remuen fro &thorn;e estat of hys propre reste. a &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at is cleuyng to gider in hym self by stedfast resoun.  &para; As somtyme a tiraunt wende to confounde a freeman of <PB N="53">corage  &para; And wende to constreyne hym by tourment to maken hym dyscoueren and acusen folk &thorn;at wisten of a coniuracioun. whiche I clepe a confederacie &thorn;at was cast a&yogh;eins &thorn;is tyraunt  &para; But &thorn;is free man boot of hys owen tunge. and cast it in &thorn;e visage of &thorn;ilke woode tyraunte.  &para; So &thorn;at &thorn;e tourment&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;is tyraunt wende to han maked matere of cruelte. &thorn;is wyse man maked[e it] matere of vertues.  &para; But what &thorn;ing is it &thorn;at a man may don to an o&thorn;er man. &thorn;at he ne may receyue &thorn;e same &thorn;ing of o&thorn;er folke in hym self. or &thorn;us.  &para; What may a man don to folk. &thorn;at folk ne may don hym &thorn;e same.  &para; I haue herd told of busirides &thorn;at was wont to sleen hys gestes &thorn;at herburghden in hys hous. and he was slayn hym self of ercules &thorn;at was hys gest  &para; Regulus had[de] taken in bataile many men of affrike. and cast hem in to fetteres. but sone after he most[e] &yogh;iue hys handes to ben bounden with &thorn;e cheynes of hem &thorn;at he had[de] somtyme ouercomen.  &para; Wenest &thorn;ou &thorn;an &thorn;at he be my&yogh;ty. &thorn;at may nat don a &thorn;ing. &thorn;at o&thorn;er ne may don hym. &thorn;at he do&thorn; to o&thorn;er. and &yogh;it more ouer yif it so were &thorn;at &thorn;ise dignites or poweres hadden any propre or naturel goodnesse in hem self neuer nolden &thorn;ei comen to shrewes.  &para; For contrarious &thorn;inges ne ben not wont to ben yfelawshiped togidres.  &para; Nature refuse&thorn; &thorn;at contra[r]ious &thorn;inges ben yioigned.  &para; And so as I am in certeyne &thorn;at ry&yogh;t wikked folk han dignitees ofte tymes. &thorn;an shewe&thorn; it wel &thorn;at dignitees and powers ne ben not goode of hir owen kynde. syn &thorn;at &thorn;ei suffren hem self to cleuen or ioynen hem to shrewes. &para; And certys &thorn;e same &thorn;ing may most digneliche Iugen <PB N="54">and seyen of alle &thorn;e &yogh;iftis of fortune &thorn;at most plenteuously comen to shrewes.  &para; Of &thorn;e whiche &yogh;iftys I trowe &thorn;at it au&yogh;t[e] ben considered &thorn;at no man douti&thorn; &thorn;at he nis strong. in whom he see&thorn; streng&thorn;e. and in whom &thorn;at swiftnesse is  &para; So&thorn;e it is &thorn;at he is swyfte. Also musyk make&thorn; musiciens. and fysik make&thorn; phisiciens. and rethorik rethoriens.  &para; For whi &thorn;e nature of euery &thorn;ing maki&thorn; his propretee. ne it is nat entermedled wi&thorn; &thorn;e effectis of contrarious &thorn;inges. &para; And as of wil it chase&thorn; oute &thorn;inges &thorn;at to it ben contrarie  &para; But certys rycchesse may nat restreyne auarice vnstaunched  &para; Ne power [ne] make&thorn; nat a man my&yogh;ty ouer hym self. whiche &thorn;at vicious lustis holden destreined wi&thorn; cheins &thorn;at ne mowen nat ben vnbounden. and dignitees &thorn;at ben &yogh;euen to shrewed[e] folk nat oonly ne maki&thorn; hem nat digne. but it shewe&thorn; ra&thorn;er al openly &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben vnwor&thorn;i and vndigne. &para; And whi is it &thorn;us.  &para; Certis for &yogh;e han ioye to clepen &thorn;inges wi&thorn; fals[e] names. &thorn;at beren hem al in &thorn;e contrarie. &thorn;e whiche names ben ful ofte reproued 
 by &thorn;e effect of &thorn;e same &thorn;inges. so &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="14" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;ise ilke rycchesse ne au&yogh;ten nat by ry&yogh;t to ben cleped rycchesse. ne whiche power ne au&yogh;t[e] not ben cleped power. ne whiche dignitee ne au&yogh;t[e] nat ben cleped dignitee. &para; And at &thorn;e laste I may conclude &thorn;e same &thorn;inge of al &thorn;e &yogh;iftes of fortune in whiche &thorn;er nis no &thorn;ing to ben desired. ne &thorn;at ha&thorn; in hym self naturel bounte. &para; as it is ful wel sene. for ney&thorn;er &thorn;ei ne ioygnen hem nat alwey to goode men. ne maken hem alwey goode to whom &thorn;ei ben y-ioigned. 
</P></DIV2><PB N="55"><DIV2 N="6" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">NOUIMUS QUANTOS DEDERAT.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>We han wel knowen how many greet[e] harmes and destrucciouns weren do&nmacr; by &thorn;e Emperoure Nero. &para; He letee brenne &thorn;e citee of Rome and made slen &thorn;e senatours. and he cruel somtyme slou&yogh; hys bro&thorn;er. and he was maked moyst wi&thorn; &thorn;e blood of hys modir. &thorn;at is to seyn he let sleen and slitten &thorn;e body of his modir to seen where he was conceiued. and he loked[e] on euery half vpon hir colde dede body. ne no tere ne wette his face. but he was so hard herted &thorn;at he my&yogh;t[e] ben domesman or Iuge of hire dede beaute.  &para; And &yogh;itte neuer&thorn;eles gouerned[e] &thorn;is Nero by Ceptre al &thorn;e peoples &thorn;at phebus &thorn;e sonne may seen comyng from his outerest arysyng til he hidde his bemes vndir &thorn;e wawes.  &para; &thorn;at is to seyne. he gouerned[e] alle &thorn;e peoples by Ceptre imperial &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne go&thorn; aboute from est to west  &para; And eke &thorn;is Nero goueyrende by Ceptre. alle &thorn;e peoples &thorn;at ben vndir &thorn;e colde sterres &thorn;at hy&yogh;ten &thorn;e seuene triones. &thorn;is is to seyn he gouerned[e] alle &thorn;e poeples &thorn;at ben vndir &thorn;e parties of &thorn;e nor&thorn;e.  &para; And eke Nero gouerned[e] alle &thorn;e poeples &thorn;at &thorn;e violent wynde Nothus scorchi&thorn; and baki&thorn; &thorn;e brennynge sandes by his drie hete. &thorn;at is to seyne. alle &thorn;e poeples in &thorn;e sou&thorn;e. [but yit ne myhte nat al his heye power torne the woodnesse of this wykkyd nero / Allas it is greuous fortune it is]. as ofte as wicked swerde is ioygned to cruel venym. &thorn;at is to sein. venimous cruelte to lordshipe. 
</P></DIV2><PB N="56"><DIV2 N="7" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">TUM EGO SCIS INQUAM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;anne seide I &thorn;us.  &thorn;ou wost wel &thorn;iself &thorn;at &thorn;e couetise of mortal &thorn;inges ne hadden neuer lordshipe of me. but I haue wel desired matere of &thorn;inges to done. as who sei&thorn;. I desired[e] to han matere of gouernaunce ouer comunalites.  &para; For vertue stille ne sholde not elden. &thorn;at is to seyn. &thorn;at list &thorn;at or he wex olde  &para; His uertue &thorn;at lay now ful stille. ne sholde nat perisshe vnexcercised in gouernaunce of comune. &para; For whiche men my&yogh;ten speke or writen of his goode gouernement.  &para; <HI REND="i">Philosophie.</HI>  &para; For so&thorn;e quod she. and &thorn;at is a &thorn;ing &thorn;at may drawen to gouernaunce swiche hertes as ben wor&thorn;i and noble of hir nature. but na&thorn;eles it may nat drawen or tollen swiche hertes as ben y-brou&yogh;t to &thorn;e ful[le] perfeccioun of vertue. &thorn;at is to seyn couetyse of glorie and renoun to han wel administred &thorn;e comune &thorn;inges. or doon goode decertes to profit of &thorn;e comune. for se now and considere how litel and how voide of al prise is &thorn;ilke glorie.  &para; Certeine &thorn;ing is as &thorn;ou hast lerned by demonstracioun of astronomye &thorn;at al &thorn;e envyronynge of &thorn;e er&thorn;e aboute ne halt but &thorn;e resoun of a prykke at regard of &thorn;e gretnesse of heuene. &thorn;at is to seye. &thorn;at yif &thorn;at &thorn;er were maked comparisoun of &thorn;e er&thorn;e to &thorn;e gretnesse of heuene. men wolde Iugen in alle &thorn;at er&thorn;e [ne] helde no space  &para; Of &thorn;e whiche litel regioun of &thorn;is worlde &thorn;e fer&thorn;e partie is enhabitid wi&thorn; lyuyng beestes &thorn;at we knowen. as &thorn;ou hast &thorn;i self lerned by tholome &thorn;at prouit&hbar; it.  &para; yif &thorn;ou haddest wi&thorn; drawen and abated in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;te fro &thorn;ilke fer&thorn;e partie as myche space as &thorn;e see and [the] mareys contenen and ouergon and as myche space as &thorn;e regioun of droughte ouerstrecche&thorn;. <PB N="57">&thorn;at is to seye sandes and desertes wel vnne&thorn; sholde <MILESTONE N="14b" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;er dwellen a ry&yogh;t streite place to &thorn;e habitacioun of  
men. and &yogh;e &thorn;an &thorn;at ben environed and closed wi&thorn; inne &thorn;e leest[e] prikke of &thorn;ilk prikke &thorn;enke &yogh;e to manifesten &yogh;oure renoun and don &yogh;oure name to ben born for&thorn;e. but &yogh;oure glorie &thorn;at is so narwe and so streyt y&thorn;rongen in to so litel boundes. how myche contein&thorn;e it in largesse and in greet doynge.  And also sette &thorn;is &thorn;er to &thorn;at many a nacioun dyuerse of tonge and of maneres. and eke of resoun of hir lyuyng ben enhabitid in &thorn;e cloos of &thorn;ilke litel habitacle.  &para; To &thorn;e whiche naciouns what for difficulte of weyes. and what for diuersite of langages. and what for defaute of vnusage entercomunynge of marchaundise. nat only &thorn;e names of singler men ne may [nat] strecchen. but eke &thorn;e fame of Citees ne may nat strecchen.  &para; At &thorn;e last[e] Certis in &thorn;e tyme of Marcus tulyus as hym self write&thorn; in his book &thorn;at &thorn;e renoun of &thorn;e comune of Rome ne hadde nat &yogh;itte passed ne cloumben ouer &thorn;e mountaigne &thorn;at hy&yogh;t Caucasus. and &yogh;itte was &thorn;ilk tyme rome wel wexen and gretly redouted of &thorn;e parthes. and eke of o&thorn;er folk enhabityng aboute.  &para; Sest &thorn;ou nat &thorn;an how streit and how compressed is &thorn;ilke glorie &thorn;at &yogh;e trauailen aboute to shew and to multiplie.  May &thorn;an &thorn;e glorie of a singlere Romeyne strecchen &thorn;ider as &thorn;e fame of &thorn;e name of Rome may nat clymben ne passen.  &para; And eke sest &thorn;ou nat &thorn;at &thorn;e maners of diuerse folk and eke hir lawes ben discordaunt amonge hem self. so &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at sommen iugen wor&thorn;i of preysynge. o&thorn;er folk iugen &thorn;at it is wor&thorn;i of torment. &para; and &thorn;er of come&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh; a man delite hym in <PB N="58">preysyng of his renoun. he ne may nat in no wise bryngen fur&thorn;e ne spreden his name to many manere peoples.  &para; And &thorn;erfore euery maner man au&yogh;te to ben paied of hys glorie &thorn;at is puplissed among hys owen ney&yogh;bores.  &para; And &thorn;ilke noble renoun shal be restreyned wi&thorn;-inne &thorn;e boundes of o maner folk but how many a man &thorn;at was ful noble in his tyme. ha&thorn; &thorn;e nedy and wrecched for&yogh;etynge of writers put oute of mynde and don awey.  &para; Al be it so &thorn;at certys &thorn;ilke writynges profiten litel. &thorn;e whiche writynges longe and derke elde do&thorn; aweye bo&thorn;e hem and eke her autours. but &yogh;e men semen to geten &yogh;ow a perdurablete whan &yogh;e &thorn;enke &thorn;at in tyme comyng &yogh;oure fame shal lasten.  &para; But na&thorn;eles yif &thorn;ou wilt maken comparisoun to &thorn;e endeles space of eternite what &thorn;ing hast &thorn;ou by whiche &thorn;ou maist reioysen &thorn;e of long lastyng of &thorn;i name.  &para; For if &thorn;er were maked comparysoun of &thorn;e abidyng of a moment to ten &thorn;ousand wynter. for as myche as bo&thorn;e &thorn;o spaces ben endid.  &para; For &yogh;it ha&thorn; &thorn;e moment some porcioun of hit al &thorn;ou&yogh; it a litel be.  &para; But na&thorn;eles &thorn;ilke self noumbre of &yogh;eres. and eke as many &yogh;eres as &thorn;er to may be multiplied. ne may nat certys be comparisound to &thorn;e perdurablete &thorn;at is een[de]les. &para; For of &thorn;inges &thorn;at han ende may be mad comparisoun [but of thinges that ben with-owtyn ende to thinges &thorn;at han ende may be maked no comparysoun].  &para; And for &thorn;i is it al &thorn;ou&yogh; renoun of as longe tyme as euer &thorn;e lyst to &thorn;inken were &thorn;ou&yogh;t by &thorn;e regard of eternite. &thorn;at is vnstauncheable and infinit. it ne sholde nat oonly semen litel. but pleinliche ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t.  &para; But &yogh;e men certys ne konne <PB N="59">don no &thorn;ing ary&yogh;t. but &yogh;if it be for &thorn;e audience of poeple. and for ydel rumours. and &yogh;e forsaken &thorn;e grete wor&thorn;inesse of conscience and of vertue. and &yogh;e seken &yogh;oure gerdouns of &thorn;e smale wordes of strange folke.  &para; Haue now here and vndirstonde in &thorn;e ly&yogh;tnesse of whiche pride and veyne glorie. how a man scorned[e] festiualy and myrily swiche vanite. somtyme &thorn;ere was a man &thorn;at had[de] assaied wi&thorn; striuyng wordes an o&thorn;er man.  &para; &thorn;e whiche nat for vsage of verrey vertue. but for proude veyne glorie had[de] taken vpon hym falsly &thorn;e name of a philosopher.  &para; &thorn;is ra&thorn;er man &thorn;at I speke of &thorn;ou&yogh;t[e] he wolde assay[e] where he &thorn;ilke were a philosopher or no. &thorn;at is to seyne yif he wolde han suffred ly&yogh;tly in pacience &thorn;e wronges <MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;at weren don vnto  
hym.  &para; &thorn;is feined[e] philosophre took pacience a litel while. and whan he hadde receiued wordes of outerage he as in stryuynge a&yogh;eine and reioysynge of hym self seide at &thorn;e last[e] ry&yogh;t &thorn;us.  &para; vndirstondest &thorn;ou nat &thorn;at I am a philosophere. &thorn;at o&thorn;er man answered[e] a&yogh;ein ful bityngly and seide.  &para; I had[de] wel vndirstonden [yt]. yif &thorn;ou haddest holden &thorn;i tonge stille.  &para; But what is it to &thorn;ise noble wor&thorn;i men. For certys of swyche folk speke .I. &thorn;at seken glorie wi&thorn; vertue. what is it quod she. what atteini&thorn; fame to swiche folk whan &thorn;e body is resolued by &thorn;e dee&thorn;. atte &thorn;e last[e].  &para; For yif so be &thorn;at men dien in al. &thorn;at is to seyne body and soule. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ing oure resoun defendi&thorn; vs to byleuen &thorn;anne is &thorn;ere no glorie in no wyse.  For what sholde &thorn;ilke glorie ben. for he of whom &thorn;is glorie is seid to be nis ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t in no wise. and &yogh;if &thorn;e soule whiche &thorn;at ha&thorn; in it self science of <PB N="60">goode werkes vnbounden fro &thorn;e prisoun of &thorn;e er&thorn;e wende&thorn; frely to &thorn;e heuene. dispise&thorn; it nou&yogh;t &thorn;an alle er&thorn;ely occupaciouns. and beynge in heuene reioise&thorn; &thorn;at it is exempt from alle er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges [as wo seith / thanne rekketh the sowle of no glorye of renoun of this world].</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="7" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUICUMQUE SOLAM MENTE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Who so &thorn;at wi&thorn; ouer&thorn;rowyng &thorn;ou&yogh;t only seke&thorn; glorie of fame. and weni&thorn; &thorn;at it be souereyne good &para; Lete hym loke vpon &thorn;e brode shewyng contreys of &thorn;e heuen. and vpon &thorn;e streite sete of &thorn;is er&thorn;e. and he shal be ashamed of &thorn;e encres of his name. &thorn;at may nat fulfille &thorn;e litel compas of &thorn;e er&thorn;e.  &para; O what coueiten proude folke to liften vpon hire nekkes in ydel and dedely &yogh;ok of &thorn;is worlde.  &para; For al &thorn;ou&yogh; [&thorn;at] renoune y-spradde passynge to ferne poeples go&thorn; by dyuerse tonges. and al &thorn;ou&yogh; grete houses and kynredes shyne wi&thorn; clere titles of honours.  &yogh;it na&thorn;eles dee&thorn; dispise&thorn; al heye glorie of fame. and dee&thorn; wrappe&thorn; to gidre &thorn;e heye heuedes and &thorn;e lowe and make&thorn; egal and euene &thorn;e heyest[e] to &thorn;e lowest[e].  &para; where wonen now &thorn;e bones of trewe fabricius.  what is now brutus or stiern Caton &thorn;e &thorn;inne fame &yogh;it lastynge of hir ydel names is markid wi&thorn; a fewe lettres. but al &thorn;ou&yogh; we han knowen &thorn;e faire wordes of &thorn;e fames of hem. it is nat &yogh;euen to knowe hem &thorn;at ben dede and consumpt.  Liggi&thorn; &thorn;anne stille al vtterly vnknowable ne fame ne make&thorn; &yogh;ow nat knowe. and yif &yogh;e wene to lyuen &thorn;e lenger for wynde of &yogh;oure mortal name. whan o cruel day shal rauyshe &yogh;ow. &thorn;an is &thorn;e secunde dee&thorn; dwellyng in &yogh;ow.  <FOREIGN LANG="l">Glosa.</FOREIGN> &thorn;e first dee&thorn; he clepi&thorn; <PB N="61">here &thorn;e departynge of &thorn;e body and &thorn;e soule.  &para; and &thorn;e secunde dee&thorn; he clepe&thorn; as here. &thorn;e styntynge of &thorn;e renoune of fame.</P><NOTE>The next three chapters are from Camb. MS.</NOTE></DIV2> <DIV2 N="8" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">[SET NE ME INEXORABILE CONTRA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Bvt for-as-mochel as thow shalt nat wenen quod she &thorn;at I bere vntretable batayle ayenis fortune // yit som-tyme it by-falleth &thorn;at she desseyuable desserueth to han ryht good thank of men // And &thorn;at is whan she hire self opneth / and whan she descouereth hir frownt / and sheweth hir maneres par-auenture yit vndirstondesthow nat &thorn;at .I. shal seye // it is a wondyr &thorn;at .I. desyre to telle / and forthi vnnethe may I. vnpleyten my sentense with wordes for I. deme &thorn;at contraryos fortune profiteth more to men than fortune debonayre // For al-wey whan fortune semeth debonayre than she lyeth falsly in by-hetynge the hope of welefulnesse // but forsothe contraryos fortune is alwey sothfast / whan she sheweth hir self vnstable thorw hyr chaungynge // the amyable fortune desseyueth folk / the contrarye fortune techeth // the amyable fortune byndeth with the beaute of false goodys the hertes of folk &thorn;at vsen hem / the contrarye fortune vnbyndeth hem by &thorn;<HI REND="sup">e</HI> knowynge of freele welefulnesse // the amyable fortune maysthow sen alwey wyndynge and flowynge / and euere mysknowynge of hir self // the contrarye fortune is a-tempre and restreynyd and wys thorw excersyse of hir aduersyte // at the laste amyable fortune with hir flaterynges draweth mys wandrynge men fro the souereyne good // the contraryos fortune ledith ofte folk ayein to sothfast goodes / and haleth hem ayein as with an hooke / weenesthow thanne &thorn;at thow owhtest to leten this a lytel thing / &thorn;at this aspre and horible fortune hath discoueryd to the / the thowhtes of thy trewe frendes // For-why this ilke fortune 
<PB N="62">hath departyd and vncoueryd to the bothe the certeyn vysages and ek the dowtos visages of thy felawes // whan she departyd awey fro the / she took awey hyr frendes and lafte the thyne frendes // now whan thow were ryche and weleful as the semede / with how mochel woldesthow han bowht the fulle knowynge of this // &thorn;at is to seyn the knowynge of thy verray freendes // now pleyne the nat thanne of Rychesse .I.-lorn syn thow hast fowndyn the moste presyos kynde of Rychesses &thorn;at is to seyn thy verray frendes.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="8" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUOD MUNDUS STABILI FIDE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>That &thorn;<HI REND="sup">e</HI> world with stable feith / varieth acordable chaungynges // &thorn;at the contraryos qualite of element&yogh; holden amonge hem self aliaunce perdurable / &thorn;at phebus the sonne with his goldene chariet / bryngeth forth the rosene day / &thorn;at the mone hath commaundement ouer the nyhtes // whiche nyhtes hesperus the eue sterre hat browt // &thorn;at &thorn;<HI REND="sup">e</HI> se gredy to flowen constreyneth with a certeyn ende hise floodes / so &thorn;at it is nat l[e]ueful to strechche hise brode termes or bowndes vp-on the erthes // &thorn;at is to seyn to couere alle the erthe // Al this a-cordaunce of thinges is bownden with looue / &thorn;at gouerneth erthe and see / and hath also commaundement&yogh; to the heuenes / and yif this looue slakede the brydelis / alle thinges &thorn;at now louen hem to gederes / wolden maken a batayle contynuely and stryuen to fordoon the fasoun of this worlde / the which they now leden in acordable feith by fayre moeuynges // this looue halt to gideres poeples Ioygned with an hooly bond / and knytteth sacrement of maryages of chaste looues // And loue enditeth lawes to trewe felawes // O weleful weere mankynde / yif thilke loue &thorn;at gouerneth heuene gouerned[e] yowre corages /</P></DIV2><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="l">EXPLICIT LIBER 2<HI REND="sup">us</HI>.</FOREIGN></TRAILER></DIV1><PB N="63"><DIV1 N="3" TYPE="book"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">INCIPIT LIBER 3<HI REND="sup">us</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD><DIV2 N="1" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">IAM CANTUM ILLA FINIERAT.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>By this she hadde endid hire songe / whan the swetnesse of hire ditee hadde thorw perced me &thorn;at was desirous of herkninge / and .I. astoned hadde yit streyhte myn Eres / &thorn;at is to seyn to herkne the bet / what she wolde seye // so &thorn;at a litel here after .I. seyde thus // O thow &thorn;at art souereyn comfort of Angwissos corages // So thow hast remounted and norysshed me with the weyhte of thy sentenses and with delit of thy syngynge // so &thorn;at.I. trowe nat now &thorn;at .I. be vnparygal to the strokes of fortune / as who seyth. I. dar wel now suffren al the assautes of fortune and wel deffende me fro hyr // and tho remedies whyche &thorn;at thow seydest hire byforn weren ryht sharpe Nat oonly &thorn;at .I. am nat agrysen of hem now // but .I. desiros of herynge axe gretely to heeren tho remedyes // than seyde she thus // &thorn;at feelede .I. ful wel quod she // whan &thorn;at thow ententyf and stylle rauysshedest my wordes // and .I. abood til &thorn;at thow haddest swych habyte of thy thowght as thow hast now // or elles tyl &thorn;at .I. my self had[de] maked to the the same habyt / which &thorn;at is a moore verray thinge // And certes the remenaunt of thinges &thorn;at ben yit to seye / ben swyche // &thorn;at fyrst whan men tasten hem they ben bytynge / but whan they ben resseyuyd with-inne a whyht than ben they swete // but for thow seyst &thorn;at thow art so desirous to herkne hem // wit[h] how gret brennynge woldesthow glowen / yif thow wystest whyder .I. wol leden the // whydyre is &thorn;at quod .I. // to thilke verray welefulnesse quod she // of whyche thynge herte dremeth // but for as moche as thy syhte is ocupied and distorbed / by Imagynasyon of herthely thynges / thow mayst nat yit sen thilke selue welefulnesse // do quod .I. and shewe <PB N="64">me / what is thilke verray welefulnesse / .I. preye the with-howte tarynge // &thorn;at wole .I. gladly don quod she / for the cause of the // but .I. wol fyrst marken the by wordes / and I wol enforcen me to enformen the // thilke false cause of blysfulnesse &thorn;at thow more knowest / so &thorn;at whan thow hast fully by-holden thilke false goodes and torned thyne eyen to &thorn;at oother syde / thow mowe knowe the clernesse of verray blysfulnesse //]</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="1" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><NOTE>Here the Add. MS. begins again.</NOTE><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUI SERERE INGENIUM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&para; Who so wil sowe a felde plentiuous. lat hym first delyuer it of &thorn;ornes and kerue asondre wi&thorn; his hooke &thorn;e bushes and &thorn;e ferne so &thorn;at &thorn;e corne may comen heuy of eres and of greins. hony is &thorn;e more swete yif mou&thorn;es han firste tastid sauoures &thorn;at ben wikke.  &para; &thorn;e sterres shynen more agreably whan &thorn;e wynde Nothus leti&thorn; his ploungy blastes. and aftir &thorn;at lucifer &thorn;e day sterre ha&thorn; chased awey &thorn;e derke ny&yogh;t. &thorn;e day &thorn;e feirer ledi&thorn; &thorn;e rosene horse of &thorn;e sonne.  &para; Ry&yogh;t so &thorn;ou byholdyng first &thorn;e fals[e] goodes. bygynne to wi&thorn;drawe &thorn;i nek[ke] fro &thorn;e &yogh;ok of er&thorn;ely affecciouns. and afterwarde &thorn;e verrey goodes shollen entre in to &thorn;i corage.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="2" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">TUNC DEFIXO PAULULUM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;o fastned[e] she a lytel &thorn;e sy&yogh;t of hir eyen and wi&thorn;drow hir ry&yogh;t as it were in to &thorn;e streite sete of hir &thorn;ou&yogh;t. and bygan to speke ry&yogh;t &thorn;us.  Alle &thorn;e cures quod she of mortal folk whiche &thorn;at trauaylen hem in many manere studies gon certys by diuerse weies. 
 &para; But na&thorn;eles &thorn;ei enforced hem <MILESTONE N="15b" UNIT="fol.">to comen oonly to on <PB N="65">ende of blisfulnesse [And blysfulnesse] is swiche a goode &thorn;at who so ha&thorn; geten it he ne may ouer &thorn;at no &thorn;ing more desiire. and &thorn;is &thorn;ing for so&thorn;e is &thorn;e souereyne good &thorn;at conteini&thorn; in hym self al manere goodes. to &thorn;e whiche goode yif &thorn;ere failed[e] any &thorn;ing. it my&yogh;t[e] nat ben souereyne goode. &para; For &thorn;an were &thorn;ere som goode out of &thorn;is ilke souereyne goode &thorn;at my&yogh;t[e] ben desired. Now is it clere and certeyne &thorn;an &thorn;at blisfulnesse is a perfit estat by &thorn;e congregacioun of alle goodes.  &para; &thorn;e whiche blisfulnesse as I haue seid alle mortal folke enforcen hem to geten by dyuerse weyes.  &para; For-whi &thorn;e couetise of verray goode is naturely y-plaunted in &thorn;e hertys of men.  &para; But &thorn;e myswandryng errour mysledi&thorn; hem in to fals[e] goodes. &para; of &thorn;e whiche men some of hem wenen &thorn;at souereygne goode is to lyue wi&thorn; outen nede of any &thorn;ing. and traueilen hem to ben habundaunt of rycchesse. and some o&thorn;er men demen. &thorn;at souerein goode be forto be ry&yogh;t digne of reuerences. and enforcen hem to ben reuerenced among hir ney&yogh;bours. by &thorn;e honours &thorn;at &thorn;ei han ygeten &para; and some folk &thorn;er ben &thorn;at halden &thorn;at ry&yogh;t hey&yogh;e power to be souereyn goode. and enforcen hem forto regnen or ellys to ioignen hem to hem &thorn;at regnen.  &para; And it seme&thorn; to some o&thorn;er folk &thorn;at noblesse of renoun be &thorn;e souerein goode. and hasten hem to geten glorious name by &thorn;e artes of werre or of pees. and many folke mesuren and gessen &thorn;at souerein goode be ioye and gladnesse and wenen &thorn;at it be ry&yogh;t blisful [thynge] to ploungen hem in uoluptuous delit.  &para; And &thorn;er ben folk &thorn;at enterchaungen &thorn;e causes and &thorn;e endes <PB N="66">of &thorn;ise forseide goodes as &thorn;ei &thorn;at desiren rycchesse to han power and delices.  Or ellis &thorn;ei desiren power forto han moneye or for cause of renoun.  &para; In &thorn;ise &thorn;inges and in swyche o&thorn;er &thorn;inges is tourned al &thorn;e entencioun of desirynges and [of] werkes of men.  &para; As &thorn;us. &para; Noblesse and fauour of poeple whiche &thorn;at &yogh;iue&thorn; as it seme&thorn; a manere clernesse of renoun.  &para; and wijf and children &thorn;at men desiren for cause of delit and mirinesse. &para; But forso&thorn;e frendes ne shollen nat ben rekkened among &thorn;e goodes of fortune but of vertue. for it is a ful holy manere &thorn;ing. alle &thorn;ise o&thorn;er &thorn;inges forso&thorn;e ben taken for cause of power.  or ellis for cause of delit.  &para; Certis now am I redy to referen &thorn;e goodes of &thorn;e body to &thorn;ise forseide &thorn;inges abouen.  &para; For it seme&thorn; &thorn;at streng&thorn;e and gretnesse of body &yogh;euen power and wor&thorn;inesse.  &para; and &thorn;at beaute and swiftenesse &yogh;euen noblesse and glorie of renoun. and hele of body seme&thorn; &yogh;iuen delit.  &para; In alle &thorn;ise &thorn;ingus it seme&thorn; oonly &thorn;at blisfulnesse is desired.  &para; For-whi &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at euery man desire&thorn; moost ouer alle &thorn;inges. he demi&thorn; &thorn;at be &thorn;e souereyne goode.  &para; But I haue diffined &thorn;at blisfulnesse is &thorn;e souereyne goode.  for whiche euery wy&yogh;t demi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ilke estat &thorn;at he desire&thorn; ouer alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at it be &thorn;e blisfulnesse.  &para; Now hast &thorn;ou &thorn;an byforne [thy eyen] almost al &thorn;e purposed forme of &thorn;e welfulnesse of mankynde. &thorn;at is to seyne rycchesse. honours. power. glorie. and delit&yogh;. &thorn;e whiche delit oonly considered Epicurus Iuged and establissed. &thorn;at delit is &thorn;e souereyne goode. for as myche as alle o&thorn;er &thorn;inges as hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t[e] by-refte awey ioie and myr&thorn;e from &thorn;e herte.  &para; But I retourne a&yogh;eyne to &thorn;e studies of meen. <PB N="67">of whiche men &thorn;e corage alwey rehersi&thorn; and seeke&thorn; &thorn;e souereyne goode of alle be it so &thorn;at it be wi&thorn; a derke memorie [but he not by whiche paath].  &para; Ry&yogh;t as a dronke man not nat by whiche pa&thorn;e he may retourne home to hys house.  &para; Seme&thorn; it &thorn;anne &thorn;at folk folyen and erren &thorn;at enforcen hem to haue nede of no &thorn;ing &para; Certys &thorn;er nys non o&thorn;er &thorn;ing &thorn;at may so weel perfourny blisfulnesse as an estat plenteuous <MILESTONE N="16" UNIT="fol.">of alle  
goodes &thorn;at ne ha&thorn; nede of none o&thorn;er &thorn;ing. but &thorn;at it is suffisant of hym self. vnto hym self. and foleyen swyche folk &thorn;anne. &thorn;at wenen &thorn;at &thorn;ilk &thorn;ing &thorn;at is ry&yogh;t goode. &thorn;at it be eke ry&yogh;t wor&thorn;i of honour and of reuerence.  &para; Certis nay. for &thorn;at &thorn;ing nys ney&thorn;er foule ne wor&thorn;i to ben dispised &thorn;at al &thorn;e entencioun of mortel folke trauaille forto geten it.  &para; And power au&yogh;t[e] nat &thorn;at eke to be rekened amonges goodes what ellis. for it nys nat to wene &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at is most wor&thorn;i of alle &thorn;inges be feble and wi&thorn; out streng&thorn;e and clernesse of renoun au&yogh;te &thorn;at to ben dispised.  &para; Certys &thorn;er may no man forsake &thorn;at al &thorn;ing &thorn;at is ry&yogh;t excellent and noble. &thorn;at it ne seme&thorn; to be ry&yogh;t clere and renomed. &para; For certis it nedi&thorn; nat to seie. &thorn;at blisfulnesse be anguissous ne dreri ne subgit to greuances ne to sorwes. syn &thorn;at in ry&yogh;t litel &thorn;ingus folk seken to haue and to vsen &thorn;at may deliten hem.  &para; Certys &thorn;ise ben &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at men wolen and desyren to geten. and for &thorn;is cause desiren &thorn;ei rycches. dignites. regnes. glorie and delices  &para; For &thorn;erby wenen &thorn;ei to han suffisaunce honour power. renoun and gladnesse.  &para; &thorn;anne is it goode. &thorn;at men seken &thorn;us by so many dyuerse studies.  In whiche desijr it may ly&yogh;tly be shewed. <PB N="68">how grete is &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of nature.  &para; For how so &thorn;at men han dyuerse sentences and discordyng algates men accordyn alle in lyuynge &thorn;e ende of goode.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="2" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUANTAS RERUM FLECTAT.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>It like&thorn; me to shew[e] by subtil songe wi&thorn; slakke and delitable soun of strenges how &thorn;at nature my&yogh;ty encline&thorn; and flitte&thorn; gouernement&yogh; of &thorn;inges  &para; and by whiche lawes she purueiable kepi&thorn; &thorn;e grete worlde. and how she bindynge restreine&thorn; alle &thorn;ingus by a bonde &thorn;at may nat be vnbounden.  &para; Al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;e liouns of &thorn;e contree of pene beren &thorn;e fair[e] cheines. and taken metes of &thorn;e handes of folk &thorn;at &yogh;euen it hem. and dreden her sturdy maystres of whiche &thorn;ei ben wont to suffren [betinges]. yif &thorn;at hir horrible mou&thorn;es ben bibled. &thorn;at is to sein of bestes devoured.  &para; Hir corage of tyme passe&thorn; &thorn;at ha&thorn; ben ydel and rested. repaire&thorn; a&yogh;ein &thorn;at &thorn;ei roren greuously. and remembren on hir nature. and slaken hir nekkes from hir cheins vnbounden. and hir maistre first to-teren wi&thorn; blody to&thorn;e assaie&thorn; &thorn;e woode wra&thorn;&thorn;es of hem.  &para; &thorn;is is to sein &thorn;ei freten hir maister.  &para; And &thorn;e Iangland brid &thorn;at syngi&thorn; on &thorn;e heye braunches. &thorn;is is to sein in &thorn;e wode and after is inclosed in a streit cage.  &para; al &thorn;ou&yogh; [&thorn;at] &thorn;e pleiyng besines of men &yogh;eue&thorn; hem honied[e] drinkes and large metes. wi&thorn; swete studie.  &para; &yogh;it na&thorn;eles yif &thorn;ilke brid skippynge oute of hir streite cage see&thorn; &thorn;e agreable shadewes of &thorn;e wodes. she defoule&thorn; wi&thorn; hir fete hir metes yshad and seke&thorn; mournyng oonly &thorn;e wode and twitri&thorn; desirynge &thorn;e wode wi&thorn; hir swete voys.  &para; &thorn;e &yogh;erde of a tree &thorn;at is haled adoun by my&yogh;ty <PB N="69">streng&thorn;e bowi&thorn; redely &thorn;e croppe adoun. but yif &thorn;at &thorn;e hande of hym &thorn;at it bente lat it gon a&yogh;ein.  &para; An oon &thorn;e crop loke&thorn; vp ry&yogh;t to heuene.  &para; &thorn;e sonne phebus &thorn;at faille&thorn; at euene in &thorn;e westrene wawes retorni&thorn; a&yogh;ein eftsones his cart by a priue pa&thorn;e &thorn;ere as it is wont aryse.  &para; Alle &thorn;inges seken a&yogh;ein in to hir propre cours. and alle &thorn;inges reioisen hem of hir retournynge a&yogh;ein to hir nature ne noon ordinaunce nis bytaken to &thorn;inges but &thorn;at. &thorn;at ha&thorn; ioignynge &thorn;e endynge to &thorn;e bygynnynge. and ha&thorn; makid &thorn;e cours of it self stable &thorn;at it chaunge&thorn; nat from hys propre kynde.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="3" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">VOSQUE TERRENA ANIMALIA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P><MILESTONE N="16b" UNIT="fol.">CErtis also &yogh;e men &thorn;at ben er&thorn;eliche bestes dremen  
alwey [yowre bygynnynge] al &thorn;ou&yogh; it be wi&thorn; a &thorn;inne ymaginacioun. and by a maner &thorn;ou&yogh;t al be it nat clerly ne perfitly &yogh;e looken from a fer til &thorn;ilk verray fyn of blisfulnesse. and &thorn;erfore &thorn;e naturel entencioun lede&thorn; &yogh;ow to &thorn;ilk verray good  &para; But many manere errours mistourni&thorn; &yogh;ow &thorn;er fro.  &para; Considere now yif &thorn;at be &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges by whiche a man weni&thorn; to gete hym blysfulnesse. yif &thorn;at he may comen to &thorn;ilke ende &thorn;at he wene&thorn; to come by nature  &para; For yif &thorn;at moneye or honours or &thorn;ise o&thorn;er forseide &thorn;inges bryngen to men swiche a &thorn;ing &thorn;at no goode ne faille hem. ne seme&thorn; faille.  &para; Certys &thorn;an wil I graunt[e] &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben maked blisful. by &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ei han geten. &para; but yif so be &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges ne mowe nat perfourmen &thorn;at &thorn;ei by-heten and &thorn;at &thorn;er be defaute of many goodes.  &para; Shewe&thorn; it nat &thorn;an clerely &thorn;at fals beaute of blisfulnesse is knowe and a-teint in &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges.  &para; First and forward &thorn;ou &thorn;i self &thorn;at haddest <PB N="70">haboundaunces of rycchesses nat long agon.  &para; I axe &yogh;if &thorn;at in &thorn;e haboundaunce of alle &thorn;ilk[e] rycchesses &thorn;ou were neuer anguissous or sory in &thorn;i corage of any wrong or greuaunce &thorn;at by-tidde &thorn;e on any syde. &para; Certys quod I it remembre&thorn; me nat &thorn;at euere I was so free of my &thorn;ou&yogh;t. &thorn;at I ne was al-wey in anguyshe of somwhat. &thorn;at was &thorn;at &thorn;ou lakkedest &thorn;at &thorn;ou noldest han lakked.  or ellys &thorn;ou haddest &thorn;at &thorn;ou noldest han had.  ry&yogh;t so is it quod I &thorn;an.  desiredest &thorn;ou &thorn;e presence of &thorn;at oon and &thorn;e absence of &thorn;at o&thorn;er. I graunt[e] wel quod .I. for so&thorn;e quod she &thorn;an nedi&thorn; &thorn;er somwhat &thorn;at euery man desire&thorn;. &yogh;e &thorn;er nedi&thorn; quod I. &para; Certis quod she and he &thorn;at ha&thorn; lakke or nede of a wy&yogh;t nis nat in euery way suffisaunt to hym self. no quod .I. and &thorn;ou quod she in alle &thorn;e plente of &thorn;i rycchesse haddest &thorn;ilke lak of suffisaunce.  &para; what ellis quod .I. &para; &thorn;anne may nat rycchesse maken &thorn;at a man nis nedy. ne &thorn;at he be suffisaunt to hym self. and &thorn;at was it &thorn;at &thorn;ei byhy&yogh;ten as it seme&thorn;. &para; and eke certys I trowe &thorn;at &thorn;is be gretly to consydere &thorn;at moneye ne ha&thorn; nat in hys owen kynde &thorn;at it ne may ben by-nomen of hem &thorn;at han it maugre hem.  &para; I by-knowe it wel quod I  &para; whi sholdest &thorn;ou nat by-knowen it quod she. whan euery day &thorn;e strenger folke by-nymen it fram &thorn;e febler maugre hem.  &para; Fro whennes comen ellys alle &thorn;ise foreine compleintes or quereles of pletyngus.  &para; But for &thorn;at men axen a&yogh;eine her moneye &thorn;at ha&thorn; be by-nomen hem by force or by gyle. and alwey maugre hem.  &para; Ry&yogh;t so it is quod I. &thorn;an quod she ha&thorn; a man nede to seken hym foreyne helpe by whiche he may defende hys moneye. who may say nay <PB N="71">quod .I.  &para; Certis quod she and hym nedi&thorn; no helpe yif he ne hadde no moneye &thorn;at he my&yogh;t[e] leese.  &para; &thorn;at is doutles quod .I. &thorn;anne is &thorn;is &thorn;ing turned in to &thorn;e contrarie quod she &para; For rycchesse &thorn;at men wenen sholde make suffisaunce. &thorn;ei maken a man ra&thorn;er han nede of foreine helpe.  &para; whiche is &thorn;e manere or &thorn;e gise quod she &thorn;at rycches may dryuen awey nede.  &para; Riche folk may &thorn;ei nei&thorn;er han hungre ne &thorn;rest. &thorn;ise ryche men may &thorn;ei feele no colde on hir lymes in wynter.  &para; But &thorn;ou wilt answere &thorn;at ryche men han y-nou&yogh; wher wi&thorn; &thorn;ei may staunchen her hunger. and slaken her &thorn;rest and don awey colde.  &para; In &thorn;is wise may nede be conforted by rycchesses. but certys nede ne may nat al outerly be don awey. for &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;is nede &thorn;at is alwey gapyng and gredy be fulfilled wi&thorn; rycchesses. and axe any &thorn;ing &yogh;it dwelle&thorn; &thorn;anne a nede &thorn;at my&yogh;t[e] ben fulfilled. &para; I holde me stille and telle nat how &thorn;at litel &thorn;ing suffise&thorn; to nature. but certys to auarice ynou&yogh; ne suffise&thorn; no &thorn;inge.<MILESTONE N="17" UNIT="fol.">&para; For syn &thorn;at rychesse ne may nat  
al don awey nede. but rychesse maken nede. what may it &thorn;anne be &thorn;at &yogh;e wenen &thorn;at rychesses mowen &yogh;euen &yogh;ow suffisaunce.</P></DIV2><DIV2 REND="3" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUAMUIS FLUENTER DIUES.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Al were it so &thorn;at a ryche couetous man hadde riuer fletynge alle of golde &yogh;itte sholde it neuer staunche hys couetise. &para; And &thorn;ou&yogh; he hadde his nekke I-charged wi&thorn; preciouse stones of &thorn;e rede see. and &thorn;ou&yogh; he do erye his feldes plentiuous wi&thorn; an hundre&thorn; oxen neuere ne shal his bytyng bysynesse forleten hym while he <PB N="72">lyue&thorn;. ne &thorn;e ly&yogh;t[e] rychesses ne shal nat beren hym compaignie whanne he is dede.</P></DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">SET DIGNITATIBUS.</FOREIGN><NOTE>Read <FOREIGN LANG="l">dignitates</FOREIGN></NOTE></HEAD><P>Bvt dignitees to whom &thorn;ei ben comen make &thorn;ei hym honorable and reuerent. han &thorn;ei nat so grete streng&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ei may putte vertues in &thorn;e hertis of folk. &thorn;at vsen &thorn;e lordshipes of hem. or ellys may &thorn;ei don awey &thorn;e vices.  Certys &thorn;ei [ne] ben nat wont to don awey wikkednesses. but &thorn;ei ben wont ra&thorn;er to shew[en] wikkednesses. and &thorn;er of come&thorn; it &thorn;at I haue ry&yogh;t grete desdeyne. &thorn;at dignites ben &yogh;euen ofte to wicked men. &para; For whiche &thorn;ing catullus clepid a consul of Rome &thorn;at hy&yogh;t nonius postum. or boch. as who sei&thorn; he clepi&thorn; hym a congregacioun of uices in his brest as a postum is ful of corrupcioun.  al were &thorn;is nonius set in a chayere of dignitee.  Sest &thorn;ou nat &thorn;an how gret vylenye dignitees don to wikked men.  &para; Certys vnwor&thorn;ines of wikked men sholde ben &thorn;e lasse ysen yif &thorn;ei nere renomed of none honours.  &para; Certys &thorn;ou &thorn;i self ne my&yogh;test nat ben brou&yogh;t wi&thorn; as many perils as &thorn;ou my&yogh;test suffren &thorn;at &thorn;ou woldest bere &thorn;i magistrat wi&thorn; decorat. &thorn;at is to seyn. &thorn;at for no peril &thorn;at my&yogh;t[e] bifallen &thorn;e by &thorn;e offence of &thorn;e kyng theodorik &thorn;ou noldest nat ben felawe in gouernaunce with decorat. whanne &thorn;ou say[e] &thorn;at he had[de] wikkid corage of a likerous shrewe and of an acusor.  &para; Ne I ne may nat for swiche honours Iugen hem wor&thorn;i of reuerence &thorn;at I deme and holde vnwor&thorn;i to han &thorn;ilke same honours.  &para; Now yif &thorn;ou saie a man &thorn;at were fulfilled of wisdom. certys &thorn;ou 
<PB N="73">ne my&yogh;test nat demen &thorn;at he were vnwor&thorn;i to &thorn;e honour. or ellys to &thorn;e wisdom of whiche he is fulfilled. No quod .I.  &para; Certys dignitees quod she appertienen properly to vertue. and uertue transporte&thorn; dignite anon to &thorn;ilke man to whiche she hir self is conioigned. &para; And for as moche as honours of poeple ne may nat maken folk digne of honour. it is wel seyn clerly &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne han no propre beaute of dignite.  &para; And &yogh;it men au&yogh;ten take more hede in &thorn;is.  &para; For if it so be &thorn;at he is most out cast &thorn;at most folk dispisen. or as dignite ne may nat maken shrewes wor&thorn;i of no reuerences. &thorn;an make&thorn; dignites shrewes more dispised &thorn;an preised. &thorn;e whiche shrewes dignit[e] schewe&thorn; to moche folk &para; and for so&thorn;e nat vnpunissed. &thorn;at is forto sein. &thorn;at shrewes reuengen hem a&yogh;einward vpon dignites. for &thorn;ei &yogh;elden a&yogh;ein to dignites as gret gerdoun whan &thorn;ei byspotten and defoulen dignites wi&thorn; hire vylenie.  &para; And for as moche as &thorn;ou mow[e] knowe &thorn;at &thorn;ilke verray reuerence ne may nat comen by &thorn;e shadewy transitorie dignitees. vndirstonde now &thorn;is. yif &thorn;at a man hadde vsed and hadde many manere dignites of consules and were comen perauenture amonges straunge naciouns. sholde &thorn;ilke honour maken hym worshipful and redouted of straunge folk  &para; Certys yif &thorn;at honour of poeple were a naturel &yogh;ifte to dignites. it ne my&yogh;te neuer cesen nowher amonges no maner folke to done hys office. &para; Ry&yogh;t as fire in euery contre ne stinte&thorn; nat to enchaufen and <MILESTONE N="17b" UNIT="fol.">to ben hote. but for as myche as forto  
be holden honorable or reuerent ne come&thorn; nat to folk of <PB N="74">hir propre streng&thorn;e of nature. but only of &thorn;e fals[e] opinioun of folk. &thorn;at is to sein. &thorn;at wenen &thorn;at dignites maken folk digne of honour.  An on &thorn;erfore whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei comen &thorn;er as folk ne knowen nat &thorn;ilke dignites. her honours vanissen awey and &thorn;at on oon. but &thorn;at is a-mong straung folk. maist &thorn;ou sein.  but amongus hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren born duren &thorn;ilk[e] dignites alwey. &para; Certys &thorn;e dignite of &thorn;e prouostrie of Rome was somtyme a grete power. now is it no &thorn;ing but an ydel name. and &thorn;e rente of &thorn;e senatorie a gret charge. and yif a whi&yogh;t somtyme hadde &thorn;e office to taken he[de] to &thorn;e vitailes of &thorn;e poeple as of corne and what o&thorn;er &thorn;inges he was holden amonges grete. but what &thorn;ing is more nowe out cast &thorn;anne &thorn;ilke prouostrie &para; And as I haue seid a litel here byforne. &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at ha&thorn; no propre beaute of hym self resceyue&thorn; somtyme pris and shinynge and somtyme lesi&thorn; it by &thorn;e opinioun of vsaunces.  &para; Now yif &thorn;at dignites &thorn;anne ne mowen nat maken folk digne of reuerence. and yif &thorn;at dignites wexen foule of hir wille by &thorn;e fil&thorn;e of shrewes.  &para; and yif &thorn;at dignites lesen hir shynynge by chaungyng of tymes. and yif &thorn;ei wexen foule by estimacioun of poeple. what is it &thorn;at &thorn;ei han in hem self of beaute &thorn;at au&yogh;te ben desired. as who sei&thorn; none. &thorn;anne ne mowen &thorn;ei &yogh;iuen no beaute of dignite to none o&thorn;er.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="4" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUAMUIS SE TIRIO.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;e proude nero wi&thorn; al his woode luxurie kembed hym and apparailed hym wi&thorn; faire purpers of Tirie and wi&thorn; white perles.  Algates &yogh;itte throf he <PB N="75">hateful to alle folk &para; &thorn;is is to seyn &thorn;at al was he byhated of alle folk. &para; &yogh;itte &thorn;is wicked Nero hadde gret lordship and &yogh;af somtyme to &thorn;e dredeful senatours &thorn;e vnworshipful setes of dignites.  &para; vnworshipful setes he clepi&thorn; here fore &thorn;at Nero &thorn;at was so wikked &yogh;af &thorn;o dignites. who wolde &thorn;anne resonably wenen &thorn;at blysfulnesse were in swiche honours as ben &yogh;euen by vicious shrewes.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="5" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">AN UERO REGNA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Bvt regnes and familarites of kynges may &thorn;ei maken a man to ben my&yogh;ty. how ellys.  &para; whanne hir blysfulnesse dure&thorn; perpetuely but certys &thorn;e olde age of tyme passe&thorn;. and eke of present tyme now is ful of ensaumples how &thorn;at kynges &thorn;at han chaunged in to wrechednesse out of hir welefulnesse. &para; O a noble &thorn;ing and a cler &thorn;ing is power &thorn;at is nat founden my&yogh;ty to kepe it self. &para; And yif &thorn;at power of realmes be auctour and maker of blisfulnesse. yif &thorn;ilke power lakke&thorn; on any side. amenusi&thorn; it nat &thorn;ilke blisfulnesse and brynge&thorn; in wrechednesse. but yif al be it so &thorn;at realmes of mankynde stretchen broode. &yogh;it mot &thorn;er nede ben myche folk ouer whiche &thorn;at euery kyng ne ha&thorn; no lordshipe ne comaundement &para; and certys vpon &thorn;ilke syde &thorn;at power faille&thorn; whiche &thorn;at maki&thorn; folk blisful. ry&yogh;t on &thorn;at same side nounpower entri&thorn; vndirne&thorn; &thorn;at make&thorn; hem wreches.  &para; In &thorn;is manere &thorn;anne moten kynges han more porcioun of wrechednesse &thorn;an of welefulnesse. &para; A tyraunt &thorn;at was kyng of sisile &thorn;at had[de] assaied &thorn;e peril of his estat shewid[e] by similitude &thorn;e dredes of realmes by gastnesse of a swerde &thorn;at heng ouer &thorn;e heued of his familier. what &thorn;ing is &thorn;an &thorn;is power &thorn;at <PB N="76">may nat don awey &thorn;e bytynges of besines ne eschewe &thorn;e prikkes of drede. and certys &yogh;it wolden &thorn;ei lyuen <MILESTONE N="18" UNIT="fol."> in sykernesse. but &thorn;ei may nat. and &yogh;it &thorn;ei glorifien hem in her power  &para; Holdest &thorn;ou &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;ilk[e] man be my&yogh;ty &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest &thorn;at he wolde don &thorn;at he may nat don.  &para; And holdest &thorn;ou &thorn;an hym a my&yogh;ty man &thorn;at ha&thorn; environed hise sydes wi&thorn; men of armes or seruauntes and drede&thorn; more [hem] &thorn;at he make&thorn; agast. &thorn;en &thorn;ei dreden hym. and &thorn;at is put in &thorn;e handes of hise seruaunt&yogh;. for he sholde seme my&yogh;ty but of familiers [or] seruaunt&yogh; of kynges.  &para; what sholde I telle &thorn;e any &thorn;ing. syn &thorn;at I my self haue shewed &thorn;e &thorn;at realmes hem self ben ful of gret feblenesse. &thorn;e whiche familiers certis &thorn;e real power of kynges in hool estat and in estat abated ful [ofte] &thorn;rowe&thorn; adoun.  &para; Nero constreined[e] his familier and his maistre seneca to chesen on what dee&thorn; he wolde deien.  &para; Antonius comaundid[e] &thorn;at kny&yogh;tis slowen wi&thorn; her swerdis Papinian his familier whiche Papinian had[de] ben long tyme ful my&yogh;ty a-monges hem of &thorn;e courte. and &yogh;it certis &thorn;ei wolde bo&thorn;e han renounced her power. of whiche [two] senek enforced[e] hym to &yogh;iuen to Nero his rychesses. and also to han gon in to solitarie exil.  &para; But whan &thorn;e grete wey&yogh;t.  &thorn;at is to sein of lordes power or of fortune drawe&thorn; hem &thorn;at sholden falle.  ney&thorn;er of hem ne my&yogh;t[e] do &thorn;at he wolde. what &thorn;ing is &thorn;anne &thorn;ilke power &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh; men han it &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben agast.  &para; and whan &thorn;ou woldest han it &thorn;ou nart nat siker.  &para; And yif &thorn;ou woldest forleten it &thorn;ou mayst nat eschewen it. &para; But whe&thorn;ir swiche men ben frendes at nede as ben conseiled by fortune and nat by vertue.  Certys swiche <PB N="77">folk as weleful fortune make&thorn; frendes. contrarious fortune make&thorn; hem enmyse.  &para; And what pestilence is more my&yogh;ty forto anoye a wi&yogh;t &thorn;an a familier enemy.</P></DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUI SE UALET</FOREIGN><NOTE>Read <FOREIGN LANG="l">uolet</FOREIGN></NOTE><FOREIGN LANG="l"> ESSE POTENTEM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Who so wolde ben my&yogh;ty he mot daunten hys cruel corage. ne put[te] nat his nekke ouercomen vndir &thorn;e foule reines of lecherie. for al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;i lordship[e] strecche so fer &thorn;at &thorn;e contre Inde quaki&thorn; at &thorn;i comaundement. or at &thorn;i lawes. and &thorn;at &thorn;e leest isle in &thorn;e see &thorn;at hy&yogh;t tile be &thorn;ral to &thorn;e  &para; &yogh;it yif &thorn;ou mayst nat puten awey &thorn;i foule derk[e] desijres and dryuen oute fro &thorn;e wreched compleyntes.  Certis it nis no power &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="6" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">GLORIA UERO QUAM FALLAX.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Bvt glorie how deceiuable and how foule is it ofte. for whiche &thorn;ing nat vnskilfully a tregedien &thorn;at is to sein a maker of dites &thorn;at hy&yogh;ten tregedies cried[e] and seide.  &para; O glorie glorie quod he. &thorn;ou nart no &thorn;ing ellys to &thorn;ousandes of folkes. but a gret sweller of eres. for many[e] han had ful gret renoun by &thorn;e fals[e] oppinioun of poeple. and what &thorn;ing may ben &thorn;ou&yogh;t fouler &thorn;en swiche preisynge for &thorn;ilk[e] folk &thorn;at ben preised falsly. &thorn;ei moten nedes han shame of hir preisynges. and yif &thorn;at folk han geten hem &thorn;ank or preysyng by her desertes.  what &thorn;ing ha&thorn; &thorn;ilk pris echid or encresed to &thorn;e conscience of wise folk &thorn;at mesuren hire good. not by &thorn;e rumour of &thorn;e poeple. but by &thorn;e so&thorn;efastnesse of conscience. and yif it seme a fair &thorn;ing a man to han encresid and sprad his name. &thorn;an folwe&thorn; 

<PB N="78">it. &thorn;at it is demed to ben a foule &thorn;inge yif it ne be ysprad ne encresed. but as I seide a litel her byforne. &thorn;at syn &thorn;er mot nedes ben many folk to whiche folk &thorn;e renoun of a man ne may nat comen. it byfalle&thorn; &thorn;at he &thorn;at &thorn;ou wenest be glorious and renomed. semi&thorn; in &thorn;e nexte parties of &thorn;e er&thorn;e to ben wi&thorn; out glorie. and wi&thorn; out renoun. &para; and certis amonges &thorn;ise &thorn;inges I ne trowe nat &thorn;at &thorn;e pris and grace of &thorn;e poeple nis nei&thorn;er wor&thorn;i <MILESTONE N="18b" UNIT="fol."> to ben remembrid ne come&thorn; of wise iugement. ne is ferm perdurably.  &para; But now of &thorn;is name of gentilesse. what man is it &thorn;at ne may wel seen how veyne and how flittyng a &thorn;ing it is.  &para; For if &thorn;e name of gentilesse be referred to renoun and clernesse of linage. &thorn;an is gentil name but a for[e]ine &thorn;ing. &thorn;at is to sein to hem &thorn;at glorifien hem of hir linage.  &para; For it seme&thorn; &thorn;at gentilesse be a maner preysynge &thorn;at come&thorn; of decert of auncestres.  &para; And yif preysynge make&thorn; gentilesse &thorn;an moten &thorn;ei nedes be gentil &thorn;at ben preysed.  For whiche &thorn;ing it folwe&thorn;. &thorn;at yif &thorn;ou ne haue no gentilesse of &thorn;i self. &thorn;at is to sein pris &thorn;at come&thorn; of &thorn;i deserte foreine gentilesse ne make&thorn; &thorn;e nat gentil.  &para; But certis yif &thorn;er be any goode in gentilesse. I trowe it be in al oonly &thorn;is. &thorn;at it seme&thorn; as &thorn;at a maner necessitee be imposed to gentil men. for &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne sholden nat outraien or forliuen fro &thorn;e uertues of hire noble kynrede.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="6" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">OMNE HOMINUM GENUS IN TERRIS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Al &thorn;e linage of men &thorn;at ben in er&thorn;e ben of semblable bur&thorn;e.  On al one is fadir of &thorn;inges.  On alone minyst[r]e&thorn; alle &thorn;inges.  &para; He &yogh;af to &thorn;e sonne hys bemes. he &yogh;af to &thorn;e moone hir hornes. he &yogh;af &thorn;e men to &thorn;e er&thorn;e. he &yogh;af &thorn;e sterres to &thorn;e heuene.  &para; he enclose&thorn; <PB N="79">wi&thorn; membres &thorn;e soules &thorn;at comen fro hys heye sete. &para; &thorn;anne comen alle mortal folk of noble seed. whi noysen &yogh;e or bosten of &yogh;oure eldris  &para; For yif &thorn;ou look[e] &yogh;oure bygynnyng. and god &yogh;oure auctour and &yogh;oure makere. &thorn;an is &thorn;er no forlyued wy&yogh;t but &yogh;if he norisse his corage vnto vices and forlete his propre bur&thorn;e.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="7" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUID AUTEM DE CORPORIBUS.</FOREIGN><NOTE>Read<FOREIGN LANG="l">corporis voluptatibus</FOREIGN></NOTE></HEAD><P>But what shal I seie of delices of body. of whic[h]e delices &thorn;e desiringes ben ful of anguisse. and &thorn;e fulfillinges of hem ben ful of penaunce.  &para; How grete sekenesse and how grete sorwes vnsuffrable ry&yogh;t as a manere fruit of wickednesse ben &thorn;ilke delices wont to bryngen to &thorn;e bo[d]ies of folk &thorn;at vsen hem.  &para; Of whiche delices I not what ioye may ben had of hir moeuyng.  &para; But &thorn;is woot I wel &thorn;at who so euere wil remembren hym of hys luxuries. he shal wel vndirstonde. &thorn;at &thorn;e issues of delices ben sorowful and sory. &para; And yif &thorn;ilke delices mowen make folk blisful. &thorn;an by &thorn;e same cause moten &thorn;ise bestes ben clepid blisful. &para; Of whiche bestes al &thorn;e entencioun haste&thorn; to fulfille hire bodyly iolyte. and &thorn;e gladnesse of wijf [and] children were [an] honest &thorn;ing. but it ha&thorn; ben seid. &thorn;at it is ouer myche a&yogh;eins kynde &thorn;at children han ben founden tormentours to hir fadres I not how many. &para; Of whiche children how bitynge is euery condicioun. It nede&thorn; nat to tellen it &thorn;e &thorn;at hast or &thorn;is tyme assaied it. and art &yogh;it now anguyssous.  In &thorn;is approue I &thorn;e sentence of my disciple Euridippus.  &thorn;at seide &thorn;at he &thorn;at ha&thorn; no children is weleful by infortune.</P></DIV2><PB N="80"><DIV2 N="7" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">HABET HOC UOLUPTAS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Euery delit ha&thorn; &thorn;is. &thorn;at it anguisse&thorn; hem wi&thorn; prikkes &thorn;at vsen it.  &para; It resembli&thorn; to &thorn;ise flying flyes &thorn;at we clepen been. &thorn;at aftre &thorn;at &thorn;e bee ha&thorn; shed hys agreable honies he flee&thorn; awey and stynge&thorn; &thorn;e hertes of hem &thorn;at ben ysmyte wi&thorn; bytynge ouer longe holdynge.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="8" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">NICHIL IGITUR DUBIUM EST.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Now nis it no doute &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;ise weyes ne ben a maner mysledyng to blisfulnesse. ne &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne mowe nat leden folke &thorn;ider as &thorn;ei byheten to leden 
 hem.  &para; But wi&thorn; how grete harmes &thorn;ise <MILESTONE N="19" UNIT="fol.">forseide weyes ben enlaced.  &para; I shal shewe &thorn;e shortly.  &para; For whi yif &thorn;ou enforcest &thorn;e to assemble moneye. &thorn;ou most byreuen hym his moneye &thorn;at ha&thorn; it. and yif &thorn;ou wilt shynen wi&thorn; dignites. &thorn;ou most bysechen and supplien hem &thorn;at &yogh;iuen &thorn;o dignitees.  &para; And yif &thorn;ou coueitest by honour to gon by-fore o&thorn;er folk &thorn;ou shalt defoule &thorn;i self by humblesse of axing.  yif &thorn;ou desiryst power. &thorn;ou shalt by awaites of &thorn;i subgit&yogh; anoyously be cast vndir many periles. axest &thorn;ou glorie &thorn;ou shalt ben so destrat by aspre &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalt forgone sykernesse. &para; And yif &thorn;ou wilt leden &thorn;i lijf in delices. euery whi&yogh;t shal dispisen &thorn;e and forleten &thorn;e as &thorn;ou &thorn;at art &thorn;ral to &thorn;ing &thorn;at is ry&yogh;t foule and brutel. &thorn;at is [to] sein seruaunt to &thorn;i body.  &para; Now is it &thorn;an wel yseen how lytel and how brutel possessioun &thorn;ei coueiten &thorn;at putten &thorn;e goodes of &thorn;e body abouen hire owen resoun. &para; For mayst &thorn;ou sourmounten &thorn;ise olifu&nmacr;t&yogh; in gretnesse or wey&yogh;t of body.  Or mayst &thorn;ou ben strenger &thorn;an &thorn;e bole.  Mayst &thorn;ou ben swifter &thorn;an &thorn;e tigre. biholde &thorn;e <PB N="81">spaces and &thorn;e stablenesse and &thorn;e swyfte cours of &thorn;e heuene. and stynte somtyme to wondren on foule &thorn;inges. &thorn;e whiche heuene certys nis nat ra&thorn;er for &thorn;ise &thorn;inges to ben wondred vpon. &thorn;an for &thorn;e resoun by whiche it is gouerned. but &thorn;e shynynge of &thorn;i forme &thorn;at is to seien &thorn;e beaute of &thorn;i body. how swiftly passyng is it and how transitorie.  &para; Certis it is more flittynge &thorn;an &thorn;e mutabilite of floures of &thorn;e somer sesoun.  For so as aristotil telle&thorn; &thorn;at yif &thorn;at men hadden eyen of a beest &thorn;at hi&yogh;t lynx. so &thorn;at &thorn;e lokyng of folk my&yogh;t[e] percen &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at wi&thorn;stonden it. who so lokid &thorn;an in &thorn;e entrailes of &thorn;e body of alcibiades &thorn;at was ful fayr in &thorn;e superfice wi&thorn; oute.  it shulde seme ry&yogh;t foule. and for &thorn;i yif &thorn;ou semest faire. &thorn;i nature ne maki&thorn; nat &thorn;at. but &thorn;e desceiuaunce of &thorn;e fieblesse of &thorn;e eyen &thorn;at loken.  &para; But preise &thorn;e goodes of &thorn;i body as moche as euer &thorn;e list. so &thorn;at &thorn;ou know[e] algates &thorn;at what so it be. &thorn;at is to seyn of &thorn;e goodes of &thorn;i body whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ou wondrest vpon may ben destroied or dessolued by &thorn;e hete of a feuere of &thorn;re dayes.  &para; Of alle whiche forseide &thorn;inges I may reducen &thorn;is shortly in a somme.  &para; &thorn;at &thorn;ise worldly goodes whiche &thorn;at ne mowen nat &yogh;iuen &thorn;at &thorn;ei byheten. ne ben nat perfit by &thorn;e congregacioun of alle goodes. &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne ben nat weyes ne pa&thorn;es &thorn;at bryngen men to blysfulnesse ne maken men to ben blysful.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="8" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">HEU QUE MISEROS TRAMITE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Allas whiche folie and whiche ignoraunce mysledi&thorn; wandryng wrecches fro &thorn;e pa&thorn;e of verrey good. &para; Certis &yogh;e ne seken no golde in grene trees. ne &yogh;e ne <PB N="82">gadren [nat] precious stones in &thorn;e vines. ne &yogh;e ne hiden nat &yogh;oure gynnes in hey&yogh;e mountaignes to kachen fisshe of whiche &yogh;e may maken ryche festes. and yif &yogh;ow lyke&thorn; to hunte to roos. &yogh;e ne gon nat to &thorn;e foordes of &thorn;e water &thorn;at hy&yogh;t tyrene. and ouer &thorn;is men knowen wel &thorn;e crikes and &thorn;e cauernes of &thorn;e see yhidd in &thorn;e floodes. and knowen eke whiche water is most plentiuous of white perles. and knowen whiche water habunde&thorn; most of rede purpre. &thorn;at is to seyen of a maner shelfisshe with whiche men dien purpre. and knowen whiche strondes habounden most of tendre fisshes or of sharpe fisshes &thorn;at hy&yogh;ten echynnys. but folk suffren hem self to ben so blynde &thorn;at hem ne recchi&thorn; nat to knowe where &thorn;ilk[e] goodes ben yhidd whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ei coueiten but ploungen hem in er&thorn;e and seken &thorn;ere &thorn;ilke goode &thorn;at sourmounte&thorn; &thorn;e heuene &thorn;at bere&thorn; &thorn;e 
 sterres. &para; what <MILESTONE N="19b" UNIT="fol.">preyere may I make &thorn;at be digne to &thorn;e nice &thorn;ou&yogh;tis of men. but I preye &thorn;at &thorn;ei coueiten rycches and honours so &thorn;at whan &thorn;ei han geten &thorn;o false goodes wi&thorn; greet trauayle &thorn;at &thorn;erby &thorn;ei mowe knowen &thorn;e verray goodes.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="9" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">HACTENUS MENDACIS FORMAM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>It suffisi&thorn; &thorn;at I haue shewed hider to &thorn;e forme of false wilfulnesse. so &thorn;at yif &thorn;ou look[e] now clerely &thorn;e ordre of myn entencioun requeri&thorn; from hennes for&thorn;e to shewen &thorn;e verray wilfulnesse.  &para; For quod .I. (b)[I.] se wel now &thorn;at suffisaunce may nat comen by richesse. ne power by realmes. ne reuerence by dignitees. ne gentilesse by glorie. ne ioye by delices. and (p) hast &thorn;ou wel knowen quod she &thorn;e cause whi it is.  Certis me seme&thorn; <PB N="83">quod .I. &thorn;at .I. se hem ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ou&yogh; it were &thorn;oru&yogh; a litel clifte. but me were leuer knowen hem more openly of &thorn;e.  Certys quod she &thorn;e resoun is al redy  &para; For &thorn;ilk &thorn;ing &thorn;at symply is on &thorn;ing wi&thorn; outen ony diuisioun. &thorn;e errour and folie of mankynde departe&thorn; and diuidi&thorn; it. and misledi&thorn; it and transporte&thorn; from verray and perfit goode. to goodes &thorn;at ben false and inperfit.  &para; But seye me &thorn;is. wenest &thorn;ou &thorn;at he &thorn;at ha&thorn; nede of power &thorn;at hym ne lakke&thorn; no &thorn;ing.  Nay quod .I  &para; Certis quod she &thorn;ou seist ary&yogh;t.  For yif so be &thorn;at &thorn;er is a &thorn;ing &thorn;at in any partie be fieble of power. Certis as in &thorn;at it most[e] nedes be nedy of foreine helpe.  &para; Ri&yogh;t so it is quod .I. Suffisaunce and power ben &thorn;an of on kynde  &para; So seme&thorn; it quod I.  &para; And demyst &thorn;ou quod she &thorn;at a &thorn;ing &thorn;at is of &thorn;is manere. &thorn;at is to seine suffisaunt and my&yogh;ty au&yogh;t[e] to ben dispised. or ellys &thorn;at it be ry&yogh;t digne of reuerences abouen alle &thorn;inges.  &para; Certys quod I it nys no doute &thorn;at it nis ry&yogh;t wor&thorn;i to ben reuerenced. &para; Lat vs quod she &thorn;an adden reuerence to suffisaunce and to power  &para; So &thorn;at we demen &thorn;at &thorn;ise &thorn;re &thorn;inges ben alle o &thorn;ing.  &para; Certis quod I lat vs adden it. yif we willen graunten &thorn;e so&thorn;e. what demest &thorn;ou &thorn;an quod she is &thorn;at a dirke &thorn;ing and nat noble &thorn;at is suffisaunt reuerent and my&yogh;ty. or ellys &thorn;at is ry&yogh;t clere and ry&yogh;t noble of celebrete of renoun. &para; Considere &thorn;an quod she as we han grauntid her byforne. &thorn;at he &thorn;at ne ha&thorn; ne[de] of no &thorn;ing and is most my&yogh;ty and most digne of honour yif hym nedi&thorn; any clernesse of renoun whiche clernesse he my&yogh;t[e] nat graunten of hym self.  &para; So &thorn;at for lakke of &thorn;ilke clerenesse he my&yogh;t[e] seme febler on any syde or &thorn;e <PB N="84">more outcaste.  <FOREIGN LANG="l">Glosa.</FOREIGN> &thorn;is is to seyne nay.  &para; For who so &thorn;at is suffisaunt my&yogh;ty and reuerent. clernesse of renoun folwe&thorn; of &thorn;e forseide &thorn;inges. he ha&thorn; it alredy of hys suffisaunce.  <HI REND="i">boice</HI>. I may nat quod I denye it. &para; But I mot graunten as it is. &thorn;at &thorn;is &thorn;ing be ry&yogh;t celebrable by clernesse of renoun and noblesse.  &para; &thorn;an folwe&thorn; it quod she &thorn;at we adden clernesse of renoun to &thorn;e &thorn;re forseide &thorn;inges. so &thorn;at &thorn;er ne be amonges hem no difference. and &thorn;is is a consequente quod .I. &thorn;is &thorn;ing &thorn;an quod she &thorn;at ne ha&thorn; no nede of no foreine &thorn;ing. and &thorn;at may don alle &thorn;inges by his streng&thorn;es. and &thorn;at is noble and honourable. nis nat &thorn;at a myrie &thorn;ing and a ioyful.  <HI REND="i">boice</HI>. but wenest quod I &thorn;at any sorow my&yogh;t[e] comen to &thorn;is &thorn;ing &thorn;at is swiche. &para; Certys I may nat &thorn;inke. <HI REND="i">P.</HI> &para; &thorn;anne moten we graunt[e] quod she &thorn;at &thorn;is &thorn;ing be ful of gladnesse yif &thorn;e forseide &thorn;inges be so&thorn;e.  &para; And also certys mote we graunten. &thorn;at suffisaunce power noblesse reuerence and gladnesse ben only dyuerse bynames.  but hir substaunce ha&thorn; no diuersite.  <HI REND="i">Boice</HI>. It mot nedely be so quod .I. <HI REND="i">P.</HI> &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge &thorn;an quod she &thorn;at is oon and simple in his nature. 
 &thorn;e wikkednesse of men departi&thorn; it<MILESTONE N="20" UNIT="fol.">diuidi&thorn; it. and whan &thorn;ei enforcen hem to gete partie of a &thorn;ing &thorn;at ne ha&thorn; no part. &thorn;ei ne geten hem nei&thorn;er &thorn;ilk[e] partie &thorn;at nis none. ne &thorn;e &thorn;ing al hole &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne desire nat. <HI REND="i">.b.</HI>In whiche manere quod .I. <HI REND="i">p.</HI> &thorn;ilke man quod she &thorn;at seke&thorn; rychesse to fleen pouerte. he ne trauayle&thorn; hym nat to for to gete power for he ha&thorn; leuer ben dirk and vile. and eke wi&thorn;drawe&thorn; from hym selfe many naturel delit&yogh; for he nolde lesen &thorn;e moneye &thorn;at he ha&thorn; assembled. <PB N="85">but certis in &thorn;is manere he ne geti&thorn; hym nat suffisaunce &thorn;at power forleti&thorn;. and &thorn;at moleste preke&thorn;. and &thorn;at fil&thorn;e make&thorn; outcaste. and &thorn;at derknesse hide&thorn;. and certis he &thorn;at desire&thorn; only power he wasti&thorn; and scatri&thorn; rychesse and dispise&thorn; delices and eke honour &thorn;at is wi&thorn; out power. ne he ne preise&thorn; glorie no &thorn;ing. &para; Certys &thorn;us seest &thorn;ou wel &thorn;at many &thorn;ingus failen to hym. for he ha&thorn; somtyme faute of many necessites. and many anguysses biten hym &para; and whan he may nat don &thorn;o defautes awey. he forlete&thorn; to ben my&yogh;ty. and &thorn;at is &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at he most desire&thorn;. and ry&yogh;t &thorn;us may I make semblable resouns of honours and of glorie and of delices.  &para; For so as euery of &thorn;ise forseide &thorn;inges is &thorn;e same &thorn;at &thorn;ise o&thorn;er &thorn;inges ben. &thorn;at is to sein. al oon &thorn;ing. who so &thorn;at euer seke&thorn; to geten &thorn;at oon of &thorn;ise and nat &thorn;at o&thorn;er. he ne gete&thorn; nat &thorn;at he desire&thorn;. <HI REND="i">Boice</HI> .  &para; what seist &thorn;ou &thorn;an yif &thorn;at a man coueite&thorn; to geten alle &thorn;ise &thorn;inges to gider.  <HI REND="i">P.</HI> Certys quod she .I. wolde seie &thorn;at he wolde geten hym souereyne blisfulnes. but &thorn;at shal he nat fynde in &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at .I. haue shewed &thorn;at ne mowe nat &yogh;euen &thorn;at &thorn;ei byheten. <HI REND="i">boice</HI>. Certys no quod .I.  &para; &thorn;an quod she ne sholden men nat by no weye seken blysfulnesse in swiche &thorn;inges as men wenen &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne mowe &yogh;euen but o &thorn;ing senglely of alle &thorn;at men seken.  I graunt[e] wel quod .I. ne no so&thorn;er &thorn;ing ne may nat ben said.  <HI REND="i">P.</HI> &para; Now hast &thorn;ou &thorn;an quod she &thorn;e forme and &thorn;e causes of false welefulnesse.  &para; Now turne and flitte &thorn;e eyen of &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t. for &thorn;ere shalt &thorn;ou seen an oon &thorn;ilk verray blysfulnesse &thorn;at I haue byhy&yogh;t &thorn;ee.  <HI REND="i">b.</HI>Certys quod .I. it is cler and opyn. &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at it were to a blynde man. and &thorn;at shewedest &thorn;ou me [ful wel] a <PB N="86">lytel her byforne. whan &thorn;ou enforcedest &thorn;e to shewe me &thorn;e causes of &thorn;e false blysfulnesse &para; For but yif I be bygiled. &thorn;an is &thorn;ilke &thorn;e verray perfit blisfulnesse &thorn;at perfitly maki&thorn; a man suffisaunt. my&yogh;ty. honourable noble. and ful of gladnesse. and for &thorn;ou shalt wel knowe &thorn;at I haue wel vndirstonden &thorn;ise &thorn;inges wi&thorn; inne myne herte. I knowe wel &thorn;ilke blisfulnesse &thorn;at may verrayly &yogh;euen on of &thorn;e forseide &thorn;inges syn &thorn;ei ben al oon .I. knowe douteles &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing is &thorn;e fulle of blysfulnesse.  <HI REND="i">P.</HI>O my nurry quod she by &thorn;is oppinioun quod she I sey[e] &thorn;at &thorn;ou art blisful yif &thorn;ou putte &thorn;is &thorn;er to &thorn;at I shal seine. what is &thorn;at quod .I  &para; Trowest &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;er be any &thorn;ing in &thorn;is er&thorn;ely mortal toumblyng &thorn;inges &thorn;at may bryngen &thorn;is estat.  Certys quod I trowe it nat. and &thorn;ou hast shewed me wel &thorn;at ouer &thorn;ilke goode &thorn;er is no &thorn;ing more to ben desired.  <HI REND="i">P.</HI> &thorn;ise &thorn;inges &thorn;an quod she. &thorn;at is to seyne er&thorn;ely suffisaunce and power. and swiche &thorn;inges ey&thorn;er &thorn;ei semen likenesse of verray goode. or ellys it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ei &yogh;euen to mortal folk a maner of goodes &thorn;at ne ben nat perfit.  &para; But &thorn;ilke goode &thorn;at is verray and perfit. &thorn;at may &thorn;ei nat &yogh;euen. <HI REND="i">boice</HI>. I. accorde me wel quod .I. &thorn;an quod she for as moche as &thorn;ou hast knowen whiche is &thorn;ilke verray blisfulnesse. and eke whiche &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges ben &thorn;at lien falsly blisfulnesse.  &thorn;at is to seyne.  &thorn;at by desceit semen verray goodes.  &para; Now byhoue&thorn; &thorn;e to knowen <MILESTONE N="20b" UNIT="fol."> whennes and where &thorn;ou mowe seek[e] &thorn;ilke verray blisfulnesse.  &para; Certys quod I &thorn;at desijr I gretly and haue abiden longe tyme to herkene it.  &para; But for as moche quod she as it like&thorn; to my disciple plato in his book of in thimeo. &thorn;at in ry&yogh;t lytel &thorn;inges men sholde bysechen &thorn;e helpe of god.  &para; what iugest &thorn;ou &thorn;at be <PB N="87">[now] to done so &thorn;at we may deserue to fynde &thorn;e sete of &thorn;ilke souereyne goode.  <HI REND="i">B.</HI> &para; Certys quod .I. I. deme &thorn;at we shulle clepen to &thorn;e fadir of alle goodes.  &para; For wi&thorn; outen hym nis &thorn;er no &thorn;ing founden ary&yogh;t. &thorn;ou seist a-ry&yogh;t quod she. and bygan on-one to syngen ry&yogh;t &thorn;us.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="9" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">O QUI PERPETUA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>O &thorn;ou fadir creatour of heuene and of er&thorn;es &thorn;at gouernest &thorn;is worlde by perdurable resoun &thorn;at comaundist &thorn;e tymes for to gon from tyme &thorn;at age had[de] bygynnyng. &thorn;ou &thorn;at dwellest &thorn;i self ay stedfast and stable and &yogh;iuest alle o&thorn;er &thorn;inges to ben moeued. ne forein causes necesseden &thorn;e neuer to compoune werke of floterynge mater.  but only &thorn;e forme of souereyne goode y-set wi&thorn; inne [&thorn;e] wi&thorn; outen envie &thorn;at moeued[e] &thorn;e frely. &thorn;ou &thorn;at art al&thorn;erfairest beryng &thorn;e faire worlde in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t. formedest &thorn;is worlde to &thorn;e likkenesse semblable of &thorn;at faire worlde in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t. &thorn;ou drawest alle &thorn;inges of &thorn;i souereyne ensampler. and comaundedist &thorn;at &thorn;is worlde perfitlyche ymaked haue frely and absolut hyse perfit parties.  &para; &thorn;ou byndest &thorn;e element&yogh; by noumbres proporcionables.  &thorn;at &thorn;e colde &thorn;inges mowen accorde wi&thorn; &thorn;e hote &thorn;inges. and &thorn;e drye &thorn;inges wi&thorn; &thorn;e moyst &thorn;inges. &thorn;at &thorn;e fire &thorn;at is purest ne fleye nat ouer heye. ne &thorn;at &thorn;e heuynesse ne drawe nat adoun ouer lowe &thorn;e er&thorn;es &thorn;at ben plounged in &thorn;e watres. &para; &thorn;ou knyttest to-gidre &thorn;e mene soule of treble kynde moeuyng alle &thorn;inges. and diuidest it by membres accordynge. &para; And whan it is &thorn;us diuided it ha&thorn; assembled a moeuyng in two roundes.  &para; It go&thorn; to tourne <PB N="88">a&yogh;ein to hym owen self. and environe&thorn; a fulle deep &thorn;ou&yogh;t. and tourni&thorn; &thorn;e heuene by semblable ymage. &thorn;ou by euenlyk causes enhaunsest &thorn;e soules and &thorn;e lasse liues and ablynge hem heye by ly&yogh;t[e] cartes. &thorn;ou sewest hem in to heuene and in to er&thorn;e. and whan &thorn;ei ben conuertid to &thorn;e by &thorn;i benigne lawe.  &para; &thorn;ou makest hem retorne a&yogh;eine to &thorn;e by a&yogh;ein ledyng fijr.  &para; O fadir yif &thorn;ou to &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t to stien vp in to &thorn;i streite sete. and graunte [hym] to enviroune &thorn;e welle of good. and &thorn;e ly&yogh;te yfounde graunte hym to ficchen &thorn;e clere sy&yogh;tes of hys corage in &thorn;e.  &para; And scatre &thorn;ou and to-breke [thow] &thorn;e wey&yogh;tes and &thorn;e cloudes of er&thorn;ely heuynesse. and shyne &thorn;ou by &thorn;i bry&yogh;tnes. for &thorn;ou art clernesse &thorn;ou art peisible to debonaire folke.  &para; &thorn;ou &thorn;i self art bygynnynge. berere. ledere. pa&thorn; and terme to loke on &thorn;e [&thorn;at] is oure ende.  <HI REND="i">Glose</HI>.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="10" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUONIAM IGITUR QUI SCIT.</FOREIGN><NOTE>Read <FOREIGN LANG="l">que sit.</FOREIGN></NOTE></HEAD><P>FOr as moche &thorn;an as &thorn;ou hast seyn. whiche is &thorn;e forme of goode &thorn;at nys nat perfit. and whiche is &thorn;e forme of goode &thorn;at is perfit. now trowe I &thorn;at it were goode to shewe in what &thorn;is perfeccioun of blisfulnesse is set. and in &thorn;is &thorn;ing I trowe &thorn;at we sholden first enquere forto witen yif &thorn;at any swiche manere goode as &thorn;ilke goode &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast diffinissed a lytel her byforne. &thorn;at is to seine souereyne goode may be founden in &thorn;e nature of &thorn;inges.  For &thorn;at veyne ymaginacioun of &thorn;ou&yogh;t ne desceiue vs nat. and putte vs oute of &thorn;e so&thorn;efastnesse of &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge &thorn;at is summyttid to vs. &thorn;is is to seyne. but it may nat ben denoyed &thorn;at &thorn;ilke goode ne is. &para; and &thorn;at it nis ry&yogh;t as a welle of alle goodes.  &para; For 

<PB N="89">al &thorn;ing &thorn;at is cleped inperfit. is proued inperfit by &thorn;e amenusynge of perfeccioun. or of &thorn;ing &thorn;at is perfit. and her of come&thorn; it. &thorn;at in euery &thorn;ing general. yif &thorn;at. &thorn;at men seen any &thorn;ing &thorn;at is inperfit <MILESTONE N="21" UNIT="fol.">certys in &thorn;ilke general  
&thorn;er mot ben somme &thorn;ing &thorn;at is perfit.  &para; For yif so be &thorn;at perfeccioun is don awey. men may nat &thorn;inke nor seye fro whennes &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing is &thorn;at is cleped inperfit. &para; For &thorn;e nature of &thorn;inges ne token nat her bygynnyng of &thorn;inges amenused and inperfit. but it procedi&thorn; of &thorn;ingus &thorn;at ben al hool. and absolut. and descende&thorn; so doune in to outerest &thorn;inges and in to &thorn;ingus empty and wi&thorn; oute fruyt. but as I haue shewed a litel her byforne. &thorn;at yif &thorn;er be a blisfulnesse &thorn;at be frele and vein and inperfit. &thorn;er may no man doute. &thorn;at &thorn;er nys som blisfulnesse &thorn;at is sad stedfast and perfit. b. &thorn;is is concludid quod I fermely and so&thorn;efastly.  <HI REND="i">P.</HI> But considere also quod she in wham &thorn;is blisfulnesse enhabite&thorn;. &thorn;e commune acordaunce and conceite of &thorn;e corages of men proue&thorn; and graunte&thorn; &thorn;at god prince of alle &thorn;ingus is good.  &para; For so as no &thorn;ing ne may ben &thorn;ou&yogh;t bettre &thorn;an god. it may nat ben douted &thorn;an &thorn;at [he &thorn;at] no &thorn;ing is bettre. &thorn;at he nys good.  &para; Certys resoun shewe&thorn; &thorn;at god is so goode &thorn;at it proue&thorn; by verray force &thorn;at perfit goode is in hym.  &para; For yif god ne is swiche. he ne may nat ben prince of alle &thorn;inges. for certis som &thorn;ing possessyng in hym self perfit goode sholde ben more &thorn;an god. and [it] sholde seme &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing were first and elder &thorn;an god.  &para; For we han shewed apertly &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben perfit. ben first or &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben inperfit. &para; And for &thorn;i for as moche as [that] my resoun or my proces ne go nat awey wi&thorn;oute an ende.  we ou&yogh;t[e] to graunten &thorn;at &thorn;e souereyne god is ry&yogh;t ful of <PB N="90">souereyne perfit goode. and we han establissed &thorn;at &thorn;e souereyne goode is verrey blisfulnesse. &thorn;an mot it nedes ben [&thorn;at verray blysfulnesse is] yset in souereyne god. <HI REND="i">B.</HI> &thorn;is take I wel quod .I. ne &thorn;is ne may nat be wi&thorn;seid in no manere.  &para; But I preie &thorn;e quod she see now how &thorn;ou mayst preuen holily and wi&thorn;-outen corrupcioun &thorn;is &thorn;at I haue seid. &thorn;at &thorn;e souereyne god is ry&yogh;t ful of souereyne goode. [In whych manere quod I.] wenest &thorn;ou ou&yogh;t quod she &thorn;at &thorn;is prince of alle &thorn;inges haue ytake &thorn;ilke souereyne good any where &thorn;an of hym self. &para; of whiche souereyne goode men proue&thorn; &thorn;at he is ful ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ou my&yogh;test &thorn;inken. &thorn;at god &thorn;at ha&thorn; blisfulnesse in hym self. and &thorn;at ilke blisfulnesse &thorn;at is in hym were diuers in substaunce.  &para; For yif &thorn;ou wene &thorn;at god haue receyued &thorn;ilke good oute of hym self. &thorn;ou mayst wene &thorn;at he &thorn;at &yogh;af &thorn;ilke good to god. be more goode &thorn;an is god.  &para; But I am byknowen and confesse and &thorn;at ry&yogh;t dignely &thorn;at god is ry&yogh;t wor&thorn;i abouen alle &thorn;inges.  &para; And yif so be &thorn;at &thorn;is good be in hym by nature.  but &thorn;at it is diuers from [hym] by wenyng resoun. syn we speke of god prince of alle &thorn;inges feyne who so feyne may. who was he &thorn;at [hath] conioigned &thorn;ise diuers &thorn;inges to-gidre. and eke at &thorn;e last[e] se wel &thorn;at o &thorn;ing &thorn;at is diuers from any &thorn;ing. &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing nis nat &thorn;at same &thorn;ing. fro whiche it is vndirstonden to ben diuers. &thorn;an folwe&thorn; it. &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at by hys nature is dyuers from souereyne good. &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ing nys nat souereyne good. but certys &thorn;at were a felonous corsednesse to &thorn;inken &thorn;at of hym. &thorn;at no &thorn;ing nis more wor&thorn;e.  For alwey of alle &thorn;inges. &thorn;e nature <PB N="91">of hem ne may nat ben better &thorn;an his bygynnyng. &para; For whiche I may concluden by ry&yogh;t uerray resoun. &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;at is bygynnyng of alle &thorn;inges. &thorn;ilke same &thorn;ing is good in his substaunce.  <HI REND="i">B.</HI> &thorn;ou hast seid ry&yogh;tfully quod .I.  <HI REND="i">P.</HI> But we han graunted quod she &thorn;at souereyne good is blysfulnes. &thorn;at is so&thorn;e quod .I. &thorn;an quod she mote we nedes graunten and confessen &thorn;at &thorn;ilke same souereyne goode be god.  &para; Certys <MILESTONE N="21b" UNIT="fol.">quod .I. I ne may nat denye ne wi&thorn;stonde &thorn;e resouns purposed. and I see wel &thorn;at it folwe&thorn; by streng&thorn;e of &thorn;e premisses.  &para; Loke nowe quod she yif &thorn;is be proued [yit] more fermely &thorn;us.  &para; &thorn;at &thorn;er ne mowen nat ben two souereyne goodes &thorn;at ben diuerse amo[n]ges hem self. &thorn;at on is nat &thorn;at &thorn;at o&thorn;er is. &thorn;an [ne] mowen nei&thorn;er of hem ben perfit. so as ey&thorn;er of hem lakki&thorn; to o&thorn;ir. but &thorn;at &thorn;at nis nat perfit men may seen apertly &thorn;at it nis nat souereyne. &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;an &thorn;at ben souereynely goode ne mowen by no wey ben diuerse. &para; But I haue wel conclude &thorn;at blisfulnesse and god ben [the] souereyne goode. For whiche it mot nedes be &thorn;at souereyne blisfulnesse is souerey[ne] dyuynite.  &para; No &thorn;ing quod I nis more so&thorn;efast &thorn;an &thorn;is ne more ferme by resoun. ne a more wor&thorn;i &thorn;ing &thorn;an god may nat ben concluded.  <HI REND="i">P.</HI> vpon &thorn;ise &thorn;inges &thorn;an quod she. ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ise geometriens whan &thorn;ei han shewed her proposiciouns ben wont to bryngen in &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ei clepen porismes or declaraciouns of forseide &thorn;inges. ry&yogh;t so wil I &yogh;eue &thorn;e here as a corolarie or a mede of coroune.  For whi. for as moche as by &thorn;e getynge of blisfulnesse men ben maked blysful. and blisfulnesse is diuinite.  &para; &thorn;an is it manifest and open &thorn;at by &thorn;e getyng of diuinite men ben makid blisful.  ry&yogh;t as by &thorn;e getynge of iustice .  .  .  <PB N="92">and by &thorn;e getyng of sapience &thorn;ei ben maked wise. &para; Ry&yogh;t so nedes by &thorn;e semblable resoun whan &thorn;ei han getyn diuinite &thorn;ei ben maked goddys. &thorn;an is euery blisful man god.  &para; But certis by nature. &thorn;er nys but oon god. but by &thorn;e participaciouns of diuinite &thorn;ere ne lette&thorn; ne disturbe&thorn; no &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;er ne ben many goddes.  &para; &thorn;is is quod .I. a faire &thorn;ing and a precious.  &para; Clepe it as &thorn;ou wolt. be it corolarie or porisme or mede of coroune or declarynges  &para; Certys quod she no &thorn;ing nis fairer. &thorn;an is &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at by resoun sholde ben added to &thorn;ise forseide &thorn;inges. what &thorn;ing quod .I.  &para; So quod she as it seme&thorn; &thorn;at blisfulnesse conteni&thorn; many &thorn;inges. it were forto witen whe&thorn;ir [&thorn;at] alle &thorn;ise &thorn;inges maken or conioignen as a maner body of blysfulnesse by diuersite of parties or [of] membris.  Or ellys yif any of alle &thorn;ilke &thorn;ingus be swyche &thorn;at it acomplise by hym self &thorn;e substaunce of blisfulnesse. so &thorn;at alle &thorn;ise o&thorn;er &thorn;inges ben referred and brou&yogh;t to blisfulnesse. &thorn;at is to seyne as to &thorn;e chief of hem.  &para; I wolde quod I &thorn;at &thorn;ou makedest me clerly to vndirstonde what &thorn;ou seist. and &thorn;at &thorn;ou recordest me &thorn;e forseide &thorn;inges.  &para; Haue I nat iuged quod she. &thorn;at blisfulnesse is goode. &yogh;is forso&thorn;e quod .I. and &thorn;at souereyne goode.  &para; Adde &thorn;an quod she &thorn;ilke goode &thorn;at is maked blisfulnes to alle &thorn;e forseide &thorn;inges.  &para; For &thorn;ilke same blisfulnesse &thorn;at is demed to ben souereyne suffisaunce.  &thorn;ilke self is souereyne power. souereyne reuerence. souereyne clernesse or noblesse and souereyne delit. what seist &thorn;ou &thorn;an of alle &thorn;ise &thorn;inges. &thorn;at is to seyne. suffisance power and &thorn;ise o&thorn;er &thorn;inges. ben &thorn;ei &thorn;an as membris of blisfulnesse. or ben &thorn;ei referred and brou&yogh;t to souereyne good. &para; Ry&yogh;t as alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben brou&yogh;t to &thorn;e chief of hem. <PB N="93"><HI REND="i">b.</HI> I vndirstonde wel quod .I. what &thorn;ou purposest to seke. but I desijr[e] to herkene &thorn;at &thorn;ou shewe it me. <HI REND="i">p.</HI> Take now &thorn;us &thorn;e discressioun of &thorn;is questioun quod she. yif al &thorn;ise &thorn;inges quod she weren membris to felicite. &thorn;an weren &thorn;ei diuerse &thorn;at oon fro &thorn;at o&thorn;er. &para; And swiche is &thorn;e nature of parties or of membris. &thorn;at dyuerse membris compounen a body.  &para; Certis quod I it ha&thorn; wel ben shewed her byforne. &thorn;at alle &thorn;ise &thorn;inges ben alle on &thorn;ing. &thorn;an ben &thorn;ei none membris quod she. for ellys it sholde seme &thorn;at blisfulnesse were conioigned <MILESTONE N="22" UNIT="fol.">al of one membre alone. but &thorn;at is a &thorn;ing  
&thorn;at may nat ben doon. &thorn;is &thorn;ing quod .I. nys nat doutous. but I abide to herkene &thorn;e remenaunt of &thorn;e questioun. &thorn;is is open and clere quod she. &thorn;at alle o&thorn;er &thorn;inges ben referred and brou&yogh;t to goode.  &para; For &thorn;erfore is suffisaunce requered.  For it is demed to ben good. and for&thorn;i is power requered. for men trowen also &thorn;at it be goode. and &thorn;is same &thorn;ing mowe we &thorn;inken and coueiten of reuerence and of noblesse and of delit. &thorn;an is souereyne good &thorn;e soume and &thorn;e cause of alle &thorn;at au&yogh;t[e] be desired. forwhi &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at wi&thorn;-holde&thorn; no good in it self ne semblaunce of goode it ne may nat wel in no manere be desired ne requered. and &thorn;e contrarie. For &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;inges by hir nature ne ben nat goode algates yif men wene &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben goode &yogh;it ben &thorn;ei desired as &thorn;ou&yogh; [&thorn;at] &thorn;ei were verrayly goode. and &thorn;erfore is it &thorn;at men au&yogh;ten to wene by ry&yogh;t &thorn;at bounte be souereyne fyn and &thorn;e cause of alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben to requeren.  &para; But certis &thorn;ilke &thorn;at is cause for whiche men requeren any &thorn;ing.  &para; it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ilke same &thorn;ing be most desired. as &thorn;us yif &thorn;at a wy&yogh;t wolde ryde for cause of hele.  he ne desire&thorn; nat so mychel &thorn;e <PB N="94">moeuyng to ryden as &thorn;e effect of his heele.  Now &thorn;an syn &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges ben requered for &thorn;e grace of good. &thorn;ei ne ben [nat] desired of alle folk more &thorn;an &thorn;e same good  &para; But we han graunted &thorn;at blysfulnesse is &thorn;at &thorn;ing for whiche &thorn;at alle &thorn;ise o&thorn;er &thorn;inges ben desired. &thorn;an is it &thorn;us &thorn;at certis only blisfulnesse is requered and desired  &para; By whiche &thorn;ing it shewe&thorn; clerely &thorn;at good and blisfulnesse is al oone and &thorn;e same substaunce. &para; I se nat quod I wher fore &thorn;at men my&yogh;t[en] discorden in &thorn;is. <HI REND="i">p.</HI> and we han shewed &thorn;at god and verrey blysfulnesse is al oon &thorn;ing &para; &thorn;at is so&thorn;e quod .I. &thorn;an mowe we conclude sikerly &thorn;at &thorn;e substaunce of god is set in &thorn;ilke same good and in noon o&thorn;er place.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="10" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">NUNC OMNES PARITER ETC.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>O Come&thorn; alle to-gidre now &yogh;e &thorn;at ben ycau&yogh;t and ybounde wi&thorn; wicked[e] cheines by &thorn;e deceiuable delit of er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges inhabytynge in &yogh;oure &thorn;ou&yogh;t. here shal ben &thorn;e reste of &yogh;oure laboures. here is &thorn;e hauene stable in peisible quiete. &thorn;is al oone is &thorn;e open refut to wreches.  <FOREIGN LANG="l">Glosa.</FOREIGN>  &thorn;is is to seyn. &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;at ben combred and deceyued wi&thorn; worldly affecciouns come&thorn; now to &thorn;is souereyne good &thorn;at is god. &thorn;at is refut to hem &thorn;at wolen come to hym.  <FOREIGN LANG="l">Textus.</FOREIGN>  &para; Alle &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;e ryuere Tagus &yogh;iue&thorn; &yogh;ow wi&thorn; his golden[e] grauels. or ellys alle &thorn;e &thorn;ynges &thorn;at &thorn;e ryuere hermus. &yogh;iue&thorn; wi&thorn; his rede brynke. or &thorn;at yndus &yogh;iue&thorn; &thorn;at is nexte &thorn;e hote partie of &thorn;e worlde.  &thorn;at medele&thorn; &thorn;e grene stones (smaragde) wi&thorn; &thorn;e white (margarits). ne sholde nat cleren &thorn;e lokynge of &yogh;oure &thorn;o&yogh;t. but hiden ra&thorn;er &yogh;oure blynde corages wi&thorn; inne hire dirkenesse  &para; Alle &thorn;at like&thorn; &yogh;ow here and exciti&thorn; and moeue&thorn; &yogh;oure &thorn;ou&yogh;tes. <PB N="95">&thorn;e er&thorn;e ha&thorn; noryshed it in hys lowe caues. but &thorn;e shynyng by &thorn;e whiche &thorn;e heuene is gouerned and whennes &thorn;at it ha&thorn; hys streng&thorn;e &thorn;at chase&thorn; &thorn;e derke ouer&thorn;rowyng of &thorn;e soule.  &para; And who so euer may knowen &thorn;ilke ly&yogh;t of blisfulnesse. he shal wel seine &thorn;at &thorn;e white bemes of &thorn;e sonne ne ben nat cleer.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="11" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">ASSENCIOR INQUAM CUNCTA.</FOREIGN>  Boice.</HEAD><P>I assent[e] me quod .I. For alle &thorn;ise &thorn;inges ben strongly bounden wi&thorn; ry&yogh;t ferme resouns. how mychel wilt &thorn;ou preisen it quod she. yif &thorn;at &thorn;ou knowe what &thorn;ilke goode is. I wol preise it quod I by price wi&thorn; outen ende.  &para; yif it shal bytyde me to knowe also to-gidre god &thorn;at is good.  &para; certys quod she &thorn;at shal I do &thorn;e by verray resoun. yif &thorn;at &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at I haue conclude[d] a litel her by <MILESTONE N="22b" UNIT="fol.">forne dwellen oonly  
in hir first[e] grauntyng.  <HI REND="i">Boice</HI>. &thorn;ei dwellen graunted to &thorn;e quod .I. &thorn;is is to seyne as who sei&thorn; .I. graunt &thorn;i forseide conclusiouns.  &para; Haue I nat shewed &thorn;e quod she &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben requered of many folke. ne ben nat verray goodes ne perfit. for &thorn;ei ben diuerse &thorn;at oon fro &thorn;at o&thorn;er. and so as eche of hem is lakkyng to o&thorn;er. &thorn;ei ne han no power to bryngen a good &thorn;at is ful and absolute.  &para; But &thorn;an atte arst ben &thorn;ei verray good whan &thorn;ei ben gadred to-gidre al in to a forme and in to oon wirchyng. so &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at is suffisaunce. &thorn;ilk same be power and reuerence. and noblesse and mir&thorn;e.  &para; And forso&thorn;e but alle &thorn;ise &thorn;inges ben alle o same &thorn;ing &thorn;ei ne han nat wher by &thorn;at &thorn;ei mowen ben put in &thorn;e noumbre of &thorn;inges. &thorn;at au&yogh;ten ben requered or desired.  <HI REND="i">b.</HI> &para; It is shewed quod .I. ne her of may &thorn;er no man douten. <HI REND="i">p.</HI> &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;an quod she &thorn;at ne <PB N="96">ben none goodes whan &thorn;ei ben diuerse. and whan &thorn;ei bygynnen to ben al o &thorn;ing. &thorn;an ben &thorn;ei goodes.  ne comi&thorn; it hem nat &thorn;an by &thorn;e getynge of unite &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben maked goodes. <HI REND="i">b.</HI> so it seme&thorn; quod .I. but alle &thorn;ing &thorn;at is good quod she grauntest &thorn;ou &thorn;at it be good by participacioun of good or no.  &para; I graunt[e] it quod .I. &para; &thorn;an mayst &thorn;ou graunt[en] it quod she by sembleable resoun &thorn;at oon and good ben o same &thorn;ing.  &para; For of &thorn;inges [of] whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e effect nis nat naturely diuerse nedys &thorn;e substaunce mot ben o same &thorn;inge I ne may nat denye it quod I.  &para; Hast &thorn;ou nat knowen wel quod she. &thorn;at al &thorn;ing &thorn;at is ha&thorn; so longe his dwellyng and his substaunce. as longe is it oone.  &para; but whan it forleti&thorn; to ben oone it mot nedis dien and corrumpe to-gidre. &para; In whiche manere quod .I.  &para; Ry&yogh;t as in beestes quod she.  whan &thorn;e soule and &thorn;e body ben conioigned in oon and dwellen to-gidre it is cleped a beest. and whan hire vnite is destroied by disseueraunce &thorn;at oon fram &thorn;at o&thorn;ir. &thorn;an shewe&thorn; it wel &thorn;at it is a dede &thorn;ing. and &thorn;at it is no lenger no beste. and &thorn;e body of a wy&yogh;t while it dwelle&thorn; in oon forme by coniunccioun of membris it is wel seyn &thorn;at it is a figure of mankynde. and yif &thorn;e partyes of &thorn;e body ben [so] diuide[d] and disseuered &thorn;at oon fro &thorn;at o&thorn;ir &thorn;at &thorn;ei destroien vnite. &thorn;e body forleti&thorn; to ben &thorn;at it was byforne. &para; And who so wolde renne in &thorn;e same manere by alle &thorn;inges he sholde seen &thorn;at wi&thorn; outen doute euery &thorn;inge is in his substaunce as longe as it is oon. and whan it forleti&thorn; to ben oon it die&thorn; and perissi&thorn;. <HI REND="i">boice</HI>. whan I considre quod I many &thorn;inges I see noon o&thorn;er. &para; Is &thorn;er any &thorn;ing &thorn;anne quod she &thorn;at in as moche as it lyue&thorn; naturely. &thorn;at forleti&thorn; &thorn;e appetit or talent of <PB N="97">hys beynge. and desire&thorn; to come to dee&thorn; and to corrupcioun. &para; yif I considere quod I &thorn;e beestes &thorn;at han any manere nature of willynge or of nillynge I ne fynde no &thorn;ing. but yif it be constreyned fro wi&thorn; out for&thorn;e. &thorn;at forleti&thorn; or dispise&thorn; to lyue and to duren or &thorn;at wole his &thorn;ankes hasten hym to dien.  &para; For euery beest trauayle&thorn; hym to defende and kepe &thorn;e sauuacioun of lijf. and eschewe&thorn; dee&thorn; and destruccioun. <HI REND="i">b.</HI> but certys I doute me of herbes and of trees. &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;at I am in a doute of swiche &thorn;inges as herbes or trees &thorn;at ne han no felyng soule. ne no naturel wirchynges seruyng to appetite as beestes han whe&thorn;er &thorn;ei han appetite to dwellen and to duren.  &para; Certis quod she ne &thorn;er of &thorn;ar &thorn;e nat doute.  &para; Now look vpon &thorn;ise herbes and &thorn;ise trees. &thorn;ei waxen firste in swiche place as ben couenable to hem. in whiche place &thorn;ei ne mowen nat sone dien ne dryen as longe as hire nature may defenden hem.  &para; For some of hem waxen in feldes and some in mountaignes. and o&thorn;ir waxen in mareis.  <NOTE REND="i">A leaf lost here, and supplied from C.</NOTE>[and oothre cleuyn on Roches / and soume waxen plentyuos in sondes / and yif &thorn;at any wyht enforce hym to beryn hem in to oother places / they wexen drye // For nature yeueth to euery thing &thorn;at / &thorn;at is conuenient to hym and trauaylith &thorn;at they ne dye nat as longe as they han power to dwellyn and to lyuen // what woltow seyn of this / &thorn;at they drawen alle hyr norysshynges by hyr rootes / ryht as they haddyn hyr Mowthes I.-plounged with in the erthes / and shedyn by hyr maryes (i. medullas) hyr wode and hyr bark / and what woltow seyn of this &thorn;at thilke thing / &thorn;at is ryht softe as the marye (i. sapp) is / &thorn;at is alwey hidd in the feete al with inne and &thorn;at it is defendid fro with owte by the stidefastnesse of wode // and &thorn;at the vttereste bark is put ayenis the destempraunce <PB N="98">of the heuene / as a defendowr myhty to suffren harm / and thus certes maystow wel sen / how gret is the diligence of nature / For alle thinges renouelen and pupllisen hem withseed.I.-multiplyed / ne ther nis no man &thorn;at ne wot wel &thorn;at they ne ben ryht as a foundement and edyfice for to duren / nat only for a tyme / but ryht as forto duren perdurablely by generacyoun // and the thinges ek &thorn;atmen wenen ne hauen none sowles / ne desire they natech of hem by sem[b]lable resoun to kepyn &thorn;at that is hirs / &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;at is acordynge to hyr nature in conseruacioun of hyr beynge and endurynge // For wher for elles berith lythnesse the flaumbes vp / and the weyhte presseth the erthe a-doun // but For as moche as thilke places and thilke moeuynges ben couenable to euerich of hem // and forsothe euery thing kepith thilke &thorn;at is acordynge and propre to hym // ryht as thinges &thorn;at ben contraryes and enemys corompen hem // and yit the harde thinges as stoones clyuen and holden hyr partyes to gydere ryht faste and harde / and deffenden hem in withstondenge &thorn;at they ne departe nat lyhtly a twyne // and the thinges &thorn;at ben softe and fletynge as is water and Eyr they departyn lyhtly // and yeuen place to hem &thorn;at brekyn or deuyden hem // but natheles they retornen sone ayein in to the same thinges fro whennes they ben arraced // but fyr [fleet&hbar;] and refuseth alle deuysyoun / ne I. ne trete nat heere now of weleful moeuynges of the sowle &thorn;at is knowynge // but of the naturel entencioun of thinges // As thus ryht as we swolwe the mete &thorn;at we resseyuen and ne thinke nat on it / and as we drawen owre breth in slepynge &thorn;at we wite it nat whil we slepyt // For certes in the beestys the loue of hyr lyuynges ne of hyr beeinges ne comth nat of the wilnynges of the sowle // but of the bygynnyngis of nature // For certes thorw constreynynge causes / wil desireth and embraceth ful <PB N="99">ofte tyme / the deth &thorn;at nature dredith // that is to seyn as thus that a man may be constreynyd so by som cause that his wil desireth and taketh the deth which &thorn;at nature hateth and dredeth ful sore // And som tyme we seeth the contrarye / as thus that the wil of a wight / destorbeth and constreyneth &thorn;at &thorn;at nature desireth / and requereth al-wey // that is to sein the werk of generacioun / by the whiche generacioun only / dwelleth and is sustenyd the longe durablete of mortal thinges // And thus this charite and this Loue &thorn;at euery thing hath to hym self ne comth nat of the moeuynge of the sowle / but of the entencioun of nature // For the puruyance of god hat yeuen to thinges &thorn;at ben creat of hym / this &thorn;at is a ful gret cause / to lyuen and to duren / for which they desiren naturelly hyr lyf as longe as euer they mowen // For w[h]ych thou maist nat drede by no manere / that alle the thinges / that ben anywhere / that they ne requeren naturelly / the ferme stablenesse of perdurable dwellynge / and ek the eschuynge of destruccyoun // B // now confesse I. wel quod I. that I. see wel now certeynly / with owte dowtes / the thinges that whylom semeden vncerteyn to me / P.// but quod she thilke thyng &thorn;at desiret&hbar; to be and to dwellyn perdurablely / he desireth to ben oon // For yif &thorn;at that oon weere destroied // certes beinge ne shulde ther non dwellyn to no wiht // that is soth quod I. // Thanne quod she desirin alle thinges oon // .I. assente quod .I. // and I haue shewyd quod she that thilke same oon is thilke that is good // B // ye forsothe quod I. // Alle thinges thanne quod she requyren good // And thilke good thanne [&thorn;ow] maist descryuen ryht thus // Good is thilke thing &thorn;at euery wyht desireth // Ther ne may be thowht quod .I. no moore verray thing / for either alle thinges ben referred and browht to nowht / and floteryn with owte gouernour <PB N="100">despoiled of oon / as of hir propre heued / or elles yif ther be any thinge / to which &thorn;at alle thinges tenden and hyen / that thing moste ben the souereyn good of alle goodes / P /. thanne seyde she thus // O my norry quod she I haue gret gladnesse of the // For thow hast fichched in thin herte the myddel sothtfastnesse // that is to seyn the prykke // but this thing hath ben descouered to the / in that thow seydyst &thorn;at thow wystest nat a lytel her by-forn // what was that quod I. // That thow ne wystest nat quod she whych was the ende of thinges // and Certes that is the thing &thorn;at euery wiht desireth // and for as mochel as we han gaderid / and comprehendyd that good is thilke thing that is desired of alle / thanne moten we nedes confessun / that good is the fyn of alle thinges.</P></DIV2><DIV2 REND="11" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUISQUIS PROFUNDA MENTE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Who so that sekith sot&hbar; by a deep thoght And coueyteth nat to ben deseyuyd by no mys-weyes // lat hym rollen and trenden with Inne hym self / the Lyht of his inward syhte // And lat hym gadere ayein enclynynge in to a compas the longe moeuynges of hys thowhtes / And lat hym techen his corage that he hath enclosed and hyd / in his tresors / al &thorn;at he compaseth or sekith fro with owte // And thanne thilke thing that the blake cloude of errour whilom hadde y-couered / shal lyhten more clerly thanne phebus hym self ne shyneth // <FOREIGN LANG="l">Glosa</FOREIGN><NOTE>Chaucer's gloss.</NOTE> // who so wole seken the dep[e] grounde / of soth in his thowht / and wol nat be deceyuyd by false proposiciouns / that goon amys fro the trouthe // lat hym wel examine / and rolle with inne hym self the nature and the propretes of the thing // and lat hym yit eft sones examine and rollen his thowhtes by good deliberacioun <PB N="101">or that he deme // and lat hym techen his sowle that it hat by naturel pryncyplis kyndeliche y-hyd with in it self alle the trowthe the whiche he ymagynith to ben in thinges with owte // And thanne alle the dyrknesse of his mysknowynge shal seen more euydently to [&thorn;e] syhte of his vndyrstondynge thanne the sonne ne semyth to [&thorn;e] syhte with owte forth / For certes the body bryngynge the weyhte of foryetynge / ne hath nat chasyd owt of yowre thowhte al the clernesse of yowre knowyng // For certeynly the seed of sooth haldith and clyueth with in yowre corage / and it is a-waked and excited by the wynde and by the blastes of doctryne // For where for elles demen ye of yowre owne wyl the ryhtes whan ye ben axed // but yif so were &thorn;at the noryssynges of resoun ne lyuede .I.-plowngyd in the depthe of yowre herte // this [is] to seyn how sholden men demen &thorn;e sooth of any thing &thorn;at weere axed / yif ther neere a Roote of sothfastnesse &thorn;at weere yplowngyd and hyd in the nature[l] pryncyplis / the whiche sothfastnesse lyued with in the depnesse of the thowght // and yif so be &thorn;at the Muse and the doctryne of plato syngyth sooth // al &thorn;at euery whyht lerneth / he ne doth no thing elles thanne but recordeth as men recordyn thinges &thorn;at ben foryetyn.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="12" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">TUM EGO PLATONI INQUAM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Thanne seide I thus // I acorde me gretly to plato / for thow remenbrist and recordist me thise thinges yit] <NOTE> Addit. MS. 10,340, fol. 23.</NOTE>&thorn;e seconde tyme. &thorn;at is to seyn. first whan I lost[e] my memorie by &thorn;e contagio&umacr;s coniunccioun of &thorn;e body wi&thorn; &thorn;e soule. and eftsones afterward whan I lost[e] it confounded by &thorn;e charge and by &thorn;e burden of my sorwe. &para; And &thorn;an sayde she &thorn;us.  &para; If &thorn;ou look[e] quod she firste &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast graunted it ne shal nat 

<PB N="102">ben ry&yogh;t feer &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne shalt remembren &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou seidest &thorn;at &thorn;ou nistest nat. what &thorn;ing quod I. &para; by whiche gouerment quod she &thorn;at &thorn;is worlde is gouerned.  Me remembri&thorn; it wel quod I. and I confesse wel &thorn;at I ne wist[e] it nat &para; But al be it so &thorn;at I se now from afer what &thorn;ou purposest &para; Algates I desire &yogh;it to herkene it of &thorn;e more pleynely.  &para; &thorn;ou ne wendest nat quod she a litel here byforne &thorn;at men sholden doute &thorn;at &thorn;is worlde is gouerned by god. &para; Certys quod I ne &yogh;itte doute I it nau&yogh;t. ne I nil neuer wene &thorn;at it were to doute. as who sei&thorn;. but I wot wel &thorn;at god gouerne&thorn; &thorn;is worlde.  &para; And I shal shortly answere &thorn;e by what resouns I am brou&yogh;t to &thorn;is. &para; &thorn;is worlde quod I of so many dyuerse and contrarious parties ne my&yogh;ten neuer han ben assembled in o forme. but yif &thorn;ere ne were oon &thorn;at conioigned so many[e diuerse] &thorn;inges.  &para; And &thorn;e same diuersite of hire natures &thorn;at so discordeden &thorn;at oon fro &thorn;at o&thorn;er most[e] departen and vnioignen &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben conioigned. yif &thorn;ere ne were oon &thorn;at contened[e] &thorn;at he ha&thorn; conioigned and ybounde. ne &thorn;e certein ordre of nature ne sholde. nat brynge fur&thorn;e so ordinee moeuynge. by places. by tymes. by doynges. by spaces. by qualites. yif &thorn;ere ne were oon &thorn;at were ay stedfast dwellynge. &thorn;at ordeyned[e] and disposed[e] &thorn;ise diuersites of moeuynges.  &para; and &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge what so euer it be. by whiche &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges ben maked and ylad.  I clepe hym god &thorn;at is a worde &thorn;at is vsed to alle folke. &thorn;an seide she. syn &thorn;ou felest &thorn;us &thorn;ise &thorn;inges quod she. I trowe &thorn;at I haue lytel more to done. &thorn;at &thorn;ou my&yogh;ty of <PB N="103">wilfulnesse hool and sounde ne se eftsones &thorn;i contre. &para; But lat vs loken &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at we han purposed herbyforn. &para; Haue I nat noumbred and seid quod she &thorn;at suffisaunce is in blisfulnesse. and we han accorded &thorn;at god is and &thorn;ilke same blisfulnesse.  &para; yis forso&thorn;e quod I. and &thorn;at to gouerne &thorn;is worlde quod she. ne shal he neuer han nede of none helpe fro wi&thorn;oute. for ellys yif he had[de] nede of any helpe. he ne sholde not haue [no] ful suffisaunce. &yogh;is &thorn;us it mot nedes be quod I. &para; &thorn;an ordeyne&thorn; he by hym self al oon alle &thorn;inges quod she. &thorn;at may nat ben denied quod I.  &para; And I haue shewed &thorn;at god is &thorn;e same good.  &para; It remembre&thorn; me wel quod I.  &para; &thorn;an ordeine&thorn; he alle &thorn;inges by &thorn;ilke goode quod she.  Syn he whiche we han accorded to ben good gouerne&thorn; alle &thorn;ingus by hym self. and he is a keye and a stiere by whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e edifice of &thorn;is worlde is ykept stable and wi&thorn; oute corumpynge &para; I accorde me gretly quod I. and I aperceiuede a litel here byforn &thorn;at &thorn;ou woldest seyne &thorn;us.  Al be it so &thorn;at it were by a &thorn;inne suspecioun. I trowe it wel quod she.  &para; For as I trowe &thorn;ou leedest nowe more ententifly &thorn;ine eyen to loken &thorn;e verray goodes &para; but na&thorn;eles &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at I shal telle &thorn;e &yogh;it ne shewe&thorn; nat lasse to loken. what is &thorn;at quod I.  &para; So as men trowen quod she and &thorn;at ry&yogh;tfully &thorn;at god gouerne&thorn; alle &thorn;inges by &thorn;e keye of his goodnesse.  &para; And alle &thorn;ise same &thorn;inges as I [haue] tau&yogh;t &thorn;e. hasten hem by naturel entencioun to comen to goode &thorn;er may no man douten. &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne ben gouerned uoluntariely. and &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne conuerten [hem] nat of her owen wille to &thorn;e wille of hire ordenour. as &thorn;ei &thorn;at ben accordyng and enclinynge to her gouernour <PB N="104">
 and her kyng.  &para; It mot nedys be so quod. I.<MILESTONE N="23b" UNIT="fol.">&para; For &thorn;e realme ne sholde not seme blisful &yogh;if &thorn;ere were a &yogh;ok of mysdrawynges in diuerse parties ne &thorn;e sauynge of obedient &thorn;inges ne sholde nat be. &thorn;an is &thorn;ere no &thorn;ing quod she &thorn;at kepi&thorn; hys nature&meper; &thorn;at enforce&thorn; hym to gone a&yogh;eyne god.  &para; No quod. I. &para; And if &thorn;at any &thorn;ing enforced[e] hym to wi&thorn;stonde god. my&yogh;t[e] it auayle at &thorn;e laste a&yogh;eyns hym &thorn;at we han graunted to ben al my&yogh;ty by &thorn;e ry&yogh;t of blisfulnesse.  &para; Certis quod I al outerly it ne my&yogh;t[e] nat auaylen hym. &thorn;an is &thorn;ere no &thorn;ing quod she &thorn;at ey&thorn;er wol or may wi&thorn;stonde to &thorn;is souereyne good.  &para; I trowe nat quod.  I  &para; &thorn;an is &thorn;ilke &thorn;e souereyne good quod she &thorn;at alle &thorn;ingus gouerne&thorn; strongly and ordeyne&thorn; hem softly. &thorn;an seide I &thorn;us. I delite me quod I nat oonly in &thorn;e endes or in &thorn;e sommes of [the] resouns &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast concludid and proued.  &para; But &thorn;ilke wordes &thorn;at &thorn;ou vsest deliten me moche more.  &para; So at &thorn;e last[e] fooles &thorn;at somtyme renden greet[e] &thorn;inges au&yogh;ten ben asshamed of hem self.  &para; &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;at we fooles &thorn;at reprehenden wickedly &thorn;e &thorn;ingus &thorn;at touchen goddes gouernaunce we au&yogh;ten ben asshamed of oure self.  As I &thorn;at seide god refuse&thorn; oonly &thorn;e werkes of men. and ne entremeti&thorn; nat of hem. <HI REND="i">p.</HI> &thorn;ou hast wel herd quod she &thorn;e fables of &thorn;e poetes. how &thorn;e geauntes assailden &thorn;e heuene wi&thorn; &thorn;e goddes. but for so&thorn;e &thorn;e debonaire force of god disposed[e] hem so as it was wor&thorn;i. &thorn;at is to seyne distroied[e] &thorn;e geauntes. as it was wor&thorn;i.  &para; But wilt &thorn;ou &thorn;at we ioygnen togedre &thorn;ilke same resouns. for perauenture of swiche coniunccioun may sterten vp some faire sperkele of so&thorn;e  &para; Do quod I as &thorn;e list. wenest &thorn;ou quod she <PB N="105">&thorn;at god ne is almy&yogh;ty. no man is in doute of it. Certys quod I no wy&yogh;t ne defendi&thorn; it if he be in hys mynde. but he quod she &thorn;at is al my&yogh;ty &thorn;ere nis no &thorn;ing &thorn;at he ne may do. &thorn;at is so&thorn;e quod I.  May god done yuel quod she. nay for so&thorn;e quod. I.  &para; &thorn;an is yuel no &thorn;ing quod she.  &para; Syn &thorn;at he ne may not done yuel &thorn;at may done alle &thorn;inges. scornest &thorn;ou me quod. I. or ellys pleyest &thorn;ou or deceiuest &thorn;ou me. &thorn;at hast so wouen me wi&thorn; &thorn;i resouns. &thorn;e house of didalus so entrelaced. &thorn;at it is vnable to ben vnlaced. &thorn;ou &thorn;at o&thorn;er while entrest &thorn;ere &thorn;ou issest and o&thorn;er while issest &thorn;ere &thorn;ou entrest. ne fooldest &thorn;ou nat to gidre by replicacioun of wordes a maner wondirful cercle or envirounynge of symplicite deuyne.  &para; For certys a litel her byforne whan &thorn;ou bygunne atte blisfulnesse &thorn;ou seidest &thorn;at it is souereyne good. and seidest &thorn;at it is set in souereyne god. and &thorn;at god is &thorn;e ful[le] blisfulnesse. for whiche &thorn;ou &yogh;af[e] me as a couenable &yogh;ifte. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;at no wy&yogh;t nis blisful. but yif he be good al so &thorn;er wi&thorn; and seidest eke &thorn;at &thorn;e forme of goode is &thorn;e substaunce of god. and of blisfulnesse. and seidest &thorn;at &thorn;ilke same oone is &thorn;ilke same goode &thorn;at is requered and desired of al &thorn;e kynde of &thorn;inges. and &thorn;ou proeuedest in disputynge &thorn;at god gouerne&thorn; alle [the] &thorn;inges of &thorn;e worlde by &thorn;e gouernementys of bountee. and seydest &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges wolen ybeyen to hym. and seidest &thorn;at &thorn;e nature of yuel nis no &thorn;ing. and &thorn;ise &thorn;inges ne shewedest &thorn;ou nat wi&thorn; no resouns ytake fro wi&thorn;oute but by proues in cercles and homelyche knowen.  &para; &thorn;e whiche proeues drawen to hem self hir fei&thorn; and hir accorde eueriche [of] hem of o&thorn;er. &thorn;an seide she &thorn;us. I ne scorne &thorn;e nat ne pleye ne desseyue <PB N="106">&thorn;e. but I haue shewed to &thorn;e &thorn;inge &thorn;at is grettest ouer alle &thorn;inges by &thorn;e &yogh;ifte of god &thorn;at we some tyme prayden &para; For &thorn;is is &thorn;e forme of [the] deuyne substaunce. &thorn;at is swiche &thorn;at it ne slyde&thorn; nat in to outerest foreine &thorn;inges. ne ne rec[e]yue&thorn; no strange &thorn;inges in hym. but ry&yogh;t as parmaynws seide in grek of &thorn;ilke deuyne substaunce. he seide &thorn;us &thorn;at &thorn;ilke deuyne substaunce torne&thorn; &thorn;e worlde and &thorn;ilke cercle moeueable of &thorn;inges while &thorn;ilke dyuyne substaunce kepi&thorn; it self wi&thorn; outen  moeuynge. &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="24" UNIT="fol."> is to seyne &thorn;at it ne moeui&thorn; neuere mo. and &yogh;itte it moeue&thorn; alle o&thorn;er &thorn;inges. but na-&thorn;eles yif I [haue] stered resouns &thorn;at ne ben nat taken fro wi&thorn; oute &thorn;e compas of &thorn;e &thorn;inge of whiche we treten. but resouns &thorn;at ben bystowed wi&thorn; inne &thorn;at compas &thorn;ere nis nat whi &thorn;at &thorn;ou sholde[st] merueylen. sen &thorn;ou hast lerned by &thorn;e sentence of plato &thorn;at nedes &thorn;e wordes moten ben cosynes to &thorn;o &thorn;inges of whiche &thorn;ei speken.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="12" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">FELIX QUI POTERIT. ET CETERA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Blisful is &thorn;at man &thorn;at may seen &thorn;e clere welle of good. blisful is he &thorn;at may vnbynde hym fro &thorn;e bonde of heuy er&thorn;e.  &para; &thorn;e poete of trace [orpheus] &thorn;at somtyme hadde ry&yogh;t greet sorowe for &thorn;e dee&thorn; of hys wijf. aftir &thorn;at he hadde maked by hys wepely songes &thorn;e wodes meueable to rennen. and hadde ymaked &thorn;e ryueres to stonden stille. and maked &thorn;e hertys and hyndes to ioignen dredles hir sides to cruel lyouns to herkene his songe. and had[de] maked &thorn;at &thorn;e hare was nat agast of &thorn;e hounde whiche &thorn;at was plesed by hys songe. so &thorn;at whane &thorn;e most[e] ardaunt loue of hys wijf brende &thorn;e <PB N="107">entrailes of his brest. ne &thorn;e songes &thorn;at hadde ouer comen alle &thorn;inges ne my&yogh;ten nat assuage hir lorde orpheus.  &para; He pleyned[e] hym of &thorn;e godes &thorn;at weren cruel to hym. he wente hym to &thorn;e houses of helle and &thorn;ere he tempred[e] hys blaundissyng songes by resounyng of hys strenges.  &para; And spak and song in wepynge alle &thorn;at euer he hadde resceyued and laued oute of &thorn;e noble welles of hys modir calliope &thorn;e goddesse. and he song wi&thorn; as mychel as he my&yogh;t[e] of wepynge. and wi&thorn; as myche as loue &thorn;at doubled[e] his sorwe my&yogh;t[e] &yogh;euen hym and teche hym in his seke herte.  &para; And he commoeuede &thorn;e helle and requered[e] and sou&yogh;te by swete preiere &thorn;e lordes of soules in helle of relesynge. &thorn;at is to seyne to &yogh;elden hym hys wif. &para; Cerberus &thorn;e porter of helle wi&thorn; his &thorn;re heuedes was cau&yogh;t and al abaist for &thorn;e new[e] songe. and &thorn;e &thorn;re goddesses furijs and vengerisse of felonies &thorn;at tourmenten and agasten &thorn;e soules by anoye wexen sorweful and sory and wepen teres for pitee. &thorn;an was nat &thorn;e heued of Ixione ytourmented by &thorn;e ouer&thorn;rowing whele.  &para; And tantalus &thorn;at was destroied by &thorn;e woodnesse of longe &thorn;rust dispise&thorn; &thorn;e flodes to drynke. &thorn;e fowel &thorn;at hy&yogh;t voltor &thorn;at eti&thorn; &thorn;e stomak or &thorn;e giser of ticius is so fulfilled of his songe &thorn;at it nil etyn ne tyren no more. &para; Atte &thorn;e laste &thorn;e lorde and Iuge of soules was moeued to misericordes and cried[e] we ben ouer comen quod he. yif[e] we to orpheus his wijf to bere hym compaignye he ha&thorn; welle I-bou&yogh;t hir by his faire songe and <PB N="108">his ditee. but we wil putten a lawe in &thorn;is. and couenaunt in &thorn;e &yogh;ifte. &thorn;at is to seyne. &thorn;at til he be out of helle yif he loke byhynden hym [&thorn;at] hys wijf shal comen a&yogh;eine to vs &para; but what is he &thorn;at may &yogh;eue a lawe to loueres. loue is a gretter lawe and a strengere to hym self &thorn;an any lawe &thorn;at men may &yogh;euen.  &para; Allas whan Orpheus and his wijf were al most at &thorn;e termes of &thorn;e ny&yogh;t. &thorn;at is to seyne at &thorn;e last[e] boundes of helle. Orpheus loked[e] abakwarde on Erudice his wijf and lost[e] hir and was deed.  &para; &thorn;is fable apperteine&thorn; to &yogh;ow alle who so euer desire&thorn; or seki&thorn; to lede his &thorn;ou&yogh;te in to &thorn;e souereyne day. &thorn;at is to seyne to clerenes[se] of souereyne goode.  &para; For who so &thorn;at euere be so ouer comen &thorn;at he fycche hys eyen in to &thorn;e put[te] of helle. &thorn;at is to seyne who so sette&thorn; his &thorn;ou&yogh;tes in er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges. al &thorn;at euer he ha&thorn; drawen of &thorn;e noble good celestial he lesi&thorn; it whan he loke&thorn; &thorn;e helles. &thorn;at is to seyne to lowe &thorn;inges of &thorn;e er&thorn;e.</P></DIV2><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="l">EXPLICIT LIBER TERCIUS.</FOREIGN></TRAILER></DIV1><DIV1 N="4" TYPE="book"><MILESTONE N="24b" UNIT="fol."><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">INCIPIT LIBER QUARTUS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><DIV2 N="1" TYPE="prose">


<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">HEC CUM PHILOSOPHIA DIGNITATE UULTUS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Whanne philosophie hadde songen softly and delitably &thorn;e forseide &thorn;inges kepynge &thorn;e dignitee of hir choere in &thorn;e wey&yogh;te of hir wordes. I &thorn;an &thorn;at ne hadde nat al outerly for&yogh;eten &thorn;e wepyng and mournyng &thorn;at was set in myne herte for-brek &thorn;e entencioun of hir &thorn;at entended[e] &yogh;itte to seyne o&thorn;er &thorn;inges.  &para; Se quod I. &thorn;ou &thorn;at art gideresse of verray ly&yogh;te &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ou <PB N="109">hast seid [me] hider to ben to me so clere and so shewyng by &thorn;e deuyne lokyng of hem and by &thorn;i resouns &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne mowe nat ben ouercomen.  &para; And &thorn;ilke &thorn;ingus &thorn;at &thorn;ou toldest me. al be it so &thorn;at I hadde som tyme fo[r]&yogh;eten hem for [the] sorwe of &thorn;e wronge &thorn;at ha&thorn; ben don to me. &yogh;it na&thorn;eles &thorn;ei ne were nat alouterly vnknowen to me. but &thorn;is same is namly a gret cause of my sorwe. &thorn;at so as &thorn;e gouernoure of &thorn;inges is goode. yif &thorn;at yuelys mowen ben by any weyes. or ellys yif &thorn;at yuelys passen wi&thorn; outen punyssheinge. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;inge oonly how wor&thorn;i it is to ben wondred vpon. &thorn;ou considerest it weel &thorn;i self certeynly. but &yogh;itte to &thorn;is &thorn;ing &thorn;ere is an o&thorn;er &thorn;ing y-ioigned more to ben ywondred vpon.  &para; For felonie is emperisse and flowre&thorn; ful of rycchesse. and vertues nis nat al oonly wi&thorn; outen medes. but it is cast vndir and fortroden vndir &thorn;e feet of felonous folk. and it abie&thorn; &thorn;e tourmentes in sted of wicked felouns &para; Of al[le] whiche &thorn;ing &thorn;er nis no wy&yogh;t &thorn;at [may] merueyllen ynou&yogh; ne compleyne &thorn;at swiche &thorn;inges ben don in &thorn;e regne of god &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges woot. and alle &thorn;inges may and ne wool nat but only goode &thorn;inges.  &para; &thorn;an seide she &thorn;us. certys quod she &thorn;at were a grete meruayle and an enbaissynge wi&thorn;outen ende. and wel more horrible &thorn;an alle monstres yif it were as &thorn;ou wenest. &thorn;at is to sein. &thorn;at in &thorn;e ry&yogh;t ordeyne house of so mochel a fader and an ordenour of meyne. &thorn;at &thorn;e vesseles &thorn;at ben foule and vyle sholde ben honoured and heried.  and &thorn;e precious uesseles sholde ben defouled and vyle. but it nis nat so.  For yif &thorn;e &thorn;inges <PB N="110">&thorn;at I haue concluded a litel here byforne ben kept hoole and vnraced. &thorn;ou shalt wel knowe by &thorn;e auctorite of god. of &thorn;e whos regne I speke &thorn;at certys &thorn;e good[e] folk ben alwey my&yogh;ty. and shrewes ben alwey yuel and feble. ne &thorn;e vices ben neuere mo wi&thorn; outen peyne&meper; ne &thorn;e vertues ne ben nat wi&thorn; outen mede. and &thorn;at blisfulnesses comen alwey to goode folke. and infortune come&thorn; alwey to wicked folke.  &para; And &thorn;ou shalt wel knowe many[e] &thorn;inges of &thorn;is kynde &thorn;at sholle cessen &thorn;i pleyntes. and stedfast &thorn;e wi&thorn; stedfast saddenesse.  &para; And for &thorn;ou hast seyn &thorn;e forme of &thorn;e verray blisfulnesse by me &thorn;at [haue] somtyme I-shewed it &thorn;e.  And &thorn;ou hast knowen in whom blysfulnesse is set. alle &thorn;inges I treted &thorn;at I trowe ben nessessarie to put[te] fur&thorn;e &para; I shal shewe &thorn;e. &thorn;e weye &thorn;at shal brynge &thorn;e a&yogh;eyne vnto &thorn;i house and I shal ficche fe&thorn;eres in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t by whiche it may arysen in hey&yogh;te. so &thorn;at al tribulacioun don awey &thorn;ou by my gidyng & by my pa&thorn;e and by my sledes shalt mowen retourne hool and sounde in to &thorn;i contre.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="1" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">SUNT ETENIM PENNE. ET CETERA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>I Haue for so&thorn;e swifte fe&thorn;eres &thorn;at surmounten &thorn;e hey&yogh;t of &thorn;e heuene whan &thorn;e swifte &thorn;ou&yogh;t ha&thorn; clo&thorn;ed it self. in &thorn;o fe&thorn;eres it dispise&thorn; &thorn;e hat[e]ful er&thorn;es. and surmounte&thorn; &thorn;e hey&yogh;enesse of &thorn;e greet[e] eyir. and it sei&thorn; &thorn;e cloudes by-hynde hir bak and passe&thorn; &thorn;e hey&yogh;t of &thorn;e regioun of &thorn;e fire &thorn;at eschaufi&thorn; by &thorn;e swifte moeuyng of &thorn;e firmament. til &thorn;at she a-reisi&thorn; hir in til &thorn;e houses &thorn;at <PB N="111">beren &thorn;e sterres. and ioygne&thorn; hir weyes wi&thorn; &thorn;e sonne phebus. and felawshipe&thorn; &thorn;e weye of &thorn;e olde colde saturnus. and she ymaked a kny&yogh;t of &thorn;e clere sterre. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;at &thorn;e soule is maked goddys kny&yogh;t by &thorn;e sekyng of treu&thorn;e to comen to &thorn;e verray knowlege of god. and &thorn;ilke soule renne[&thorn;] by &thorn;e cercle <MILESTONE N="25" UNIT="fol.">of &thorn;e sterres  
in alle &thorn;e places &thorn;ere as &thorn;e shynyng ny&yogh;t is depeynted. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;e ny&yogh;t &thorn;at is cloudeles. for on ny&yogh;tes &thorn;at ben cloudeles it seme&thorn; as &thorn;e heuene were peynted wi&thorn; dyuerse ymages of sterres. and whan &thorn;e soule ha&thorn; gon ynou&yogh; she shal forleten &thorn;e last[e] poynt of &thorn;e heuene. and she shal pressen and wenden on &thorn;e bak of &thorn;e swifte firmament. and she shal ben maked perfit of &thorn;e dredefulle clerenesse of god. &para; &thorn;ere halde&thorn; &thorn;e lorde of kynges &thorn;e ceptre of his my&yogh;t and attempere&thorn; &thorn;e gouernementes of &thorn;is worlde. and &thorn;e shynynge iuge of &thorn;inges stable in hym self gouerne&thorn; &thorn;e swifte carte. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;e circuler moeuyng of [the] sonne. and yif &thorn;i weye lede&thorn; &thorn;e a&yogh;eyne so &thorn;at &thorn;ou be brou&yogh;t &thorn;ider. &thorn;an wilt &thorn;ou seye now &thorn;at &thorn;at is &thorn;e contre &thorn;at &thorn;ou requeredest of whiche &thorn;ou ne haddest no mynde. but now it remenbre&thorn; me wel here was I born. here wil I fastne my degree. here wil I dwelle. but yif &thorn;e lyke &thorn;an to loken on &thorn;e derkenesse of &thorn;e er&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast for-leten. &thorn;an shalt &thorn;ou seen &thorn;at &thorn;ise felonous tyrauntes &thorn;at &thorn;e wrecched[e] poeple drede&thorn; now shule ben exiled from &thorn;ilke faire contre. 
</P></DIV2><PB N="112"><DIV2 N="2" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">TUNC EGO PAPE INQUAM. ET CETERA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;Anne seide I &thorn;us. [owh] I wondre me &thorn;at &thorn;ou by-hetest me so grete &thorn;inges. ne I ne doute nat &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne mayst wel performe &thorn;at &thorn;ou by-hetest. but I preie &thorn;e oonly &thorn;is. &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne tarie nat to telle me &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast meoued. first quod she &thorn;ou most nedes knowen. &thorn;at good[e] folk ben al wey strong[e] and my&yogh;ty. and &thorn;e shrewes ben feble and desert and naked of alle streng&thorn;es. and of &thorn;ise &thorn;inges certys eueryche of hem is declared and shewed by o&thorn;er.  &para; For so as good and yuel ben two contraries. yif so be &thorn;at goode be stedfast. &thorn;an shewe&thorn; &thorn;e fieblesse of yuel al openly. and yif &thorn;ou knowe clerely &thorn;e freelnesse of yuel. &thorn;e stedfastnesse of goode is knowen. but for as moche as &thorn;e fey of my sentence shal be &thorn;e more ferme and haboundaunt. I wil goon by &thorn;at oon wey and by &thorn;at o&thorn;er and I wil conferme &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben purposed now on &thorn;is side and now on &thorn;at syde.  &para; Two &thorn;inges &thorn;er ben in whiche &thorn;e effect of alle &thorn;e dedes of man kynde standi&thorn;. &thorn;at is to seyn. wil and power. and yif &thorn;at oon of &thorn;ise two fayle&thorn; &thorn;ere nis no &thorn;ing &thorn;at may be don. for yif &thorn;at wil lakke&thorn; &thorn;ere nys no wy&yogh;t &thorn;at vndirtake&thorn; to done &thorn;at he wol not don. and yif power fayle&thorn; &thorn;e wille nis but in ydel and stant for nau&yogh;t. and &thorn;er of come&thorn; it &thorn;at yif &thorn;ou se a wy&yogh;t &thorn;at wolde geten &thorn;at he may nat geten. &thorn;ou mayst nat douten &thorn;at power ne fayle&thorn; hym to hauen &thorn;at he wolde.  &para; &thorn;is is open and clere quod I. ne it may nat ben denyed in no manere. and yif &thorn;ou se a wy&yogh;t quod she. &thorn;at ha&thorn; don &thorn;at he wolde don &thorn;ou nilt nat douten &thorn;at he ne ha&thorn; had power to done it. no quod. I. and in &thorn;at. &thorn;at euery wy&yogh;t may. in &thorn;at &thorn;at men may holden <PB N="113">hym my&yogh;ty. as who sei&thorn; in as moche as a man is my&yogh;ty to done a &thorn;ing. in so moche men halden hym my&yogh;ty. and in &thorn;at &thorn;at he ne may. in &thorn;at men demen hym to ben feble. I confesse it wel quod I.  Remembri&thorn; &thorn;e quod she &thorn;at I. haue gadred and shewed by forseide resouns &thorn;at al &thorn;e entencioun of &thorn;e wil of mankynde whiche &thorn;at is lad by diuerse studies hasti&thorn; to comen to blisfulnesse. &para; It remembre&thorn; me wel quod I &thorn;at it hath ben shewed. and recorde&thorn; &thorn;e nat &thorn;an quod she. &thorn;at blisfulnesse is &thorn;ilke same goode &thorn;at men requeren. so &thorn;at whan &thorn;at blisfulnesse is requered <MILESTONE N="25b" UNIT="fol.">of alle. &thorn;at goode [also] is requered  
and desired of al.  It recorde&thorn; me wel quod I. for haue it gretly alwey ficche[d] in my memorie. alle folk &thorn;an quod she goode and eke badde enforcen hem wi&thorn; oute difference of entencioun to comen to goode. &thorn;at is a uerray consequence quod I. and certeyne is quod she &thorn;at by &thorn;e getyng of goode ben men ymaked goode. &thorn;is is certeyne quod. I.  &para; &thorn;an geten goode men &thorn;at &thorn;ei desiren. so seme&thorn; it quod I. but wicked[e] folk quod she yif &thorn;ei geten &thorn;e goode &thorn;at &thorn;ei desiren &thorn;ei [ne] mowen nat ben wicked. so is it quod .I.  &para; &thorn;an so as &thorn;at oon and &thorn;at o&thorn;er [quod she] desiren good. and &thorn;e goode folk geten good and nat &thorn;e wicked folk  &para; &thorn;an nis it no doute &thorn;at &thorn;e goode folk ne ben my&yogh;ty and &thorn;e wicked folk ben feble.  &para; who so &thorn;at euer quod I doute&thorn; of &thorn;is. he ne may nat considre &thorn;e nature of &thorn;inges. ne &thorn;e consequence of resoun. and ouer &thorn;is quod she.  &para; yif &thorn;at &thorn;er ben two &thorn;inges &thorn;at han o same purpos by kynde. and &thorn;at one of hem pursue&thorn; and performe&thorn; &thorn;ilke same &thorn;inge by naturel office. and &thorn;at o&thorn;er ne may nat done &thorn;ilk naturel office.  but folwe&thorn; by o&thorn;er manere &thorn;an is couenable to nature  &para; Hym &thorn;at <PB N="114">acomplisi&thorn; hys purpos kyndely. and &yogh;it he ne acomplisi&thorn; nat hys owen purpos. whe&thorn;er of &thorn;ise two demest &thorn;ou for more my&yogh;ty.  &para; yif &thorn;at I coniecte quod .I. &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt seye algates. &yogh;it I desire to herkene it more pleynely of &thorn;e. &thorn;ou nilt nat &thorn;an denye quod she &thorn;at &thorn;e moeuement&yogh; of goynge nis in men by kynde. no for so&thorn;e quod I. ne &thorn;ou ne doutest nat quod she &thorn;at &thorn;ilke naturel office of goynge ne be &thorn;e office of feet.  I ne doute it nat quod .I. &thorn;an quod she yif &thorn;at a wy&yogh;t be my&yogh;ty to moeue and go&thorn; vpon hys feet. and ano&thorn;er to whom &thorn;ilke naturel office of feet lakke&thorn;. enforce&thorn; hym to gone crepynge vpon hys handes.  &para; whiche of &thorn;ise two au&yogh;te to ben holden more my&yogh;ty by ry&yogh;t. knyt fur&thorn;e &thorn;e remenaunt quod I.  &para; For no wy&yogh;t ne doute&thorn; &thorn;at he &thorn;at may gone by naturel office of feet. ne be more my&yogh;ty &thorn;an he &thorn;at ne may nat  &para; but &thorn;e souereyne good quod she &thorn;at is euenlyche purposed to &thorn;e good folk and to badde. &thorn;e good folke seken it by naturel office of uertues. and &thorn;e shrewes enforcen hem to geten it by dyuerse couetise of er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges. whiche &thorn;at nis no naturel office to geten &thorn;ilke same souereyne goode. trowest &thorn;ou &thorn;at it be any o&thorn;er wyse. nay quod .I. for &thorn;e consequence is open and shewynge of &thorn;inges &thorn;at I haue graunted.  &para; &thorn;at nedes goode folk moten ben my&yogh;ty. and shrewes feble and vnmy&yogh;ty.  &para; &thorn;ou rennest ary&yogh;t byfore me quod she. and &thorn;is is &thorn;e iugement &thorn;at is to seyn.  &para; I iuge of &thorn;e ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ise leches ben wont forto hopen of seke folk whan &thorn;ei aperceyuen &thorn;at nature is redressed and wi&thorn;stonde&thorn; to &thorn;e maladie.  &para; But for I see &thorn;e now al redy to &thorn;e vndirstandynge I shal shewe &thorn;e more &thorn;ilke and continuel resouns.  &para; For loke now <PB N="115">how gretly shewi&thorn; &thorn;e feblesse and infirmite of wicked folke. &thorn;at ne mowen nat come to &thorn;at hire naturel entencioun lede&thorn; hem. and &yogh;itte almost &thorn;ilk naturel entencioun constreine&thorn; hem.  &para; and what were to deme &thorn;an of shrewes. yif &thorn;ilke naturel helpe hadde for-leten hem.  &para; &thorn;e whiche naturel helpe of entencioun go&thorn; alwey byforne hem. and is so grete &thorn;at vnne&thorn; it may be ouercomen.  &para; Considre &thorn;an how gret defaute of power and how gret feblesse &thorn;ere is in grete felonous folk as who sei&thorn; &thorn;e gretter &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben coueited and &thorn;e desire nat accomplissed of &thorn;e lasse my&yogh;t is he &thorn;at coueite&thorn; it and may nat acomplisse.  &para; And for&thorn;i philosophie sei&thorn; &thorn;us by souereyne good.  &para; Sherewes ne requere nat ly&yogh;t[e] medes ne veyne gaines whiche &thorn;ei ne may nat folwen ne holden. but &thorn;ei faylen of &thorn;ilke some of &thorn;e hey&yogh;te of &thorn;inges &thorn;at is to seyne souereyne good. ne &thorn;ise wrecches ne comen nat to &thorn;e effect of souereyne good. <MILESTONE N="26" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;e whiche &thorn;ei enforcen hem oonly to geten by ny&yogh;tes  
and by dayes.  &para; In &thorn;e getyn[g] of whiche goode &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of good folk. is ful wel ysen.  For ry&yogh;t so as &thorn;ou my&yogh;test demen hym my&yogh;ty of goynge &thorn;at go&thorn; on hys feet til he my&yogh;t[e] come to &thorn;ilke place fro &thorn;e whiche place &thorn;ere ne lay no wey for&thorn;er to be gon.  Ry&yogh;t so most &thorn;ou nedes demen hym for ry&yogh;t my&yogh;ty &thorn;at geti&thorn; and atteini&thorn; to &thorn;e ende of alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben to desire. by-&yogh;onde &thorn;e whiche ende &thorn;at &thorn;er nis no &thorn;ing to desire. &para; Of whiche power of good folk men may conclude &thorn;at wicked men semen to ben bareyne and naked of alle streng&thorn;e.  For whi forleten &thorn;ei vertues and folwen vices. nis it nat for &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne knowen nat &thorn;e goodes. <PB N="116">&para; But what &thorn;ing is more feble and more caitif &thorn;an is &thorn;e blyndenesse of ignoraunce. or ellys &thorn;ei knowen ful wel whiche &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ei au&yogh;ten to folwen  &para; but lecherye and couetise ouer&thorn;rowe&thorn; hem mysturned.  &para; and certis so do&thorn; distemperaunce to feble men. &thorn;at ne mowen nat wrastle a&yogh;eins &thorn;e vices  &para; Ne knowen &thorn;ei nat &thorn;an wel &thorn;at &thorn;ei foreleten &thorn;e good wilfully. and turnen hem vilfully to vices.  &para; And in &thorn;is wise &thorn;ei ne forleten nat oonly to ben my&yogh;ty. but &thorn;ei forleten al outerly in any wise forto ben &para; For &thorn;ei &thorn;at forleten &thorn;e comune fyn of alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben. &thorn;ei for-leten also &thorn;erwi&thorn; al forto ben. and perauenture it sholde semen to som folk &thorn;at &thorn;is were a merueile to seyne &thorn;at shrewes whiche &thorn;at contienen &thorn;e more partie of men ne ben nat. ne han no beynge.  &para; but na&thorn;eles it is so. and &thorn;us stant &thorn;is &thorn;ing for &thorn;ei &thorn;at ben shrewes I denye nat &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben shrewes. but I denye and sey[e] symplely and pleynly &thorn;at &thorn;ei [ne] ben nat. ne han no beynge. for ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ou my&yogh;test seyn of &thorn;e careyne of a man &thorn;at it were a ded man. &para; but &thorn;ou ne my&yogh;test nat symplely callen it a man. &para; So graunt[e] I wel for so&thorn;e &thorn;at vicious folk ben wicked. but I ne may nat graunten absolutely and symplely &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben.  &para; For &thorn;ilk &thorn;ing &thorn;at wi&thorn; holde&thorn; ordre and kepi&thorn; nature. &thorn;ilk &thorn;ing is and ha&thorn; beynge. but &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at faile&thorn; of &thorn;at. &thorn;at is to seyne he &thorn;at forleti&thorn; naturel ordre he for-leti&thorn; &thorn;ilk beyng &thorn;at is set in hys nature. but &thorn;ou wolt sein &thorn;at shrewes mowen.  &para; Certys &thorn;at ne denye I nat.  &para; but certys hir power ne descende&thorn; nat of streng&thorn;e but of feblesse. for &thorn;ei mowen don wickednesses. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ei ne my&yogh;ten nat don yif &thorn;ei my&yogh;ten dwelle in &thorn;e forme and <PB N="117">in &thorn;e doynge of goode folke.  &para; And &thorn;ilke power shewe&thorn; ful euydently &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne mowen ry&yogh;t nau&yogh;t. &para; For so as I haue gadered and proued a lytel her byforn &thorn;at yuel is nau&yogh;t. and so as shrewes mowen oonly but shrewednesse. &thorn;is conclusioun is al clere. &thorn;at shrewes ne mowen ry&yogh;t nat to han power. and for as moche as &thorn;ou vndirstonde whiche is &thorn;e streng&thorn;e &thorn;at is power of shrewes. I haue diffinised a lytel here byforn &thorn;at no &thorn;ing nis so my&yogh;ty as souereyne good  &para; &thorn;at is so&thorn;e quod .I. [and thilke same souereyn good may don non yuel // Certes no quod I] &para; Is &thorn;er any wy&yogh;t &thorn;an quod she &thorn;at weni&thorn; &thorn;at men mowen don alle &thorn;inges. No man quod .I. but yif he be out of hys witte.  &para; but certys sherewes mowen do&nmacr; yuel quod she.  &para; &yogh;e wolde god quod I &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne my&yogh;ten don none. &thorn;at quod she so as he &thorn;at is my&yogh;ty to done oonly but good[e] &thorn;inges may don alle &thorn;inges. and &thorn;ei &thorn;at ben my&yogh;ty to done yuel[e] &thorn;inges ne mowen nat alle &thorn;inges. &thorn;an is &thorn;is open &thorn;ing and manifest &thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;at mowen don yuel ben of lasse power. and &yogh;itte to proue &thorn;is conclusioun &thorn;ere helpe&thorn; me &thorn;is &thorn;at I haue shewed here byforne. &thorn;at al power is to be noumbred amonge &thorn;inges &thorn;at men au&yogh;ten requere. and haue shewed &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at au&yogh;ten ben desired ben referred to good ry&yogh;t as to a manere hey&yogh;te of hyr nature.  &para; But for to mowen don yuel and felonye ne may nat ben referred to good. &thorn;an nis nat yuel of &thorn;e noumbre of &thorn;inges &thorn;at au&yogh;ten. <MILESTONE N="26b" UNIT="fol.">be desired. but  
al power au&yogh;t[e] ben desired and requered.  &para; &thorn;an is it open and cler &thorn;at &thorn;e power ne &thorn;e moeuyng of shrewes nis no powere. and of alle &thorn;ise &thorn;inges it shewe&thorn; wel &thorn;at <PB N="118">&thorn;e goode folk ben certeynly my&yogh;ty. and &thorn;e shrewes ben douteles vnmy&yogh;ty &para; And it is clere and open &thorn;at &thorn;ilke sentence of plato is uerray and so&thorn;e. &thorn;at sey&thorn; &thorn;at oonly wisemen may [doon] &thorn;at &thorn;ei desiren. and shrewes mowen haunten &thorn;at hem lyke&thorn;. but &thorn;at &thorn;ei desiren &thorn;at is to seyne to comen to souereyne good &thorn;ei ne han no power to acomplissen &thorn;at.  &para; For shrewes don &thorn;at hem list whan by &thorn;o &thorn;inges in whiche &thorn;ei deliten &thorn;ei wenen to atteyne to &thorn;ilke good &thorn;at &thorn;ei desiren. but &thorn;ei ne geten ne atteynen nat &thorn;er to.  &para; for vices ne comen nat to blisfulnesse.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="2" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUOS UIDES SEDERE CELSOS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Who so &thorn;at &thorn;e couertures of her veyn apparailes my&yogh;t[e] strepen of &thorn;ise proude kynges &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest sitten on hey&yogh;e in her chayeres glyterynge in shynynge purpre envyroned wi&thorn; sorweful armures manasyng wi&thorn; cruel mou&thorn;e. blowyng by woodnesse of herte.  &para; He sholde se &thorn;an &thorn;at ilke lordes beren wi&thorn; inne hir corages ful streyte cheynes for leccherye tormenti&thorn; hem on &thorn;at oon syde wi&thorn; gredy venyms and troublable Ire &thorn;at araise&thorn; in hem &thorn;e floodes of troublynges tourmenti&thorn; vpon &thorn;at o&thorn;er side hir &thorn;ou&yogh;t. or sorwe halt hem wery or ycau&yogh;t. or slidyng and disseyuyng hope tourmenti&thorn; hem.  And &thorn;erfore syn &thorn;ou seest on heed. &thorn;at is to seyne oon tyraunt bere so many[e] tyrauntis. &thorn;an ne do&thorn; &thorn;ilk tyraunt nat &thorn;at he desiri&thorn;. syn he is cast doune wi&thorn; so many[e] wicked lordes. &thorn;at is to seyn wi&thorn; so many[e] vices. &thorn;at han so wicked lordshipes ouer hym. 
</P></DIV2><PB N="119"><DIV2 N="3" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">VIDES NE IGITUR QUANTO.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Seest &thorn;ou nat &thorn;an in how gret fil&thorn;e &thorn;ise shrewes ben ywrapped. and wi&thorn; whiche cleernesse &thorn;ise good folk shynen.  In &thorn;is shewe&thorn; it wel &thorn;at to good folk ne lakke&thorn; neuer mo hir medes. ne shrewes ne lakken neuer mo tourmentis. for of alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben ydon &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing for whiche any &thorn;ing is doon. it seme&thorn; as by ry&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing be &thorn;e mede of &thorn;at. as &thorn;us.  &para; yif a man renne&thorn; in &thorn;e stadie or in &thorn;e forlonge for &thorn;e corone. &thorn;an lie&thorn; &thorn;e mede in &thorn;e corone for whiche he renne&thorn;. &para; And I haue shewed &thorn;at blisfulnesse is &thorn;ilke same good for whiche &thorn;at alle &thorn;ingus ben don. &thorn;an is &thorn;ilke same good purposed to &thorn;e werkes of mankynde ry&yogh;t as a comune mede. whiche mede ne may ben disseuered fro good folk. for no wy&yogh;t as by ry&yogh;t fro &thorn;ennes for&thorn;e &thorn;at hym lakki&thorn; goodnesse ne shal ben cleped good. For whiche &thorn;ing folk of good[e] maneres her medes ne forsaken hem neuer mo.  For al be it so &thorn;at sherewes waxen as wood as hem list a&yogh;eynes good[e] folk. &yogh;itte neuer &thorn;e les &thorn;e corone of wise men ne shal nat fallen ne faden.  &para; For foreine shrewednesse ne bynyme&thorn; nat fro &thorn;e corages of good[e] folk hire propre honoure. but yif &thorn;at any wy&yogh;t reioise&thorn; hem of goodnesse &thorn;at &thorn;ei had[de] taken fro wi&thorn;oute. as who sei&thorn; yif [&thorn;at] any wy&yogh;t had[de] hys goodnesse of any o&thorn;er man &thorn;an of hym self. certys he &thorn;at &yogh;af hym &thorn;ilke goodnesse or ellys som o&thorn;er wy&yogh;t my&yogh;t[e] bynym[e] it hym. but for as moche as to euery wy&yogh;t hys owen propre bounte &yogh;eue&thorn; hym hys mede. &thorn;an at arst shal he faylen of mede whan he forleti&thorn; to ben good. and at &thorn;e laste so as alle medes ben requered for men wenen &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben <PB N="120">good[e]. who is he &thorn;at wolde deme &thorn;at he &thorn;at is ry&yogh;t my&yogh;ty of goode were partles of mede. <MILESTONE N="27" UNIT="fol.">and of what mede shal he be gerdoned. certys of ry&yogh;t faire mede and ry&yogh;t greet abouen alle medes.  &para; Remembre &thorn;e of &thorn;ilk noble corolarie &thorn;at I &yogh;af &thorn;e a lytel here byforne. and gadre it to gidre in &thorn;is manere. so as god hym self is blisfulnesse. &thorn;an is it clere and certeyn. &thorn;at alle good folk ben makid blisful for &thorn;ei ben good[e]. and &thorn;ilke folk &thorn;at ben blisful it accordi&thorn; and is couenable to ben godde[s]. &thorn;an is &thorn;e mede of goode folk swiche. &thorn;at no day [ne] shal enpeyren it. ne no wickednesse shal endirken it. ne power of no wy&yogh;t ne shal nat amenusen it &thorn;at is to seyn to ben maked goddes. &para; and syn it is &thorn;us &thorn;at goode men ne faylen neuer mo of hire medes. &para; certys no wise man ne may doute of &thorn;e vndepartable peyne of shrewes.  &para; &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;at &thorn;e peyne of shrewes ne departi&thorn; nat from hem self neuer mo. &para; For so as goode and yuel and peyne and medes ben contrarie it mot nedes ben &thorn;at ry&yogh;t as we seen by-tiden in gerdoun of goode. &thorn;at also mot &thorn;e peyne of yuel answere by &thorn;e contrarie partye to shrewes. now &thorn;an so as bounte and prowesse ben &thorn;e medes to goode folk. also is shrewednesse it self torment to shrewes  &para; &thorn;an who so &thorn;at euer is entecched and defouled wi&thorn; yuel. yif shrewes wolen &thorn;an preisen hem self may it semen to hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben wi&thorn; outen partye of tourment. syn &thorn;ei ben swiche &thorn;at &thorn;e [vtteriste wikkednesse / &thorn;at is to seyn wikkede thewes / which &thorn;at is the] outereste and &thorn;e w[or]ste kynde of shrewednesse ne defouli&thorn; nat ne entecehi&thorn; nat hem oonly but infecti&thorn; and enuenemy&thorn; hem gretely  &para; And al so loke on shrewes &thorn;at ben &thorn;e <PB N="121">contrarie partye of goode men. how grete peyne felawshipe&thorn; and folwe&thorn; hem.  &para; For &thorn;ou hast lerned a litel here byforn &thorn;at al &thorn;ing &thorn;at is and ha&thorn; beynge is oon. and &thorn;ilke same oon is good. &thorn;an is &thorn;is consequence &thorn;at it seme&thorn; wel. &thorn;at al &thorn;at is and ha&thorn; beynge is good. &thorn;is is to seyne. as who sei&thorn; &thorn;at beynge and vnite and goodnesse is al oon. and in &thorn;is manere it folwe&thorn; &thorn;an. &thorn;at al &thorn;ing &thorn;at faile&thorn; to ben good. it stynti&thorn; forto be. and forto haue any beynge. wher fore it is &thorn;at shrewes stynten forto ben &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren. but &thorn;ilke o&thorn;er forme of mankynde. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;e forme of &thorn;e body wi&thorn; oute. shewi&thorn; &yogh;it &thorn;at &thorn;ise shrewes were somtyme men. &para; wher fore whan &thorn;ei ben peruerted and torned in to malice. certys &thorn;an han &thorn;ei forlorn &thorn;e nature of mankynde. but so as oonly bounte and prowesse may enhawnse euery man ouer o&thorn;er men. &thorn;an mot it nedes be &thorn;at shrewes whiche &thorn;at shrewednesse ha&thorn; cast out of &thorn;e condicioun of mankynde ben put vndir &thorn;e merite and &thorn;e deserte of men. &thorn;an bitidi&thorn; it &thorn;at yif &thorn;ou seest a wy&yogh;t &thorn;at be transformed in to vices. &thorn;ou ne mayst nat wene &thorn;at he be a man.  &para; For &yogh;if he [be] ardaunt in auarice. and &thorn;at he be a rauynour by violence of foreine rychesse. &thorn;ou shalt seyn &thorn;at he is lyke to a wolf. and yif he be felonous and wi&thorn; out reste and exercise hys tonge to chidynges. &thorn;ou shalt lykene hym to &thorn;e hounde. and yif he be a preue awaitour yhid and reioyse&thorn; hym to rauysshe by wyles. &thorn;ou shalt seyne hym lyke to &thorn;e fox whelpes.  &para; And yif he be distempre and quaki&thorn; for ire men shal wene &thorn;at he bere&thorn; &thorn;e corage of a lyoun. and yif he be dredeful and fleynge and drede&thorn; &thorn;inges &thorn;at ne au&yogh;ten nat ben dred. men <PB N="122">shal holde hym lyke to &thorn;e herte. and yif he be slowe and astoned and lache. he lyue&thorn; as an asse. and yif he be ly&yogh;t and vnstedfast of corage and chaunge&thorn; ay his studies. he is lickened to briddes.  &para; and yif he be plounged in foule and vnclene luxuries. he is wi&thorn;holden in &thorn;e foule delices of &thorn;e foule soowe.  &para; &thorn;an folwe&thorn; it &thorn;at he &thorn;at forleti&thorn; bountee and prowesse. he forleti&thorn; to ben a man. syn he ne may nat passe in to &thorn;e condicioun of god. he is tourned in to a beest. 
</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="3" TYPE="metre"><MILESTONE N="27b" UNIT="fol."><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">V[E]LA NARICII DUCIS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Evrus &thorn;e wynde aryue&thorn; &thorn;e sayles of vlixes duc of &thorn;e contre of narice. and hys wandryng shippes by &thorn;e see in to &thorn;e isle &thorn;ere as Circe &thorn;e fayre goddesse dou&yogh;ter of &thorn;e sonne dwelle&thorn; &thorn;at medly&thorn; to hir newe gestes drynkes &thorn;at ben touched and maked wi&thorn; enchauntment&yogh;. and after &thorn;at hir hande my&yogh;ty of &thorn;e herbes had[de] chaunged hir gestes in to dyuerse maneres. &thorn;at oon of hem is couered his face wi&thorn; forme of a boor. &thorn;at o&thorn;er is chaunged in to a lyoun of &thorn;e contre of marmorike. and his nayles and his te&thorn;e wexen.  &para; &thorn;at o&thorn;er of hem is newliche chaunged in to a wolf. and howeli&thorn; whan he wolde wepe. &thorn;at o&thorn;er go&thorn; debonairly in &thorn;e house as a tigre of Inde. but al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;e godhed of mercurie &thorn;at is cleped &thorn;e bride of arcadie ha&thorn; had mercie of &thorn;e duc vlixes byseged wi&thorn; diuerse yueles and ha&thorn; vnbounden hym fro &thorn;e pestilence of hys oosteresse algates &thorn;e rowers and &thorn;e maryners hadden by &thorn;is ydrawen in to hir mou&thorn;es and dronken &thorn;e wicked[e] <PB N="123">drynkes &thorn;ei &thorn;at were woxen swyne hadden by &thorn;is chaunged hire mete of brede forto ete acorns of ookes. non of hir lymes ne dwelli&thorn; wi&thorn; hem hoole. but &thorn;ei han lost &thorn;e voys and &thorn;e body.  Oonly hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t dwelle&thorn; wi&thorn; hem stable &thorn;at wepi&thorn; and bywaili&thorn; &thorn;e monstruous chaungynge &thorn;at &thorn;ei suffren.  &para; O ouer ly&yogh;t hand. as who sei&thorn;.  &para; O feble and ly&yogh;t is &thorn;e hand of Circes &thorn;e enchaunteresse &thorn;at chaunge&thorn; &thorn;e bodies of folk in to bestes to regarde and to comparisoun of mutacioun &thorn;at is makid by vices. ne &thorn;e herbes of circes ne ben nat my&yogh;ty. for al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;ei may chaungen &thorn;e lymes of &thorn;e body.  &para; algates &yogh;it &thorn;ei may nat chaunge &thorn;e hertes. for wi&thorn; inne is yhid &thorn;e streng&thorn;e and &thorn;e vigour of men in &thorn;e secre toure of hire hertys. &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of resoun. but &thorn;ilke uenyms of vices todrawen a man to hem more my&yogh;tily &thorn;an &thorn;e venym of circes.  &para; For vices ben so cruel &thorn;at &thorn;ei percen and &thorn;oru&yogh; passen &thorn;e corage wi&thorn; inne. and &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei ne anoye nat &thorn;e body. &yogh;itte vices wooden to distroien men by wounde of &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="4" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">TUNC EGO FATEOR INQUAM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;an seide I &thorn;us I confesse and am aknowe quod I. ne I ne se nat &thorn;at men may seyn as by ry&yogh;t. &thorn;at shrewes ne ben nat chaunged in to beestes by &thorn;e qualite of hir soules.  &para; Al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;ei kepen &yogh;itte &thorn;e forme of &thorn;e body of mankynde. but I nolde nat of shrewes of whiche &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t cruel woode&thorn; alwey in to destruccioun of good[e] men. &thorn;at it were leueful to hem to done &thorn;at.  &para; Certys quod she ne it nis nat leueful to hem as I shal wel shewen &thorn;e in couenable place. &para; But na&thorn;eles yif so were &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;at men wenen ben <PB N="124">leueful for shrewes were bynomen hem. so &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne my&yogh;ten nat anoyen or don harme to goode men.  &para; Certys a gret party of &thorn;e peyne to shrewes shulde ben allegged and releued.  &para; For al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;is ne seme nat credible &thorn;ing perauenture to somme folk &yogh;it mot it nedes be &thorn;at shrewes ben more wrecches and vnsely. whan &thorn;ei may don and performe &thorn;at &thorn;ei coueiten [than yif they myhte nat complyssen &thorn;at they coueyten]. &para; For yif so be &thorn;at it be wrecchednesse to wilne to don yuel&meper; &thorn;an is it more wrecchednesse to mowen don yuel. wi&thorn; oute whiche moeuyng &thorn;e wrecched wille sholde languisshe wi&thorn; oute effecte.  &para; &thorn;an syn &thorn;at eueryche of &thorn;ise &thorn;inges ha&thorn; hys wrecchednesse. &thorn;at is to seyne wil to done yuel. and moeuynge to done yuel. it mot nedes be. &thorn;at &thorn;ei (shrewes) ben constreyned by &thorn;re vnselynesses &thorn;at wolen and mowen and performen felonyes and shrewednesses.  &para; I accorde me quod I.  but I desire gretely &thorn;at shrewes losten sone &thorn;ilke vnselynesses. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;at shrewes were despoyled of moeuyng to don yuel.  &para; so shullen &thorn;ei quod she. sonnere 
 perauenture &thorn;en &thorn;ou woldest <MILESTONE N="28" UNIT="fol.">or sonnere &thorn;en &thorn;ei hem self wenen to lakken mowynge to done yuel.  &para; For &thorn;ere nis no &thorn;ing so late in so short boundes of &thorn;is lijf &thorn;at is longe to abide. namelyche to a corage inmortel. Of whiche shrewes &thorn;e grete hope and &thorn;e heye compassyngus of shrewednesse is often destroyed by a sodeyne ende or &thorn;ei ben war. and &thorn;at &thorn;ing establi&thorn; to shrewes &thorn;e ende of hir shrewednesse.  &para; For yif &thorn;at shrewednesse maki&thorn;e wrecches. &thorn;an mot he nedes be most wrecched &thorn;at lengest is a shrewe. &thorn;e whiche wicked shrewes wolde ydemen aldirmost vnsely and <PB N="125">caytifs yif &thorn;at hir shrewednes ne were yfinissed. at &thorn;e leste weye by &thorn;e outerest[e] dee&thorn;. for [yif] I haue concluded so&thorn;e of &thorn;e vnselynesse of shrewednesse. &thorn;an shewe&thorn; it clerely &thorn;at &thorn;ilke shrewednesse is wi&thorn; outen ende &thorn;e whiche is certeyne to ben perdurable.  &para; Certys quod I &thorn;is [conclusion] is harde and wonderful to graunte. &para; But I knowe wel &thorn;at it accorde&thorn; moche to [the] &thorn;inges &thorn;at I haue graunted her byforne.  &para; &thorn;ou hast quod she &thorn;e ry&yogh;t estimacioun of &thorn;is. but who so euere wene &thorn;at it be an harde &thorn;ing to acorde hym to a conclusioun. it is ry&yogh;t &thorn;at he shewe &thorn;at somme of &thorn;e premisses ben fals. or ellys he mot shewe &thorn;at &thorn;e colasioun of preposiciouns nis nat spedful to a necessarie conclusioun.  &para; and yif it be nat so. but &thorn;at &thorn;e premisses ben ygranted &thorn;er nis nat whi he sholde blame &thorn;e argument. for &thorn;is &thorn;ing &thorn;at I shal telle &thorn;e nowe ne shal not seme lasse wondirful. but of &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben taken al so it is necessarie as who so sei&thorn; it folwe&thorn; of &thorn;at whiche &thorn;at is purposed byforn. what is &thorn;at quod I.  &para; certys quod she &thorn;at is &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ise wicked shrewes ben more blysful or ellys lasse wrecches. &thorn;at byen &thorn;e tourmentes &thorn;at &thorn;ei han deserued. &thorn;an yif no peyne of Iustice ne chastied[e] hem. ne &thorn;is ne seye I nat now for &thorn;at any man my&yogh;t[e] &thorn;enk[e] &thorn;at &thorn;e maneres of shrewes ben coriged and chastised by veniaunce. and &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben brou&yogh;t to &thorn;e ry&yogh;t wey by &thorn;e drede of &thorn;e tourment. ne for &thorn;at &thorn;ei &yogh;euen to o&thorn;er folk ensample to fleyen from vices.  &para; But I vndirstonde &yogh;itte [in] an o&thorn;er manere &thorn;at shrewes ben more vnsely whan &thorn;ei ne ben nat punissed al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;ere ne ben had no resoun or lawe of correccioun. ne none ensample of lokynge.  &para; And what manere <PB N="126">shal &thorn;at ben quod I.  ou&thorn;er &thorn;an ha&thorn; ben told here byforn  &para; Haue we nat graunted &thorn;an quod she &thorn;at good[e] folk ben blysful. and shrewes ben wrecches. &yogh;is quod I. [thanne quod she] &yogh;if &thorn;at any good were added to &thorn;e wrecchenesse of any wy&yogh;t. nis he nat more blisful &thorn;an he &thorn;at ne ha&thorn; no medelyng of goode in hys solitarie wrecchednesse. so seme&thorn; it quod I. and what seyst &thorn;ou &thorn;an quod she of &thorn;ilke wrecche &thorn;at lakke&thorn; alle goodes. so &thorn;at no goode nis medeled in hys wrecchednesse. and &yogh;itte ouer alle hys wickednesse for whiche he is a wrecche &thorn;at &thorn;er be &yogh;itte ano&thorn;er yuel anexid and knyt to hym. shal not men demen hym more vnsely &thorn;an &thorn;ilke wrecche of whiche &thorn;e vnselynesse is re[le]ued by &thorn;e participacioun of som goode. whi sholde he nat quod I.  &para; &thorn;an certys quod she han shrewes whan &thorn;ei ben punissed somwhat of good anexid to hir wrecchednesse. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;e same peyne &thorn;at &thorn;ei suffren whiche &thorn;at is good by &thorn;e resoun of Iustice.  And whan &thorn;ilke same shrewes ascapen wi&thorn; outen tourment. &thorn;an han &thorn;ei somwhat more of yuel &yogh;it ouer &thorn;e wickednesso &thorn;at &thorn;ei han don. &thorn;at is to seye defaute of peyne. whiche defaute of peyne &thorn;ou hast graunted is yuel. &para; For &thorn;e desert of felonye I ne may nat denye it quod I.  &para; Moche more &thorn;an quod she ben shrewes vnsely whan &thorn;ei ben wrongfully delyuered fro peyne. &thorn;an whan &thorn;ei be&thorn; punissed by ry&yogh;tful vengeaunce. but &thorn;is is open &thorn;ing and clere &thorn;at it is ry&yogh;t &thorn;at shrewes ben punissed. and it is wickednesse and wrong &thorn;at &thorn;ei escapin vnpunissed &para;who my&yogh;t[e] denye<MILESTONE N="28b" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;at quod I. but quod she may any man denye. &thorn;at al &thorn;at is ry&yogh;t nis good. and also &thorn;e contrarie. &thorn;at alle &thorn;at is wrong nis <PB N="127">wicked. certys quod I &thorn;ise &thorn;inges ben clere ynou&yogh;. and &thorn;at we han concludid a litel here byforne. but I preye &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou telle me yif &thorn;ou accordest to leten no tourment to &thorn;e soules aftir &thorn;at &thorn;e body is dedid by &thorn;e de&thorn;e. &thorn;is [is] to seyn. vndirstondest &thorn;ou ou&yogh;t &thorn;at soules han any tourment after &thorn;e de&thorn;e of &thorn;e body.  &para; Certis quod she &yogh;e and &thorn;at ry&yogh;t grete. of whiche soules quod she I trowe &thorn;at somme ben tourmentid by asprenesse of peyne. and somme soules I trowe be excercised by a purging mekenesse. but my conseil nys nat to determyne of &thorn;is peyne. but I haue trauayled and told it hider to.  &para; For &thorn;ou sholdest knowe &thorn;at &thorn;e mowynge [.i. myght] of shrewes whiche mowynge &thorn;e seme&thorn; to ben. vnwor&thorn;i nis no mowynge. and eke of shrewes of whiche &thorn;ou pleynedest &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne were nat punissed. &thorn;at &thorn;ou woldest seen &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne weren neuer mo wi&thorn; outen &thorn;e torment of hire wickednesse. and of &thorn;e licence of mowynge to done yuel. &thorn;at &thorn;ou preidest &thorn;at it my&yogh;t[e] sone ben endid. and &thorn;at &thorn;ou woldest fayne lerne. &thorn;at it ne sholde nat longe endure. and &thorn;at shrewes ben more vnsely yif &thorn;ei were of lenger duryng. and most vnsely yif &thorn;ei weren perdurable. and after &thorn;is I haue shewed &thorn;e &thorn;at more vnsely ben shrewes whan &thorn;ei escapen wi&thorn; oute ry&yogh;tful peyne. &thorn;an whan &thorn;ei ben punissed by ry&yogh;tful uengeaunce. and of &thorn;is sentence folwe&thorn; it &thorn;at &thorn;an ben shrewes constreyned atte laste wi&thorn; most greuous tourment. whan men wene &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne ben nat ypunissed. whan I considre &thorn;i resouns quod I. I. ne trowe nat &thorn;at men seyn any &thorn;ing more verrely. and yif I tourne a&yogh;eyn to &thorn;e studies of men. who is [he] to whom it sholde seme &thorn;at [he] ne sholde nat only leuen &thorn;ise &thorn;inges. but eke gladly herkene hem.  Certys quod <PB N="128">she so it is. but men may nat. for &thorn;ei han hire eyen so wont to derkenesse of er&thorn;ely &thorn;inges. &thorn;at &thorn;ei may nat liften hem vp to &thorn;e ly&yogh;t of clere so&thorn;efastnes.  &para; But &thorn;ei ben lyke to briddes of whiche &thorn;e ny&yogh;t ly&yogh;tne&thorn; hyre lookyng. and &thorn;e day blynde&thorn; hem. for whan men loken nat &thorn;e ordre of &thorn;inges but hire lustes and talent&yogh;. &thorn;ei wene &thorn;at o&thorn;ir &thorn;e leue or &thorn;e mowynge to done wickednesse or ellys &thorn;e escaping wi&thorn; oute peyne be weleful. but considere &thorn;e iugement of &thorn;e perdurable lawe. for if &thorn;ou conferme &thorn;i corage to &thorn;e beste &thorn;inges. &thorn;ou ne hast no nede to no iuge to &yogh;iuen &thorn;e pris or meede. for &thorn;ou hast ioigned &thorn;i self to &thorn;e most excellent &thorn;ing. and yif &thorn;ou haue enclined &thorn;i studies to &thorn;e wicked &thorn;inges. ne seek no foreyn wrekere out of &thorn;i self. for &thorn;ou &thorn;i self hast &thorn;rest &thorn;e in to wicked &thorn;inges. ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ou my&yogh;test loken by dyuerse tymes &thorn;e foule er&thorn;e and &thorn;e heuene. and &thorn;at alle o&thorn;er &thorn;inges stynten fro wi&thorn; oute. so &thorn;at &thorn;ou [nere neyther in heuene ne in erthe] ne say[e] no &thorn;ing more. &thorn;an sholde it semen to &thorn;e as by only resoun of lokynge. &thorn;at &thorn;ou were in &thorn;e sterres. and now in &thorn;e er&thorn;e. but &thorn;e poeple ne loke&thorn; nat on &thorn;ise &thorn;inges. what &thorn;an shal we &thorn;an approchen vs to hem &thorn;at I haue shewed &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben lyke to &thorn;e bestes. (q. d. non) &para; And what wilt &thorn;ou seyne of &thorn;is &para; yif &thorn;at a man hadde al forlorn hys sy&yogh;t. and had[de] for&yogh;eten &thorn;at he euer saw and wende &thorn;at no &thorn;ing ne fayled[e] hym of perfeccioun of mankynde. now we &thorn;at my&yogh;ten sen &thorn;e same &thorn;ing wolde we nat wene &thorn;at he were blynde (q. d. sic). ne also ne accorde&thorn; nat &thorn;e poeple to &thorn;at I shal seyne. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ing is susteyned by a stronge foundement of resouns. &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;at more vnsely ben &thorn;ei <PB N="129">&thorn;at don wrong to o&thorn;er folk. &thorn;en &thorn;ei &thorn;at &thorn;e wrong suffren.  &para; I wolde heren &thorn;ilke <MILESTONE N="29" UNIT="fol.">same resouns quod I  
&para; Deniest &thorn;ou quod she &thorn;at alle shrewes ne ben wor&thorn;i to han tourment. nay quod I. but quod she I am certeyne by many resouns &thorn;at shrewes ben vnsely. it accorde&thorn; quod I. &thorn;an [ne] dowtest &thorn;ou nat quod she &thorn;at &thorn;ilke folk &thorn;at ben wor&thorn;i of tourment &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne ben wrecches.  It accorde&thorn; wel quod I. yif &thorn;ou were &thorn;an quod she yset a Iuge or a knower of &thorn;inges. whe&thorn;er trowest &thorn;ou &thorn;at men sholde tourment[e] hym &thorn;at ha&thorn; don &thorn;e wronge. or hym &thorn;at ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;e wronge.  I ne doute nat quod I. &thorn;at I nolde don suffissaunt satisfaccioun to hym &thorn;at had[de] suffred &thorn;e wrong by &thorn;e sorwe of hym &thorn;at had[de] don &thorn;e wronge.  &para; &thorn;an seme&thorn; it quod she &thorn;at &thorn;e doar of wrong is more wrecche &thorn;an he &thorn;at ha&thorn; suffred &thorn;e wrong. &thorn;at folwe&thorn; wel quod [I]. &thorn;an quod she by &thorn;ise causes and by o&thorn;er causes &thorn;at ben enforced by &thorn;e same roate &thorn;at fil&thorn;e or synne by &thorn;e propre nature of it make&thorn; men wrecches. and it shewe&thorn; wel &thorn;at &thorn;e wrong &thorn;at men don nis nat &thorn;e wrecchenesse of hym &thorn;at receyue&thorn; &thorn;e wrong. but &thorn;e wrecchednesse of hym &thorn;at do&thorn; &thorn;e wronge  &para; but certys quod she &thorn;ise oratours or aduocat&yogh; don al &thorn;e contrarie for &thorn;ei enforcen hem to commoeue &thorn;e iuges to han pite of hem &thorn;at han suffred and resceyued &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben greuous and aspre. and &yogh;itte men sholden more ry&yogh;tfully han pitee on hem &thorn;at don &thorn;e greuaunces and &thorn;e wronges. &thorn;e whiche shrewes it were a more couenable &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;e accusours or aduocat&yogh; not wro&thorn;e but pitous and debonaire ladden &thorn;e shrewes &thorn;at han don wrong to &thorn;e Iugement. ry&yogh;t as men leden seke folk to &thorn;e leche. for &thorn;at &thorn;ei sholden seken out &thorn;e maladies of synne by <PB N="130">tourment&yogh;. and by &thorn;is couenaunt ey&thorn;er &thorn;e entent of &thorn;e defendours or aduocat&yogh; sholde fayle and cesen in al. or ellys yif &thorn;e office of aduocat&yogh; wolde bettre profiten to men. it sholde be tourned in to &thorn;e habit of accusacioun. &thorn;at is [to] s[e]yn &thorn;ei sholden accuse shrewes. and nat excuse hem. and eke &thorn;e shrewes hem self. &yogh;it it were leueful to hem to seen at any clifte &thorn;e vertue &thorn;at &thorn;ei han forleten. and sawen &thorn;at &thorn;ei sholde putten adoun &thorn;e fil&thorn;es of hire vices by [the] tourment&yogh; of peynes. &thorn;ei ne au&yogh;ten nat ry&yogh;t for &thorn;e recompensacioun forto geten hem bounte and prowesse whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ei han lost demen ne holden &thorn;at &thorn;ilke peynes weren tourmentes to hem. and eke &thorn;ei wolden refuse &thorn;e attendaunce of hir aduocat&yogh; and taken hem self to hire iuges and to hir accusours. for whiche it bytide&thorn; [&thorn;at] as to &thorn;e wise folk &thorn;er nis no place ylete to hate. &thorn;at is to seyn. &thorn;at hate ne ha&thorn; no place amonges wise men.  &para; For no wy&yogh;t wolde haten gode men. but yif he were ouer moche a fole.  &para; and forto haten shrewes it nis no resoun. &para; For ry&yogh;t so as languissing is maladie of body. ry&yogh;t so ben vices and synne maladies of corage. &para; and so as we ne deme nat &thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;at ben seek of hire body ben wor&thorn;i to ben hated. but ra&thorn;er wor&thorn;i of pite. wel more wor&thorn;i nat to ben hated. but forto ben had in pite ben &thorn;ei of whiche &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;tes ben constreined by felonous wickednesse. &thorn;at is more cruel &thorn;an any languissinge of body.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="4" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUID TANTOS IUUAT.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>What delite&thorn; it &yogh;ow to exciten so grete moewynges of hatredes and to hasten and bisien [the] fatal disposicioun of &yogh;oure dee&thorn; wi&thorn; &yogh;oure propre handes. &thorn;at is to seyn by batailes or [by] contek. for yif &yogh;e axen &thorn;e <PB N="131">dee&thorn; it hastisi&thorn; hym of hys owen wille. ne dee&thorn; ne tarie&thorn; nat hys swifte hors. and [the] men &thorn;at &thorn;e serpent&yogh; and &thorn;e lyouns. and &thorn;e tigre. and &thorn;e beere and &thorn;e boore seken to sleen wi&thorn; her te&thorn;e. &yogh;it &thorn;ilke same men seken to sleen eueryche of hem o&thorn;er wi&thorn; swerde. loo for her maners ben<MILESTONE N="29b" UNIT="fol.">diuerse and discordaunt &para; &thorn;ei  
moeuen vnry&yogh;tful oostes and cruel batailes. and wilne to perisse by enterchaungynge of dartes. but &thorn;e resoun of cruelte nis nat ynou&yogh; ry&yogh;tful. wilt &thorn;ou &thorn;an &yogh;elden a couenable gerdoun to &thorn;e desertes of men &para; Loue ry&yogh;tfully goode folk&meper; and haue pite on shrewes.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="5" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">HINC EGO UIDEO INQUAM. ET CETERA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;us see I wel quod I. ey&thorn;er what blisfulnesse or ellys what vnselinesse is estab[l]issed in &thorn;e desertys of goode men and of shrewes.  &para; but in &thorn;is ilke fortune of poeple I see somwhat of goode. and somwhat of yuel. for no wise man ha&thorn; nat leuer ben exiled pore and nedy and nameles. &thorn;an forto dwellen in hys Citee and flouren of rychesses. and be redoutable by honoure. and stronge of power for in &thorn;is wise more clerely and more witnesfully is &thorn;e office of wise men ytretid whan &thorn;e blisfulnes and [the] pouste of gouernours is as it were yshad amonges poeples &thorn;at ben ney&yogh;boures and subgit&yogh;. syn &thorn;at namely prisoun lawe and &thorn;ise o&thorn;er tourment&yogh; of lawful peynes ben ra&thorn;er owed to felonous Cite&yogh;eins. for &thorn;e whiche felonous Cite&yogh;eins &thorn;o peynes ben establissed. &thorn;an for goode folk.  &para; &thorn;an I merueile me gretly quod I. whi [&thorn;at] &thorn;e &thorn;inges ben so mys entrechaunged. &thorn;at tourment&yogh; of felounes pressen and confounden goode folk. and shrewes rauyssen medes of <PB N="132">vertue and ben in honours. and in grete estatis. and I desire eke to witen of &thorn;e. what seme&thorn; &thorn;e to ben &thorn;e resoun of &thorn;is so wrongful a confusioun  &para; For I wolde wondre wel &thorn;e lasse yif I trowed[e] &thorn;at alle &thorn;ise &thorn;inges were medeled by fortuouse hap.  &para; But now hepe&thorn; and encrese&thorn; myne astonyenge god gouernour of &thorn;inges. &thorn;at so as god &yogh;eue&thorn; ofte tymes to good[e] men goodes and myr&thorn;es. and to shrewes yuel and aspre &thorn;inges. and &yogh;eue&thorn; a&yogh;eynewarde to goode folk hardnesse. and to shrewes [he] graunte&thorn; hem her wille and &thorn;at &thorn;ei desiren. what difference &thorn;an may &thorn;er be bitwixen &thorn;at &thorn;at god do&thorn;. and &thorn;e hap of fortune. yif men ne knowe nat &thorn;e cause whi &thorn;at [it] is. it nis no merueile quod she &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at men wenen &thorn;at &thorn;er be somwhat folysche and confus whan &thorn;e resoun of &thorn;e order is vnknowe.  &para; But alle &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou ne know nat &thorn;e cause of so gret a disposicioun. na&thorn;eles for as moche as god &thorn;e good[e] gouernour attempre&thorn; and gouerne&thorn; &thorn;e world. ne doute &thorn;e nat &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges ne ben doon ary&yogh;t.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="5" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">SI QUIS ARCTURI</FOREIGN><NOTE>MS. <FOREIGN LANG="l">arituri</FOREIGN></NOTE><FOREIGN LANG="l">SYDERA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Who so &thorn;at ne knowe nat &thorn;e sterres of arctour ytourned neye to &thorn;e souereyne contre or point. &thorn;at is to seyne ytourned neye to &thorn;e souereyne pool of &thorn;e firmament and woot nat whi &thorn;e sterre boetes passe&thorn; or gaderi&thorn; his wey[n]es. and drenche&thorn; his late flaumbes in &thorn;e see. and whi &thorn;at boetes &thorn;e sterre vnfoldi&thorn; his ouer swifte arisynges. &thorn;an shal he wondren of &thorn;e lawe of &thorn;e heye eyre. and eke if &thorn;at he ne knowe nat why &thorn;at &thorn;e hornes of &thorn;e ful[le] moene waxen pale and infect by &thorn;e boundes of &thorn;e derke ny&yogh;t  &para; and how &thorn;e moene dirk 

<PB N="133">and confuse discouere&thorn; &thorn;e sterres. &thorn;at she had[de] ycouered by hir clere visage. &thorn;e commune errour moeue&thorn; folk and maki&thorn; wery hir bacines of bras by &thorn;ikke strookes. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;at &thorn;er is a maner poeple &thorn;at hy&yogh;t[e] coribandes &thorn;at wenen &thorn;at whan &thorn;e moone is in &thorn;e eclips &thorn;at it be enchauntid. and &thorn;erfore forto rescowe &thorn;e moone &thorn;ei betyn hire basines wi&thorn; &thorn;ikke strokes. &para; Ne no man ne wondre&thorn; whan &thorn;e blastes of &thorn;e wynde chorus betyn &thorn;e strondes of &thorn;e see by quakynge floodes. ne no man ne wondre&thorn; whan &thorn;e wey&yogh;te of &thorn;e snowe yhardid by &thorn;e colde. is resolued by &thorn;e brennynge hete of phebus &thorn;e sonne.  &para; For here seen men redyly &thorn;e causes. but &thorn;e<MILESTONE N="30" UNIT="fol."> causes yhid &thorn;at is to seye in heuene  
trouble &thorn;e brestes of men.  &para; &thorn;e mocueable poeple is a-stoned of alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at comen selde and sodeynely in oure age. but yif &thorn;e troubly errour of oure ignorance departid[e] from vs. so &thorn;at we wisten &thorn;e causes whi &thorn;at swiche &thorn;inges bitiden. certys &thorn;ei sholden cesse to seme wondres.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="6" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">ITA EST INQUAM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;vs is it quod I. but so as &thorn;ou hast &yogh;euen or byhy&yogh;t me to vnwrappen &thorn;e hidde causes of &thorn;inges  &para; and to discoueren me &thorn;e resouns couered with dirknesses I preye &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou diuise and Iuge me of &thorn;is matere. and &thorn;at &thorn;ou do me to vndrestonden it.  &para; For &thorn;is miracle or &thorn;is wondre trouble&thorn; me ry&yogh;t gretely. and &thorn;an she a htel [what] smylyng seide.  &para; &thorn;ou clepest me quod she to telle &thorn;ing. &thorn;at is grettest of alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at mowen ben axed.  &para; And to &thorn;e whiche questioun vnne&thorn;[e]s is &thorn;ere au&yogh;t ynow to lauen it. as who sei&thorn;. vnne&thorn;es is &thorn;er suffisauntly any &thorn;ing to answere perfitly to &thorn;i questioun. <PB N="134">&para; For &thorn;e matere of it is swiche &thorn;at whan oon doute is determined and kut awey &thorn;er wexen o&thorn;er doutes wi&thorn;outen noumbre. ry&yogh;t as &thorn;e heuedes waxen of ydre &thorn;e serpent &thorn;at hercules slou&yogh;.  &para; Ne &thorn;ere ne were no manere ne noon ende. but yif &thorn;at a wy&yogh;t constreined[e] &thorn;o doutes. by a ry&yogh;t lyuely and a quik fire of &thorn;ou&yogh;t. &thorn;at is to seyn by vigour and streng&thorn;e of witte.  &para; For in &thorn;is matere men weren wont to maken questiouns of &thorn;e simplicite of &thorn;e purueaunce of god and of &thorn;e ordre of destine. and of sodeyne hap. and of &thorn;e knowyng and predestinacioun deuine and of &thorn;e lyberte of fre wille. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ing &thorn;ou &thorn;i self aperceiust wel of what wey&yogh;t &thorn;ei ben. but for as mochel as &thorn;e knowynge of &thorn;ise &thorn;inges is a manere porcioun to &thorn;e medicine to &thorn;e. al be it so &thorn;at I haue lytel tyme to don it. &yogh;it na&thorn;eles I wole enforcen me to shewe somwhat of it.  &para; but al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e norissinges of dite of musike delite&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ow most suffren. and forberen a litel of &thorn;ilk delite while &thorn;at I weue (<FOREIGN LANG="l">contexo</FOREIGN>) to &thorn;e resouns yknyt by ordre &para; As it like&thorn; to &thorn;e quod I so do.  &para; &thorn;o spak she ry&yogh;t a[s] by an o&thorn;er bygynnyn[ge] and seide &thorn;us.  &para; &thorn;e engendrynge of alle &thorn;inges quod she and alle &thorn;e progressiouns of muuable nature. and alle &thorn;at moeue&thorn; in any manere taki&thorn; hys causes. hys ordre. and hys formes. of &thorn;e stablenesse of &thorn;e deuyne &thorn;ou&yogh;t [and thilke deuyne thowht] &thorn;at is yset and put in &thorn;e toure. &thorn;at is to seyne in &thorn;e hey&yogh;t of &thorn;e simplicite of god. stablisi&thorn; many manere gyses to &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben to don.  &para; &thorn;e whiche manere whan &thorn;at men loken it in &thorn;ilke pure clerenesse of &thorn;e deuyne intelligence. it is ycleped purueaunce  &para; but whan &thorn;ilke manere is referred <PB N="135">by men to &thorn;inges &thorn;at it moeue&thorn; and dispone&thorn; &thorn;an of olde men. it was cleped destine.  &para; &thorn;e whiche &thorn;inges yif &thorn;at any wy&yogh;t loke&thorn; wel in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t. &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of &thorn;at oon and of &thorn;at o&thorn;er he shal ly&yogh;tly mowen seen &thorn;at &thorn;ise two &thorn;inges ben diuers.  &para; For purueaunce is &thorn;ilke deuyne resoun &thorn;at is establissed in &thorn;e soucreyne prince of &thorn;inges. &thorn;e whiche purueaunce disponi&thorn; alle &thorn;inges. but destine is &thorn;e disposicioun and ordenaunce cleuynge to moeuable &thorn;inges. by &thorn;e whiche disposicioun &thorn;e purueaunce knyte&thorn; alle &thorn;inges in hire ordres.  &para; For purueaunce enbrace&thorn; alle &thorn;inges to hepe. al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben dyuerse and al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei ben wi&thorn; outen fyn. but destynie departe&thorn; and ordeyne&thorn; alle &thorn;inges singlerly and diuide&thorn;. in moeuynges. in places. in formes. in tymes. departi&thorn; [as] &thorn;us. so &thorn;at &thorn;e vnfoldyng of temporel ordenaunce assembled and ooned in &thorn;e lokyng of &thorn;e deuyne &thorn;ou&yogh;t  &para; Is purueaunce and &thorn;ilke same assemblynge. and oonyng diuided and vnfolden by tymes. lat &thorn;at ben called destine. and al be <MILESTONE N="30b" UNIT="fol.">it so &thorn;at  
&thorn;ise &thorn;inges ben dyuerse. &yogh;itte na&thorn;eles hange&thorn; &thorn;at oon on &thorn;at o&thorn;er. forwhi &thorn;e ordre destinal procedi&thorn; of &thorn;e simplicite of purueaunce. for ry&yogh;t as a werkman &thorn;at aperceiue&thorn; in hys &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;e forme of &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at he wil make moeue&thorn; &thorn;e effect of &thorn;e werke. and ledi&thorn; &thorn;at he had[de] loked byforne in hys &thorn;ou&yogh;t symply and presently by temporel &thorn;ou;t.  &para; Certys ry&yogh;t so god disponi&thorn; in hys purueaunce singlerly and stably &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben to done. but he amynistre&thorn; in many maneres and in dyuerse tymes by destyne. &thorn;ilke same &thorn;inges &thorn;at he ha&thorn; disponed &thorn;an whe&thorn;ir &thorn;at destine be excercised. ey&thorn;er by somme dyuyne spirites seruaunte&yogh; to &thorn;e deuyne purueaunce. or ellys by somme soule (<FOREIGN LANG="l">anima</FOREIGN><PB N="136"> <FOREIGN LANG="l">mundi</FOREIGN>). or ellys by al nature seruynge to god. or ellys by &thorn;e celestial moeuyng of sterres. or ellys by &thorn;e vertue of aungels. or ellys by &thorn;e dyuerse subtilite of deueles. or ellys by any of hem. or ellys by hem alle &thorn;e destynal ordynaunce is ywouen or accomplissed. certys it is open &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;e purueaunce is an vnmoeueable and symple forme of &thorn;inges to done. and &thorn;e moeueable bonde and &thorn;e temporel ordynaunce of &thorn;inges whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e deuyne simplicite of purueaunce ha&thorn; ordeyned to done. &thorn;at is destine.  For whiche it is &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben put vndir destine ben certys subgit&yogh; to purueaunce. to whiche purueaunce destine it self is subgit and vndir. &para; But somme &thorn;inges ben put vndir purueaunce &thorn;at sourmounten &thorn;e ordinaunce of destine. and &thorn;o ben &thorn;ilke &thorn;at stably ben yficched ney to &thorn;e first godhed &thorn;ei sourmounten &thorn;e ordre of destinal moeuablite.  &para; For ry&yogh;t as cercles &thorn;at tournen aboute a same Centre or about a poynt. &thorn;ilke cercle &thorn;at is inrest or moost wi&thorn;ynne ioine&thorn; to &thorn;e symplesse of &thorn;e myddel and is as it were a Centre or a poynt to &thorn;at o&thorn;er cercles &thorn;at tournen abouten hym.  &para; and &thorn;ilke &thorn;at is outerest compased by larger envyronnynge is vnfolden by larger spaces in so mochel as it is for&thorn;est fro &thorn;e mydel symplicite of &thorn;e poynt. and yif &thorn;er be any &thorn;ing &thorn;at knytte&thorn; and felawshippe&thorn; hym selfe to &thorn;ilke mydel poynt it is constreyned in to symplicite. &thorn;at is to seyn in to [vn]moeueablete. and it ceseth to ben shad and to fletin dyuersly.  &para; Ry&yogh;t so by semblable resoun. &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge &thorn;at departi&thorn; fir&thorn;est fro &thorn;e first &thorn;ou&yogh;t of god. it is vnfolden and summittid to grettere bondes of destine. and in so moche is &thorn;e &thorn;ing more free and lovs fro destyne as it axe&thorn; and <PB N="137">holde&thorn; hym ner to &thorn;ilke Centre of &thorn;inges &thorn;at is to seyne god.  &para; and if &thorn;e &thorn;inge cleue&thorn; to &thorn;e stedfastnesse of &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t of god. and be wi&thorn; oute moeuyng certys it sourmounte&thorn; &thorn;e necessite of destyne. &thorn;an ry&yogh;t swiche comparisoun as [it] is of skilynge to vndirstondyng and of &thorn;ing &thorn;at is engendred to &thorn;ing &thorn;at is. and of tyme to eternite. and of &thorn;e cercle to &thorn;e Centre. ry&yogh;t so is &thorn;e ordre of moeueable destine to &thorn;e stable symplicite of purueaunce.  &para; &thorn;ilke ordinaunce moeue&thorn; &thorn;e heuene and &thorn;e sterres and attempre&thorn; &thorn;e elyment&yogh; to gider amonges hem self. and transforme&thorn; hem by enterchaungable mutacioun.  &para; and &thorn;ilke same ordre newe&thorn; a&yogh;ein alle &thorn;inges growyng and fallyng a-doune by sembleables progressiouns of seedes and of sexes. &thorn;at is to sein. male and female. and &thorn;is ilke ordre constreyne&thorn; &thorn;e fortunes and &thorn;e dedes of men by a bonde of causes nat able to ben vnbounden (indissolubili). &thorn;e whiche destinal causes whanne &thorn;ei passen oute fro &thorn;e bygynnynges of &thorn;e vnmoeueable purueaunce it mot nedes be &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne be nat mutable. and &thorn;us ben &thorn;e &thorn;inges ful wel ygouerned. yif &thorn;at &thorn;e symplicite dwellynge<MILESTONE N="31" UNIT="fol."> in &thorn;e  
deuyne &thorn;ou&yogh;t shewe&thorn; fur&thorn;e &thorn;e ordre of causes. vnable to be I-bowed. and &thorn;is ordre constreyne&thorn; by hys propre stablete &thorn;e moeueable &thorn;inges. or ellys &thorn;ei sholde fleten folily for whiche it is &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges semen to be confus and trouble to vs men. for we ne mowe nat considere &thorn;ilke ordinaunce.  &para; Na&thorn;eles &thorn;e propre manere of euery &thorn;ing dressynge hem to goode disponit hem alle. for &thorn;ere nis no &thorn;inge don for cause of yuel. ne &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at is don by wicked[e] folk nis nat don for yuel &thorn;e whiche shrewes as I haue shewed [ful] plentiuously <PB N="138">seken goode. but wicked errour mystourni&thorn; hem.  &para; Ne &thorn;e ordre comynge fro &thorn;e poynt of souereyne goode ne decline&thorn; nat fro hys bygynnynge. but &thorn;ou mayst sein what vnreste may ben a wors confusioun &thorn;an &thorn;at goode men han somme tyme aduersite. and somtyme prosperite. &para; and shrewes also han now &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ei desiren. and now &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ei haten  &para; whe&thorn;er men lyuen now in swiche hoolnesse of &thorn;ou&yogh;t. as who sei&thorn;. ben men now so wise. &thorn;at swiche folk as &thorn;ei demen to ben goode folk or shrewes &thorn;at it mot nedes ben &thorn;at folk ben swiche as &thorn;ei wenen. but in &thorn;is manere &thorn;e domes of men discorden. &thorn;at &thorn;ilke men &thorn;at somme folk demen wor&thorn;i of mede. o&thorn;er folk demen hem wor&thorn;i of tourment. but lat vs graunt[e] I pose &thorn;at som man may wel demen or knowen &thorn;e goode folk and &thorn;e badde.  May he &thorn;an knowen and seen &thorn;ilke inrest attemperaunce of corages. as it ha&thorn; ben wont to be said of bodyes. as who sai&thorn; may a man speken and determine of attemperaunce in corages. as men were wont to demen or speken of complexiouns and attemperaunces of bodies (q' non). ne it [ne] is nat an vnlyke miracle to hem &thorn;at ne knowen it nat.  &para; As who sei&thorn;. but is lyke a merueil or a miracle to hem &thorn;at ne knowen it nat. whi &thorn;at swete &thorn;inges [ben] couenable to some bodies &thorn;at ben hool and to some bodies bittre &thorn;inges ben couenable. and also whi &thorn;at some seke folk ben holpen with ly&yogh;t medicines [and some folk ben holpen with sharppe medicynes] but na&thorn;eles &thorn;e leche &thorn;at knowe&thorn; &thorn;e manere and &thorn;e attemperaunce of heele and of maladie ne merueile&thorn; of it no &thorn;ing. but what o&thorn;er &thorn;ing seme&thorn; hele of corages but bounte and prowesse. and what o&thorn;er &thorn;ing seme&thorn; maladie of corages but vices. who is ellys kepere of good or <PB N="139">dryuere awey of yuel but god gouernour and leecher of &thorn;ou&yogh;tes. &thorn;e whiche god whan he ha&thorn; by-holden from &thorn;e heye toure of hys purueaunce he knowe&thorn; what is couenable to euery wy&yogh;t. and lene&thorn; hem &thorn;at he wot [&thorn;at] is couenable to hem.  Loo here of come&thorn; and here of is don &thorn;is noble miracle of &thorn;e ordre destinal. whan god &thorn;at alle knowe&thorn; do&thorn; swiche &thorn;ing. of whiche &thorn;ing [&thorn;at] vnknowyng folk ben astoned but forto constreine as who sei&thorn;  &para; But forto comprehende and telle a fewe &thorn;inges of &thorn;e deuyne depnesse &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at mans resoun may vnderstonde.  &para; &thorn;ilk man &thorn;at &thorn;ou wenest to ben ry&yogh;t Iuste and ry&yogh;t kepyng of equite. &thorn;e contrarie of &thorn;at seme&thorn; to &thorn;e deuyne purueaunce &thorn;at al woot. &para; And lucan my familier telle&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e victories cause liked[e] to &thorn;e goddes and causes ouercomen liked[e] to catoun. &thorn;an what so euer &thorn;ou mayst seen &thorn;at is don in &thorn;is [world] vnhoped or vnwened. certys it is &thorn;e ry&yogh;t[e] ordre of &thorn;inges. but as to &thorn;i wicked[e] oppinioun it is a confusioun. but I suppose &thorn;at som man be so wel y&thorn;ewed. &thorn;at &thorn;e deuyne Iugement and &thorn;e Iugement of mankynde accorden hem to gidre of hym. but he is so vnstedfast of corage [&thorn;at] yif any aduersite come to hym he wolde for-leten perauenture to continue innocence by &thorn;e whiche he ne may nat wi&thorn;holden fortune.  &para; &thorn;an &thorn;e wise dispensacioun of god spare&thorn; hym &thorn;e whiche manere aduersite<MILESTONE N="31b" UNIT="fol.">my&yogh;t[e] enpeyren.  &para; For &thorn;at god  
wil nat suffren hym to trauaile. to whom &thorn;at trauayl nis nat couenable.  &para; An o&thorn;er man is perfit in alle uertues. and is an holy man and neye to god so &thorn;at &thorn;e purueaunce of god wolde demen &thorn;at it were a felony &thorn;at he were touched wi&thorn; any aduersites. so &thorn;at he ne <PB N="140">wil nat suffre &thorn;at swiche a man be moeued wi&thorn; any manere maladie.  &para; But so as seide a philosophre [the moore excellent by me]. &thorn;e aduersites comen nat (he seide in grec&meper;) &thorn;ere &thorn;at uertues han edified &thorn;e bodie of &thorn;e holy man. and ofte tyme it bitide&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e somme of &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben to don is taken to good folk to gouerne. for &thorn;at &thorn;e malice habundaunt of shrewes sholde ben abatid. and god &yogh;eue&thorn; and departi&thorn; to o&thorn;er folk prosp[er]ites and aduersites ymedeled to hepe aftir &thorn;e qualite of hire corages and remordi&thorn; som folk by aduersites. for &thorn;ei ne sholden nat wexen proude by longe welefulnesse. and o&thorn;er folk he suffre&thorn; to ben trauayled wi&thorn; harde &thorn;inges.  &para; For &thorn;at &thorn;ei sholden conferme &thorn;e vertues of corage by &thorn;e vsage and exercitacioun of pacience. and o&thorn;er folke dreden more &thorn;en &thorn;ei au&yogh;ten &thorn;e wiche &thorn;ei my&yogh;t[en] wel beren. and &thorn;ilke folk god ledi&thorn; in to experience of hem self by aspre and sorweful &thorn;inges.  &para; And many o&thorn;er folk han bou&yogh;t honorable renoune of &thorn;is worlde by &thorn;e pris of glorious dee&thorn;. and som men &thorn;at ne mowen nat ben ouer-comen by tourment han &yogh;euen ensample to o&thorn;er folk &thorn;at vertue ne may nat be ouer-comen by aduersites.  &para; and of alle &thorn;ise &thorn;inges &thorn;er nis no doute &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne ben don ry&yogh;tfully and ordeinly to &thorn;e profit of hem to whom we seen &thorn;ise &thorn;inges bitide.  &para; For certys &thorn;at aduersite come&thorn; some tyme to shrewes. and some tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ei desiren it come&thorn; of &thorn;ise forseide causes and of sorweful &thorn;inges &thorn;at bytyden to shrewes.  Certys no man ne wondre&thorn;.  For alle men wenen &thorn;at &thorn;ei han wel deserued it. and &thorn;ei ben of wicked merite of whiche <PB N="141">shrewes &thorn;e tourment som tyme agaste&thorn; o&thorn;er to done folies. and som tyme it amende&thorn; hem &thorn;at suffren &thorn;e tourmentis.  &para; And &thorn;e prosperite &thorn;at is &yogh;euen to shrewes shewe&thorn; a grete argument to good[e] folk what &thorn;ing &thorn;ei sholde demen of &thorn;ilk wilfulnesse &thorn;e whiche prosperite men seen ofte serue to shrewes. in &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ing I trowe &thorn;at god dispensi&thorn;. for perauenture &thorn;e nature of som man is so ouer&thorn;rowyng to yuel and so vncouenable &thorn;at &thorn;e nedy pouerte of hys house-hold my&yogh;t[e] ra&thorn;er egren hym to done felonies. and to &thorn;e maladie of hym god putti&thorn; remedie to &yogh;iuen hym rychesse. and som o&thorn;er man byholdi&thorn; hys conscience defouled wi&thorn; synnes and maki&thorn; comparisoun of his fortune and of hym self &para; and dredi&thorn; perauenture &thorn;at hys blisfulnesse of whiche &thorn;e vsage is ioyful to hym &thorn;at &thorn;e lesynge of &thorn;ilke blisfulnesse ne be nat sorweful to hym. and &thorn;erfore he wol chaunge hys maneres. and for he dredi&thorn; to lese hys fortune. he forleti&thorn; hys wickednesse. to o&thorn;er folk is welefulnesse y&yogh;euen vnwor&thorn;ily &thorn;e whiche ouer&thorn;rowe&thorn; hem in to destruccioun &thorn;at &thorn;ei han deserued. and to som o&thorn;er folk is &yogh;euen power to punissen. for &thorn;at it shal be cause of continuacioun and exercisinge to good[e] folk. and cause of tourment to shrewes.  &para; For so as &thorn;er nis none alyaunce bytwixe good[e] folke and shrewes. ne shrewes ne mowen nat accorden amonges hem self and whi nat. for shrewes discorden of hem self by her vices &thorn;e whiche vices al to renden her consciences. and don oft[e] tyme &thorn;inges &thorn;e whiche &thorn;inges whan &thorn;ei han don hem. &thorn;ei demen &thorn;at &thorn;o &thorn;inges ne sholde nat han ben don. for whiche &thorn;inge &thorn;ilke soucreyne purueaunce ha&thorn; maked oft[e] tyme <PB N="142">[faire] miracle so &thorn;at shrewes han maked oftyme shrewes to ben good[e] men. for whan &thorn;at som shrewes <MILESTONE N="32" UNIT="fol."> seen &thorn;at &thorn;ei suffren wrongfully felonies of o&thorn;er shrewes &thorn;ei wexen eschaufed in to hat[e] of hem &thorn;at anoien hem. and retournen to &thorn;e fruit of uertue. when &thorn;ei studien to ben vnlyke to hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei han hated. &para; Certys &thorn;is only is &thorn;e deuyne my&yogh;t to &thorn;e whiche my&yogh;t yueles ben &thorn;an good. whan it vse&thorn; &thorn;o yueles couenably and drawe&thorn; out &thorn;e effect of any good. as who sei&thorn; &thorn;at yuel is good oonly by &thorn;e my&yogh;t of god. for &thorn;e my&yogh;t of god ordeyne&thorn; &thorn;ilk yuel to good.  For oon ordre enbrasi&thorn; alle &thorn;inges. so &thorn;at what wy&yogh;t [&thorn;at] departi&thorn; fro &thorn;e resoun of &thorn;e ordre whiche &thorn;at is assigned to hym. algates &yogh;it he slide&thorn; in to an o&thorn;er ordre. so &thorn;at no&thorn;ing nis leueful to folye in &thorn;e realme of &thorn;e deuyne purueaunce. as who sei&thorn; no &thorn;ing nis wi&thorn;outen ordinaunce in &thorn;e realme of &thorn;e deuyne purueaunce.  &para; Syn &thorn;at &thorn;e ry&yogh;t strong[e] god gouerni&thorn; alle &thorn;inges in &thorn;is worlde for it nis nat leueful to no man to comprehenden by witte ne vnfolden by worde alle &thorn;e subtil ordinaunces and disposiciouns of &thorn;e deuyne entent. for oonly it au&yogh;t[e] suffice to han loked &thorn;at god hym self makere of alle natures ordeyni&thorn; and dressi&thorn; alle &thorn;inges to good. while &thorn;at he hasti&thorn; to wi&thorn;halden &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at he ha&thorn; maked in to hys semblaunce. &thorn;at is to seyn forto wi&thorn;holden &thorn;inges in to good. for he hym self is good he chase&thorn; oute al yuel of &thorn;e boundes of hys communalite by &thorn;e ordre of necessite destinable.  For whiche it folwe&thorn; &thorn;at yif &thorn;ou loke &thorn;e purueaunce ordeynynge &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at men wenen ben haboundaunt in er&thorn;es. &thorn;ou ne shalt not seen in no place no &thorn;ing of yuel.  &para; but I se now &thorn;at <PB N="143">&thorn;ou art charged wi&thorn; &thorn;e wey&yogh;te of &thorn;e questiou[n] and wery wi&thorn; leng&thorn;e of my resoun. and &thorn;at &thorn;ou abidest som swetnesse of songe. tak &thorn;an &thorn;is drau&yogh;t and whan &thorn;ou art wel refresshed and refet &thorn;ou shalt ben more stedfast to stye in to heyere questiouns.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="6" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">SI UIS CELSI IURA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Yif &thorn;ou wolt demen in &thorn;i pure &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;e ry&yogh;tes or &thorn;e lawes of &thorn;e heye &thorn;und[ere]re. &thorn;at is to seyne of god. loke &thorn;ou and bihold &thorn;e hey&yogh;tes of souereyne heuene. &para; &thorn;ere kepen &thorn;e sterres by ry&yogh;tful alliaunee of &thorn;inges hir olde pees. &thorn;e sonne ymoeued by hys rody fire. ne destourbi&thorn; nat &thorn;e colde cercle of &thorn;e moone.  &para; Ne &thorn;e sterre yclepid &thorn;e bere. &thorn;at enclini&thorn; hys rauyssynge courses abouten &thorn;e souereyne hey&yogh;t of &thorn;e worlde. ne &thorn;e same sterre vrsa nis neuer mo wasshen in &thorn;e depe westerne see. ne coueiti&thorn; nat to dy&yogh;en hys flaumbes in &thorn;e see of [the] occian. al &thorn;ou&yogh; he see o&thorn;er sterres yplounged in to &thorn;e see.  &para; And hesperus &thorn;e sterre bodi&thorn; and telli&thorn; alwey &thorn;e late ny&yogh;tes.  And lucifer &thorn;e sterre brynge&thorn; a&yogh;eyne &thorn;e clere day.  &para; And &thorn;us maki&thorn; loue enterchaungeable &thorn;e perdurable courses. and &thorn;us is discordable bataile yput oute of &thorn;e contre of &thorn;e sterres. &thorn;is accordaunce attempre&thorn; by euene-lyke manere[s] &thorn;e elementes. &thorn;at &thorn;e moyste &thorn;inges striuen nat wi&thorn; &thorn;e drye &thorn;inges. but &yogh;iuen place by stoundes. and &thorn;at &thorn;e colde &thorn;inges ioynen hem by fei&thorn; to &thorn;e hote &thorn;inges. and &thorn;at &thorn;e ly&yogh;t[e] fyre arist in to hey&yogh;te. and &thorn;e heuy er&thorn;es aualen by her wey&yogh;tes.  &para; by &thorn;ise same cause &thorn;e floury yere &yogh;elde&thorn; swote smellys in &thorn;e fyrste somer sesoun warmynge. and &thorn;e hote somer drye&thorn; &thorn;e cornes. and <PB N="144">autumpne come&thorn; a&yogh;eyne heuy of apples. and &thorn;e fletyng reyne bydewe&thorn; &thorn;e wynter. &thorn;is attemperaunce noryssi&thorn; and bryngge&thorn; fur&thorn;e al &thorn;inge &thorn;at bredi&thorn; lyfe in &thorn;is worlde. &para; and &thorn;ilk same attemperaunce rauyssyng hide&thorn; and bynyme&thorn; and drenche&thorn; vndir &thorn;e last[e] de&thorn;e alle <MILESTONE N="32b" UNIT="fol."> &thorn;inges yborn.  &para; Amonges &thorn;ise &thorn;inges sitte&thorn; &thorn;e heye makere kyng and lorde. welle and bygynnynge. lawe and wise Iuge. to don equite and gouerni&thorn; and enclini&thorn; &thorn;e bridles of &thorn;inges. and &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at he stire&thorn; to don by moeuynge he wi&thorn;drawe&thorn; and aresti&thorn; and affermi&thorn; &thorn;e moeueable or wandryng &thorn;inges.  &para; For &yogh;if &thorn;at he ne clepi&thorn; nat a&yogh;ein &thorn;e ry&yogh;t goynge of &thorn;inges. and &yogh;if &thorn;at he ne constreyned[e] hem nat eftesones in to roundenesse enclined &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben now continued by stable ordinaunce. &thorn;ei sholde deperten from hir welle. &thorn;at is to sein from hir bygynnynge and failen. &thorn;at is to sein tournen in to nau&yogh;t.  &para; &thorn;is is &thorn;e commune loue of alle &thorn;inges. and alle &thorn;inges axen to be holden by &thorn;e fyn of good.  For ellys ne my&yogh;ten &thorn;ei nat lasten yif &thorn;ei ne come nat eftesones a&yogh;eine by loue retourned to &thorn;e cause &thorn;at ha&thorn; &yogh;euen hem beynge. &thorn;at is to seyn to god.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="7" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">IAM NE IGITUR UIDES.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Sest &thorn;ou nat &thorn;an what &thorn;ing folwe&thorn; alle &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at I haue seid. what &thorn;ing quod I.  &para; Certys quod she outerly &thorn;at al fortune is good. and how may &thorn;at be quod .I.  &para; Now vndirstand quod she so as [alle fortune wheyther so it be Ioyeful fortune / or aspre] fortune is &yogh;iuen ei&thorn;er by cause of gerdonynge or ellys of exercisynge of goode folk or ellys by cause to punissen. <PB N="145">or ellys to chastysen shrewes.  &para; &thorn;an is alle fortune good. &thorn;e whiche fortune is certeyne &thorn;at it be ei&thorn;er ry&yogh;tful or profitable.  &para; For so&thorn;e &thorn;is is a ful verray resoun quod I. and yif I considere &thorn;e purueaunce and &thorn;e destine &thorn;at &thorn;ou tau&yogh;test me a litel here byforne &thorn;is sentence is susteyned by stedfast resouns. but yif it like vnto &thorn;e lat vs noumbre hem amonges &thorn;ilk[e] &thorn;inges of whiche &thorn;ou seidest a litel here byforne &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne were nat able to ben ywened to &thorn;e poeple.  &para; whi so quod she. for &thorn;at &thorn;e comune worde of men mysusi&thorn; quod I. &thorn;is manere speche of fortune. and sein ofte tymes [&thorn;at] &thorn;e fortune of som wy&yogh;t is wicked. wilt &thorn;ou &thorn;an quod she &thorn;at I proche a litel to &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e poeple so it seme nat to hem &thorn;at I be ouer moche departid as fro &thorn;e vsage of man kynde. as &thorn;ou wolt quod I.  &para; Demest &thorn;ou nat quod she &thorn;at al &thorn;ing &thorn;at profiti&thorn; is good. &yogh;is quod I. certis &thorn;ilk &thorn;ing &thorn;at exercisi&thorn; or corigi&thorn; profiti&thorn;. I confesse it wel quod I. &thorn;an is it good quod she. whi nat quod I. but &thorn;is is &thorn;e fortune [quod she] of hem &thorn;at ei&thorn;er ben put in vertue and batailen a&yogh;eins aspre &thorn;inges. or ellys of hem &thorn;at eschewen and declinen fro vices and taken &thorn;e weye of vertue.  &para; &thorn;is ne may nat I denye quod I  &para; But what seist &thorn;ou of &thorn;e myrye fortune &thorn;at is &yogh;euen to good folk in gerdoun deuini&thorn; ou&yogh;t &thorn;e poeples &thorn;at it is wicked. nay forso&thorn;e quod I. but &thorn;ei demen as it so&thorn;e is &thorn;at it is ry&yogh;t good.  &para; And what seist &thorn;ou of &thorn;at o&thorn;er fortune quod she. &thorn;at al &thorn;ou&yogh; it be aspre and restreini&thorn; &thorn;e shrewes by ry&yogh;tful tourment. weni&thorn; ou&yogh;t &thorn;e poeple &thorn;at it be good. nay quod I.  &para; But &thorn;e poeple demi&thorn; &thorn;at it be most wrecched of alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at may ben &thorn;ou&yogh;t. war now and loke wel quod she lest &thorn;at we in folwyng &thorn;e opynioun of poeple haue confessed <PB N="146">and concluded &thorn;ing &thorn;at is vnable to be wened to &thorn;e poeple. what is &thorn;at quod I  &para; Certys quod she it folwe&thorn; or come&thorn; of &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben graunted &thorn;at alle fortune what so euer it be. of hem &thorn;at ey&thorn;er ben in possessioun of vertue. [or in the encres of vertu] or ellys in &thorn;e purchasynge of vertue. &thorn;at &thorn;ilke fortune is good. &para; And &thorn;at alle fortune is ry&yogh;t wicked to hem &thorn;at dwellen in shrewednesse. as who sei&thorn;. and &thorn;us wene&thorn; nat &thorn;e poeple.  &para; &thorn;at is so&thorn;e quod I.  &para; Al be it so &thorn;at noman dar confessen it ne byknowen it.  &para; whi so quod she.  For ry&yogh;t as no strong man ne seme&thorn; nat to 
 abassen or disdaignen as <MILESTONE N="33" UNIT="fol.">ofte tyme as he here&thorn; &thorn;e noise of &thorn;e bataile. ne also it ne seme&thorn; nat to &thorn;e wyse man to beren it greuously as oft[e] as he is lad in to &thorn;e strif of fortune. for bo&thorn;e to &thorn;at on man and eke to &thorn;at o&thorn;er &thorn;ilke difficulte is &thorn;e matere to &thorn;at oon man of encrese of his glorious renoun. and to &thorn;at o&thorn;er man to conferme hys sapience. &thorn;at is to seine &thorn;e asprenesse of hys estat. &para; For &thorn;erfore is it called uertue. for &thorn;at it susteni&thorn; and enforce&thorn; by hys streng&thorn;es &thorn;at it nis nat ouer-comen by aduersites.  &para; Ne certys &thorn;ou &thorn;at art put in &thorn;e encrese or in &thorn;e hey&yogh;t of uertue ne hast nat comen to fleten wi&thorn; delices and forto welken in bodyly lust.  &para; &thorn;ou sowest or plauntest a ful egre bataile in &thorn;i corage a&yogh;eins euery fortune. for &thorn;at &thorn;e sorweful fortune ne confounde &thorn;e nat. ne &thorn;at &thorn;e myrye fortune ne corrumpe &thorn;e nat. &para; Occupy &thorn;e mene by stedfast streng&thorn;es. for al &thorn;at euer is vndir &thorn;e mene. or ellys al &thorn;at ouer-passe&thorn; &thorn;e mene despise&thorn; welefulnesses.  &para; As who sei&thorn;. it is vicious and ne ha&thorn; no mede of hys trauaile.  &para; For it is set in &yogh;oure hand. as who sei&thorn; it lie&thorn; in &yogh;oure power what fortune &yogh;ow is leuest. &thorn;at is to seyne good or yuel.  &para; For alle fortune <PB N="147">&thorn;at seme&thorn; sharpe or aspre yif it ne exercise nat &thorn;e good folk. ne chastisi&thorn; &thorn;e wicked folk. it punisse&thorn;.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="7" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">BELLA BIS QUENIS. ET CETERA.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;e wrekere attrides  &para; &thorn;at is to seyne agamenon &thorn;at wrou&yogh;t[e] and continued[e] &thorn;e batailes by ten &yogh;ere recouered[e] and purged[e] in wrekyng by &thorn;e destruccioun of troie &thorn;e loste chambres of mariage of hys bro&thorn;er &thorn;is is to seyn &thorn;at [he] agamenon wan a&yogh;ein Eleine &thorn;at was Menelaus wif his bro&thorn;er.  In &thorn;e mene while &thorn;at &thorn;ilke agamenon desired[e] to &yogh;euen sailes to &thorn;e grekysshe nauye and bou&yogh;t[e] a&yogh;ein &thorn;e wyndes by blode. he vnclo&thorn;ed[e] hym of pite as fader. and &thorn;e sory prest &yogh;iue&thorn; in sacrifiynge &thorn;e wreched kuyttyng of &thorn;rote of &thorn;e dou&yogh;ter.  &para; &thorn;at is to sein &thorn;at agamenon lete kuytten &thorn;e &thorn;rote of hys dou&yogh;ter by &thorn;e prest. to maken alliaunce wi&thorn; hys goddes. and for to haue wynde wi&thorn; whiche he my&yogh;t[e] wende to troie.  &para; Itakus &thorn;at is to sein vlixies bywept[e] hys felawes ylorn &thorn;e whiche felawes &thorn;e fiers[e] pholifemus ligginge in his grete Caue had[de] freten and dreint in hys empty wombe. but na&thorn;eles polifemus wood for his blinde visage &yogh;eld to vlixies ioye by hys sorowful teres. &thorn;is is to seyn &thorn;at vlixes smot oute &thorn;e eye of poliphemus &thorn;at stod in hys forhede. for whiche vlixes hadde ioie whan he saw poliphemus wepyng and blynde.  &para; Hercules is celebrable for hys hard[e] trauaile he dawntede &thorn;e proude Centauris half hors half man. and he rafte &thorn;e despoylynge fro &thorn;e <PB N="148">cruel lyoun &thorn;at is to seyne he slou&yogh; &thorn;e lyoun and rafte hym hys skyn. he smot &thorn;e brids &thorn;at hy&yogh;ten arpijs [in &thorn;e palude of lyrne] wi&thorn; certeyne arwes. he rauyssed[e] applis fro &thorn;e wakyng dragoun. and hys hand was &thorn;e more heuy for &thorn;e golde[ne] metal.  He drou&yogh; Cerberus &thorn;e hound of helle by hys treble cheyne. he ouer-comer as it is seid ha&thorn; put an vnmeke lorde fodre to hys cruel hors  &para; &thorn;is is to sein. &thorn;at hercules slou&yogh; diomedes and made his hors to etyn hym. and he hercules slou&yogh; Idra &thorn;e serpent and brend[e] &thorn;e venym. and achelaus &thorn;e flode defouled[e] in his forhede dreint[e] his shamefast visage in his strondes. &thorn;is to sein &thorn;at achelaus cou&thorn;e transfigure hym self in to dyuerse lykenesse. and as he fau&yogh;t wi&thorn; orcules at &thorn;e laste he turnid[e] hym in to a bole and hercules brak of oon of hys hornes. and achelaus for shame hidde hym in hys ryuer.  &para; And [he] hercules <MILESTONE N="33b" UNIT="fol."> adoun Antheus &thorn;e geaunt in &thorn;e strondes of libye. and kacus apaised[e] &thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;es of euander. &thorn;is is to sein &thorn;at hercules slou&yogh; &thorn;e Monstre kacus and apaised[e] wi&thorn; &thorn;at dee&thorn; &thorn;e wra&thorn;&thorn;e of euander.  &para; And &thorn;e bristled[e] boor marked[e] wi&thorn; scomes &thorn;e sholdres of hercules. &thorn;e whiche sholdres &thorn;e heye cercle of heuene sholde &thorn;reste. and &thorn;e laste of his labours was &thorn;at he sustened[e] &thorn;e heuene vpon his nekke vnbowed. and he deserued[e] eftsones &thorn;e heuene to ben &thorn;e pris of his laste trauayle  &para; Go&thorn; now &thorn;an &yogh;e stronge men &thorn;ere as &thorn;e heye weye of &thorn;e grete ensample lede&thorn; &yogh;ou.  &para; O nice men whi nake &yogh;e &yogh;oure bakkes. as who sei&thorn;.  &para; O &yogh;e <PB N="149">slowe and delicat men whi fley &yogh;e aduersites. and ne fy&yogh;ten nat a&yogh;eins hem by vertue to wynnen &thorn;e mede of &thorn;e heuene. for &thorn;e er&thorn;e ouer-comen &yogh;eue&thorn; &thorn;e sterres. &para; &thorn;is is to seyne &thorn;at whan &thorn;at er&thorn;ely lust is ouer-comen. a man is maked wor&thorn;i to &thorn;e heuene.</P></DIV2><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="l">EXPLICIT LIBER QUARTUS.</FOREIGN></TRAILER></DIV1><DIV1 N="5" TYPE="book"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">INCIPIT LIBER QUINTUS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><DIV2 N="1" TYPE="prose">

<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">DIXERAT ORACIONISQUE CURSUM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>She hadde seid and tourned[e] &thorn;e cours of hir resoun to somme o&thorn;er &thorn;inges to ben tretid and to ben ysped. &thorn;an seide I.  Certys ry&yogh;tful is &thorn;in amonestyng and ful digne by auctorite. but &thorn;at &thorn;ou seidest som tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e questioun of &thorn;e deuyne purueaunce is enlaced wi&thorn; many o&thorn;er questiouns. I vndir-stonde wel and proue it by &thorn;e same &thorn;inge. but I axe yif &thorn;at &thorn;ou wenest &thorn;at hap be any &thorn;ing in any weys. and if &thorn;ou wenest &thorn;at hap be any [thing] what is it. &thorn;an quod she. I haste me to &yogh;elden and assoilen &thorn;e to &thorn;e dette of my byheste and to shewen and opnen &thorn;e wey by whiche wey &thorn;ou maist come a&yogh;ein to &thorn;i contre.  &para; but al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;inges whiche &thorn;at &thorn;ou axest ben ry&yogh;t profitable to knowe. &yogh;itte ben &thorn;ei diuers somwhat fro &thorn;e pa&thorn;e of my purpos. And it is to douten &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne be maked weery by mysweys so &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne mayst nat suffise to mesuren &thorn;e ry&yogh;t weye.  &para; Ne doute &thorn;e &thorn;er-of no &thorn;ing quod I. for forto knowen &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges to-gidre in &thorn;e whiche &thorn;inges I delite me gretly. &thorn;at shal ben to me in stede of reste. Syn it nis nat to douten of &thorn;e &thorn;inges folwynge whan euery side of &thorn;i disputisoun shal be stedfast to me by vndoutous fei&thorn;.  &thorn;an seide she. &thorn;at manere wol I don <PB N="150">&thorn;e. and bygan to speken ry&yogh;t &thorn;us  &para; Certys quod she yif any wy&yogh;t diffinisse hap in &thorn;is manere. &thorn;at is to seyn. &thorn;at hap is bytidynge y-brou&yogh;t for&thorn;e by foelyshe moeuynge. and by no knyttyng of causes.  &para; I conferme &thorn;at hap nis ry&yogh;t nau&yogh;t in no wise. and I deme al outerly &thorn;at hap nis ne dwelli&thorn; but a voys.  &para; As who sei&thorn;. but an ydel worde wi&thorn; outen any significacioun of &thorn;ing summittid to &thorn;at vois. for what place my&yogh;t[e] ben left or dwellynge to folie and to disordinaunce. syn &thorn;at god ledi&thorn; and streyni&thorn; alle &thorn;inges by ordre.  &para; For &thorn;is sentence is verray and so&thorn;e &thorn;at no &thorn;inge ne ha&thorn; his beynge of nou&yogh;t. to [the] whiche sentence none of &thorn;ise olde folk ne wi&thorn;seide neuere al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne vndirstoden ne moeueden it nau&yogh;t by god prince and gynner of wirkyng. but &thorn;ei casten as a manere foundement of subgit material. &thorn;at is to seyn of [the] nature of alle resoun. and &yogh;if &thorn;at ony &thorn;inge is woxen or comen of no causes. &thorn;an shal it seme &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge is comen or woxen of nou&yogh;t. but yif &thorn;is ne may nat ben don. &thorn;an is it nat possible &thorn;at &thorn;ere ha&thorn; ben any swiche &thorn;ing as I haue diffinissid a litel here byforne.  &para; How shal it &thorn;an ben quod I. nis &thorn;er &thorn;an no &thorn;ing &thorn;at by ry&yogh;t may be cleped ey&thorn;er happe or ellis auenture of fortune. or is 
 &thorn;er ou&yogh;t al <MILESTONE N="34" UNIT="fol.">be it so &thorn;at it is hidd fro &thorn;e poeple to whiche &thorn;ise wordes ben couenable.  Myn aristotul quod she. in &thorn;e book of his phisik diffinisse&thorn; &thorn;is &thorn;ing by short resoun and ney&yogh;e to &thorn;e so&thorn;e.  &para; In whiche manere quod I.  &para; As ofte quod she as men don any &thorn;ing for grace of any o&thorn;er &thorn;ing. and an o&thorn;er &thorn;inge &thorn;an &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at men ententen to doon bytide&thorn; by som[e] causes it is ycleped happe.  &para; Ry&yogh;t as a man dalf &thorn;e er&thorn;e by <PB N="151">cause of tylienge of &thorn;e felde. and fond &thorn;ere a gobet of golde by-doluen. &thorn;an wenen folk &thorn;at it is fallen by fortunous bytydyng. but for so&thorn;e it nis nat for nau&yogh;t for it ha&thorn; hys propre causes of whiche causes &thorn;e cours vnforseyn and vnwar semi&thorn; to han maked happe.  &para; For yif &thorn;e tilier in &thorn;e er&thorn;e ne delue nat in &thorn;e felde. and yif &thorn;e hider of &thorn;e golde ne hadde hidd &thorn;e golde in &thorn;ilke place. &thorn;e golde ne had[de] nat ben founde. &thorn;ise ben &thorn;an &thorn;e causes of &thorn;e abreggynge of fortune hap. &thorn;e whiche abreggynge of fortune hap come&thorn; of causes encountrynge and flowyng to-gidre to hem selfe. and nat by &thorn;e entencioun of &thorn;e doer.  &para; For nei&thorn;er &thorn;e hider of &thorn;e gold. ne &thorn;e deluer of &thorn;e felde ne vndirstanden nat &thorn;at &thorn;e golde sholde han be founde. but as I seide. it bytidde and ran to-gidre &thorn;at he dalf &thorn;ere as &thorn;at o&thorn;er hadde hidd &thorn;e golde.  Now may I &thorn;us diffinissen happe.  &para; Happe is an vnwar bytydyng of causes assembled in &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben don for som o&thorn;er &thorn;inge. but &thorn;ilke ordre procedynge by an vneschewable byndynge to-gidre. whiche &thorn;at descende&thorn; fro &thorn;e wel of purueaunce &thorn;at ordeine&thorn; alle &thorn;inges in hire places and in hire tymes make&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e causes rennen and assemblen to-gidre.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="1" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">RUPIS ACHEMENIE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>TIgris [and] eufrates resoluen and spryngen of a welle in &thorn;e kragges of &thorn;e roche of &thorn;e contre of achemenye &thorn;ere as &thorn;e fleenge [batayle] ficchi&thorn; hire dartes retournid in &thorn;e brestes of hem &thorn;at folwen hem.  &para; And sone aftre &thorn;e same ryueres tigris and eufrates vnioygnen and departen <PB N="152">hire watres. and yif &thorn;ei comen to-gidre and ben assembled and clepid to-gidre in to o cours. &thorn;an moten &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges fletyn to-gidre whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e water of &thorn;e entrechaungyng flode brynge&thorn; &thorn;e shippes and &thorn;e stokkes araced wi&thorn; &thorn;e flood moten assemble. and &thorn;e watres ymedlyd wrappi&thorn; or implie&thorn; many fortunel happes or maneres. &thorn;e whiche wandryng happes na&thorn;eles &thorn;ilke enclinyng lowenes of &thorn;e er&thorn;e. and &thorn;e flowynge ordre of &thorn;e slidyng water gouerni&thorn;.  &para; Ry&yogh;t so fortune &thorn;at seme&thorn; as [&thorn;at] it fleti&thorn; wi&thorn; slaked or vngouerned[e] bridles.  It suffri&thorn; bridles &thorn;at is to seyn to ben gouerned and passe&thorn; by &thorn;ilke lawe. &thorn;at is to sein by &thorn;e deuyne ordinaunce.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="2" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">ANIMADUERTO INQUAM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;is vndirstonde I wel quod I. and accorde wel &thorn;at it is ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ou seist. but I axe yif &thorn;er be any liberte or fre wil in &thorn;is ordre of causes &thorn;at cliuen &thorn;us to-gidre in hem self.  &para; or ellys I wolde witen yif &thorn;at &thorn;e destinal cheine constreini&thorn; &thorn;e moeueuynge of &thorn;e corages of men. yis quod she &thorn;er is liberte of fre wille. ne &thorn;er ne was neuer no nature of resoun &thorn;at it ne hadde liberte of fre wille.  &para; For euery &thorn;ing &thorn;at may naturely vsen resoun. it ha&thorn; doom by whiche it discerni&thorn; and demi&thorn; euery &thorn;ing.  &para; &thorn;an knowe&thorn; it by it self &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben to fleen. and &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben to desiren. and &thorn;ilk &thorn;ing &thorn;at any wy&yogh;t deme&thorn; to ben desired &thorn;at axe&thorn; or desire&thorn; he and flee&thorn; [thilke] &thorn;ing &thorn;at he troue&thorn; ben to fleen. &para; wher-fore in alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at resoun is. in hem also is libertee of willyng and of nillynge.  &para; But I ne ordeyne nat. as who sei&thorn;. I ne graunte nat &thorn;at &thorn;is libertee be euene like in alle &thorn;inges. forwhi in &thorn;e souereyns deuynes 
 substaunces. &thorn;at is to <MILESTONE N="34b" UNIT="fol.">seyn in spirit&yogh;  &para; Iugement is <PB N="153">more clere and wil nat be corumped. and ha&thorn; my&yogh;t redy to speden &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben desired.  &para; But &thorn;e soules of men moten nedes ben more free whan &thorn;ei loken hem in &thorn;e speculacioun or lokynge of &thorn;e deuyne &thorn;ou&yogh;t. and lasse free whan &thorn;ei sliden in to &thorn;e bodies. and &yogh;it lasse free whan &thorn;ei ben gadred to-gidre and comprehendid in er&thorn;ely membris. but &thorn;e last[e] seruage is whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben &yogh;euen to vices. and han yfalle fro &thorn;e possessioun of hire propre resoun  &para; For after &thorn;at &thorn;ei han cast aweye hir eyen fro &thorn;e ly&yogh;t of &thorn;e souereyn so&thorn;efastnesse to lowe &thorn;inges and dirke  &para; Anon &thorn;ei dirken by &thorn;e cloude of ignoraunce and ben troubled by felonous talent&yogh;. to &thorn;e whiche talent&yogh; whan &thorn;ei approchen and assenten. &thorn;ei hepen and encresen &thorn;e seruage whiche &thorn;ei han ioigned to hem self. and in &thorn;is manere &thorn;ei ben caitifs fro hire propre libertee. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;inges na&thorn;eles &thorn;e lokynge of &thorn;e deuyne purueaunce see&thorn; &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges byholde&thorn; and see&thorn; fro eterne. and ordeyne&thorn; hem eueryche in her merites. as &thorn;ei ben prodestinat. and it is seid in grek. &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges he see&thorn; and alle &thorn;inges he here&thorn;.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="2" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">PURO CLARUM LUMINE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>HOmer wi&thorn; &thorn;e hony mou&thorn;e. &thorn;at is to seyn. homer wi&thorn; &thorn;e swete dites synge&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne is cleer by pure ly&yogh;t. na&thorn;eles &yogh;it ne may it nat by &thorn;e inferme ly&yogh;t of hys bemes breken or percen &thorn;e inwarde entrailes of &thorn;e er&thorn;e. or ellys of &thorn;e see.  &para; so ne see&thorn; nat god makere of &thorn;e grete worlde to hym &thorn;at loke&thorn; alle &thorn;inges from on heye ne wi&thorn;standi&thorn; nat no &thorn;inges by heuynesses of er&thorn;e. ne &thorn;e ny&yogh;t ne wi&thorn;stonde&thorn; nat to hym by &thorn;e blake cloudes.  &para; &thorn;ilke god see&thorn; in o strook of &thorn;ou&yogh;t alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben or weren or schullen come.  &para; and &thorn;ilke <PB N="154">god for he loke&thorn; and see&thorn; alle &thorn;inges al oon. &thorn;ou maist seyn &thorn;at he is &thorn;e verray sonne.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="3" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">TAMEN EGO EN INQUAM.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;an seide I now am I confounded by a more harde doute &thorn;an I was.  what doute is &thorn;at quod she. &para; For certys I coniecte now by whiche &thorn;inges &thorn;ou art troubled.  It seme&thorn; quod I to repugnen and to contrarien gretly &thorn;at god knowe&thorn; byforn alle &thorn;inges. and &thorn;at &thorn;er is any fredom of liberte. for yif so be &thorn;at god loke&thorn; alle &thorn;inges byforn. ne god ne may nat ben desseiuid in no manere. &thorn;an mot it nedes ben &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges bytyden &thorn;e whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e purueaunce of god ha&thorn; sein byforn to comen.  &para; For whiche yif &thorn;at god knowe&thorn; by-forn nat oonly &thorn;e werkes of men. but also hir conseils and hir willes. &thorn;an ne shal &thorn;er be no liberte of arbitre. ne certys &thorn;er ne may ben noon o&thorn;er dede ne no wille but &thorn;ilke whiche &thorn;e deuyne purueaunce &thorn;at ne may nat ben desseiued ha&thorn; feled byforn  &para; For yif &thorn;at &thorn;ei my&yogh;ten wry&thorn;en awey in o&thorn;er manere &thorn;an &thorn;ei ben purueyed. &thorn;an ne sholde &thorn;er ben no stedfast prescience of &thorn;inge to comen but ra&thorn;er an vncerteyn oppinioun. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;inge to trowen on god I deme it felonie and vnleueful.  &para; Ne I ne proeue nat &thorn;ilk same resoun. as who sei&thorn; I ne allowe nat. or I ne preise nat &thorn;ilke same resoun by whiche &thorn;at som men wenen &thorn;at &thorn;ei mowen assoilen and vnknytten &thorn;e knot of &thorn;is questioun.  &para; For certys &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;at &thorn;ing nis nat to come for &thorn;at &thorn;e purueaunce of god ha&thorn; seyn it byforne. &thorn;at is to comen but ra&thorn;er &thorn;e contrarie.  &para; And &thorn;at is &thorn;is &thorn;at for &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ing is to comen &thorn;at &thorn;erfore ne may it nat ben hyd fro &thorn;e purueaunce of god. <PB N="155"><MILESTONE N="35" UNIT="fol.">and in &thorn;is manere &thorn;is necessite slydi&thorn; a&yogh;ein in to &thorn;e  
contrarie partie. ne it ne byhoue&thorn; [nat] nedes &thorn;at &thorn;inges bytiden &thorn;at ben ypurueid. [but it by-houeth nedes / &thorn;at thinges &thorn;at ben to comyn ben yporueyid] but as it were ytrauailed. as who sei&thorn;. &thorn;at &thorn;ilke answere procedi&thorn; ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ou&yogh; men trauailden or weren bysy to enqueren &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ing is cause of whiche &thorn;inges. as whe&thorn;er &thorn;e prescience is cause of &thorn;e necessite of &thorn;inges to comen. or ellys &thorn;at &thorn;e necessite of &thorn;inges to comen is cause of &thorn;e purueaunce.  &para; But I ne enforce me nat now to shewen it &thorn;at &thorn;e bytidyng of &thorn;inges y-wist byforn is necessarie. how so or in what manere &thorn;at &thorn;e ordre of causes ha&thorn; it self. al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at it ne seme nat &thorn;at &thorn;e prescience brynge in necessite of bytydynge of &thorn;inges to comen.  &para; For certys yif &thorn;at any wy&yogh;t sitte&thorn; it byhoue&thorn; by necessite &thorn;at &thorn;e oppinioun be so&thorn;e of hym &thorn;at coniecti&thorn; &thorn;at he sitte&thorn;. and a&yogh;einward. al so is it of &thorn;e contrarie. yif &thorn;e oppinioun be so&thorn;e of any wy&yogh;t for &thorn;at he sitte&thorn; it byhoue&thorn; by necessite &thorn;at he sitte &para; &thorn;an is here necessite in &thorn;at oon and in &thorn;at o&thorn;er. for in &thorn;at oon is necessite of sittynge. and certys in &thorn;at o&thorn;er is necessite of so&thorn;e but &thorn;erfore ne sitte&thorn; nat a wy&yogh;t for &thorn;at &thorn;e oppinioun of sittyng is so&thorn;e. but &thorn;e oppinioun is ra&thorn;er so&thorn;e for &thorn;at a wy&yogh;t sitte&thorn; by-forn. and &thorn;us al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;e cause of so&thorn;e come&thorn; of [&thorn;e] syttyng. and nat of &thorn;e trewe oppinioun.  Algates &yogh;itte is &thorn;er comune necessite in &thorn;at oon and in &thorn;at o&thorn;er.  &para; &thorn;us shewe&thorn; it &thorn;at I may make semblable skils of &thorn;e purueaunce of god and of &thorn;inges to come.  &para; For al &thorn;ou&yogh; for &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;inges ben to comen. &thorn;er-fore ben &thorn;ei purueid. nat certys for &thorn;ei ben purueid. &thorn;er-fore ne bytide &thorn;ei nat. &yogh;it na&thorn;eles byhoue&thorn; it by necessite &thorn;at ei&thorn;er &thorn;e &thorn;inges to comen ben ypurueied of god. or ellys &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben <PB N="156">purueied of god bitiden [.s.] by necessite.  &para; And &thorn;is &thorn;ing oonly suffise&thorn; I-nou&yogh; to distroien &thorn;e fredome of oure arbitre. &thorn;at is to seyn of oure fre wille &para; But now [certes] shewe&thorn; it wel how fer fro &thorn;e so&thorn;e and how vp so doun is &thorn;is &thorn;ing &thorn;at we seyn &thorn;at &thorn;e bytidinge of temporel &thorn;inges is &thorn;e cause of &thorn;e eterne prescience. &para; But forto wenen &thorn;at god puruei&thorn; [the] &thorn;inges to comen. for &thorn;ei ben to comen. what o&thorn;er &thorn;ing is it but forto wene &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges &thorn;at bitiden som tyme ben causes of &thorn;ilke souereyne purueaunce &thorn;at is in god.  &para; And her-to I adde &yogh;itte &thorn;is &thorn;ing &thorn;at ry&yogh;t as whan &thorn;at I woot &thorn;at o &thorn;ing is it byhoue&thorn; by necessite &thorn;at &thorn;ilke self &thorn;ing be. and eke &thorn;at whan I haue knowe &thorn;at any &thorn;inge shal bitiden so byhoue&thorn; it by necessite &thorn;at &thorn;ilk[e] same &thorn;ing bytide. so folwe&thorn; it &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;e bytydynge of &thorn;e &thorn;inge Iwist by-forn ne may nat ben eschewed.  &para; And at &thorn;e last[e] yif &thorn;at any wy&yogh;t wene a &thorn;ing to ben o&thorn;er weyes &thorn;an it is. it nys nat oonly vnscience. but it is deceiuable oppinioun ful diuerse and fer fro &thorn;e so&thorn;e of science.  &para; wher-fore yif any &thorn;ing be so to comen so &thorn;at &thorn;e bytydynge of it ne be nat certeyne ne necessarie. &para; who may weten [byforn] &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing is to come. &para; For ry&yogh;t as science ne may nat be medelyd wi&thorn; falsnesse. as who sei&thorn; &thorn;at yif I woot a &thorn;ing. it ne may nat be fals &thorn;at I ne woot it.  &para; Ry&yogh;t so &thorn;ilk &thorn;ing &thorn;at is conceyued by science ne may [nat] ben noon o&thorn;er weyes &thorn;an [as] it is conceiued.  For &thorn;at is &thorn;e cause whi &thorn;at science wanti&thorn; lesynge. as who sei&thorn;. whi &thorn;at witynge ne receyue&thorn; nat lesynge of &thorn;at it woot.  &para; For it byhoue&thorn; by necessite &thorn;at euery &thorn;inge [be] ry&yogh;t as science comprehendi&thorn; it to be. what shal I &thorn;an sein.  &para; In whiche manere knowe&thorn; god byforn &thorn;e &thorn;inges to comen. <PB N="157">&para; yif &thorn;ei ne be nat certeyne.  &para; For yif &thorn;at he deme &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben to comen vneschewably. and so may be &thorn;at it is possible &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne shullen <MILESTONE N="35b" UNIT="fol.">nat comen. god is  
desseiued. but nat only to trowen &thorn;at god is desseiued. but for to speke it wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e it is a felonous synne. &para; But yif &thorn;at god woot &thorn;at ry&yogh;t so as &thorn;inges ben to comen. so shulle &thorn;ei comen. so &thorn;at he wit[e] egaly. as who sei&thorn; indifferently &thorn;at &thorn;inges mowen ben don or ellys nat don. what is &thorn;ilke prescience &thorn;at ne comprehendi&thorn; no certeyne &thorn;inge ne stable. or ellys what difference is &thorn;er bytwixe &thorn;e prescience. and &thorn;ilke iape-wor&thorn;i dyuynynge of Tiresie &thorn;e diuinour &thorn;at seide.  &para; Al &thorn;at I seie quod he ey&thorn;er it shal be. or ellys it ne shal nat be.  Or ellis how moche is wor&thorn;e &thorn;e diuyne prescience more &thorn;an &thorn;e oppinioun of mankynde yif so be &thorn;at it deme&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;inges vncerteyne as men don. of &thorn;e whiche domes of men &thorn;e bytydynge nis nat certeyne.  &para; But yif so be &thorn;at noon vncerteyne &thorn;inge may ben in hym &thorn;at is ry&yogh;t certeyne welle of alle &thorn;inges. &thorn;an is &thorn;e bytydynge certeyne of &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges whiche he ha&thorn; wist byforn fermely to comen.  For whiche it folwe&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e fredom of &thorn;e conseils and of &thorn;e werkes of mankynde nis non syn &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t of god see&thorn; alle &thorn;inges with outen errour of falsnesse bynde&thorn; and constreini&thorn; hem to a bitidynge by necessite. and yif [this] &thorn;ing be on-is grauntid and receyued. &thorn;at is to seyn. &thorn;at &thorn;er nis no fre wille. &thorn;an shewe&thorn; it wel how gret distruccioun and how grete damages &thorn;er folwen of &thorn;inges of mankynde. &para; For in ydel ben &thorn;er &thorn;an purposed and byhy&yogh;t medes of goode folk. and peynes to badde folk. syn &thorn;at no moeuynge of free corage uoluntarie ne ha&thorn; nat deserued hem. &thorn;at is to seyn nei&thorn;er mede nor peyne.  &para; And it sholde seme &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge is al&thorn;er worste whiche <PB N="158">&thorn;at is nowe demed. for al&thorn;er moste iuste and moste ry&yogh;tful. &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;at shrewes ben punyssed. or ellys &thorn;at good[e] folk ben ygerdoned. &thorn;e whiche folk syn &thorn;at &thorn;e propre wille [ne] sent hem nat to &thorn;at oon ne to &thorn;at o&thorn;er. &thorn;at is to seyn. ne&thorn;er to good[e] ne to harme. but constreine&thorn; hem certeyne necessite of &thorn;inges to comen.  &para; &thorn;anne ne shollen &thorn;er neuer ben ne neuer weren vice ne vertue. but it sholde ra&thorn;er ben confusioun of alle desertes medlid wi&thorn;oute discresioun.  &para; And &yogh;itte &thorn;er folwe&thorn; an o&thorn;er inconuenient of &thorn;e whiche &thorn;er ne may ben &thorn;ou&yogh;t ne more felonous ne more wikke. and &thorn;at is &thorn;is &thorn;at so as &thorn;e ordre of &thorn;inges is yledd and come&thorn; of &thorn;e purueaunce of god. ne &thorn;at no &thorn;ing nis leueful to &thorn;e conseils of mankynde. as who sei&thorn; &thorn;at men han no power to done no &thorn;ing. ne wilne no &thorn;ing. &thorn;an folwe&thorn; it &thorn;at oure vices ben refferred to &thorn;e mak[er]e of alle good. as who sei&thorn; &thorn;an folwe&thorn; it. &thorn;at god au&yogh;t[e] han &thorn;e blame of oure vices. syn he constreini&thorn; by necessite to don vices. &thorn;an nis &thorn;er no resoun to han hopen in god. ne forto preien to god.  &para; For what sholde any wy&yogh;t hopen to god. or whi sholde he preien to god. syn &thorn;at &thorn;e ordenaunce of destine whiche &thorn;at ne may nat ben enclined. knytte&thorn; and streini&thorn; alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at men may desiren.  &para; &thorn;an sholde &thorn;ere be don awey &thorn;ilke oonly alliaunce bytwixen god and men. &thorn;at is to seien to hopen and to preien. but by &thorn;e preis of ry&yogh;tfulnesse and of veray mekenesse we deserue &thorn;e gerdoun of &thorn;e deuyne grace whiche &thorn;at is inestimable. &thorn;at is to sein &thorn;at it is so grete &thorn;at it ne may nat ben ful ypreised. and &thorn;is is oonly &thorn;e manere. &thorn;at is to seyen hope and prayeres. for whiche it seme&thorn; &thorn;at [men] mowen speken <PB N="159">wi&thorn; god. and by resoun of supplicacioun ben conioigned to &thorn;ilk clernesse &thorn;at nis nat approched no ra&thorn;er or &thorn;at men byseken it and emprenten it.  And yif men ne wene [nat] &thorn;at [hope] ne preiers ne han no streng&thorn;es. by &thorn;e necessite of &thorn;inges to comen y-resceiued. what &thorn;ing is &thorn;er &thorn;an by whiche we mowen be conioygned and clyuen to &thorn;ilke souereyne prince of &thorn;inges.  &para; For whiche it byhoue&thorn; by necessite &thorn;at &thorn;e lynage of mankynde as <MILESTONE N="36" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;ou songe a litel here byforne ben departed  
and vnioyned from hys welle and faylen of hys bygynnynge. &thorn;at is to seien god.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="3" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUE NAM DISCORS</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>What discordable cause ha&thorn; to-rent and vnioigned &thorn;e byndyng or &thorn;e alliaunce of &thorn;inges. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;e coniunccioun of god and of man.  &para; whiche god ha&thorn; establissed so grete bataile bitwixen &thorn;ise two so&thorn;efast or verray &thorn;inges. &thorn;at is to sein bytwixen &thorn;e purueaunce of god and fre wille. &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben synguler and diuided. ne &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne wolen nat ben medeled ne coupled to-gidre. but &thorn;er nis no discorde to [tho] verray &thorn;inges. but &thorn;ei cleuen certeyne al wey to hem self. but &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t of man confounded and ouer&thorn;rowen by &thorn;e dirke membris of &thorn;e body ne may nat by fir of his dirk[ed] lokynge. &thorn;at is to seyn by &thorn;e vigour of hys insy&yogh;t while &thorn;e soule is in &thorn;e body knowen &thorn;e &thorn;inne subtil knyttynges of &thorn;inges.  &para; But wherfore eschaufi&thorn; it so by so grete loue to fynden &thorn;ilke note[s] of so&thorn;e y-couered. (<FOREIGN LANG="l">glosa</FOREIGN>) &thorn;at is to sein wherfore eschaufi&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t of man by so grete desir to knowen &thorn;ilke notificaciouns &thorn;at ben yhidd vndir &thorn;e couertours of so&thorn;e. woot it ou&yogh;t &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges <PB N="160">&thorn;at it anguissous desire&thorn; to knowe. as who sei&thorn; nay. &para; For no man ne trauaile&thorn; forto witen &thorn;inges &thorn;at he woot. and &thorn;erfore &thorn;e texte sei&thorn; &thorn;us. &para; [<FOREIGN LANG="l">Glosa</FOREIGN>] <FOREIGN LANG="l">Si enim anima ignorat istas subtiles connexiones. responde. vnde est quod desiderat scire cum nil ignotum possit desiderare.</FOREIGN>&para; But who traua[i]le&thorn; to wyten &thorn;inges y-knowe. and yif &thorn;at he ne knowe&thorn; hem nat. what seki&thorn; &thorn;ilke blynde &thorn;ou&yogh;t. what is he &thorn;at desire&thorn; any &thorn;inge of whiche he woot ry&yogh;t nat. as who sei&thorn; who so desiri&thorn; any &thorn;ing nedis som what he knowe&thorn; of it. or ellys he ne cou&thorn;e nat desire it. or who may folwen &thorn;inges &thorn;at ne ben nat ywist &para; and &thorn;ou&yogh; [&thorn;at] he seke &thorn;o &thorn;inges where shal he fynden hem. what wy&yogh;t &thorn;at is al vnknowynge and ignoraunt may knowe &thorn;e forme &thorn;at is yfounde.  &para; But whan &thorn;e soule byholde&thorn; and see&thorn; &thorn;e heye &thorn;ou&yogh;t. &thorn;at is to seyn god. &thorn;an knowe&thorn; it to-gidre &thorn;e somme and &thorn;e singularites. &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;e principles and eueryche by hym self.  &para; But now while &thorn;e soule is hidd in &thorn;e cloude and in &thorn;e derknesse of &thorn;e membris of &thorn;e body. it ne ha&thorn; nat al for&yogh;eten it selfe. but it wi&thorn;holde&thorn; &thorn;e somme of &thorn;inges and lesi&thorn; &thorn;e singularites. &thorn;an who so &thorn;at seke&thorn; so&thorn;enesse. he nis in nei&thorn;er nou&thorn;ir habit. for he not nat alle ne he ne ha&thorn; nat alle for-&yogh;eten.  &para; But &yogh;itte hym remembri&thorn; &thorn;e somme of &thorn;inges &thorn;at he wi&thorn;holde&thorn; and axe&thorn; counseil and treti&thorn; depelyche &thorn;inges ysein byforne. [<FOREIGN LANG="l">Glosa</FOREIGN>] &thorn;at is to sein &thorn;e grete somme in hys mynde. [<FOREIGN LANG="l">textus</FOREIGN>] so &thorn;at he mowe adden &thorn;e parties &thorn;at he ha&thorn; for&yogh;eten. to &thorn;ilke &thorn;at he ha&thorn; wi&thorn;holden. 
</P></DIV2><PB N="161"><DIV2 N="4" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">TAMEN ILLA UETUS INQUIT HEC EST.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;anne seide she. &thorn;is is quod she &thorn;e olde questioun of &thorn;e purueaunce of god. and marcus tulius whan he deuided[e] &thorn;e deuinaciouns. &thorn;at is to sein in hys booke &thorn;at he wroot of deuinaciouns. he moeued[e] gretly &thorn;is questioun. and &thorn;ou &thorn;i self hast sou&yogh;t it mochel and outerly and long[e]. but &yogh;it ne ha&thorn; it nat ben determined ne yspedd fermely and diligently of any of yow. &para; And &thorn;e cause of &thorn;is derkenesse and [of this] difficulte is for &thorn;at &thorn;e moeuynge of &thorn;e resoun of mankynde ne may nat moeuen to. &thorn;at is to sein applien or ioygnen to &thorn;e simplicite of &thorn;e deuyne prescience.  &para; &thorn;e whiche symplicite of &thorn;e deuyne prescience &yogh;if &thorn;at men [myhten thinken it in any manere/&thorn;at is to seyn/&thorn;at yif men] my&yogh;te &thorn;inken and comprehenden &thorn;e &thorn;inges as god see&thorn; hem. &thorn;an ne sholde &thorn;er dwellen outerly no doute. &thorn;e whiche resoun and cause of difficulte I shal assaie at &thorn;e laste to shewen and to speden.  &para; whan I haue <MILESTONE N="36b" UNIT="fol.">firste  
[yspendyd/and] ansewered to &thorn;o resouns by whiche &thorn;ou art ymoeued.  &para; For I axe whi &thorn;ou wenest &thorn;at &thorn;ilk[e] resouns of hem &thorn;at assoilen &thorn;is questioun ne ben nat spedeful ynou&yogh; ne sufficient &thorn;e whiche solucioun or &thorn;e whiche resoun for &thorn;at it demi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e prescience nis nat cause of necessite to &thorn;inges to comen. &thorn;an ne wene&thorn; it nat &thorn;at fredom of wille be distourbed or ylett by prescience. for ne drawest &thorn;ou nat argumentes from ellys where of &thorn;e necessite of &thorn;inges to comen.  As who sei&thorn; any o&thorn;er wey &thorn;an &thorn;us. but &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge[s] &thorn;at &thorn;e prescience woot byforn [ne] mowen nat vnbitide. &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;at &thorn;ei moten bitide.  &para; But &thorn;an yif &thorn;at prescience ne putte&thorn; no necessite to &thorn;inges to comen. as &thorn;ou &thorn;i self <PB N="162">hast confessed it and by knowen a litel her byforne. &para; what cause [or what] is it. as who sei&thorn; &thorn;ere may no cause be. by whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e endes (<FOREIGN LANG="l">exitus</FOREIGN>) uoluntarie of &thorn;inges my&yogh;ten be constreyned to certeyne bitydyng.  &para; For by grace of possessioun. so &thorn;at &thorn;ou mowe &thorn;e better vndirstonde &thorn;is &thorn;at folwe&thorn;.  &para; I pose (<FOREIGN LANG="l">inpossibile</FOREIGN>) &thorn;at &thorn;er ne be no prescience.  &thorn;an axe I quod she in as moche as apperteni&thorn; to &thorn;at. sholde &thorn;an &thorn;inges &thorn;at comen of frewille ben constreined to bytiden by necessite.  <HI REND="i">Boicius</HI>. nay quod I. &thorn;an a&yogh;einward quod she. I suppose &thorn;at &thorn;ere be prescience but &thorn;at ne putte&thorn; no necessite to &thorn;inges. &thorn;an trowe I &thorn;at &thorn;ilk self fredom of wille shal dwellen al hool and absolut and vnbounden. but &thorn;ou wolt sein &thorn;at al be it so &thorn;at prescience nis nat cause of &thorn;e necessite of bitidynge to &thorn;inges to comen.  &para; Algates &yogh;itte it is a signe &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;inges ben to bytiden by necessite. by &thorn;is manere &thorn;an al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e prescience ne hadde neuer yben. &yogh;it algate or at &thorn;e lest[e] wey. it is certeyne &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;e endys and &thorn;e bitydynges of &thorn;inges to comen sholde ben necessarie. &para; For euery sygne shewe&thorn; and signifie&thorn; oonly what &thorn;e &thorn;ing is  &para; but it ne maki&thorn; nat &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at it signifie&thorn;. &para; For whiche it byhoue&thorn; firste to shewen &thorn;at no &thorn;ing ne bitidi&thorn; [&thorn;at it ne bytydith] by necessite. so &thorn;at it may apere &thorn;at &thorn;e prescience is signe of &thorn;is necessite &para; or ellys yif &thorn;ere nere no necessite. certys &thorn;ilke prescience ne my&yogh;t[e] nat ben signe of &thorn;inge &thorn;at nis nat. &para; But certys it is nowe certeyne &thorn;at &thorn;e preue of &thorn;is susteni&thorn; by stedfast resoun ne shal nat ben ladd ne proued by signes ne by argumentys ytaken fro wi&thorn; oute. but by causes couenable and necessarie  &para; But &thorn;ou mayst sein how may it be &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;inges ne bitiden nat <PB N="163">&thorn;at ben ypurueyed to comen. but certys ry&yogh;t as we trowen &thorn;at &thorn;o &thorn;inges whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e purueaunce woot byforn to comen. ne ben nat to bitiden. but [&thorn;at] ne sholde we nat demen. but ra&thorn;er al &thorn;ou&yogh; [&thorn;at] &thorn;ei schal bitiden. &yogh;it ne haue &thorn;ei no necessite of hire kynde to bitiden. and &thorn;is maist &thorn;ou ly&yogh;tly aperceyuen by &thorn;is &thorn;at I shal seyn. but we seen many &thorn;inges whan &thorn;ei ben don byforn oure eyen ry&yogh;t as men seen &thorn;e karter worken in &thorn;e tournynge and in attempryng or in adressyng of hys kartes or chariottes.  &para; and by &thorn;is manere as who sei&thorn; mayst &thorn;ou vnderstonde of alle manere o&thorn;ir werkemen. &para; Is &thorn;ere &thorn;anne any necessite as who sei&thorn; in oure lokynge [&thorn;at] constreine&thorn; or compelli&thorn; any of &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges to ben don so.  <HI REND="i">b.</HI> nay quod I  &para; For in ydel and in veyne were alle &thorn;e effect of crafte yif &thorn;at alle &thorn;inges weren moeued by constreynynge. &thorn;at is to seyn by constreynynge of oure eyen or of oure sy&yogh;t.  <HI REND="i">P.</HI> &thorn;ise &thorn;ingus &thorn;an quod she &thorn;at whan men don hem ne han non necessite &thorn;at men don hem. eke &thorn;o same &thorn;inges first or &thorn;ei be don. &thorn;ei ben to comen wi&thorn; out necessite. for whi &thorn;er ben somme &thorn;inges to bytide of whiche &thorn;e endys and &thorn;e bitidynges of hem ben absolut <MILESTONE N="37" UNIT="fol.">and quit of alle  
necessite. for certys I ne trowe nat &thorn;at any man woldeseyn &thorn;is. &thorn;at &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at men don now &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne weren to bitiden. first or &thorn;ei were ydon  &para; and &thorn;ilk same &thorn;inges al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at men hadden ywyst hem byforn. &yogh;itte &thorn;ei han fre bitidynges. for ry&yogh;t as science of &thorn;inges present ne brynge&thorn; in no necessite to &thorn;inges [&thorn;at men doon // Ryht so the prescience of thinges to comen ne bryngeth in no necessite to thinges] to bytiden but &thorn;ou mayst seyn &thorn;at of &thorn;ilke same it is ydouted. as whe&thorn;er &thorn;at of &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges &thorn;at ne han non endes and <PB N="164">bytidynges necessaryes yif &thorn;er-of may ben any prescience &para; For certys &thorn;ei seme to discorde. for &thorn;ou wenest &thorn;at yif &thorn;at &thorn;inges ben yseyn byforn &thorn;at necessite folwe&thorn; hem. and yif (<FOREIGN LANG="l">et putas</FOREIGN>) necessite faile&thorn; hem &thorn;ei ne my&yogh;ten nat ben wist byforn. and &thorn;at no &thorn;inge ne may ben comprehendid by science but certeyne. and yif &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at ne han no certeyne bytidynges ben ypurueied as certeyn. it sholde ben dirkenesse of oppinioun nat so&thorn;efastnesse of science [and &thorn;ou weenyst &thorn;at it be diuerse fro the hoolnesse of science / &thorn;at any man sholde deme a thing to ben oother weys thanne it is it self]. and &thorn;e cause of &thorn;is errour is. &thorn;at of alle &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at euery wy&yogh;t ha&thorn; yknowe. &thorn;ei wenen &thorn;at &thorn;o &thorn;inges ben y-knowe al oonly by &thorn;e streng&thorn;e and by &thorn;e nature of &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben ywyst or yknowe. and it is al &thorn;e contrarie. for alle &thorn;at euere is yknowe. it is ra&thorn;er comprehendid and yknowen nat after his strenge&thorn; and hys nature. but after &thorn;e faculte &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;e power and [the] nature of hem &thorn;at knowen. and for &thorn;at &thorn;is shal mowe shewen by a short ensample &thorn;e same roundenes of a body .O. o&thorn;er weyes &thorn;e sy&yogh;t of &thorn;e eye knowe&thorn; it. and o&thorn;er weyes &thorn;e touching. &thorn;e lokynge by castynge of his bemes waite&thorn; and see&thorn; fro afer alle &thorn;e body to-gider wi&thorn; oute mouynge of it self. but &thorn;e touchinge cliui&thorn; and conioigne&thorn; to &thorn;e rounde body (<FOREIGN LANG="l">orbi</FOREIGN>) and moue&thorn; abouten &thorn;e environynge. and comprehendi&thorn; by parties &thorn;e roundenesse.  &para; and &thorn;e man hym self o&thorn;er weies wyt byholdi&thorn; hym. and o&thorn;erweyes ymaginacioun and o&thorn;er weyes resoun. and o&thorn;er weyes intelligence.  &para; For &thorn;e wit comprehendi&thorn; fro wi&thorn; outen fur&thorn;e &thorn;e figure of &thorn;e body of &thorn;e man. &thorn;at is establissed in &thorn;e matere subiect. But &thorn;e ymaginacioun [comprehendith only the figure with owte the matere / <PB N="165">Resoun surmounteth ymaginacioun] and comprehende&thorn; by an vniuersel lokynge &thorn;e commune spece (<FOREIGN LANG="l">speciem</FOREIGN>) &thorn;at is in &thorn;e singuler peces. &para; But &thorn;e eye of intelligence is hey&yogh;er for it sourmounte&thorn; &thorn;e envirounynge of &thorn;e vniuersite and looke&thorn; ouer &thorn;at by pure subtilite of &thorn;ou&yogh;t. &thorn;ilk same symple forme of man &thorn;at is perdurably in &thorn;e deuyne &thorn;ou&yogh;t. in whiche &thorn;is au&yogh;t[e] gretely to ben considered &thorn;at &thorn;e heyest streng&thorn;e to comprehenden &thorn;inges enbrace&thorn; and conteyne&thorn; &thorn;e lower[e] streng&thorn;e [but the lowere strengthe ne arysith nat in no manere to heyere strengthe]. for wit ne may no &thorn;inge comprehende oute of matere. ne &thorn;e ymagynacioun ne loke&thorn; nat &thorn;e vniuerseles speces. ne resoun ne take&thorn; nat &thorn;e symple forme. so as intelligence take&thorn; it. but &thorn;e intelligence &thorn;at loke&thorn; al abouen whan it ha&thorn; comprehendid &thorn;e forme it knowe&thorn; and deme&thorn; alle &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben vndir &thorn;at forme. but she knowe&thorn; hem vndir &thorn;ilke manere in &thorn;e whiche it comprehendi&thorn; &thorn;ilke same symple forme &thorn;at ne may neuer be knowen to non of &thorn;at o&thorn;er. &thorn;at is to seyn to non of &thorn;o &thorn;re forseide streng&thorn;es of &thorn;e soule. for it knowe&thorn; &thorn;e vniuersite of resoun and &thorn;e figure of &thorn;e ymaginacioun. and &thorn;e sensible material conseiued. and &thorn;ou wenest &thorn;at it be diuerse fro &thorn;e hoolnesse of science. &thorn;at any man sholde deme a &thorn;ing to ben o&thorn;erweyes &thorn;an it is it self and &thorn;e cause of &thorn;is errour <FOREIGN LANG="l">etc'. vt supra.</FOREIGN> by wit. ne it ne vse&thorn; nat nor of resoun ne of ymaginacioun ne of wit wi&thorn; oute for&thorn;e but it byholde&thorn; alle &thorn;inges so as I shal seye. by a strok of &thorn;ou&yogh;t formely wi&thorn; oute discours or collacioun  &para; Certys resoun whan it loke&thorn; any &thorn;ing vniuersel it ne vse&thorn; nat of ymaginacioun nor of wit and algates &yogh;it [it] comprendi&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;inges ymaginable and sensible.  for resoun is she &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="37b" UNIT="fol.">diffinisse&thorn; &thorn;e vniuersel  
<PB N="166">of hir conseite ry&yogh;t &thorn;us.  &para; Man is a resonable t[w]ofootid beest. and how so &thorn;at &thorn;is knowyng&egrave; [is] vniuersel. &yogh;it nys &thorn;er no wy&yogh;t &thorn;at ne woot wel. &thorn;at a man is [a thing] ymaginable and sensible &para; and &thorn;is same considere&thorn; wel resoun. but &thorn;at nis nat by ymaginacioun. nor by witte. but it loki&thorn; it by [a] resonable concepcioun. &para; Also ymaginacioun al be it so. &thorn;at it take&thorn; of wit &thorn;e bygynyngus to seen and to formen &thorn;e figures. algates al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at wit ne ware not present. &yogh;it it envirouni&thorn; and comprehendi&thorn; alle &thorn;inges sensible. nat by resoun sensible of demynge. but by resoun ymaginatif.  &para; sest &thorn;ou nat &thorn;an &thorn;at alle &thorn;e &thorn;inges in knowynge vsen more of hir faculte or of hir power. &thorn;an &thorn;ei don of [the] faculte or of power of &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben yknowen. ne &thorn;at nis no wronge. for so as euery iugement is &thorn;e dede or &thorn;e doynge of hym &thorn;at deme&thorn;. It byhoue&thorn; &thorn;at euery wy&yogh;t performe &thorn;e werke and hys entencioun nat of forein power&meper; but of hys propre power.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="4" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUONDAM PORTICUS ATTULIT.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;E porche &thorn;at is to sein a gate of &thorn;e toune of athenis &thorn;er as philosophres hadde hir congregacioun to dispoyten. and &thorn;ilke porche brou&yogh;t[e] somtyme olde men ful derke in hire sentences. &thorn;at is to sein philosophers &thorn;at hy&yogh;ten stoiciens. &thorn;at wenden &thorn;at ymages [and] sensibilites &thorn;at is to sein sensible ymaginaciouns. or ellys ymaginacioun of sensible &thorn;inges weren inprentid in to soules fro bodies wi&thorn; oute for&thorn;e.  &para; As who sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ilke stoiciens wenden &thorn;at &thorn;e soule hadde ben naked of it self. as a mirour or a clene parchemyn. so &thorn;at alle fygures mosten [fyrst] comen fro &thorn;inges fro wi&thorn; oute in to soules. and ben inprentid in to soules. <FOREIGN LANG="l">Textus.</FOREIGN> Ry&yogh;t as we ben wont some tyme by a swift poyntel to ficchen lettres emprentid in &thorn;e smo&thorn;enesse or in &thorn;e plainesse of <PB N="167">&thorn;e table of wex. or in parchemyn &thorn;at ne ha&thorn; no figure [ne] note in it. <FOREIGN LANG="l">Glosa.</FOREIGN> But now argui&thorn; boece a&yogh;eins &thorn;at oppinioun and sei&thorn; &thorn;us. but yif &thorn;e &thorn;riuyng soule ne vnpliti&thorn; no &thorn;ing. &thorn;at is to sein ne do&thorn; no &thorn;ing by hys propre moeuynges. but suffri&thorn; and lie&thorn; subgit to &thorn;e figures and to &thorn;e notes of bodyes wi&thorn; oute for&thorn;e. and &yogh;elde&thorn; ymages ydel and veyne in &thorn;e manere of a mirour. whennes &thorn;riue&thorn; &thorn;an or whennes come&thorn; &thorn;an &thorn;ilke knowyng in oure soule. &thorn;at discerni&thorn; and byholde&thorn; alle &thorn;inges. and whennes is &thorn;ilke streng&thorn;e &thorn;at byholde&thorn; &thorn;e syngulere &thorn;inges. or whennes is &thorn;e streng&thorn;e &thorn;at dyuyde&thorn; &thorn;inges yknowe. and &thorn;ilke streng&thorn;e &thorn;at gadere&thorn; to-gidre &thorn;e &thorn;inges deuided. and &thorn;e streng&thorn;e &thorn;at chese&thorn; hys entrechaunged wey for som tyme it heue&thorn; vp &thorn;e heued. &thorn;at is to sein &thorn;at it heue&thorn; vp &thorn;e entencioun to ry&yogh;t heye &thorn;inges. and som tyme it discendi&thorn; in to ry&yogh;t lowe &thorn;inges. and whan it retourni&thorn; in to hym self. it repreui&thorn; and destroie&thorn; &thorn;e false &thorn;inges by &thorn;e trewe &thorn;inges.  &para; Certys &thorn;is streng&thorn;e is cause more efficient and mochel more my&yogh;ty to seen and to knowe &thorn;inges. &thorn;an &thorn;ilke cause &thorn;at suffri&thorn; and resceyue&thorn; &thorn;e notes and &thorn;e figures inpressed in manere of matere algates &thorn;e passioun &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;e suffraunce or &thorn;e wit in &thorn;e quik[e] body go&thorn; byforne excitynge and moeuyng &thorn;e streng&thorn;es of &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;te. ry&yogh;t so as whan &thorn;at clerenesse smyte&thorn; &thorn;e eyen and moeui&thorn; hem to seen. or ry&yogh;t so as voys or soune hurtli&thorn; to &thorn;e eres and commoeui&thorn; hem to herkne. &thorn;an is &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t ymoeuid and excitid and clepe&thorn; fur&thorn;e &thorn;e semblable moeuynges &thorn;e speces &thorn;at it halt wi&thorn; inne it self. and addi&thorn; &thorn;o speces to &thorn;e notes and to &thorn;e &thorn;inges wi&thorn; out for&thorn;e. and medele&thorn; &thorn;e ymages of &thorn;inges wi&thorn; out for&thorn;e to &thorn;e forme[s] yhid wi&thorn; inne hym self. 
</P></DIV2><PB N="168"><DIV2 N="5" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUOD SI IN CORPORIBUS SENCIENDIS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><MILESTONE N="38" UNIT="fol."><HEAD TYPE="sub"><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUESTIO.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>But what [yif] &thorn;at in bodies to ben feelid &thorn;at is to sein in &thorn;e takynge of knowelechinge of bodyly &thorn;inges. and al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;e qualites of bodies &thorn;at ben obiect fro wi&thorn; oute for&thorn;e moeuen and entalenten &thorn;e instrumentes of &thorn;e wittes. and al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;e passioun of &thorn;e body &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;e witte [or the] suffraunce [goth to-forn the strengthe of the workynge corage / the which passioun or suffraunce] clepi&thorn; fur&thorn;e &thorn;e dede of &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t in hym self. and moeue&thorn; and exite&thorn; in &thorn;is mene while &thorn;e formes &thorn;at resten wi&thorn; in for&thorn;e. and yif &thorn;at in sensible bodies as I haue seid oure corage nis nat ytau&yogh;t or enprentid by passioun to knowe &thorn;ise &thorn;inges. but demi&thorn; and knowe&thorn; of hys owen streng&thorn;e &thorn;e passioun or suffraunce subiect to &thorn;e body.  Moche more &thorn;an &thorn;oo &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben absolut and quit fram alle talent&yogh; or affecciouns of bodies. as god or hys aungels ne folwen nat in discernynge &thorn;inges obiect from wi&thorn; oute for&thorn;e. but &thorn;ei accomplissen and speden &thorn;e dede of hir &thorn;ou&yogh;t by &thorn;is resoun.  &para; &thorn;an &thorn;ere comen many manere knowynges to dyuerse and differyng substaunces. for &thorn;e wit of &thorn;e body &thorn;e whiche witte is naked and despoyled of alle o&thorn;er knowynges. &thorn;ilke witte come&thorn; to bestes &thorn;at ne mowen nat moeuen hem self here ne &thorn;ere. as oystres and muscles and o&thorn;er swiche shelle fysshe of &thorn;e see. &thorn;at cliuen and ben norissed to roches. but &thorn;e ymaginacioun come&thorn; to remuable bestes &thorn;at semen to han talent to fleen or to desiren any &thorn;inge. but resoun is al only to &thorn;e lynage of mankynde ry&yogh;t as intelligence is oonly &thorn;e deuyne nature. of whiche it folwe&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ilke knowyng is more wor&thorn;e &thorn;an [th]is[e] o&thorn;er. syn it knowe&thorn; by hys <PB N="169">propre nature nat only hys subiect. as who sei&thorn; it ne knowe&thorn; nat al oonly &thorn;at apperteini&thorn; proprely to hys knowynge. but it knowe&thorn; &thorn;e subgit&yogh; of alle o&thorn;er knowynges. but how shal it &thorn;an be yif &thorn;at wit and ymaginacioun stryuen a&yogh;eins resonynge and sein &thorn;at of &thorn;ilke vniuersel &thorn;inges. &thorn;at resoun wene&thorn; to seen &thorn;at it nis ry&yogh;t nau&yogh;t. for wit and ymaginacioun seyn &thorn;at &thorn;at. &thorn;at is sensible or ymaginable it ne may nat ben vniuersel. &thorn;an is ei&thorn;er &thorn;e iugement of resoun [soth]. ne &thorn;at &thorn;er nis no &thorn;inge sensible. or ellys for &thorn;at resoun woot wel &thorn;at many &thorn;inges ben subiect to wit and to ymaginacioun. &thorn;an is &thorn;e consepcioun of resoun veyn and fals whiche &thorn;at looke&thorn; and comprehendi&thorn;. &thorn;at &thorn;at is sensible and synguler as uniuersele. and &yogh;if &thorn;at resoun wolde answeren a&yogh;ein to &thorn;ise two &thorn;at is to sein to wit and to ymaginacioun. and sein &thorn;at so&thorn;ely she hir self. &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;at resoun loke&thorn; and comprehendi&thorn; by resoun of vniuersalite. bo&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;at is sensible and &thorn;at &thorn;at is ymaginable. and &thorn;at &thorn;ilke two &thorn;at is to seyn wit and ymaginacioun ne mowen nat strecchen ne enhaunsen hem self to knowynge of vniuersalite for &thorn;at &thorn;e knowyng of hem ne may exceden nor sourmounten &thorn;e bodyly figure[s]  &para; Certys of &thorn;e knowyng of &thorn;inges men au&yogh;ten ra&thorn;er &yogh;eue credence to &thorn;e more stedfast and to &thorn;e more perfit iugement.  In &thorn;is manere stryuynge &thorn;an we &thorn;at han streng&thorn;e of resonynge and of ymaginynge and of wit &thorn;at is to seyn by resoun and by ymaginacioun and by wit. [and] we sholde ra&thorn;er preise &thorn;e cause of resoun. as who sei&thorn; &thorn;an &thorn;e cause of wit or ymaginacioun. semblable &thorn;inge is it &thorn;at &thorn;e resoun of mankynde ne wene&thorn; nat &thorn;at &thorn;e deuyne intelligence byholde&thorn; or knowe&thorn; &thorn;inges to comen.  but ry&yogh;t as &thorn;e resoun of mankynde knowe&thorn; hem. for &thorn;ou arguist and seist &thorn;us. &thorn;at <PB N="170">yif it ne seme nat to men &thorn;at somme &thorn;inges han certeyne and necessarie bytidynges. &thorn;ei ne mowen nat ben wist byforn certeynely to bytiden. &thorn;an nis [ther] no prescience of &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges. and yif we trowen &thorn;at prescience ben in &thorn;ise &thorn;inges. &thorn;an is &thorn;er no &thorn;inge &thorn;at it ne bitidi&thorn; by necessite. but certys yif we my&yogh;ten han &thorn;e 
 iugement of &thorn;e deuyne &thorn;ou&yogh;t as we <MILESTONE N="38b" UNIT="fol.">ben parsoners of resoun. ry&yogh;t so as we han demed. it byhoue&thorn; &thorn;at ymaginacioun and wit ben byne&thorn;e resoun. ry&yogh;t so wolde we demen &thorn;at it were ry&yogh;tful &thorn;ing &thorn;at mans resoun au&yogh;t[e] to summitten it self and to ben byne&thorn;e &thorn;e deuyne &thorn;ou&yogh;t. for whiche &thorn;at yif we mowen. as who sei&thorn;. &thorn;at yif &thorn;at we mowen I conseil[e] &thorn;at we enhanse vs in to &thorn;e hey&yogh;t of &thorn;ilke souereyne intelligence. for &thorn;ere shal resoun wel seen &thorn;at &thorn;at it ne may nat by-holden in it self. and certys &thorn;at is &thorn;is in what manere &thorn;e prescience of god see&thorn; alle &thorn;inges certeins and difinissed al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei ne han no certein issues or by-tydynges. ne &thorn;is is non oppinioun but it is ra&thorn;er &thorn;e simplicite of &thorn;e souereyn science &thorn;at nis nat enclosed nor yshet wi&thorn;inne no boundes.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="5" TYPE="metre"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">QUAM UARIIS FIGURIS.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;E bestes passen by &thorn;e er&thorn;es by ful dyuerse figures for somme of hem han hir bodies strau&yogh;t and crepen in &thorn;e dust and drawen after hem a trais or a forghe contynued. &thorn;at is to sein as addres or snakes. and o&thorn;er bestes by [the] wandryng ly&yogh;tnesse of hir wenges beten &thorn;e wyndes and ouer-swymmen &thorn;e spaces of &thorn;e longe eyer by moist flee[y]nge. and o&thorn;er bestes gladen hem to diggen her traas or her stappes in &thorn;e er&thorn;e wi&thorn; hir goynge or wi&thorn; her feet. or to gone ey&thorn;e[r] by &thorn;e grene feldes or [elles] to walken vnder &thorn;e wodes. <PB N="171">and al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest &thorn;at &thorn;ei alle discorden by dyuerse formes. algate hire [faces] enclini[n]g heuie&thorn; hire dulle wittes. Onlyche &thorn;e lynage of man heue&thorn; heyest hys hey&yogh;e heued and stonde&thorn; ly&yogh;t wi&thorn; hys vpry&yogh;t body and byholde&thorn; &thorn;e er&thorn;e vndir hym. [and] but-&yogh;if &thorn;ou er&thorn;ely man wexest yuel oute of &thorn;i witte. &thorn;is figure amoneste&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;at axest &thorn;e heuene wi&thorn; &thorn;i ry&yogh;t[e] visage. and hast areised &thorn;i forhede to beren vp on heye &thorn;i corage so &thorn;at &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t ne be nat yheuied ne put lowe vndir foot. sen &thorn;at &thorn;i body is so heye areised.</P></DIV2><DIV2 N="6" TYPE="prose"><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="l">PROSA VLTIMA. <LB>QUONIAM IGITUR UTI PAULO ANTE.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;Er-fore &thorn;an as I haue shewed a litel her byforne &thorn;at al &thorn;inge &thorn;at is ywist nis nat knowen by hys nature propre. but by &thorn;e nature of hem &thorn;at comprehenden it. &para; Lat vs loke now in as moche as it is leueful to vs. as who sei&thorn; lat vs loken now as we mowen whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e estat is of &thorn;e deuyne substaunce so &thorn;at we mowen [ek] knowen what his science is. &thorn;e comune iugement of alle creatures resonables &thorn;an is &thorn;is &thorn;at god is eterne. lat vs considere &thorn;an what is eternite.  For certys &thorn;at shal shewen vs to-gidre &thorn;e deuyne nature and &thorn;e deuyne science  &para; Eternite &thorn;an is perfit possessioun and al togidre of lijf interminable and &thorn;at shewe&thorn; more clerely by &thorn;e comparisoun or collacioun of temporel &thorn;inges. for al &thorn;ing &thorn;at lyue&thorn; in tyme it is present and procedi&thorn; fro preterit&yogh; in to futures. &thorn;at is to sein. fro tyme passed in to tyme comynge. ne &thorn;er nis no &thorn;ing establissed in tyme &thorn;at may enbracen to-gidre al &thorn;e space of hys lijf. for certys &yogh;it ne ha&thorn; it nat taken &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e morwe. and it ha&thorn; lost &thorn;at of &yogh;ister-day. and certys in &thorn;e lijf <PB N="172">of &thorn;is day &yogh;e ne lyuen no more but ry&yogh;t as in &thorn;is moeueable and transitorie moment. &thorn;an &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge &thorn;at suffri&thorn; temporel condicioun. a[l]&thorn;oughe &thorn;at [it] bygan neuer to be. ne &thorn;oughe it neuere cese forto be. as aristotle demde of &thorn;e worlde. and al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;e lif of it be strecchid wi&thorn; infinite of tyme. &yogh;it al<MILESTONE N="39" UNIT="fol.">gates nis it no swiche &thorn;ing &thorn;at men my&yogh;ten trowen by ry&yogh;t &thorn;at it is eterne.  for al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at it comprehende and embrace &thorn;e space of life infinite. &yogh;it algates ne [em]brace&thorn; it nat &thorn;e space of &thorn;e lif alto-gidre. for it ne ha&thorn; nat &thorn;e futures &thorn;at ne ben nat &yogh;it. ne it ne ha&thorn; no lenger &thorn;e preterit&yogh; &thorn;at ben ydon or ypassed. but &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;an &thorn;at ha&thorn; and comprehendi&thorn; to-gidre alle &thorn;e plente of &thorn;e lif interminable. to whom &thorn;ere ne faili&thorn; nat of &thorn;e future. and to whom &thorn;er nis nat of &thorn;e preterit escapid nor ypassed. &thorn;ilk[e] same is ywitnessed or yproued by ry&yogh;t to ben eterne. and it byhoue&thorn; by necessite &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge be alwey present to hym self and compotent. as who sei&thorn; alwey present to hym self and so my&yogh;ty &thorn;at al by ry&yogh;t at hys plesaunce. and &thorn;at he haue al present &thorn;e infinit of &thorn;e moeuable tyme.  wherfore som men trowen wrongefully &thorn;at whan &thorn;ei heren &thorn;at it semid[e] to plato &thorn;at &thorn;is worlde ne had[de] neuer bygynnynge of tyme. ne &thorn;at it neuere shal haue faylynge. &thorn;ei wenen in &thorn;is manere &thorn;at &thorn;is worlde ben maked coeterne wi&thorn; his makere. as who sei&thorn;. &thorn;ei wenen &thorn;at &thorn;is worlde and god ben maked to-gidre eterne. and it is a wrongful wenynge. for o&thorn;er &thorn;ing is it to ben yladd by lif interminable as plato graunted[e] to &thorn;e worlde. and o&thorn;er &thorn;ing is it to embracen to-gidre alle &thorn;e presence to &thorn;e lif interminable. &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ing it is clere and manifest <PB N="173">&thorn;at it is propre to &thorn;e deuine &thorn;ou&yogh;t. ne it ne sholde nat semen to vs &thorn;at god is elder &thorn;an &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben ymaked by quantite of tyme. but ra&thorn;er by &thorn;e proprete of hys symple nature. for &thorn;is ilke infinit[e] moeuyng of temporel &thorn;inges folwi&thorn; &thorn;is presentarie estat of &thorn;e lijf inmocueable. and so as it ne may nat contrefeten it ne feynen it ne ben euene lyke to it. for &thorn;e inmoeueablete. &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;at is in &thorn;e eternite of god.  &para; it faile&thorn; and falle&thorn; in to moeuynge fro &thorn;e simplicite of [the] presence of god. and disencresi&thorn; to &thorn;e infinite quantite of future and of preterit. and so as it ne may nat han togidre al &thorn;e plente of &thorn;e lif. algates &yogh;itte for as moche as it ne cesi&thorn; neuere forto ben in som manere it seme&thorn; somde[l] to vs &thorn;at it folwi&thorn; and resembli&thorn; &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at it ne may nat attayne to. ne fulfille. and bynde&thorn; it self to som manere presence of &thorn;is litel and swifte moment. &thorn;e whiche presence of &thorn;is lytele and swifte moment. for &thorn;at it bere&thorn; a manere ymage or lykenesse of &thorn;e ay dwellynge presence of god. it graunte&thorn; to swiche manere &thorn;inges as it bitidi&thorn; to &thorn;at it seme&thorn; hem &thorn;at &thorn;ise &thorn;inges han ben and ben and for [&thorn;at] &thorn;e presence of swiche litel moment ne may nat dwelle &thorn;er-for [it] rauyssid[e] and took &thorn;e infinit[e] wey of tyme. &thorn;at is to seyn by successioun. and by &thorn;is manere it is ydon. for &thorn;at it sholde continue &thorn;e lif in goynge of &thorn;e whiche lif it ne my&yogh;t[e] nat embrace &thorn;e plente in dwellynge. and for &thorn;i yif we willen putte wor&thorn;i name[s] to &thorn;inges and folwen plato. lat vs seyn &thorn;an so&thorn;ely &thorn;at god is eterne. and &thorn;at &thorn;e worlde is perpetuel. &thorn;an syn &thorn;at euery iugement knowe&thorn; and comprehendi&thorn; by hys owen nature &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben subiect vnto hym. &thorn;ere is so&thorn;ely al-wey to god an eterne and presentarie estat. and &thorn;e <PB N="174">science of hym &thorn;at ouer-passe&thorn; alle temporel moe[ue]ment dwelli&thorn; in &thorn;e symplicite of hys presence and embrace&thorn; and considere&thorn; alle &thorn;e infinit spaces of tymes preterit&yogh; and futures and loke&thorn; in &thorn;is symple knowynge alle &thorn;inges of preterit ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ei weren ydoon presently ry&yogh;t now  &para; yif &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;an &thorn;enke and avisen &thorn;e 
 prescience by whiche it knowe&thorn; al[le] &thorn;inges <MILESTONE N="39b" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;ou ne shalt nat demen it as prescience of &thorn;inges to comen. but &thorn;ou shalt demen [it] more ry&yogh;tfully &thorn;at it is science of presence or of instaunce &thorn;at neuer ne fayle&thorn;. for whiche it nis nat ycleped prouidence but it sholde ra&thorn;er be cleped purueaunce &thorn;at is establissed ful fer fro ry&yogh;t lowe &thorn;inges. and byholde&thorn; from a-fer alle &thorn;inges ry&yogh;t as it were fro &thorn;e heye hey&yogh;te of &thorn;inges. whi axest &thorn;ou &thorn;an or why disputest &thorn;ou &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges ben don by necessite whiche &thorn;at ben yseyen and yknowen by &thorn;e deuyne sy&yogh;t. syn &thorn;at for so&thorn;e men ne maken nat &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges necessarie.  whiche &thorn;at &thorn;e[i] seen be ydoon in hire sy&yogh;t. for addi&thorn; &thorn;i byholdynge any necessite to &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges &thorn;at &thorn;ou byholdest present.  &para; Nay quod I. <HI REND="i">p.</HI>Certys &thorn;an yif men my&yogh;te maken any digne comparisoun or collacioun of &thorn;e presence diuine. and of &thorn;e presence of mankynde. ry&yogh;t so as &yogh;e seen somme &thorn;inges in &thorn;is temporel presente. ry&yogh;t so see&thorn; god alle &thorn;inges by hys eterne present.  &para; wherfore &thorn;is dyuyne prescience ne chaunge&thorn; nat &thorn;e nature ne &thorn;e proprete of &thorn;inges but byholde&thorn; swyche &thorn;inges present to hym ward. as &thorn;ei shollen bytiden to &yogh;ow ward in tyme to come. ne it ne confounde&thorn; nat &thorn;e Iugement&yogh; of &thorn;inges but by of sy&yogh;t of hys &thorn;ou&yogh;t he knowe&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;inges to comen as wel necessarie as nat necessarie. ry&yogh;t so as whan &yogh;e seen togidre a man walke on &thorn;e er&thorn;e and &thorn;e sonne arysen in [the] heuene. al be it so &thorn;at &yogh;e seen and byholden &thorn;at <PB N="175">oon and &thorn;at o&thorn;er to-gidre. &yogh;it na&thorn;eles &yogh;e demen and discerne &thorn;at &thorn;at oon is uoluntarie and &thorn;at o&thorn;er is necessarie. &para; Ry&yogh;t so &thorn;an [the] deuyne lokynge byholdynge alle &thorn;inges vndir hym ne trouble&thorn; nat &thorn;e qualite of &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben certeynely present to hym ward. but as to &thorn;e condicioun of tyme for so&thorn;e &thorn;ei ben future. for whiche it folwi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;is nis non oppinioun. but ra&thorn;er a stedfast knowyng ystrenge&thorn;ed by so&thorn;enes. &thorn;at whan &thorn;at god knowe&thorn; any &thorn;inge to be he ne vnwoot nat &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge wante&thorn; necessite to be. &thorn;is is to seyn &thorn;at whan &thorn;at god knowe&thorn; any &thorn;inge to bitide. he woot wel &thorn;at it ne ha&thorn; no necessite to bitide. and yif &thorn;ou seist here &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge &thorn;at god see&thorn; to bytide it ne may nat vnbytide. as who sei&thorn; it mot bitide.  &para; and &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge &thorn;at &thorn;at ne may nat vnbytide it mot bitide by necessite. and &thorn;at &thorn;ou streine me to &thorn;is name of necessite. certys I wol wel confessen and byknowe a &thorn;inge of ful sadde trou&thorn;e. but vnne&thorn; shal &thorn;ere any wy&yogh;t [mowe] seen it or comen &thorn;er-to. but yif &thorn;at he be byholder of &thorn;e deuyne &thorn;ou&yogh;te.  &para; for I wol answere &thorn;e &thorn;us. &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge &thorn;at is future whan it is referred to &thorn;e deuyne knowyng &thorn;an is it necessarie. but certys whan it is vndirstonden in hys owen kynde men sen it [is] vtterly fre and absolut from alle necessite. for certys &thorn;er ben two maneres of necessites. &thorn;at oon necessite is symple as &thorn;us. &thorn;at it byhoue&thorn; by necessite &thorn;at alle men be mortal or dedely. an o&thorn;er necessite is condicionel as &thorn;us. yif &thorn;ou wost &thorn;at a man walki&thorn;. it byhoue&thorn; by necessite &thorn;at he walke. &thorn;ilke &thorn;inge &thorn;an &thorn;at any wy&yogh;t ha&thorn; yknowe to be. it ne may ben non o&thorn;er weyes &thorn;an he knowe&thorn; it to be. &para; but &thorn;is condicioun ne drawe&thorn; nat wi&thorn; hir &thorn;ilke necessite symple.  For certys &thorn;is necessite condicionel. <PB N="176">&thorn;e propre nature of it ne make &thorn;it nau&yogh;t. but &thorn;e adieccioun of &thorn;e condicioun maki&thorn; it. for no necessite ne constreyne&thorn; a man to [gon / &thorn;at] goo&thorn; by his propre wille. al be it so &thorn;at whan he goo&thorn; &thorn;at it is necessarie &thorn;at he goo&thorn;. &para; Ry&yogh;t on &thorn;is same manere &thorn;an. yif &thorn;at &thorn;e purueaunce 
 of god see&thorn; any &thorn;ing present. &thorn;an mot &thorn;ilke<MILESTONE N="40" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;inge be by necessite. al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at it ne haue no necessite of hys owen nature. but certys &thorn;e futures &thorn;at bytyden by fredom of arbitre god see&thorn; hem alle to-gidre present&yogh;. &thorn;ise &thorn;inges &thorn;an [yif] &thorn;ei ben referred to &thorn;e deuyne sy&yogh;t. &thorn;an ben &thorn;ei maked necessarie to &thorn;e condicioun of &thorn;e deuyne knowynge. but certys yif &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges ben considred by hem self &thorn;ei ben absolut of necessite. and ne forleten nat ne cesen nat of &thorn;e liberte of hire owen nature.  &thorn;an certys wi&thorn; outen doute alle &thorn;e &thorn;ingus shollen be doon whiche &thorn;at god woot by-forn &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben to comen. but somme of hem comen and bitiden of [free] arbitre or of fre wille. &thorn;at al be it so &thorn;at &thorn;ei bytiden. &yogh;it algates ne lese &thorn;ei nat hire propre nature ne beynge. by &thorn;e whiche first or &thorn;at &thorn;ei were doon &thorn;ei hadden power nat to han bitidd.  <HI REND="i">Boece</HI>. what is &thorn;is to seyn &thorn;an quod I. &thorn;at &thorn;inges ne ben nat necessarie by hire propre nature. so as &thorn;ei comen in alle maneres in &thorn;e lykenesse of necessite by &thorn;e condicioun of &thorn;e deuyne science.  <HI REND="i">Philosophie.</HI> &thorn;is is &thorn;e difference quod she. &thorn;at &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at I purposed[e] &thorn;e a litel here byforn. &thorn;at is to seyn &thorn;e sonne arysynge and &thorn;e man walkynge &thorn;at &thorn;erwhiles &thorn;at &thorn;ilke &thorn;inges ben ydon. &thorn;ei ne my&yogh;ten nat ben vndon. na&thorn;eles &thorn;at oon of hem or it was ydon it byhoued[e] by necessite &thorn;at it was ydon. but nat &thorn;at o&thorn;er. ry&yogh;t so it is here &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;inges &thorn;at god ha&thorn; present. <PB N="177">wi&thorn; outen doute &thorn;ei shulle ben. but somme of hem descendi&thorn; of &thorn;e nature of &thorn;inges as &thorn;e sonne arysynge. and somme descendi&thorn; of &thorn;e power of &thorn;e doers as &thorn;e man walkynge.  &para; &thorn;an seide I. no wronge &thorn;at yif &thorn;at &thorn;ise &thorn;inges ben referred to &thorn;e deuyne knowynge &thorn;an ben &thorn;ei necessarie. and yif &thorn;ei ben considered by hem selfe &thorn;an ben &thorn;ei absolut from &thorn;e bonde of necessite. ry&yogh;t so [as] alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at appiere&thorn; or shewe&thorn; to &thorn;e wittes yif &thorn;ou referre it to resoun it is vniuersel. and yif &thorn;ou referre it or look[e] it to it self. &thorn;an is it synguler. but now yif &thorn;ou seist &thorn;us &thorn;at yif it be in my power to chaunge my purpose. &thorn;an shal I voide &thorn;e purueaunce of god. whan &thorn;at perauenture I shal han chaunged &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at he knowe&thorn; byforn. &thorn;an shal I answere &thorn;e &thorn;us &para; Certys &thorn;ou maist wel chaungen &thorn;i purpos but for as mochel as &thorn;e present so&thorn;enesse of &thorn;e deuyne purueaunce byholde&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayst chaungen &thorn;i purpose. and whe&thorn;ir &thorn;ou wolt chaunge it or no. and whider-ward &thorn;at &thorn;ou tourne it. &thorn;ou maist nat eschewen &thorn;e deuyne prescience ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ou ne mayst nat fleen &thorn;e sy&yogh;t of &thorn;e present eye. al &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;ou tourne &thorn;i self by &thorn;i fre wille in to dyuerse accioun.  &para; But &thorn;ou mayst seyn a&yogh;eyne how shal it &thorn;an be. shal nat &thorn;e dyuyne science ben chaunged by my disposicioun whan &thorn;at I wol o &thorn;ing now and now an o&thorn;er. and &thorn;ilke prescience ne seme&thorn; it nat to enterchaunge stoundes of knowynges. as who sei&thorn;. ne shal it nat seme to vs &thorn;at &thorn;e deuyne prescience enterchaunge&thorn; hys dyuers stoundes of knowynge. so &thorn;at it knowe somme tyme o &thorn;ing and somme tyme &thorn;e contrarie. &para; No for so&thorn;e. [quod I] for &thorn;e deuyne sy&yogh;t renne&thorn; to-forne and see&thorn; alle futures and clepe&thorn; hem a&yogh;ein <PB N="178">and retourni&thorn; hem to &thorn;e presence of hys propre knowynge. ne he ne entrechaunge&thorn; nat [so] as &thorn;ou wenest &thorn;e stoundes of forknowyng [as] now &thorn;is now &thorn;at. but he ay dwellynge comi&thorn; byforn and enbrace&thorn; at o strook alle &thorn;i mutaciouns. and &thorn;is presence to comprehenden and to sen alle &thorn;inges. god ne ha&thorn; nat taken it of &thorn;e bitydynge of &thorn;inges forto come. but of hys propre symplicite. &para; and her by is assoiled &thorn;ilke &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou puttest a litel her byforne. &thorn;at is to seyne &thorn;at it is vnwor&thorn;i &thorn;inge to seyn &thorn;at oure futures &yogh;euen cause of &thorn;e 
 science of god  &para; For certys <MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="fol.">&thorn;is streng&thorn;e of &thorn;e deuyne science whiche &thorn;at enbrace&thorn; alle &thorn;inge by his presentarie knowynge establisse&thorn; manere to alle &thorn;ingus and it ne awi&thorn; nat to lattere &thorn;inges. and syn &thorn;at &thorn;ise &thorn;inges ben &thorn;us. &thorn;at is to seyn syn &thorn;at necessite nis nat in &thorn;inges by &thorn;e deuyne prescience. &thorn;an is &thorn;er fredom of arbitre. &thorn;at dwelle&thorn; hool and vnwemmed to mortal men. ne &thorn;e lawes ne purpose nat wikkedly meedes and peynes to &thorn;e willynges of men &thorn;at ben vnbounde and quit of alle necessite.  &para; And god byholder and forwiter of alle &thorn;inges dwelli&thorn; aboue and &thorn;e present eternite of hys sy&yogh;t renne&thorn; alwey wi&thorn; &thorn;e dyuerse qualite of oure dedes dispensyng and ordeynynge medes to good[e] men. and tourment&yogh; to wicked men. ne in ydel ne in veyn ne ben &thorn;er nat put in god hope and prayeres. &thorn;at ne mowen nat ben vnspedful ne wi&thorn; oute effect whan &thorn;ei ben ry&yogh;tful &para; wi&thorn;stond &thorn;an and eschewe &thorn;ou vices. worshippe and loue &thorn;ou vertus. areise &thorn;i corage to ry&yogh;tful hoopes. &yogh;elde &thorn;ou humble preiers an hey&yogh;e. grete necessite of prowesse and vertue is encharged and comaunded to &yogh;ow yif &yogh;e nil nat dissimulen.  &para; Syn &thorn;at &yogh;e worchen and doon. &thorn;at is to seyn &yogh;oure dedes and &yogh;oure workes <PB N="179">by-fore &thorn;e eyen of &thorn;e Iuge &thorn;at see&thorn; and deme&thorn; alle &thorn;inges.  [To whom be goye and worshipe bi Infynyt tymes / AMEN.]</P></DIV2><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="l">EXPLICIT LIBER QUINTUS. ET VLTIMUS.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
